## Section III: The Rothschild Myth

### Origins of the Sympathetic Myth

- Myth traceable to **1813**: S. J. Cohen's memoir
  *The Exemplary Life of the Immortal Banker Mr Meyer Amschel
  Rothschild* — portrayed success as divine approbation
  for a pious Jew
- 1827: **Friedrich von Gentz** (secretary to Metternich)
  wrote the "Rothschild" entry for **F. A. Brockhaus's**
  *General German Encyclopaedia for the Educated Classes*
  — sold ~80,000 copies
  - Gentz was *paid* for the piece — read it aloud to
    Rothschild clerk before publication; received his
    "actual reward" from **Salomon von Rothschild**
  - Article attributed success to: "hard work and parsimony,
    knowledge and proven integrity," and "personal moral
    character" of the five brothers
- Privately Gentz was more ambivalent — called them in 1818
  "common, ignorant Jews, who exercise their craft quite
  naturalistically [instinctively]" but also "gifted with a
  remarkable instinct which causes them always to choose
  the right"

> "It is not difficult to create a party for oneself when one is
> powerful enough to draw many people into one's interest. But to
> unite the support of all parties and . . . to win the esteem of
> great and small, requires the possession not merely of material
> resources, but also of spiritual qualities which are not always
> found in association with wealth and power."
> — Friedrich von Gentz, on the Rothschilds (Brockhaus entry)

### The Elector's Treasure Story

- Central founding myth: when the **Elector of Hesse fled
  in 1806** as the French approached, Mayer Amschel rescued
  and safeguarded his fortune at personal risk
- Story grew with each retelling: by 1836 version, Rothschild
  supposedly sacrificed his own property to save the Elector's
  millions; when Elector returned in 1813, Rothschild not only
  returned the capital but paid interest — astonishing the
  Elector, who then left money with the firm and recommended
  them at the **Congress of Vienna**
- Ferguson notes: the story was actively propagated by the
  Rothschilds themselves; Nathan told it to MP **Thomas Fowell
  Buxton** in 1834; family commissioned two paintings by
  **Moritz Daniel Oppenheim** (1861) on the subject
- Coat of arms (1817): fourth quarter depicted arm bearing
  **five arrows** (unity of five brothers) — still on N. M.
  Rothschild & Sons notepaper today
- Motto: **"Concordia, integritas, industria"**

### Gentz's Deeper Analysis (Posthumous Notes)

> "Lasting success, however, and constant failure are always . . .
> attributable to the personal virtue or the personal failings and
> shortcomings of those who are blessed by the one or damned by
> the other. Nevertheless, the most outstanding personal qualities
> may sometimes require exceptional circumstances and world-
> shattering events to come to fruition. Thus have the founders of
> dynasties established their thrones, and thus has the House of
> Rothschild become great."
> — Friedrich von Gentz, "Biographical Notes on the House
> of Rothschild" (posthumous)

- Gentz's key principle (Machiavellian): "luck" as commonly
  used is meaningless unless linked to personal virtue — lasting
  success is always due to personal qualities meeting exceptional
  circumstances

### The Disraeli Portrait (Sympathetic Fiction)

- **Benjamin Disraeli** knew the Rothschilds intimately and
  fictionalised them in *Coningsby* (1844) via character
  **Sidonia** (based on **Lionel de Rothschild**):
  father made fortune in Peninsular War, "staked all on
  the Waterloo loan," afterwards became "lord and master
  of the money-market of the world"
- In *Tancred* (1847): "Who is the richest man in Paris?" —
  "The brother, I believe, of the richest man in London"
- Disraeli's portraits are mouthpieces for his own views on
  Jews in the modern world, not realistic portraits

### The Anti-Rothschild Myth

- For every sympathetic writer, two or three took the
  opposite view — hostile myth far outnumbered positive
- Early 1820s–1830s: hard to publish criticism in Germany;
  Gentz instructed newspapers like *Allgemeine Zeitung*
  not to criticise Rothschilds
- **Friedrich Steinmann's** detailed critical history
  *The House of Rothschild, Its History and Transactions*
  (1843) could not find a publisher for 15 years
- **Friedrich List** (1826): called James de Rothschild
  "the mighty lord and master of all the coined and uncoined
  silver and gold in the Old World, before whose money-box
  Kings and Emperors humbly bow, [the] King of Kings"
- English critics used parliamentary privilege or allegorical
  cartoons (Cruikshank's *The Jew and the Doctor*)

### The Waterloo Legend

- Key anti-Rothschild narrative: Nathan had advance news of
  Napoleon's defeat at Waterloo and made a "huge sum" speculating
  on the stock exchange
- Later versions: Nathan witnessed the battle, risked a Channel
  storm, reached London ahead of official news, pocketed
  £20–£135 million; or bribed General **Grouchy** and then
  deliberately spread false news to precipitate panic-selling
- Origin in **Honoré de Balzac's** *The House of Nucingen*
  (1837–8); popularized by **Georges Dairnvaell's** pamphlet
  *The Edifying and Curious History of Rothschild I, King of
  the Jews* (1846)
- Inspiration to **Bernard Baruch** who said it inspired
  his first million

> "All rapidly accumulated wealth is either the result of luck
> or discovery, or the result of a legalised theft."
> — Honoré de Balzac, *Splendours and Sorrows of Courtesans*

- Queen **Victoria** refused to make **Lionel de Rothschild** a
  peer, questioning whether wealth "owes his great wealth to
  contracts with Foreign Govts. for loans, or to successful
  speculations on the Stock Exchange can fairly claim a British
  peerage" — "not the less a species of gambling, because it
  is on a gigantic scale"

### Political Neutrality vs. Political Bias (The Myth's Core Tension)

- Waterloo story read two ways:
  1. Proof of **political neutrality** — if Napoleon had won,
     Nathan would have been a bear, not a bull, on British bonds
  2. Proof of **political bias** — support for coalition against
     Napoleon, financing Bourbon restoration
- Radical critics (e.g., German writer **Ludwig Börne**):
  Rothschilds were "chief ally of the Holy Alliance" and
  "the nation's worst enemies" who had "done more than any
  to undermine the foundations of freedom"
- **Lord Byron**, *Don Juan* (1823), Canto XII: "Who hold
  the balance of the world? Who reign O'er Congress, whether
  royalist or liberal?" — "Jew Rothschild, and his fellow
  Christian Baring" — saw Rothschild power as transcending
  political factions

> "The Rothschilds have only ever gained from our disasters;
> when France has won, the Rothschilds have lost."
> — Georges Dairnvaell (1846)

