## Chapter: The Rothschild Myth (continued) — Critics, Conspiracy, and the Archive

### Heine's Ambivalent Analysis

- **Heinrich Heine** saw the Rothschilds as simultaneously propping up and
  undermining the old order: "revolutions are generally triggered off by
  deficiency of money" and "the Rothschild system . . . prevent[ed] such
  deficiencies" — so they stabilized reactionary regimes in the short term
- But Heine also argued their power was inherently revolutionary:

> "No one does more to further the revolution than the Rothschilds
> themselves . . . these Rothschilds, the bankers of kings, these princely
> pursestring-holders, whose existence might be placed in the gravest danger
> by a collapse of the European state system, nevertheless carry in their
> minds a consciousness of their revolutionary mission."
> — Heinrich Heine

- Heine's key insight: Rothschild "destroyed the predominance of land, by
  raising the system of state bonds to supreme power" — creating a new
  aristocracy based on money, which could never be as permanently regressive
  as the landed aristocracy
- Famous declaration (March 1841): **"[M]oney is the god of our time, and
  Rothschild is his prophet"**
- Railway development (1843 lines to Orléans and Rouen) heightened Heine's
  sense of Rothschild as revolutionary social force, though he grew more
  sceptical as the 1840s progressed and their interests converged with the
  landed aristocracy

### The Left Turns Against Them: Toussenel and Marx

- Heine's ambivalence gave way in the 1840s to outright hostility from the
  radical left, triggered by **James de Rothschild's** securing of the Paris-
  Belgium rail concession
- **Alphonse Toussenel**, *The Jews, Kings of the Epoch: A History of
  Financial Feudalism* (1846) — attacked the terms of the rail concession;
  linked Jewish capitalism to the Rothschilds specifically; France "sold to
  the Jews" by "Baron Rothschild, the King of Finance, a Jew ennobled by a
  very Christian King"
- Anonymous *Judgement Passed against Rothschild and Georges Dairnvaell*
  equated Judaism and capitalism — the name Rothschild "stands for a whole
  race—it is a symbol of a power which extends its arms over the entirety of
  Europe"
- **Karl Marx**, "On the Jewish Question" (1844) — defined "the real Jew" as
  the capitalist irrespective of religion; after 1848-9 revolutions when
  Rothschilds survived with the regimes, Marx concluded: "[E]very tyrant is
  backed by a Jew, as is every Pope by a Jesuit"
- By the 1850s, the left had comprehensively replaced Heine's ambivalence
  with a critique of Rothschilds as defenders of the status quo and archetypal
  capitalists; their Jewishness became the explanation — though never
  adequately argued *why* Jews should differ from Gentiles in economic
  attitudes

### Rothschilds vs. Crédit Mobilier

- A more sophisticated critique emerged in the **Second Empire**: the
  conservative *haute banque* (Rothschilds) vs. the new **Crédit Mobilier**
  of the **Saint-Simonian Pereire brothers** — portrayed as a political
  challenge, Napoleon III's bid to "free himself" from Rothschild tutelage
- **Jules Isaac Mirès** attributed the difference to cultural background:
  Pereires were **Sephardic Jews** (originally from Spain); Rothschilds were
  **Ashkenazim**
- Others framed it in political terms: Rothschild = "aristocracy of money" /
  "financial feudalism"; Pereires = "financial democracy" / "economic 1789"
- The Crédit Mobilier's collapse in the 1860s was read as more than financial:
  a harbinger of the Second Empire's own fall
- **James de Rothschild's** famous epigram — **"L'Empire, c'est la baisse"**
  — was cited as both prophecy and assertion of the *haute banque*'s
  political supremacy

### The Third Republic and Renewed Attacks

- The 1870 republic shifted anti-Rothschild attacks from left to right; the
  **Goncourt brothers** called them "Pariah kings of the world . . . coveting
  everything and controlling everything"
- Collapse of **Union Générale** bank (1882) — its founder blamed "Jewish
  finance" and "governmental freemasonry"; **Emile Zola's** *L'Argent*
  portrayed the Rothschildian figure Gundermann as "the banker king, the
  master of the bourse and of the world"
- **Edouard Drumont**, *Jewish France* (1886) — inverted reality by claiming
  the Union Générale itself had been established by Jews to rob Catholics;
  declared "The God Rothschild" was real master of France
- **Auguste Chirac**, *Kings of the Republic* (1883) and *The Speculation of
  1870 to 1884* (1887) — denounced "a *king* named Rothschild, with a
  courtesan or maid called *Jewish finance*"

### German and English Anti-Rothschild Literature

- Germany: *The Frankfurt Jews and the Mulcting of the People's Well-being*
  (1880, "Germanicus"), Max Bauer's *Bismarck and Rothschild* (1891),
  Friedrich von Scherb's *History of the House of Rothschild* (1893)
- Echoed in "People's" and "Christian Social" anti-Semitic parties; **Werner
  Sombart** asserted in *The Jews and Economic Life* (1911):
  "[T]he modern stock exchange is Rothschildish (and thus Jewish)"
- England: **John Reeves**, *The Rothschilds: The Financial Rulers of Nations*
  (1887) — "The Rothschilds belong to no one nationality, they are
  cosmopolitan . . . they belonged to no party, they were ready to grow rich
  at the expense of friend and foe alike"
- 1830s American magazine: "Not a cabinet moves without their advice. They
  stretch their hand, with equal ease, from Petersburg to Vienna, from Vienna
  to Paris, from Paris to London, from London to Washington"
- English diarist **Thomas Raikes**: "the metallic sovereigns of Europe"
- **Alexandre Weill**, "Rothschild and the Finances of Europe" (1841):

> "There is but one power in Europe and that is Rothschild . . . Rothschild
> had need of the states to become a Rothschild, while the states on their
> side required Rothschild. Now, however, he no longer needs the State, but
> the State still has want of him."

### The War and Peace Question

- Most frequent contemporary view: the Rothschilds *prevented* wars because
  war disrupted bond markets and threatened their loans to sovereign states
- **Prince Pückler-Muskau** (1828): Rothschild "without whom no power in
  Europe today seems able to make war"
- **Ludwig Börne** argued Rothschild sales of Austrian bonds prevented
  Metternich from intervening militarily in Italy and Belgium
- Austrian diplomat **Graf Prokesch von Osten** (1830): "It is all a question
  of ways and means and what Rothschild says is decisive, and he won't give
  any money for war"
- **Disraeli** after 1863 Polish crisis: "the peace of the world has been
  preserved, not by the statesmen, but by the capitalists"
- Even hostile **Toussenel**: "The Jew *speculates on peace*, that is on a
  rise, and that explains why peace in Europe has lasted for fifteen years"
- Attributed to **Gutle Rothschild**: "It won't come to war; my sons won't
  provide money for it"
- Contrarian view: Rothschild "pacifism" was suspect in nationalist contexts;
  Bismarck actively wanted wars of unification; **August Belmont** (NY agent)
  attacked for favoring peace with the South in the Civil War
- Henry Wickham Steed (*The Times* editor) described **Natty Rothschild's**
  efforts to avert WWI in July 1914 as "a dirty German-Jewish international
  financial attempt to bully us into advocating neutrality"
- Left critics reversed the argument: the *Labour Leader* (1891) declared the
  Rothschilds were a "blood-sucking crew" that "piled up its prodigious
  wealth chiefly through fomenting wars between States"
- **J. A. Hobson**, *Imperialism: A Study* (1902) — the Boer War engineered
  by "a small group of international financiers, chiefly German in origin and
  Jewish in race"; asked whether "a great war could be undertaken by any
  European State, or any great State loan subscribed, if the house of
  Rothschild and its connexions set their face against it?"

### Jewish Solidarity and the "Hebrew Talisman"

- Third possible motive: using financial power to advance Jewish interests
- The **"Hebrew talisman"** legend — a story (published in London four years
  after Nathan's death) held that Nathan's wealth derived from a magical
  talisman, intended "to avenge the wrongs of Israel" by restoring Jerusalem
- Notion that Rothschilds might buy back the Holy Land: American journal (1830)
  suggested the sultan might sell Jerusalem; **Charles Fourier**, *The False
  Industry* (1836); Disraeli spoke of Jews being "restor[ed]...to their own
  land" with Rothschild money
- The central dilemma: other Jews looked to Rothschilds for leadership in
  emancipation — from **Mayer Amschel's** campaign for Frankfurt Jews in the
  Napoleonic era to **Lionel's** 1840s-50s campaign for Jewish admission to
  the House of Commons
- The more the Rothschilds pursued emancipation internationally (Syria,
  Romania, Russia), the more they confirmed anti-Semitic claims about Jewish
  cosmopolitanism and lack of national loyalty
- **Thomas Carlyle** on Lionel's Commons campaign: "[H]ow can a real Jew, by
  possibility, try to be a Senator, or even a Citizen of any country, except
  his own wretched Palestine, whither all his thoughts and steps and efforts
  tend?"

### Herzl and the Zionist Confrontation

- **Theodor Herzl** believed Rothschilds were about to "liquidate" their
  capital due to anti-Semitic pressure and would therefore support his
  *Judenstaat* project
- His 66-page address "to the Rothschild Family Council" was never sent after
  an initial rebuff; he concluded they were "vulgar, contemptuous, egoistical
  people" and declared them "a national misfortune for the Jews"
- Rothschilds had no desire to leave palatial European residences for
  Palestine — the very thing their enemies demanded

### Nazi Propaganda and the Rothschild Myth's Culmination

- **Dietrich Eckart**, "To All Working People" (1919) exemplified early Nazi
  rhetoric — recycled 1840s French radical themes almost verbatim
- **Adolf Hitler** cited Rothschilds explicitly: in *Völkische Beobachter*
  (May 1921) as Jewish capitalists controlling the socialist press; in 1922
  speeches contrasting **Alfred Krupp** (national creator) vs. Rothschild
  (war-financier extracting "interest-servitude")
- Nazi propaganda used the Rothschilds even though by the 1920s there was no
  longer a Rothschild bank in Frankfurt and the remaining three houses (London,
  Paris, Vienna) had ceased to play major roles in the German economy
- **Eberhard Müller's** play *Rothschild Wins at Waterloo* (1936) had Nathan
  intone: "My Fatherland is the London Stock Exchange"; "The wealth of England
  is in my hands"
- **Julius Streicher's** anti-Jewish exhibition (Vienna, May 1938) devoted a
  room to Rothschild; Frankfurt exhibition displayed forged "facsimiles" of
  Mayer Amschel letters purporting to show a plan to send his five sons to
  dominate Gentile commerce
- **Erich Waschnek's** film *Die Rothschilds* (*Aktien auf Waterloo*, 1940) —
  one of three films (*Jud-Süss*, *Der ewige Jude*) designed to prepare
  German public for harsher anti-Jewish measures; popular in occupied France
- Contrasted with American precursor: **Darryl Zanuck's** *The House of
  Rothschild* (1934, **George Arliss**) portrayed rise as "American dream,"
  with sinister Prussian Baron Ledrantz (**Boris Karloff**) as the villain —
  the same story, moral signs reversed
- Both films use nearly identical imagery (map of Europe with Rothschild
  centers, Star of David superimposed) to opposite ends

### Modern Conspiracy Theories

- **David Icke** — Rothschilds as members of "Global Elite or Brotherhood"
  ("All-Seeing Eye Cult"), responsible for: Lincoln assassination, Boer War,
  Russian Revolution, financing Hitler, Nixon floating the dollar
- Internet variants: "World Money Cartel," Rothschilds controlling Morgan,
  Rockefellers, Kuhn Loeb, Lehman, Bank of England, Federal Reserve
- **Pat Robertson**, *The New World Order* (1991) — Rothschilds "polluted by
  the occultism of Illuminated Freemasonry"
- **Khalid Muhammad** (Nation of Islam): Rothschilds "financed Hitler" and
  "gained control of" Bank of England and Federal Reserve
- Ferguson's conclusion: a serious banking history must engage these myths
  rather than pretend they don't exist — but the goal is to supplant mythology
  with archival reality

---

## Section IV: The Archive and Its Challenges

### Why No Serious History Before

- Until recently, access to Rothschild archives was extremely restricted
- **Frankfurt archive** — largely destroyed in 1912 (including Naples papers),
  with only a few early documents sent to Paris
- **Vienna archive** — confiscated by Nazis in 1938, passed to Soviets, buried
  in KGB "trophy" archive until 1990 when it became available at the **Centre
  for the Preservation of Historical Documents**
- **Count Corti's** two-volume study (1927-8) had to rely on Austrian state
  archives and published political memoirs
- **London archive** not open to scholars before 1978
- **French archive** — deposited in Archives Nationales after nationalization
  of Banque Rothschild in 1981; basis of **Bertrand Gille's** two-volume study
  (1960s)

### The Private Letters (XI/109 Series)

- The most important source: the **"private letters"** between banking partners,
  1812-1898, filling **135 boxes** — Ferguson consulted ~5,000; full database
  contains ~13,000 entries
- Nature of the letters: mingled political intelligence, financial information,
  business enquiries, family gossip — "the telephone calls of the
  nineteenth-century"
- No rival banking archive contains a comparable series — the Rothschilds'
  geographic dispersion was unique among competitors
- **James** in the 1840s could see King Louis Philippe "daily"; his letters to
  London are "one of the most remarkable sources for nineteenth-century
  financial and diplomatic history"
- Gaps: substantial unexplained gap 1854-60; outgoing letters *from* London
  partners mostly destroyed on orders of senior partners; first Lord Rothschild
  ordered all his private correspondence burned after death
- Result: the history reads somewhat from the continental brothers' perspective
  — Nathan's voice is frustratingly sparse compared to his brothers'

### The Judendeutsch Problem

- Until the late 1860s, second-generation partners (and some third-generation)
  corresponded primarily in **Judendeutsch** — German written in Hebrew
  characters
- Reasons: (1) it was the family's first language; (2) it prevented prying
  eyes from reading private correspondence — a deliberate security measure
- Previous scholars deterred by the archaic script; relied on selective English
  extracts translated by German refugee researchers in the 1950s ("T" files)
- **Mordechai Zucker** translated / read the originals aloud onto tape for
  Ferguson — making available "a 'virgin' historical source of the very first
  importance"
- Because the letters were hard for outsiders to read, partners wrote with
  "more or less complete candour" — frank, sometimes abusive, rarely flattering
  to the monarchs and ministers they dealt with

---

## Section V: Historiographical Debates

- The five Rothschild houses constitute an early **multinational** — illuminates
  how international private partnerships worked before the corporate era
- Relevant to debate on **banks and industrialization**, especially railways
- Sheds light on **British vs. French vs. German banking** differences — the
  Rothschild houses worked similarly but not identically in each country
- New evidence on **European capital export** — contrasts with Hobson/Lenin
  paradigm
- Social history dimension: though partners were exclusively male, Ferguson
  explicitly attends to mothers, wives, and daughters who were often
  influential
- Ferguson's self-assessment: not a "model" theoretical history of banking —
  no formal treatment of asymmetric information or credit rationing — but the
  profit/loss/balance sheet data can now be compared across published bank
  histories

<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

## Preface Conclusion (pp. 61-62)

- Ferguson acknowledges writing as "an atheist from a Calvinist background,"
  trying not to misread the "exceedingly complicated relationship" between
  the Rothschilds and their "co-religionists"
- Book aims to reintegrate economic, social, cultural, political, and
  diplomatic history — finance and diplomacy were inseparable in the
  Rothschilds' own view
- Concedes omissions: book took five years instead of three; prioritized
  documents "hitherto unknown or only partially known"
- Describes the work as "something of a research agenda," especially the
  London archive

---

## Part I: Father and Sons

---

## Chapter 1: "Our Blessed Father": Origins

> *"Yes, my dear fellow, it all amounts to this: in order to do something
> you must be something. We think Dante great, but he had a civilisation of
> centuries behind him; the House of Rothschild is rich but it has required
> more than one generation to attain such wealth. Such things all lie
> deeper than one thinks."*
> — Goethe, October 1828

### The Judengasse: Frankfurt's Jewish Ghetto

- A traveller crossing the **Sachsenhäuser Bridge** to the **Fahrtor Gate**
  in 18th-century Frankfurt encountered the *Judensau* — an officially
  sanctioned obscene public graffito depicting Jews humiliating themselves
  before a sow; alongside it, an image referencing the 1475 "ritual murder"
  of **Simon of Trent**
- These were not private acts of hostility — they were "erected as a public
  monument," symbols of institutionalized anti-Jewish sentiment in a free
  imperial city
- Frankfurt's Jewish community dates to the 12th century; in 1241 more than
  three-quarters were massacred in the **"Battle of the Jews"**
  (*Judenschlacht*); a second pogrom in 1349 blamed Jews for attracting
  the plague
- In 1458 **Emperor Frederick III** confined Jews to a single narrow street:
  the **Judengasse** (Jews' Lane) — a "New Egypt" to its 110 original
  residents
- Judengasse population grew from ~400 (1542) to 1,380 (1610), driven by
  Jewish migration and paralleled by Huguenot arrivals from the Netherlands
- **Fettmilch riots** (named after shopkeeper leader **Vincenz Fettmilch**):
  wholesale looting of the Judengasse; Jews expelled temporarily; imperial
  troops quashed the revolt, hanged its leaders, and marched Jews back —
  status as imperial protégés reaffirmed

### The Stättigkeit: Legal Regime of Oppression

- **Stättigkeit** statute (read annually in the main synagogue) governed
  Jewish life until end of the 18th century:
  - Population capped at **500 families**
  - Weddings rationed to **12 per year**; marriage age fixed at 25
  - No more than **2 outside Jews** allowed to settle per year
  - Jews barred from farming, weapons, spices, wine, grain trade
  - Confined to ghetto every night, Sundays, and Christian festivals
  - Forbidden from parks, inns, coffee houses, cathedral vicinity
  - Required to enter town hall by a back door
  - Had to wear **two concentric yellow rings** (men) and a striped veil
    (women) — until 1726
  - Required a special pass to leave Frankfurt; paid **double the toll**
    of Gentiles; paid a **poll ("body") tax**
  - In court, must swear a special oath invoking "the penalties and
    maledictions which God imposed on the cursed Jews"
  - If a boy in the street cried *"Jud, mach mores!"* ("Jew, do your
    duty!"), the Jew was obliged to doff his hat and step aside

### Physical Conditions of the Ghetto

- The Judengasse was a quarter-mile long and **no more than twelve feet
  wide** (in places less than ten)
- By 1711: **3,024 people** crammed into the lane
- Houses just **8 feet wide**, up to 4 storeys, with an additional row
  behind each front row
- Fires inevitable — major conflagrations in 1711, 1721, and 1774
- Housing scarcity so extreme that a **four-room house** in the Judengasse
  cost as much as Goethe's father paid for his **twenty-room mansion**
  in the Grosse Hirschgraben
- Average mortality 58% **higher** among Jews than Gentiles in the 1780s
- A traveller in 1795: *"most of the people among the Frankfurt Jews, even
  those who are in the blooming years of their life, look like the walking
  dead"*

> *"The lack of space, the dirt, the throng of people, the disagreeable
> accents of the voice—altogether, it made the most unpleasant impression,
> even upon the passer-by who merely looked through the gate."*
> — Goethe, describing the Judengasse

- **Ludwig Börne** (born **Juda Löw Baruch**), who grew up in the lane in
  the 1780s–90s, described it as a "long dark prison, into which the highly
  celebrated light of the eighteenth century has not yet been able to
  penetrate"

### Frankfurt's Resistance to Enlightenment

- Even as other German cities relaxed Jewish restrictions, Frankfurt refused
  to implement **Emperor Joseph II's Edict of Toleration** (1782)
- Confiscated copies of **Ephraim Lessing's** philo-Semitic play
  *Nathan the Wise*
- Jewish petition in 1769 and 1784 to leave the ghetto on Sundays: rejected
  as an attempt "to put themselves on an equal footing with the Christian
  residents"
- A Jewish mathematics teacher granted permission to teach outside the
  ghetto in 1788 — popular outcry forced revocation; a Jewish doctor's
  similar request in 1795 turned down flat
- The real driver: **Gentile business community feared economic competition**
  from an emancipated Jewish population

### Cultural Life of the Judengasse

- Despite conditions, the community was not culturally closed — the culture
  was intensely religious, governed by **Halakha**
- Men summoned to morning and evening worship by the *Schul-Klopper*
  knocking on doors with a hammer
- Education at three *heder* (primary schools) and the *yeshivah*
  (rabbinical college): Torah → Rashi's commentaries → Talmud
- Community maintained its own fire brigade, hospitals, cemetery, and
  voluntary associations for the poor
- **Heinrich Heine** later insisted Frankfurt Jews "spoke nothing but the
  proper language of Frankfurt" — though Mayer Amschel's letters confirm
  rough, often ungrammatical German with Hebrew admixture
- The *Judendeutsch* of Frankfurt was distinct from Yiddish of the Polish
  stetl; no insuperable language barrier with Gentile merchants

### Frankfurt as a Financial Center

- Frankfurt sat at the junction of major trade routes: South German cities
  (Strasbourg, Ulm, Augsburg, Nuremberg) → Hanseatic ports (Hamburg,
  Bremen, Lübeck)
- Its two annual fairs (spring and autumn, medieval origin) drove commerce;
  the enormous variety of European coinage made **money-changing** and
  **bill-broking** (buying/selling IOUs) indispensable
- Frankfurt also served as financial center for the princes, archdukes, and
  electors of the region — Germany's biggest customers — whose courts
  consistently **spent more than they earned**, creating lucrative lending
  opportunities

### The Bethmann Model: Sub-Bonds

- **Simon Moritz** and **Johann Philipp Bethmann** (not Jewish) dominated
  Frankfurt banking before 1800 by importing **"sub-bonds"**
  (*Partialobligationen*) from Amsterdam: large loans subdivided into
  manageable portions for a broad investor base
- Example: 1778 loan of 20,000 gulden to the Holy Roman Emperor, sold as
  twenty 1,000-gulden bonds; between 1754–1778 the Bethmanns floated nearly
  **2 million gulden** in loans; in the following five years, 54 separate
  loans totalling **30 million gulden**
- The non-Jewish banker **Jakob Friedrich Gontard** was another notable
  participant

### Why Jews Dominated Money-Changing

- By the late 18th century, Jews were seen as the most enterprising
  operators in money-changing and lending — but the historical reason
  remains contested
- Ferguson's view: the **least unsatisfactory answer** is that most fields
  of economic activity were closed to Jews, forcing concentration on
  commerce and finance — and their Gentile rivals often **exaggerated** the
  "Jewish threat"
- Non-Jewish Frankfurt bankers complained as early as 1685 that "the Jews
  had torn the bills trade from their hands" — leading to a ban on Jews
  entering the stock exchange
- **Max Weber's** contrast of "Protestant ethic" vs. Jewish "pariah
  capitalism" is dismissed as unconvincing
- **Joseph Süss-Oppenheimer** (*Jud Süss*): the most notorious court Jew —
  rose to *Hoffaktor* and privy councillor under Duke Karl Alexander of
  Württemberg, executed 1737 for "wielding excessive political power";
  became the centerpiece of later anti-Semitic legend
- By mid-18th century, Frankfurt Jews were acting as court agents for the
  Palatinate, Mainz, Hesse-Darmstadt, Prussia, Vienna, Hesse-Kassel,
  and Saxe-Weimar — a privileged elite within the Judengasse

---

### Mayer Amschel Rothschild: Origins

- **Mayer Amschel Rothschild** born 1743 or 1744 in the Judengasse
- The name "Rothschild" (literally "red shield") was nearly accidental:
  ancestor **Isak** built a house known as "zum roten Schild" in the 1560s;
  his grandson **Naftali Herz** moved to "zur Hinterpfann" ("the warming
  pan") — descendants used both "Rothschild" and "Bauer" for generations
  before "Rothschild" solidified as a surname in Mayer Amschel's generation
- Early Rothschilds: pious, moderately successful small businessmen in
  cloth; great-grandfather **Kalman** a money-changer also dealing in wool
  and silk; grandfather **Moses** married daughters of a tax collector and
  a doctor — steady social ascent
- Mayer Amschel's father **Amschel Moses**: a studious Torah observer;
  family still living in the modest Hinterpfann house (ground-floor office,
  first-floor kitchen, cramped bedrooms) — at best consolidation, at worst
  stagnation

### Early Life: Rabbinical School and Apprenticeship

- Amschel Moses sent Mayer Amschel to rabbinical school at **Fürth** — not
  to train him for the rabbinate (as some historians assumed), but as a
  pious obligation; biographer **Cohen** confirms he "studied his religion
  in order to be a good Jew"
- Parents died of epidemic in **1755 and 1756** — Mayer Amschel was just
  **twelve years old**
- Rather than rejoining siblings (sister Gutelche, brothers Moses and
  Kalman), he was sent to **Hanover** to learn business at the firm of
  **Wolf Jakob Oppenheim** — a business associate of his father's
- This brought Mayer Amschel into direct contact with the world of
  **court agents** for the first time; the Oppenheims had deep court
  connections (grandfather Samuel had been court agent to the Austrian
  Emperor)

### The Coin Business and Prince William

- In Hanover, Mayer Amschel became a dealer in **rare coins and medals** —
  a business whose clients were almost invariably **aristocratic collectors**
- Mastered **Samuel Maddai's** complex system of numismatic classification,
  indispensable for credibility with elite clients
- Returned to Frankfurt c. **1764** when residency laws required it; within
  a year sold rare medals to **William, Hereditary Prince of Hesse-Kassel**
- First recorded transaction with William: June 1765, as the "Jew Meyer" —
  just **38 gulden and 30 kreuzers**; a trifling sum, one of many small
  purchases as William built his medal/coin collection
- This was enough to justify a request for the title of **court agent**,
  granted September **1769**

### Marriage as Strategic Alliance

- August **1770** (age 26): married **Gutle**, the sixteen-year-old daughter
  of **Wolf Salomon Schnapper**, court agent to the Prince of Saxe-Meiningen
- The match brought **2,400 gulden** in dowry — vital new capital
- Marriage as the **first in a succession of carefully calculated Rothschild
  marriages** — kinship networks as important as royal patronage

### The Antique and Coin Business (1770s–1780s)

- Initially in partnership with brother **Kalman** (until Kalman's death
  in 1782), Mayer Amschel became Frankfurt's leading dealer in coins,
  medals, and antiques
- Meticulous **catalogues** circulated to widening aristocratic clientele;
  by the 1780s: ancient Greek and Roman coins, German coins, carved figures,
  precious stones, "curiosities" — total catalogue value 2,500–5,000 gulden
- Prince William did not become a regular customer until **1790**; clients
  also included Goethe's patron, the **Duke of Weimar**
- Mayer Amschel's income in the 1770s: inferred from his *Maaserbuch*
  (tithe book recording one-tenth of income as charitable donations under
  Jewish law) at around **2,400 gulden annually** — comparable to the
  Goethe family income, more than a local tax assessor (*Schultheiss*)

### Wealth Accumulation and the Move to Banking

- 1783: sold share of Hinterpfann house and bought larger house,
  "**zum grünen Schild**" ("the green shield") for **11,000 gulden** —
  only 14 feet wide, with beds placed along side-walls due to room
  narrowness; sons later recalled sleeping "all in one little attic room"
- By mid-1780s, estimated total wealth: **150,000 gulden** (~£15,000)
- **Gutle Rothschild** gave birth nearly every year 1771–1792; of ~19
  children, **ten survived**:
  Schönche (1771), Amschel Mayer (1773), Salomon Mayer (1774),
  **Nathan Mayer** (1777), Isabella/Betty (1781), Breunle/Babette (1784),
  Kalman/Carl (1788), Gotton/Julie (1790), Jettchen/Henrietta (1791),
  **Jakob/James** (1792)

### Transition to Banking (1790s)

- Banking emerged naturally from antique-dealing: extending credit to
  suppliers and customers; coin business brought contact with the
  **Hessian mint**
- 1790: Mayer Amschel listed as creditor of **Joseph Cassel** of Deutz for
  365 gulden
- 1794: offered to sell silver to the **Hessian war treasury** "at the best
  possible price"
- The 1790s were a **real break** — rapid wealth growth:
  - 1795: taxable wealth doubled to 4,000 gulden
  - 1796: moved into the top tax bracket (property >15,000 gulden)
  - Same year: listed as **tenth richest man** in the Judengasse with
    taxable wealth over **60,000 gulden**
  - By 1800: Rothschilds among the **eleven richest families** in the
    Judengasse
- Hired multilingual accountant **Seligmann Geisenheimer** from Bingen
- Dowries as evidence of prosperity: eldest daughter married **Benedikt
  Moses Worms** (1795) with 5,000 gulden dowry plus 10,000 legacy;
  eldest son **Amschel Mayer** married **Eva Hanau** (1796) with a
  **30,000 gulden share** of the business

### The 1797 Balance Sheet: First Known Snapshot

- First known balance sheet of **M. A. Rothschild's firm**: summer 1797,
  discovered in the Moscow "trophy" archive (captured WWII documents)
- **Total assets**: 471,221 Reichsthaler = **843,485 gulden**
- **Total liabilities**: 734,981 gulden
- **Net capital**: 108,504 gulden (~£10,000) — in Mayer Amschel's words:
  *"the balance of my capital, praise God"* (*"Saldo meines Vermögens,
  Gott lob"*)
- Assets: state bonds of various sorts, personal loans and credits to a
  widely dispersed range of firms (family home excluded — capital meant
  the firm's capital)
- The geographic range of credit network: Kassel, Hanau, Hamburg, Bremen,
  Regensburg, Augsburg, Leipzig, Berlin, Vienna, **Amsterdam, Paris,
  and London**
- Creditors/debtors included eminent Gentile firms: **Bethmanns,
  de Neufvilles, Brentanos** (to whom he owed a good deal); art collector
  **Johann Friedrich Städel** had deposits of 17,600 gulden
- Hesse-Kassel government owed **24,093 gulden**; two Hessian officials —
  **Louis Harnier** and **Karl Buderus** — appear as creditors in their
  own right (significant for later dealings)
- Key finding: by 1797 Mayer Amschel was already **far more international**
  as a merchant banker than previously realized

### The Liebmann Embezzlement: Growing Pains

- 1797: junior employee **Hirsch Liebmann** (three years with the firm)
  stole **1,500–2,000 gold carolins** (~30,000 gulden) virtually under
  Mayer Amschel's nose — revealing the chaotic state of his rapidly
  expanding business
- Three systemic failures exposed:
  1. Liebmann was allowed to trade on his own account (wages: 1.5 gulden/
     month after rent) — supplementary dealing normalized, making excess
     wealth unremarkable
  2. **No safe for valuables**; office cupboard left open during business
     hours; employees and clients came and went freely
  3. **Bookkeeping woefully primitive**: when charges were laid, Mayer
     Amschel had virtually no documents proving how much had been stolen
- Discovered only when a local broker appeared claiming to buy "seed" —
  actually purchasing an Austrian bill worth 1,220 gulden that Liebmann
  had offered to sell; Liebmann had been sending money to his notoriously
  poor parents in Bockenheim (who suddenly could afford a 500 gulden dowry)
- When arrested: eight thaler coins, an imperial treasury note, silver
  spoons, a gold salt pot, a gold mug, and seven medals found on him
- Liebmann's father offered to return 1,000 gulden plus 500 more if
  Rothschild would drop charges — damning admission of guilt

<!-- pp. 81-100 -->

## Chapter 1 (cont.): The Dual Revolution

### The French Revolution and Frankfurt Jews

- By 1797, Mayer Amschel's business was so large that bags of coins
  were literally left lying on the floor and in cupboards — he told
  a court he always had large amounts of cash due to "extensive
  business dealings"
- **Friedrich von Gentz** (*Biographical Notes on the House of
  Rothschild*): praised Mayer Amschel's acumen but noted "the most
  outstanding personal qualities may sometimes require exceptional
  circumstances and world-shattering events to come to fruition"
- French troops briefly occupied Frankfurt in October 1792 — ten
  weeks after coronation of the last Holy Roman Emperor,
  **Francis II**
- Frankfurt Jews were not particularly pleased by French incursion;
  French bombardment after the Battle of Lodi (June 1796) destroyed
  nearly half the houses in the **Judengasse**
- Paradox: destruction of the Judengasse forced Frankfurt Senate to
  relax residence restrictions — ~2,000 displaced Jews allowed to
  live outside ghetto (temporary, 6 months)
  - This allowed Mayer Amschel to rent a warehouse on the
    **Schnurgasse**, expanding his operations
- War also created profitable supply contracts: Mayer Amschel and
  partners **Wolf Loeb Schott** and **Beer Nehm Rindskopf** secured
  a contract to supply the Austrian army with grain and cash in the
  Rhine-Main region
- **Geisenheimer** (Mayer Amschel's bookkeeper) benefited from
  improved Jewish legal status in the Rhineland under French
  annexation

### The British Industrial Revolution and Textiles

- The **British Industrial Revolution** — especially the mechanized
  cotton spinning and weaving in **Lancashire** — was equally
  transformative for Mayer Amschel's business
- German demand for cheap British cloth (shawls, muslins, velveteens,
  gauzes, muslinettes, etc.) grew rapidly in the 1790s
- ~15 Jewish firms in Frankfurt alone were importing English textiles
  by 1800; between 1799–1803 no fewer than **eight German merchants**
  settled in Manchester as permanent agents
- This is the commercial context for Mayer Amschel's decision to send
  his third son **Nathan** to England

### Nathan's Arrival in England

- Precise date disputed: most historians opted for 1798, but Ferguson
  argues **Nathan first arrived in Manchester in 1799**, not 1800
  - First documentary evidence from England: letter dated May 29,
    1800 requesting lodgings; another from London address
    (37 Cornhill) dated August 15, 1800
  - Nathan's own later letters explicitly state he first came to
    Manchester "the year before" (i.e. 1799)
  - Most likely: crossed Channel 1798, spent months in London,
    proceeded north ~1799

### Nathan's Famous Account of Why He Left Frankfurt

> "There was not room enough for all of us in that city. I dealt in
> English goods. One great trader came there who had the market to
> himself: he was quite the great man, and did us a favour if he
> sold us goods. Somehow I offended him, and he refused to show me
> his patterns. This was on a Tuesday; I said to my father, 'I will
> go to England.' I could speak nothing but German. On the Thursday
> I started . . ."
— Nathan Rothschild, recounting to MP **Thomas Fowell Buxton**, 1834

- Ferguson: this retrospective account was misleading — Nathan was
  romanticizing a rags-to-riches story; the claim his father gave
  him **£20,000** (roughly double the firm's 1797 net assets) on a
  youthful whim is implausible
- The archives are unequivocal: **Nathan initially operated as
  Mayer Amschel's agent**, not independently
  - Elder brother **Salomon** was sent to assist him in 1801
  - Nathan's early letters are signed "pp. Meyer Amschel Rothschild"
  - Cloth chests Nathan sent to the continent bore the insignia
    **"MAR"** (Mayer Amschel Rothschild)
  - Only gradually did Nathan begin trading on his own account

### Nathan's Manchester Business: Methods and Mechanics

- Nathan arrived with orders for British textiles from his father;
  placed orders with manufacturers from Manchester, Nottingham,
  Leeds, Stockport, and Glasgow
- **Key strategy**: pay suppliers in cash ("present bill terms")
  by drawing on London bankers at 3 months' credit, which let him
  buy cloth **15–20% cheaper** than rivals paying on credit
  - Weavers from twenty miles around Manchester sold at two–six
    months' credit, but cash buyers could get steep discounts
- Thin margins as competitive weapon: Nathan charged only **5% on
  cost price** for cash warehouse sales, as low as **9%** for goods
  sent to the continent — far below the industry norm of ~20%
- Continental customers paid in bills due three months after
  shipment, meaning Nathan was often out of pocket for five or six
  months before collecting
- Nathan's business principle:

> ". . . the nearer I got to England, the cheaper goods were. As
> soon as I got to Manchester, I laid out all my money, things were
> so cheap; and I made good profit. I soon found that there were
> three profits—the raw material, the dyeing, and the manufacturing.
> I said to the manufacturer, 'I will supply you with material and
> dye, and you will supply me with manufactured goods.' So I got
> three profits instead of one . . . My success all turned on one
> maxim. I said: I can do what another man can, and so I am a match
> for the man with the patterns . . . I was an off-hand man. I made
> a bargain at once."
— Nathan Rothschild to Thomas Fowell Buxton

- By 1804, Nathan granted letters of denization; owned a house in
  Downing Street, Ardwick (prosperous district), and a warehouse
  on Brown Street
- By 1808: "large and commodious" warehouse + "spacious, modern and
  well built" town house at **25 Mosley Street**, "the most elegant
  street in Manchester"
- Gross sales ~£800,000 over 1800–1811; estimated profit ~£40,000
  as textile merchant (at 5% margins)

### Nathan's Character: Aggression and Business Relations

- **Mayer Amschel's letters** reveal a recurring problem: Nathan was
  chronically disorganized — wrong chest numbers on consignments,
  no systematic records, careless bookkeeping
- Key letter from Mayer Amschel (one of the few surviving private
  letters):

> "[A]ll our correspondents complain about you, dear Nathan, and say
> that you are so disorganised when sending consignments . . . if
> you are so disorganised and don't have someone or a friend with
> you, then you will be swindled. What is the good of that?
> Everyone can be a millionaire if they get the [right] opportunity
> . . . I already complained in Frankfurt about your extraordinary
> expenditures and disorganisation, dear Nathan; I don't like it."

> "I have seen the orderly way in which Heckscher and the merchant
> Baresch despatch and return consignments . . . without good order
> a millionaire can go broke the more business he does, because
> the whole world is not, or not very, honest. When people see that
> you are not orderly in your despatching, they will do business
> with you only in order to cheat you."

- The same haranguing style was inherited by Mayer Amschel's elder
  sons Amschel and Salomon — a family trait
- Despite (or because of) these friction points, the archival record
  shows **Nathan was subordinate to his father's authority** until
  well into the Manchester period: he was just one of five sons
  within a patriarchal family firm

- Nathan's combative personality was vivid in his correspondence:
  - To slow Scottish manufacturers: threatened to pull all commissions
  - Accused French buyer of "chicanery"
  - When Hamburg banker **Behrens** called him "a great rascal,"
    Nathan had threatened him with his wealth; Behrens shot back:
    "Do you fancy that you might frighten me because of your money?
    I have as much as you have and I am not even living in England."
  - To the London merchant who accused him of dealing with "swindling
    houses": "I can prove to anyone that I never made a bad debt or
    lost a single penny thro' any of my friends being insolvent."

### The Napoleonic Blockade and Smuggling

- Nathan's textile turnover data (1801–1811) shows volatile boom-bust
  cycles driven by war disruptions
- Good period 1804–1805 followed by nearly two years of low turnover
- **Berlin Decree** (November 1806) — Napoleon banned all British
  imports to French-controlled territories — merely sealed an already
  collapsing market
  - As early as November 1805: "The present time is the most
    critical and the most unhappy for the Continent . . . no trade
    whatsoever, the market overstocked with goods [and] no debts
    coming in"
  - At least three of Nathan's continental correspondents collapsed
    in early 1806 before the formal blockade
- Nathan responded by becoming **a smuggler**:
  - October 1807: shipped coffee to Sweden via Amsterdam using
    American-registered ships and **fake Dutch documents**
  - Favored contraband routes: Heligoland and the Baltic ports
  - Such shipments could not legally be insured — risks were enormous
- By 1808 Nathan was known for getting "goods to the Continent" with
  "superior management, judgement, foresight and connections" —
  though "not a word was passed about . . . *how* the goods had
  been sent"
- September 1809: large shipment to Riga seized, released only via
  bribery ("a heavy tax indeed it was"); another cargo seized at
  Königsberg

### The Edict of Fontainebleau and the End of Commodity Trade

- **October 14, 1810**: Napoleon published the **Edict of
  Fontainebleau** — ordered confiscation of all English and colonial
  goods smuggled into French-controlled territory
- Two infantry regiments occupied Frankfurt; 234 firms raided based
  on reports by spy **Thiard**
- **Mayer Amschel** caught with 60,000 gulden of contraband (~half
  indigo from Nathan); Trianon tariff levied retroactively — fine of
  nearly 20,000 francs; all seized goods (~100,000 gulden total)
  publicly burnt
- Mayer Amschel escaped relatively lightly: the Bethmanns paid over
  360,000 francs in fines
- This crisis was a **watershed**: commodity trade would henceforth
  play a declining role in Rothschild business
- Nathan had already begun the transition: in **October 1806** he
  married **Hannah**, daughter of **Levi Barent Cohen**, a leading
  London merchant (dowry: £3,248 plus additional capital from his
  father)
  - Marriage gave Nathan a foothold in London's established Jewish
    financial community
  - Cohen encouraged Nathan to expand into Indian and Baltic products
    alongside British textiles — and to make the full pivot to banking

### Nathan's Transition to London Banking

- Nathan had been building credit relationships with London bankers
  throughout his Manchester years: **Lyon de Symons**, **Goldsmid
  & D'Eliason**, **Daniel Mocatta**, and continental bankers
  **Parish & Co.** and the **Schröder brothers**
- 1801: dissatisfied with suppliers, Nathan bought a **copping
  machine from Boulton & Watts** — experimented with manufacturing
  directly
- 1805: partnership with **Nehm Beer Rindskopf** (son of Mayer
  Amschel's associate) diversified into indigo, pearls,
  tortoiseshell, ivory ("colonial goods")
- Gradual shift: increasingly focused attention on the **credit
  transactions** generated by trade rather than the trade itself —
  same trajectory as his father, merchant to merchant banker
- By 1808 he had acquired a London address (12 Great St Helens);
  London ledger books show banking operations by 1810 at the latest
- **July 1811**: Nathan formally announced closure of Manchester
  operations ("Rothschild Brothers") and opened his counting-house
  at **No. 2 New Court, St Swithin's Lane, London**

---

## Chapter 2: The Elector's Treasure

### The Myth of William IX

> "The Old Man . . . made our fortune."
— **Carl Rothschild**

- The family's relationship with **William IX** (Hereditary Prince,
  Landgrave, and from 1803 **Elector/Kurfürst of Hesse-Kassel**)
  became the most celebrated — and most mythologized — episode in
  early Rothschild history
- The "Elector's treasure" story, current since 1826, has been
  accepted uncritically; Ferguson argues the Elector's significance
  has been **exaggerated or at least misunderstood**
- Even Mayer Amschel's own sons believed the Elector relationship
  was "the real foundation of their fortune" — Carl Rothschild's
  quote reflects genuine family belief

### William IX: Character and Wealth

- **William of Hesse-Kassel** was almost exactly Mayer Amschel's
  contemporary; shared his interest in old coins and money-making
  generally
- His father (Landgrave of Hesse-Kassel 1760–1785) converted to
  Catholicism, scandalizing Protestant relatives including
  **George II of England** (his father-in-law)
  - William was effectively removed from his father's care;
    during the Seven Years' War he and brother **Karl** were sent
    to Denmark, coming under Protestant influence of **Frederick V
    of Denmark** (whose daughter William married in 1763)
- Notorious for avarice and prolific illegitimacy: at least
  12 illegitimate children by three mistresses, including 7 by
  Swiss woman **Rosalie Dorothea Ritter**; gave them all grand
  titles (von Hessenstein, von Heimrodt, von Haynau)

### Hesse-Kassel's Wealth: The Mercenary Army Business

- Hesse-Kassel was unusually rich for an 18th-century German
  principality: **30–40 million gulden** at William's accession
- Wealth accumulated primarily by **selling Hessian troops** to
  the highest bidder — usually Britain
- The **mercenary army trade** reached its zenith during the
  **American War of Independence**: William sold a regiment of
  ~2,000 men from Hanau to fight for George III against the
  colonists
  - Terms: **76 gulden (~£7) per man**, plus 25 gulden per man
    wounded, 76 gulden per man killed
  - Payment came in **non-interest-bearing bills of exchange**
    credited to William's account at London bank **Van Notten & Son**
  - William sold these bills to German brokers before maturity to
    convert to cash, then reinvested at maximum interest
- The state's assets were effectively indistinguishable from
  William's personal wealth — no political restrictions on his
  disposal of it
- Despite building **Wilhelmshöhe** palace, William's overriding
  object was to invest earnings at the highest possible yield

<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

## Chapter 3 (cont.): Mayer Amschel's Rise — Hesse-Kassel and the Elector

### Hesse-Kassel as a Bank-State

- **William of Hesse-Kassel**'s finances resembled a large bank more than a state:
  - **Kammerkasse** (Exchequer): regular revenues from royal estates and indirect taxes
  - **Kriegskasse** (War Chest): funded by property taxes, mercenary hiring,
    and investment interest
- Total assets in 1806: **46 million gulden** (>£4 million)
  - 28.8 million: loans to other German princes
    (Duke of Mecklenburg-Strelitz, Prince of Lippe-Detmold)
  - 4.6 million: invested in English annuities
  - Net income after expenditures: ~**900,000 gulden/year**
- Contemporary view that William was one of Europe's richest "capitalists" was
  not far wrong — hence his magnetic attraction to ambitious bankers like
  Mayer Amschel

### Mayer Amschel's Slow Climb into William's Business

- Still a "nobody" when the new Landgrave moved to Kassel in 1785
- By 1789 managed to enter the English bills market at Kassel —
  only by offering to **pay more** than established local firms
- Initially granted only £800 credit; rival broker **Feidel David** had £25,000
- Requested £10,000; received only £2,000

### Karl Friedrich Buderus — The Inside Man

- **Karl Friedrich Buderus**: began as tutor to William's illegitimate children
  by Dorothea Ritter; moved into financial administration at Hanau (1783),
  then to Kassel to work the all-important War Chest (1792)
- A classic Rothschild "instrumental friendship based on mutual advantage"
- **First co-operation, 1794**: Buderus recommended Mayer Amschel be allowed
  to join five firms bidding for £150,000 of English bills — ignored
- **1796 breakthrough**: Two Gentile firms (Rüppell & Harnier, Preye & Jordis)
  offered 1 million gulden of Frankfurt bonds to the War Chest; Chest bought
  900,000. Buderus tipped off Mayer Amschel to offer the remaining 100,000
  at **97.5% of face value** vs. rivals' 98% — a loss-leader that secured the
  crucial foothold
- By 1798 most of the £37,000 in English bills passed through Mayer Amschel
- 1801–1806: involved in at least **eleven major loans** for William
  (Denmark, Hesse-Darmstadt, Baden, Order of St John)
  plus real estate purchases and continued medal supply

### Squeezing Out Rivals — The Danish Loans

- 1800–1801: Mayer Amschel content to take a share alongside
  Rüppell & Harnier and Bethmanns
- By ~1804: established effective **monopoly of Danish business**
  via "douceurs" and discounts to the penny-pinching William, plus
  relationship with Hamburg banker **J. D. Lawätz** (mediator
  between Kassel and Copenhagen)
- Total Danish bonds sold to William: at least **4.5 million gulden** (~£450,000)
- Loans to Hesse-Darmstadt: **1.3 million gulden**; Baden: **1.4 million gulden**
- In 1806 Rüppell & Harnier complained bitterly that "Jewish commercial rivals"
  believed "the name Rothschild" carried more credit in Hesse-Kassel than the
  Danish government itself

### Anti-Rothschild Backlash — Even from the Jewish Community

- 1802: Kassel Jewish community complained Mayer Amschel was effectively
  residing in Kassel without "protected Jew" tax status
- Forced to pay **180 gulden** for exemption, then sought protected status for
  his eldest son Amschel
- His application: with "wonderful insincerity," claimed a Rothschild presence
  "would not impair local merchants" and would benefit bill transactions
  through competition — permit not actually issued until June 1806

### Mayer Amschel's Real Role: Stockbroker, Not Banker

- Despite title of senior court agent (**Oberhofagent**, 1803), at this stage
  William was the real banker; Mayer Amschel was more a **stockbroker**
  catering to William's preference for bearer bonds over personal loans
- Commission: only **1.75–2%** per bond purchase; total profits from this
  business probably did not exceed 300,000 gulden
- On at least two occasions Mayer Amschel **borrowed from William himself**
- William was most important client but not the only one; goal was to establish
  links with as many princely courts as possible

### Court Agent Titles Collected by 1803

- Order of St John (via an ill-starred loan)
- Prince of Thurn und Taxis (hereditary postmaster of Holy Roman Empire)
- Landgrave of Hesse-Darmstadt
- Karl Friedrich Ludwig Moritz zu Isenburg, Count of Büdingen
- **Most prestigious (1800)**: imperial court agent from the Austrian Emperor —
  in return for supplying war matériel and collecting interest on the Emperor's
  borrowings from Hesse-Kassel
- Only failure: Bavaria ignored his 1802 application

> "The importance of such titles should not be exaggerated... the whole system
> of petty principalities... was on the brink of an unprecedented and
> revolutionary upheaval." — Ferguson

- Up to 1806 Rothschilds depended on princely patrons; thereafter William
  increasingly depended on Mayer Amschel

---

## The Origins of a Myth

### Napoleon's Occupation and William's Flight

- War resumed between England and France in 1803; William too committed to
  England to join the sixteen German states forming the Francophile
  **Confederation of the Rhine** (summer 1806)
- William had lent money to Austria and Prussia — badly exposed when
  **Prussian army defeated at Jena and Auerstadt** (autumn 1806)
- Desperate last moves: demobilised troops, requested to join Rhine
  Confederation, posted signs "Electorat de Hesse: Pays Neutre" —
  none deflected Napoleon
- Napoleon: "My object is to remove the House of Hesse-Kassel from rulership
  and to strike it out of the list of powers"
- William fled to brother's estate at Gottorp in Holstein (Danish territory)
- **November 2**: General Lagrange occupied Kassel as Governor-General,
  formally confiscating all William's assets and threatening trial by
  military tribunal for anyone concealing them

### The Buried Treasure Legend

- The famous story: at this critical moment William entrusted the entirety of
  his movable wealth to Mayer Amschel, who buried it in his garden while the
  French army entered Frankfurt — then returned it in full, refusing any
  interest as a reward for his faithfulness
- Story first appeared in 1827 in F. A. Brockhaus's
  **General German Encyclopaedia for the Educated Classes**
- Originally promoted by the Rothschilds themselves to illustrate **exceptional
  probity as deposit-holders**; commissioned two paintings by **Moritz Daniel
  Oppenheim** on the subject (1861)
- Later nineteenth century: acquired anti-Semitic reading — the Elector's money
  was "blood money" from mercenary sales; Mayer Amschel exploited rather than
  preserved it
- Positive/negative versions vividly juxtaposed in American film
  *The House of Rothschild* (1934) and Nazi film *Die Rothschilds* (1940)

### What Actually Happened

- **The story is fiction** — though with a tiny grain of truth
- William's property was widely dispersed; only **a few relatively unimportant
  items** came into Mayer Amschel's direct possession
- Most important valuables (bonds, without their coupons) were smuggled out by
  **Buderus**, who made a hazardous trip through French lines to Itzehoe in
  early November
- The bulk stored in caches at William's country houses:
  - **Wilhelmshöhe**: 24 chests (securities, coupons, accounts, silverware)
    hidden under the north-wing stairs; another 24 in another part of palace
  - **Löwenburg cellar**: 24 chests (securities belonging to Elector's mistress,
    official papers, porcelain, clothes)
  - **Sababurg hunting lodge**: 47 chests of silverware
- General **Lagrange** bribed with **260,000 francs** to allow 42 chests to be
  spirited away; night of November 8, convoy of carts delivered freed chests
  to Hof Stölzingen
- Documents distributed: Lennep took London investment papers back to Kassel;
  10 chests deposited with Thorbecke of Münden; 19 smuggled into Frankfurt with
  **Preye & Jordis**
- Lagrange realised he had undercharged; extorted more — agreed to understate
  total Elector assets. "Official" French inventory: **19.8 million gulden**
  (vs. actual ~27 million gulden kept off the books)
- The **four chests given to Mayer Amschel** contained only routine War Chest
  and Privy Purse papers; a few others with medals and bonds briefly left in
  his care in Hamburg

### Nathan and the English Consols — The Real Story

> "The Prince of Hesse-Cassel . . . gave my father his money; there was no time
> to be lost; he sent it to me. I had 600,000£ arrive unexpectedly by the post;
> and I put it to such good use, that the prince made me a present of all his
> wine and his linen." — Nathan Rothschild

- At start of exile William already had massive English portfolio:
  - **£635,400 in annuities** paying £20,426/year interest
  - **~£200,000 owed** by the Prince of Wales and his brothers (characteristically
    in arrears)
  - **£100,150 in English subsidies** received 1807–1810
- Critical question: what to do with the accumulating interest and subsidies
  held in William's current account with Van Notten in London
- As early as 1807, Nathan approached William's envoy **Lorentz** with investment
  suggestions — rebuffed at the Elector's express instruction
- 1809 (at Buderus's prompting): Mayer Amschel instructed to purchase **3%
  consols** (redeemable state annuities) — first purchase: face value £150,000
  at 73.5 (i.e., 73.5% of redemption price)
- **Nine such purchases** through end of 1813, totalling **£664,850** in consols

### How the Consols Deal Actually Enriched the Rothschilds

- Surface: only one-eighth of 1% brokerage — not much
- Reality: **William did not put up all cash at once** — Rothschilds effectively
  bought consols with largely borrowed money on his behalf
- Profit mechanism: difference between price/exchange rate agreed with William
  and the actual price/rate Nathan paid in London
  - First three purchases: difference of order of **2%** (consols falling as
    Britain's campaign against Napoleon was at low ebb)
  - Probable additional benefit from exchange rate differences (gulden/sterling)
- When consols hit low of **62.5** in summer 1811, William halted new purchases
  and stopped remitting — but this suited Rothschilds since consols remained
  **registered in Nathan's name** until fully paid (as late as March 1813,
  face value £121,000 nominally "Nathan's")
- Carl (1814): "the Old Man [William] had made our fortune. If Nathan had not
  had the Elector's £300,000 [sic] in hand he would have got nowhere"
- Key insight: gave Nathan a **"security"** — impression of capital resources
  far exceeding what the family actually had, allowing him to draw war bills
  of £132,000 and handle large business he could not otherwise have managed
- Amschel (1818): "Up to then Nathan did not even know what stocks looked like"

---

## French Surveillance and Rothschild Counter-Measures

### The Risks Were Real

- **Berlin Convention of 1808**: Napoleon invited Elector's debtors to settle
  with French authorities instead — offering debt reductions
- Mayer Amschel's offices searched by French police (as were Preye & Jordis)
- **August 1808**: Salomon interrogated by French police as representative of
  bank suspected of acting for William
- September 1808: Buderus and Lennep briefly arrested
- Summer 1809 (after minor anti-French revolt): **Savagner**, Special
  Commissioner of Police in Westphalia, arrested Buderus and Lennep again,
  then conducted bizarre interrogation of Mayer Amschel himself

### The Interrogation

- Savagner well-informed: knew of Mayer Amschel's Hamburg and Itzehoe visits,
  dealings with Buderus, role as Elector's court agent
- Mayer Amschel's defense: claimed "painful illness" had given him "a short
  memory"; denied knowledge of most transactions
- Gutle (his wife) played the embodiment of "feminine innocence": "She knew
  about nothing at all, she was at home throughout the year and had nothing
  whatever to do with business. She had never seen [Buderus], she only
  concerned herself with her housework."
- Savagner ultimately admitted defeat — like most Napoleonic officials he
  encountered, settled for a small "loan"

### The Secret Code System (from mid-1808)

- Correspondence relayed via Buderus and Lawätz, written in **crude code**:
  - Buderus = "Baron von Waldschmidt"
  - Knatz = "Johann Weber"
  - Mayer Amschel = "Peter Arnoldi" or "Arnold"
  - William = "Herr von Goldstein," "Johannes Adler," or "the Principal"
  - English investments = "**stock fish**" (pun on *Stockfisch*, German for cod)
- Letters sent not to Mayer Amschel but to **Juda Sichel** (whose son Bernhard
  had married Isabella Rothschild in 1802)
- When Carl and Amschel visited William in Prague: correspondence hidden in
  **secret compartments**; sometimes letters transliterated into
  **Hebrew characters**
- Almost certainly **two sets of books** kept — one complete, one doctored for
  authorities
- French police intercepted at least one letter in 1811

### Austrian Surveillance

- Even in Austrian territory (Prague), Rothschild moves monitored
- Austrian police report described Mayer Amschel as heading "an important
  propaganda scheme in favour of the Elector" — exaggerated inference from
  his constant presence at the Elector's quarters with War Secretary Knatz

### Dalberg — Playing Both Sides

- 1810: Frankfurt became a grand duchy under **Baron Karl Theodor Anton von
  Dalberg** (erstwhile Archbishop of Mainz; since 1806 Prince-Primate of the
  Rhenish Confederation)
- Mayer Amschel had already ingratiated himself with Dalberg via loan
- Facilitated **440,000 gulden** payment to secure **emancipation of Frankfurt Jews**
  by discounting bonds worth 290,000 gulden
- Advanced Dalberg **80,000 gulden** for his journey to Paris for Napoleon's
  son's baptism
- Formally became Dalberg's **"court banker"**; appointed to electoral college
  of new département of Hanau alongside Gentiles like Simon Moritz von Bethmann

> The startling symmetry: Mayer Amschel had arranged 620,000 gulden payments
> from the Elector to Austria to fund troops fighting France in 1809 —
> and shortly after his death, his son Amschel was advancing 255,000 gulden
> to Dalberg partly to purchase horses for the French army.

- **Classic Rothschild gambit**: back both sides. Double agents always risk
  forfeiting trust of both if exposed — the loser, whichever wins
- This dynamic drove Mayer Amschel's "penchant for secrecy" —
  one of his most enduring bequests to later generations

### William's Paranoia and Buderus's Conflict of Interest

- Despite all the risks, Rothschilds were never wholly trusted by William
- William suspected Mayer Amschel was swindling interest on his English stocks;
  accused him of hanging onto valuables left in Hamburg
- **Buderus** provided reassurances to William:

> "the most punctual payment which one can expect of him, the certainty that
> he always reckons by the official exchange rate on the day of a transaction,
> the conviction that he never discloses Your Majesty's transactions to anyone,
> as he has handled the realisation [of your assets] with such care that French
> officials who were sent to interrogate him . . . could find no trace of the
> money in the books which were laid before them." — Buderus to William

- Irony: **Buderus's assurances were far from disinterested**. He had secretly
  entered an agreement with Mayer Amschel making him a **sleeping partner** in
  the Rothschild firm — investing 20,000 gulden in return for advising the firm
  and advancing its interests "to the best of his ability"
- By May 1812, when William requested one of Mayer Amschel's sons move to Prague
  as court agent in exile, he was politely but firmly rebuffed — the Rothschilds
  no longer needed him as they once had

---

## Mayer Amschel's Capital Growth

- 1797 capital: **108,504 gulden** (~£10,000)
- 1807 capital: **514,500 gulden** (~£50,000)
- 1810 capital: **800,000 gulden** (~£80,000)
- Import-export business with Manchester probably more responsible for early
  growth than the William business; but managing William's portfolio drove the
  surge after 1807
- Real significance of Elector's treasure: helped Nathan transition from
  **Manchester merchant to London banker** — once achieved, Rothschilds needed
  "the Old Man" less

---

## Mayer Amschel's Legacy

### The 1810 Partnership Agreement

- **September 1810**: firm became "**Mayer Amschel Rothschild & Sons**"
- Mayer Amschel, Amschel, Salomon, and Carl issued printed circular announcing
  they would act as *wirkliche Theilhaber* (genuine partners) in a new
  *Gesellschaft* (company)
- Capital shares: Mayer Amschel 370,000 / Amschel 185,000 / Salomon 185,000 /
  Carl 30,000 (James to become partner at majority with 30,000)
- Agreement ran for **ten years**; profits divided proportionally to capital
- Key clause: **no partner could engage in business independently** of the others

### Mayer Amschel Retained Absolute Authority

- He alone could withdraw capital during the agreement period
- He alone could hire and fire employees
- Unmarried sons could marry only with his permission
- Still styled *Herr im Haus* (master of the house) — even the mercurial Nathan
  was still having to do as he was told as late as 1805

### The Rule Excluding Women

- Most remarkable clause: upon any partner's death, his widow, children, and
  guardians solemnly renounced any right to contest the surviving partners'
  valuation of the deceased's capital share, and were **denied access to the
  firm's books and correspondence**
- First formal statement of the **exclusion of Rothschild women** (both
  born-Rothschilds and those who married in) from the business core
- Repeated emphatically in Mayer Amschel's deathbed will (1812):

> "I hereby decree and therefore wish that my daughters and sons-in-law and
> their heirs have no share in the capital of the firm 'Mayer Amschel
> Rothschild & Sons' . . . Rather, the said firm shall exclusively belong to
> and be owned by my sons."

- Daughters who contested would forfeit all but their minimal statutory claims
  under the Napoleonic code
- This rule was strictly adhered to for generations

### Mayer Amschel's Death

- Had been seriously ill from ~1808 — possibly rectal abscess from chronic
  haemorrhoids; never fully recovered
- Age 66–67 when 1810 agreement signed
- **September 16, 1812**: taken ill; died three days later
- Hastily revised his will on his deathbed — withdrew only **190,000 gulden**
  as his notional capital share (obvious understatement) to protect the firm

### His Character and Appearance

- Within family: commanding and intimidating patriarch
- To Gentile business partners: conformed to the deferential stereotype of the
  **"court Jew"** — intelligent but deferential
- Modern portrayals (George Arliss, Erich Ponto) exaggerated "Jewishness"
  (long beard, fez, ringlets, skullcap); common nineteenth-century lithograph
  also fictitious
- Contemporaries: "a rather big man, who wore a round unpowdered wig and a
  small goatee beard"; dressed in the manner of a Gentile merchant of his
  generation, "albeit slightly threadbare"
- Religiously: relatively orthodox but not a *maskil* (Jewish Enlightenment
  figure); not a Reform reformer — a "middle way"
- Cohen's memoir: "a zealous believer in the Talmud and chose it alone as the
  guiding principle of all his actions"

### Charitable Character

- Paid his tenth (*tithe*) to the poor of the Jewish community conscientiously
- **Ludwig Börne** remembered the crowd of beggars who waited for Mayer Amschel
  in the street and the patience with which he distributed alms
- Notably extended charity beyond the Jewish community:
  - When a street urchin shouted "Jew!" at him, he calmly paid the boy to shout
    it again, listened "with evident pleasure," and pronounced the Hebrew blessing
    thanking God for giving Israel its laws
- In his will: bequeathed **100 gulden to "three praiseworthy, charitable
  Christian foundations"**
- 1804: played leading role founding the **Philanthropin** school for poorer
  Jewish children — thoroughly secular curriculum
  - Influenced by bookkeeper Geisenheimer and tutor **Michael Hess**
    (follower of Moses Mendelssohn, later school's headmaster)

### Family Correspondence and Firm Structure at Death

- Buderus letter (c. 1811) summarizing firm's reach:
  - Amschel Mayer and Salomon: indispensable in Frankfurt
  - Carl: almost continually travelling for William
  - Nathan: established in London
  - James: between London and Paris

- Family/private correspondence written in **Hebrew characters**;
  business correspondence in German, French, or English by clerks
- Mayer Amschel repeatedly reprimanded Nathan for mixing languages:
  "your Hebrew written letters may be good enough for family purposes, but
  for account and business matters you have to write in German, French, or
  English . . . a good deal of confusion arises"
- In-laws (Schnappers, Sichels, Beyfus brothers) involved in business but
  kept at one remove from management — called "outsiders" (*conceited
  outsiders* who couldn't be taught the indigo business)
- Mayer Amschel's rule followed strictly for over a century: **male
  descendants only** were the inner circle of the firm

<!-- pp. 121-140 -->

## Chapter 2 (continued): Mayer Amschel's Legacy — Jewish Identity, Emancipation, and Paternal Commandments

### Jewish Emancipation and Financial Leverage

- **Mayer Amschel** maintained communal Jewish education at a time many Frankfurt families sent
  children to Gentile schools; **Ludwig Börne** was one who rebelled, eventually converting to
  Christianity rather than endure discrimination
- **Heinrich Heine** recalled admiringly passing the old family home in the Judengasse in 1827,
  seeing **Gutle Rothschild** (Mayer's widow) lighting Chanukkah candles — a symbol of
  unaffected piety even after the family's extraordinary rise

> "When the good lady looks at these little lights, her eyes fill with tears, and she remembers with melancholy joy her younger days when Mayer Amschel Rothschild, of blessed memory, still celebrated the Feast of Lights with her." — Heinrich Heine

- Mayer Amschel's political activism for Jewish rights predated the French Revolution — he was
  one of seven signatories of the 1787 protest about ghetto travel restrictions
- **Dalberg** (Frankfurt's ruler under Napoleon) was cautious on emancipation, fearing he would
  "balance Christian injustice with Jewish impudence"; his 1808 Stättigkeit reimposed the
  ban on Jews living outside the Judengasse and confirmed restrictions on family numbers
- **Key financial leverage move:** Mayer Amschel paid **440,000 gulden** (twenty times the Jews'
  annual "protection" payment) to Dalberg's duchy to compensate for lost tax revenue from
  emancipation — Mayer raised 290,000 by discounting bonds
- December 1811: after further Senate negotiations, Mayer Amschel wrote his son: **"You are now
  a citizen."** The decree on "civil-legal equality of the Jewish community" came into force
  two weeks later
- Ferguson's argument: the Rothschilds were distinctive among successful Jewish families in that
  they refused to abandon Judaism to achieve civic equality — their personal ambition was
  **inseparable from the political campaign for Jewish emancipation across Europe**

### Mayer Amschel's Business Maxims (Passed to Sons)

- Sons repeatedly invoked father's sayings decades after his death — Ferguson calls this
  "unremarked by previous historians" and more revealing of character than any other source

Key aphorisms cited by sons in letters:
- **"A banker has to calculate, there is no merit in making transactions in the dark."**
  (Amschel citing father, 1814, pressing Nathan for market information)
- **"Jewish fortunes as a rule don't keep longer than two generations"** — due to household
  expenses not being controlled, and "Jewish stupidity" (father's blunt warning, 1817)
- **"The evil eye of the court brings fewer advantages than the title of consul or court banker"**
  — warning against seeking ceremonial prestige over real leverage (Salomon, 1818)
- **"With money you become an Excellency"** — on the hollowness of honorifics without wealth
- **"It is better to deal with a government in difficulties than with one that has luck on its
  side."** — the decisive maxim on seeking out weak/needy counterparties
- **"If you can't make yourself loved, make yourself feared."** — James, 1817, on rival firms
- Carl recalled father teaching him to treat even low-influence men as if everything depended
  on them — strategic flattery as relationship-building
- **"Sticking to a man in government"** — Salomon's most-cited favourite; Mayer's principle
  that "if a high-placed person enters into a [financial] partnership with a Jew, he belongs
  to the Jew" ("gehört er dem Juden")

### The Commandment of Fraternal Unity

- Mayer's final deathbed command was to maintain **fraternal unity** — Salomon attributed
  "all our luck to the benediction which our father gave us an hour before he passed away"
- Amschel's version of the deathbed words: **"Keep your brothers together and you will become
  the richest people in Germany."**
- This principle was repeatedly invoked when brothers quarrelled — Salomon reminding Nathan
  after attacks on Carl: "Our blessed father ordered us to live in peace, otherwise we shall
  lose our courage."
- Unity was formally **enshrined in partnership agreements** — the post-Nathan partnership
  agreement (drawn up after Nathan's death) quoted the father's commandment verbatim and
  called for "renewal of mutual dependence" and a "league of brotherly love"

> "Unity was what our blessed father, with his last words, enjoined me to uphold as [our] first and holiest of duties... we owe not only our wealth but also our honourable position in society primarily to the [spirit of] unity and co-operation [that binds together] all our partners, bank houses and establishments." — Amschel Rothschild, 1841

- **Friedrich Gentz** noted in the 1827 *Brockhaus Encyclopaedia* that the first guiding
  principle of the Rothschilds "obliges the five brothers to conduct their combined businesses
  in an uninterrupted community of interest... each operation is carried out according to an
  agreed plan with combined efforts, and each has an equal share in results"
- As late as 1841 — nearly 30 years after Mayer Amschel's death — Amschel was reminding
  partners who had never even met their grandfather of the unity principle; Ferguson calls
  this "a striking testament to the patriarchal power of Mayer Amschel Rothschild"
- The 1827 Brockhaus noted: "Never has a father's last testament been carried out more
  conscientiously and more profitably"

