## Chapter 3: "The Commanding General" (1813–1815)

> "My brother in London is the commanding general, I am his field marshal." — Salomon Rothschild

> "It is an established rule with us that no disapprobation shall be expressed by either of us at the conduct of the other, since as partners we act always for the joint interest and consequently neither of us has the right to blame the other when he has acted for the best." — Salomon Rothschild

### War Finance and Wellington's Cash Crisis

- Core thesis of the chapter: **Nathan Rothschild** became the principal conduit for British
  government war finance to continental battlefields — the decisive step in the family's rise
- Napoleon's maxim: "An army marches on its stomach"; Wellington's version: "To gain your
  objects you must feed." All armies 1793–1815 relied on requisitioning and supply lines,
  but protracted campaigns required cash
- Cicero's maxim applied: ***nervos belli, pecuniam infinitam*** ("the sinews of war are
  infinite money") — or as **Henry Dundas** told William Pitt: "All modern Wars are a
  Contention of Purse"

**Wellington's cash shortfall — the scale:**
- By 1813, Wellington's military chest ran at **~£100,000/month** including subsidies to
  Portugal and Spain
- March 1811: wrote to PM **Lord Liverpool** threatening to halt the campaign entirely for
  lack of cash; officers paid in depreciated paper, lower ranks not paid at all
- February 1813 nadir: Wellington "could scarcely stir out of my house on account of the
  public creditors waiting to demand payment"

**Britain's fiscal position — structural context:**
- Britain had the most efficient financial system of the ancien régime (post-Glorious
  Revolution): centralised tax collection, transparent parliamentary budgeting, funded
  national debt, Bank of England gold convertibility
- Cost of war rose 5x in real terms during Napoleonic Wars vs. a century earlier
- UK public expenditure: **£18m/year → £100m/year** (1793–1815), roughly 16% of national income
- Total war cost with France: **~£830 million**, of which **£59 million** in ally subsidies
- National debt: **£240m (1793) → £900m (1815)**, nearly 200% of national income
- 1797: Bank of England **suspended gold convertibility** → currency depreciation; prices
  roughly doubled in 20 years before 1815
- By 1812 the Iberian market for bills on London was **saturated** — Wellington could only sell
  new bills at prohibitive discounts; "The patriotic gentlemen at Lisbon will give us no money"

### How Nathan Got the Commission: Three Factors

**1. Absence of competition (luck):**
- Before 1810 the City had capable rivals: **Harman & Co.**, **Reid Irving**, **Smith Payne &
  Smith**, and above all **Baring Brothers** — who had previously relayed loans to Portugal
- Other Jewish challengers: **Abraham and Benjamin Goldsmid** (since 1790s); German newcomers
  **Schröder, Brandt, Huth** (post-1802)
- The **crisis of 1810** destroyed the competition: the **Bullion Committee** recommended
  resuming gold payments (against Bank of England advice) → prospect of tight money → slump
  in government stock prices → Barings lost ~**£43,000**; **Abraham Goldsmid** committed
  suicide → "alarm and dismay" in the City
- Simultaneous collapse of the Amsterdam market (Napoleon's annexation of the Netherlands)
  left Barings' continental partner **Hope & Co.** a "mere empty shell"

**2. John Charles Herries as Commissary-in-Chief:**
- **Herries** appointed Commissary-in-Chief October 1811 — Nathan's "Buderus," his key
  government contact
- Herries: son of a minor merchant banker; private secretary to **Nicholas Vansittart**
  (Secretary to the Treasury); served **Spencer Perceval** as Chancellor 1807–9
- Crucially a **Germanophile**: studied in Leipzig; had translated **Friedrich Gentz's**
  anti-French tract *On the State of Europe before and after the French Revolution*
- Personal connection via Leipzig: Herries had allegedly had an illegitimate child by the wife
  of **Baron Limburger**, a Leipzig tobacco merchant — the Limburgers later claimed they had
  introduced Nathan to Herries and sought £30,000–£40,000 commission
- Ferguson's verdict: Limburger was likely a blackmailer exploiting the illegitimate child;
  brothers eventually paid him off with **£15,000** "in a manner more appropriate to
  blackmailers than partners" — but he had served as useful aristocratic go-between

**3. Nathan had a solution — the bullion route:**
- Nathan's own account (retroactively simplified): bought **£800,000 of East India Company gold**
  at auction; the government needed it for Wellington; he undertook to get it to Portugal

> "When I was settled in London, the East India Company had £800,000 worth of gold to sell. I went to the sale, and bought it all... The Government sent for me and said they must have it... I undertook all that and I sent it to France; and that was the best business I ever did." — Nathan Rothschild

**The smuggling operation (reality):**
- Before March 1811 the Rothschilds were already smuggling gold bullion from England to France
  — technically a breach of the **Continental System**, but **tolerated and later licensed
  by Napoleon**, who believed bullion outflows from Britain signalled British weakness
- **James** operated from Gravelines/Dunkirk, exchanging imported guineas for **bills on
  London** (priced low in France), redeemed at profit in London
- A typical April 1812 series: **£27,300 in guineas** sent to James → returned bills from
  Paris bankers (**Hottinguer, Davillier, Faber, Morell**) with face value **£65,798**
- Code system: Nathan = **"Langbein"**; London = **"Jerusalem"**; bullion transfers = **"Rabbi
  Moses"** or **"Rabbi Mosche"**; shipments = **"beer," "fish," or "children"**
- Agents at Dover authorised to charter boats for Rothschild business; secrecy so ingrained
  that Salomon's son **Anselm** at age eleven refused to let his teacher read a letter he
  was writing his father: "How can I possibly divulge the secrets which I share with my
  father to Mr Sachs?"
- Napoleon's finance minister **François Nicholas Mollien** argued bullion outflow = British
  weakness → therefore advantageous to France; **a fatal miscalculation**, as the bullion
  network became Britain's decisive advantage

### The Official Commission — January 1814

- **January 11, 1814**: Nathan officially charged with financing Wellington's advance through
  France — the Rothschilds' **first official British government commission**
- Vansittart's instruction to Herries: employ Nathan "in the most secret and confidential
  manner to collect in Germany, France and Holland the largest quantity of French gold and
  silver coins, not exceeding in value **£600,000**" within two months
- Coins to be delivered at Dutch port **Helvoetsluys** → relayed to Wellington via **St Jean
  de Luz** near Biarritz; Nathan to "take upon himself all risks and losses prior to delivery"
- Commission: **2 per cent** on sums delivered; strict secrecy required
- Nathan brought into direct contact with Herries (who he saw "almost continually"), with
  Chancellor **Vansittart**, and PM **Lord Liverpool**

**Execution difficulties:**
- Nathan's agent **Meyer Davidson** sent to Amsterdam found French occupation had depleted
  suitable coins; new **napoléons d'or** (successor to louis d'or) had to be struck
- By end of February: only **£150,000** accumulated — "like a drop of water in the ocean"
  given the government's needs; talk of reducing target to £300,000
- Despite this, Wellington wrote February 22 to thank Bathurst for "the supplies of money
  which are very ample"
- By April Nathan and James converting over **£20,000 into guilders** for immediate use

### Allied Subsidy Business — The Russian Deal

- Beyond Wellington's army: Britain paid ~**£42 million to allies 1811–1815**; Rothschilds
  arrived late but quickly dominated
- June 1814 Herries tally of Rothschild payments (to Prussia, Austria, France, British army,
  undisbursed): **12.6 million francs** — and more to come
- Lord Liverpool to Castlereagh: **"I do not know what we should have done without him
  [Rothschild] last year [1814]."**
- By mid-May Nathan owed **£1,167,000 by the government** — Herries told his France
  representative: "They are now serving us to a very considerable extent by their credit and
  if we fail to supply them with funds to meet these engagements the weight is greater than
  any individual however rich could be expected to support"

**Russian subsidy deal — the *Meistergeschäft*:**
- Reichenbach agreement (June 1813): Britain promised **£1,333,333 to Russia** and **£666,666
  to Prussia** — but cash-strapped Britain repeatedly deferred payment
- May 1814 final agreement: **15 monthly instalments of 1 million Prussian thaler** (two-thirds
  Russia, one-third Prussia)
- Russian diplomat **Gervais** initially approached **Hope & Co.** for advance on first seven
  months at 2% discount — Hope director **Labouchère hesitated**; Rothschilds (Salomon and
  James) **snapped up** the business
- Rothschilds offered to convert 4 million thaler into louis d'or/ducats AND deliver cash
  to Hamburg, Dresden, and Warsaw — where Russian troops urgently needed pay
- James to Nathan: Gervais **"needed cash, and soon"** and no other firm would risk delivering
  to remote Warsaw

**Bribery as standard practice:**
- To secure Gervais's loyalty, Russian officials including Gervais received **commissions and
  interest-free loans** — a 1% commission went straight into Gervais's pocket
- Brothers called this **"our friend baksheesh"** ("der Freund Schmiergeld") — privately
  acknowledged it as bribery
- Brothers disagreed on amounts: Salomon thought James had given Gervais "too much of the
  profits"; James insisted: "The money given to Gervais makes all the difference"
- Payments to Gervais concealed from Herries — British officials "more subject to parliamentary
  and press scrutiny" than Russians; no question of Herries receiving similar sums directly
- Herries's private interests served more subtly: Amschel sent Nathan a letter from Madame
  Limburger about her illegitimate child (fathered by Herries) — "he may give you the
  Prussian and Russian business. And if the child gets a quarter of the profit, then we would
  have our profit, too."

**Profitability of the Russian deal:**
- Commission structure on first 4-million-thaler tranche: 2% from Britain + 2% costs + 4%
  from Russia = **~8% gross profit**; later tranches of 3.7 million francs and 5.3 million
  thaler yielded comparable returns
- Mecklenburg: willing to forgo up to **30% of its 1.5 million thaler subsidy** and pay a
  5% commission for "immediate payment" — James: **"They would do anything we want them [to
  do] in order to obtain money quickly"**
- Also furnished: **Louis XVIII** (returning French king) with bills on Paris; **Hesse-Kassel**
  skeleton administration took a **250,000 gulden Rothschild loan** when Russian troops
  requisitioned grain and the War Chest was empty

<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## Chapter 5 (continued): War of Subsidies — Exchange Rate Arbitrage & Nathan's Waterloo

### The Three Profit Streams from Subsidy Transfers

- **Two (sometimes three) ways to profit** from every inter-governmental payment:
  1. **Commissions** — ranged from 8% down to zero depending on government leverage
  2. **Exchange rate arbitrage** — exploiting currency value differences across markets
     (Frankfurt, London, Amsterdam, Paris all quoted the same currency at different rates)
  3. **Forward exchange speculation** — timing purchases of a currency at its weakest,
     selling at its strongest
- The Rothschilds were uniquely placed: permanent bases in Frankfurt and London,
  semi-permanent in Amsterdam and Paris, with brothers traveling to Berlin and Prague
- Their key advantage: the Rothschilds *themselves* were the cause of exchange
  volatility — large subsidy transfers weakened sterling, which they could then
  arbitrage against their own movements

### Controlling the Sterling Exchange Rate

- As early as June 1811, **Amschel** accused **James** of "forcing the rate of exchange
  in Jerusalem [London] too high" (i.e., pound falling against the franc)
- James to Nathan: "It is impossible to do more than I do to keep [the exchange]
  so low as possible"
- Nathan disbursed £700,000 in bills on Holland and Frankfurt "without its having
  produced the smallest effect or excited any sensation on the market" — to
  Herries's amazement; the exchange was *better* after than before
- Carl observed: **"When we buy, everybody buys"** — markets followed the
  Rothschild lead, believing they acted on behalf of the English government
- James by early 1815: "It depends solely on me whether the pound rises or falls
  in Paris"

### Arbitrage Mechanics in Practice

- Ducats delivered to Gervais (Russia) had been bought cheaper in Amsterdam by
  James, yielding ~4% extra profit
- Amschel to Salomon (joking, post-war sterling surge): "Do your stuff, make the
  Frankfurt house richer by a million francs, the Paris house richer by a million
  louis d'or and the London house richer by a million pounds, and you'll be
  awarded the order of the *Grande Armée*!"
- Risk was real: raising 600,000 gulden was, per Carl, "no joke"; Frankfurt credit
  sources were "all but exhausted" on more than one occasion
- Communications were critical: Amschel asked Nathan to send letters via multiple
  routes (Paris, Amsterdam, Dunkirk) and use **colour-coded envelopes** — blue for
  rising sterling, red for falling

### The July 1814 Sterling Crisis

- Nathan unexpectedly remitted £100,000+ to Frankfurt "like a madman," causing the
  pound to drop in Frankfurt and then Amsterdam
- **Salomon** warned Nathan: "If you are not careful you will not remain the master
  of the Stock Exchange"
- **Amschel** continued buying sterling, not knowing of the slide — Carl complained
  Amschel would buy regardless of instructions, then deny responsibility
- Salomon's conclusion: "No man on earth can at any time fix the rate of the pound
  except a government which would be ready to risk half a million pounds"
- Recovery only came gradually as Nathan worked "as much as lies in my power" to
  push the rate back up

### Bond Speculation alongside Subsidies

- Russian bonds fell from 65% of face value to just 25% between Feb–Oct 1812
  (French invasion suspended interest payments)
- News of Moscow retreat → bonds rallied to 35 (Nov 1812) → 50 (Mar 1813)
  → fell back to 41 on Napoleon's Saxon victories
- Logic: anticipate Allied victory → buy bonds of Allied states while depressed;
  British subsidy payments implied resumption of interest
- Nathan sent brother-in-law **Moses Montefiore** to Paris to buy Russian bonds —
  arrived late, bonds already near par
- Ferguson's assessment: bond speculation was much less profitable than
  the foreign exchange arbitrage operations

---

### *Nathan's Waterloo* — The Myth Demolished

- The standard myth: Nathan obtained first news of Waterloo, sold consols to
  panic the market, then bought back at the bottom before news spread —
  making £20–135 million
- **Ferguson's verdict: "reality is diametrically opposite to myth"**
- Napoleon's escape from Elba on March 1, 1815 was initially "unpleasant news"
  for the Rothschilds — they had just bought Austrian stocks in expectation of
  a bull market

### What Actually Happened in 1815

- Nathan immediately pivoted: began buying bullion in London to sell to Herries
  for shipment to Wellington
- First week of April alone: bought "100,000 guineas gold, £50,000 foreign and
  upwards of 100,000 Spanish dollars and nearly £200,000 good bills"
- By October 20: total of £2,136,916 in gold coins — 884 boxes and 55 casks
- Herries's 1815 account with Nathan: **£9,789,778** (vs. 1814's operations)
- This time Austria, Russia, Prussia, Saxony, Baden, Württemberg, Bavaria,
  Hesse, Denmark, Sardinia all paid through the Rothschilds

### The Waterloo Miscalculations

- Nathan made two fatal assumptions:
  1. That another lengthy war would be needed to defeat Napoleon
  2. That the financial paralysis of 1814 would return, leaving Rothschilds
     without competition
- In fact, barely three months elapsed from return to Waterloo; minimal
  fighting meant continental rivals (Amsterdam, Hamburg, Frankfurt) could
  compete in money markets
- By May 5 Nathan received government orders to **"desist in my operations
  owing to your having sent off so much specie"** — Wellington had more
  bullion than he could use

> "I certainly feel at a loss to understand the reason you cannot follow the
> instructions I have so repeatedly given you . . . by your inattention I have
> lost at least ⅞ of the business I expected . . . What do you suppose will
> be the result *for they are not my orders but Government's*"
> — Nathan to James, 1815

- Root cause: **continental banker Heckscher** undercut them by pointing out
  the absurdity of shipping gold from Hamburg/Amsterdam to London only to
  send it back to the continent

### The Waterloo News & Consol Purchases

- Rothschild couriers reached New Court on night of June 19 — 24 hours after
  Wellington met Blücher, ~48 hours before Major Henry Percy delivered the
  official dispatch to Cabinet (June 21, 11 p.m., Lord Harrowby's house)
- Nathan relayed the news to the government on June 20; it was not believed
- The news was "anything but good" from Nathan's perspective: he had just
  arranged a new million-pound loan in Amsterdam five days before the battle
- **Victor Rothschild** (family historian) conclusively showed: consols had
  already recovered from their nadir of 53 more than a week *before* Waterloo
- Maximum possible profit from consol purchase on June 20 (at 56.5, sold
  at 60.5 a week later): barely **£7,000**
- Nathan also bought ~£450,000 of Omnium funds at 107; if sold at 120 per
  Salomon's advice, profit ~£58,000 — not a significant sum for the scale of
  operations
- Most significant stock speculation came later: **1816**, Nathan bought
  £650,000 at average price 62, sold November 1817 at 82.75 → **£130,000 profit**
  (but made with government funds on Herries's suggestion — not his to keep)

### Post-Waterloo Crisis

- Brothers encumbered with: depreciating bullion, over a million pounds in
  treasury bills to sell in Amsterdam, half-finished subsidy contracts
- Wellington's agent **John Roworth** walked from Mons to Genappe, was
  handed back unwanted Prussian coins worth £230,000
- Carl temporarily halted payments to military chest in late July
- **Amschel** was "swimming" in money nobody needed in Frankfurt
- Amsterdam market suddenly so liquid that long-dated British treasury bills
  "could scarcely be sold at all"
- Family tragedy compounded business crisis: death of their **sister Julie**
  at age 35; Nathan: "The melancholy communication of the death of my sister
  has entirely unhinged my mind"

> "Far from being hugely profitable, the aftermath of Wellington's victory
> was a period of acute crisis for the Rothschilds."
> — Ferguson

### Recovering Losses: Prolonging the Subsidies

- Key recovery strategy: extend subsidy payments to Britain's allies as long
  as possible — Allied powers were willing accomplices (pocketing more before
  peace ended payments)
- Prussian representative Jordan privately admitted the powers were "spinning
  out negotiations" for an extra month's subsidy
- A gift of £1,100 in British stocks secured Jordan's cooperation
- **Gervais** (Russian commissar) received 2% of subsidy business routed
  to Rothschilds: "Rothschild, we must make money!" he told James
- Austria finally engaged — Carl: "not easy to do business with the Austrians
  . . . but once you have their confidence you can depend upon it"
- Anti-Semitism was a business factor: Saxe-Weimar officials sought to avoid
  "falling completely and utterly into the hands of Mr Rothschild, who is,
  after all, a Jew"

### The Accounting Chaos

- The period's chaos was so extreme that **"their already rudimentary
  accounting procedures collapsed altogether"**
- The Rothschilds did not use **double-entry bookkeeping** — a system described
  by **Luca Pacioli** in Venice in 1494 and standard in Europe by the 16th century
- Carl (June 1814): raised cash via "swindling" — issuing **accommodation bills**
  (bills unrelated to actual commodity purchases) totaling more than £2 million
- Salomon and Amschel by August 1814: "completely confused and do not know
  where the money is"
- September 1815 cash-flow crisis: Amschel bust in Berlin, Carl's funds
  frozen in Amsterdam treasury bills, James owing £120,000 in Paris alone
- The continental Rothschilds avoided bankruptcy only through short-term
  borrowing and further accommodation bills

> "You must have all our money over there with you. We here are stinking
> poor. We haven't a penny to spare. Amschel has less than a million left
> and therefore the whole lot must be with you . . . Work out where the
> family money is, my good Nathan. I don't know . . . Where is our money?
> Well, it's just absurd."
> — Salomon to Nathan, September 1815

### The Herries Investigation

- **Alexander Baring** (parliamentary critic) accused Herries of
  "maladministration" in the Commons — he had an axe to grind as a rival
- The Rothschilds had: (a) secured additional commissions from Russia without
  informing Herries, (b) exploited exchange rate differences beyond their mandate,
  (c) issued more than £2 million in "fictional" accommodation bills
- **Benjamin Davidson** assigned to reconstruct and conceal the accounts
- Davidson's conclusion: "One should have thought earlier . . . that one day
  Herries [would] have to look at these accounts"
- Davidson managed to show the British government — not the Rothschilds —
  as the principal beneficiary; Lord Liverpool's government ultimately
  accepted that verdict
- Herries honourably discharged with a pension when commissariat wound up,
  October 1816
- Salomon was still fretting about the accounts as late as January 1818

> "It is fair to conclude that the huge profits of 1814 and 1815 were made
> in ways much more mysterious—and hazardous—than the traditional
> Waterloo myth implies."
> — Ferguson

---

### *Fraternity* — The Brotherhood Myth vs. Reality

- The idea of **fraternity** was politically charged in post-Revolutionary Europe
  (Freemasons, liberals, socialists all idealised it); Schiller's "Alle Menschen
  werden Brüder" set by Beethoven carried "thinly disguised revolutionary
  significance"
- Contemporaries saw the Rothschilds as exemplifying fraternal harmony —
  **Friedrich Gentz** in the *Brockhaus Encyclopaedia*: each business proposition
  "the subject of their joint deliberations . . . all the brothers have an equal
  share in the results"
- **Simon Moritz von Bethmann** (Frankfurt rival): "The harmony between the
  brothers contributes largely to their success. None of them ever thinks of
  finding fault with another"
- **Benjamin Disraeli**: "The prosperity of the Rothschilds was as much owing
  to the unity of feeling which alike pervaded all branches of that numerous
  family as in their capital & abilities. They were like an Arabian tribe."
- This hardened into the myth of **"the five Frankfurters"** — the image of an
  indomitable phalanx never acting individually
- Ferguson's counter-argument: the myth was precisely that — a myth. The actual
  correspondence (shown throughout this chapter) reveals constant recrimination,
  blame-shifting, and near-fratricidal conflict over money and decisions
- The paradox: unlike the idealised brotherhood of poets, real brothers
  seldom worked well together — contemporaries praised the Rothschilds *because*
  harmony was unexpected, not because it was common

<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

## Chapter 3 (continued): The Bonds of Brotherhood

### Nathan's Dominance and the "Commanding General" Dynamic

- The 1815 partnership agreement made the brothers formally equal:
  profits divided equally, Nathan gave each a £50,000 promissory
  note to compensate his larger capital share — but in practice
  **Nathan** reduced the others to mere agents
- **Salomon** half-joked: Nathan was "the commanding general,"
  brothers were his "marshals," capital resources were "soldiers"
  to be kept ready — echoing Napoleon himself
- **Swinton Holland** to **Alexander Baring** (1824): "he is in money
  and funds what Bonaparte was in war, and if any sudden shake
  comes, he will fall to the ground like the other" — the
  *Finanzbonaparte* label
- **Ludwig Börne** called them all "Finanzbonaparten" — but it was
  really only Nathan who embodied the comparison

### Brotherly Conflict: The Crisis of 1814

- Tensions boiled over mid-1814 as Nathan dictated brothers'
  movements; ordered **Salomon** to Amsterdam, blasted **Amschel**
  and **Carl** in Frankfurt letters
- Carl took to bed; warned Nathan would "soon have a partner in
  the other world" from the stress; Salomon complained of "severe
  pains in my back and legs"

> "I cannot for one moment believe that even if I were the learned
> Nathan Rothschild I would regard the other four brothers as stupid
> schoolboys... We have something you in London obviously do not
> have — we keep our books in order... The English mail day is a
> regular terror for me. Every night I dream of these letters."
> — **Salomon** to Nathan, 1814

- Nathan's response: threatened to dissolve the business entirely,
  close all accounts (Paris, Amsterdam, Frankfurt), "clear up"
  the partnership — a nuclear option that silenced all protest

> "I have to admit that I was thoroughly fed up with the longwinded
> business... I think it would be best if Salomon would close the
> Paris accounts and come to London."
> — **Nathan** to brothers, 1814

- This threat worked; henceforth Salomon acknowledged Nathan as
  "commanding general" and himself as "field marshal" — but urged
  Nathan to "go on the defensive occasionally in order to safeguard
  your strength"

### The Limits of Nathan's Dominance

- Nathan's dominance was real but never absolute — not a dictatorship
- **James** (only 23 in 1815) was the least submissive; sardonically
  told Salomon Cohen he was allowing Nathan "to dictate to him
  about millions as if they were apples and pears"
- James was intellectually Nathan's equal — better educated; it was
  James who introduced **double-entry bookkeeping** to the firm
- Only the age gap obliged James to defer for the next 20 years
- **Amschel**: the most risk-averse, wanted a "quiet life," "to work
  in tranquillity" — temperamentally opposite to Nathan
- **Carl**: nervous, insecure, "I wish God would give me but little,
  enough to live, garments for myself and bread to eat" — genuinely
  afraid of Nathan after the Amsterdam treasury bills fiasco
- Salomon: intellectually capable of challenging Nathan but "too
  quiet and thoughtful," preferred to side with Nathan against others
- Key check on Nathan: brothers could restrain him when he
  overreached; Amschel to James after a major setback: "One should
  never lose one's head. Here lies the advantage of a partnership.
  If one of the partners loses his senses, the others must remain
  serene."

### Trust and Exclusivity Among Brothers

- Despite quarrels, brothers trusted no one else as completely:
  Salomon once **forged Nathan's signature** on bills Nathan had
  forgotten to endorse — inconceivable for any outsider to do
- Even senior clerks kept at arm's length; when clerk **Feidel**
  gained influence over Amschel, Carl's response was described
  as "jealous"
- Brothers-in-law (**Salomon Cohen**, **Abraham Monteore**) viewed
  with suspicion as outsiders with business designs
- James relieved to learn Nathan had cut even Davidson out of
  access to letters and business deliberations
- Ultimate bond: shared memories of the **Judengasse** — "Did anyone
  promise us more when we all slept in one little attic room?" —
  Salomon to Nathan when the latter grumbled about selling consols
  too soon

### The 1818 Partnership Agreement

- Legacy of 1814-15 transactions: tangled financial interdependence
  impossible to easily unwind
- Central question: should **James** establish a Paris house under
  the collective name "**de Rothschild Frères**"?
- Amschel feared James would embroil him in risky business; Carl
  shared anxieties; both only agreed when James conceded that
  **capital of the partnership should not be made public** —
  enduring precedent of secrecy
- **1818 agreement** defined the partnership as "three joint
  mercantile establishments conducted under their said five
  partners' mutual responsibility" but "forming but one general
  joint concern" — reconciling individual differences with
  collective fraternal purpose

---

## Chapter 4: "A Court Always Leads to Something" (1816–1825)

> "You are certainly right that there is much to be earned from a
> government which has no money. But you have to take risks."
> — **James Rothschild** to Nathan Rothschild

> "N. M. Rothschild... has the money, the strength and the power."
> — **Nathan Rothschild** to Christian Rother

### Byron and the Rise of Rothschild Fame

- In 1823, **Byron's** *Don Juan* (cantos 12-14) identified
  **Nathan Rothschild** and **Alexander Baring** as the true powers
  of Europe — "Jew Rothschild, and his fellow Christian Baring"
- Byron: "Who hold the balance of the world? Who reign / O'er
  Congress, whether royalist or liberal?" — attributed to Rothschild
  and Baring; their every loan "seats a nation or upsets a throne"
- Byron's verse also captured Nathan's **ascetic materialism** —
  "despising every sensual call, / Commands — the intellectual lord
  of all" — possibly inspired by Nathan personally
- Paradox: while **Baring** (Alexander) was a well-known public
  figure (MP since 1806, family established since 1770, absorbed
  into English social elite), the Rothschilds' wartime role was
  still largely a secret in 1823; their celebrity was a product
  of the post-war decade

### Background: The Barings as Rivals

- **Baring Brothers** founded 1770; family emigrated from Bremen 1717;
  became Lutherans and easily absorbed into social elite of Exeter
  then London
- **Francis Baring**: MP since 1784, East India Company board since
  1779, baronet since 1793
- **Alexander Baring**: MP since 1806 — by contrast, Rothschilds'
  wartime role still secret; **Jacques Laffitte** (Paris) better
  known as Governor of the Banque de France 1814-1820

### The Economic Consequences of the Peace

- **Second Peace of Paris** (post-Waterloo) imposed major reparations
  on France: 700 million francs over five years from March 1816,
  plus costs of maintaining an occupying force of 150,000 men
- Initial 50 million franc "contribution" extracted even before
  peace signed in November 1815
- Rothschilds hoped this would generate lucrative international
  transfer business — recouping losses of the Hundred Days

### Competition and Disappointment: The Reparations Payments

- Initial optimism: **Gervais** promised Russia's share to
  Rothschilds; **Herries** expected to secure large British tranche
- But peace brought **competition**: rival bankers rushed to
  challenge Rothschild monopoly on international transfers
- Rothschilds forced into loose partnerships with **Mendelssohn**
  (Berlin), **Bethmann** and **Gontard** (Frankfurt),
  **Arnstein & Eskeles** (Vienna), **Parish & Co.** (Hamburg)
  just to participate in Prussia/Austria payments
- Russian minister **Count Nesselrode** favoured Gontard; Prussian
  **Rother** declined to accept bribes; the Rothschilds' political
  leverage was eroding
- James: profits of 1.5% and less, "not much joy to be had from
  the contributions business, because there are too many people
  here" — fatalistic acceptance: "There are no big, brilliant
  deals to be made here. But now that we're here, we're happy
  to take all that we can"
- Key insight: "contacts with courts, no matter how unprofitable,
  might lead to business in the future" — strategic patience

### The French Reparations Loan: Baring's Triumph

- France could only pay reparations via a large loan — by late 1816
  this was obvious; 1816-17 budget showed a **300 million franc
  deficit**, 5% rentes trading as low as 50
- Paris capital market too weak; French **Incredible Chamber**
  (ultra-royalist assembly) unwilling to raise taxes
- Rothschilds cultivated **duc de Richelieu's** secretary for inside
  information; but Finance Minister **Corvetto** gave the business
  to **Baring** and **Pierre-César Labouchère** of **Hope & Co.**,
  wooed by **Gabriel-Julien Ouvrard**
- **1817 Baring deal**: 297 million francs for 5% rentes, issued in
  three tranches at 52.5, 55.5, and 61.5 — France increased
  national debt by 534 million francs for less than 300 million
  cash (effective rate ~9%, nearly double nominal rate)
- Rothschilds "more or less excluded" from this immense operation

> "He is quite a crook this Baring. Today he is going to dine with
> us... There is not a single man of importance amongst the
> authorities here who would not work with Baring hand in glove."
> — **Salomon** on **Alexander Baring**, 1817

- James excluded again from the **final reparations loan** (1818):
  offered a mere 10 million francs to share with David Parish,
  while 480 million went to Baring
- **Duke of Wellington** to Lord Liverpool: "The fact is that Baring,
  having the French finances in his hands... has to a certain degree
  the command of the money market of the world. He feels his power."
- This was the moment Barings truly deserved to be called "the
  sixth great power" (phrase attributed, apocryphally, to Richelieu)

### Nathan's Arguments for Caution on French Funds

- Nathan had real reasons to doubt French stability after Hundred
  Days; James in Paris heard "talk of war" May 1816; feared British
  government might replace **Louis XVIII** with **duc d'Orléans**
  (which James warned would cause civil war)
- Salomon: "no way of insuring against the hot heads of the French"
- **Salomon argued explicitly against attacking Baring** (Feb 1818):
  counter-productive if it could be said "the Rothschilds organised
  a diversion, the loan fell through, the troops can't be withdrawn"
- True cause of rente price drop at **Aix-la-Chapelle** conference:
  **Banque de France** had over-lent to Paris banks, then
  over-corrected by tightening discounting — a credit contraction,
  not Rothschild manipulation
- No archival evidence supports the legend that Rothschilds
  deliberately crashed rentes to destroy Baring's position

### Nathan's Consols Trade: The Real Victory

- Rothschilds' true triumph was in **British consols**, not French
  rentes — Nathan bought heavily at end of 1815 on Herries's advice
- Purchased 3% consols at 61.1 and 61.5; £450,000 of Omnium stocks
  at 107; held throughout 1816 ignoring brothers' pleas to sell
- By end of 1816: £1.2 million (nominal) consols — nearly the
  entire capital of the firm in one security
- Brothers' reactions:
  - **Amschel**: "stupid... to invest one's whole fortune in one
    single security"
  - **James**: enthusiastic (single investment already earned "as
    much as a loan") but questioned Nathan's target of 80
  - Even **Caroline** (Salomon's wife) had dreams about consol
    prices reaching 86 — revealing indirect female participation
- May 1817: Nathan reluctantly sold ~£600,000 at brothers' urging,
  then immediately reinvested more as rise resumed
- July 1817: consols above 82, total holding £1.6 million —
  Salomon acknowledged another "masterwork"
- **Nathan sold at peak (end of 1817)**: profit of more than
  **£250,000** — five months before market peaked at 84.25
  in December 1817; by 1820 prices back below 70
- Nathan did NOT tip off brothers-in-law or the Elector of
  Hesse-Kassel until after he had sold

> "I am very happy to learn you make as good a Bear as you formerly
> did a Bull... You have beaten your antagonists so frequently that
> I am surprised there are any so hardy to be found in the Stock
> Exchange to oppose you in any considerable operation."
> — **Moses Montefiore** to Nathan, after consols trade

### Why Nathan Sold: Inside Information from Government

- Part motivation: alarm about possible war over Spain
- More important: **inside information** from **Nicholas Vansittart**
  (Chancellor of the Exchequer) about forthcoming **funding
  operation** — issue of £27 million in new 3.5% or 3.25%
  government stocks, which would depress the market for 3% consols
- Nathan had cultivated Vansittart through proximity; also first
  direct contacts with **Duke of Wellington** in Paris
- British government itself benefited: surplus military chest funds
  had bought £650,000 consols at 62; now at 82, Treasury stood
  to profit ~£130,000 — a quid pro quo relationship
- Salomon on the relationship: "Vansittart is a very fine man,
  insofar as he gave you a hint of a forthcoming funding operation.
  He well knows that you were the only one who drove up the stocks,
  who lifted England's credit."
- The key to Rothschild success was not just market skill but
  the **information advantage** that came from proximity to power

<!-- pp. 181-200 -->

## Chapter 7 (cont.): "The Chief Ally of the Holy Alliance"

### Britain's Post-War Fiscal Crisis and the Gold Standard Debate

- British public debt had swollen to ~£900 million (~200% of national income)
  after the Napoleonic Wars
- 1815: House of Commons refused to renew wartime income tax, costing
  £14 million/year in revenue; annual debt service alone was £30 million
- **Chancellor Vansittart**'s strategy: borrow short-term via exchequer bills
  to fund Pitt's sinking fund — a hand-to-mouth system that suited Nathan,
  who traded both bills and consols
- **"Bullionists"** (led by **William Huskisson**, backed by **Robert Peel**)
  wanted resumption of gold/"cash" payments; opposed by Nathan and
  fellow bankers on practical deflation grounds
- 1819: **"Secret Committee on the Expediency of the Bank Resuming
  Cash Payments"** under Peel's chairmanship — bullionists won
- Nathan personally lobbied PM Liverpool against returning to gold,
  pursuing ministers into the country; Liverpool rebuffed him flatly

> "Nothing can be more foolish than Rothschild's following you, and
> intending to follow me, into the country. If his proceeding is known
> it can of course only augment the general alarm..."
> — *PM Liverpool to Vansittart, October 1819*

- Nathan's argument was not theoretical objection to gold but practical:
  tight money + mountainous debt = economic destabilisation

> "Money will be so very scarce, every article in this country will fall
> to such an enormous extent, that many persons will be ruined."
> — *Nathan's testimony to Committee of Cash Payments, 1820*

- Treasury official **George Harrison** shared Nathan's concern: tightening
  monetary policy while budget was unbalanced would force Nathan to
  become a net seller of stock, undermining the government's own finances
- Contrarian insight: Nathan was not wrong — the combination of monetary
  deflation and huge unfunded debt was genuinely dangerous; Abraham
  Montefiore noted the real fix (a property tax on the wealthy) was
  politically impossible since the wealthy *were* the lawmakers

### "The Chief Ally of the Holy Alliance"

- Post-1815 response to London/Paris difficulties: seek new business
  across Europe — **Austria, Prussia, Russia** (the **"Holy Alliance"**,
  formed at Tsar's suggestion), plus smaller Italian and German states
- Disraeli captured the logic in *Coningsby*: "France wanted some;
  Austria more; Prussia a little; Russia a few millions."
- The Alliance's counter-revolutionary mission (preventing recurrence
  of 1789–1815) required military intervention funds — creating
  additional financial needs the Rothschilds could supply

### The Prussian Loan of 1818 — A Watershed

- Prussia emerged from Napoleonic Wars with 188 million thaler (~£32m)
  debt, running large deficits through 1817
- Rothschild-Frankfurt arranged a small 5 million gulden (£450,000)
  Prussian loan in early 1817; floating debt hit 20 million thaler by autumn
- Original idea for a London loan came from **Barandon**, rep of Prussian
  **Seehandlung** bank — he nearly wrecked it by publishing Nathan's
  proposed terms (issue price of 60, implying 8.33% rate), provoking
  outrage in Berlin
- **Salomon** rushed to Koblenz for talks with Chancellor **Hardenberg**;
  **Carl** helped salvage negotiations in Berlin; deal finally closed in
  London end of March 1818 after five days of bargaining with finance
  official **Rother**

### Nathan's Political Demand: A Landmark in Sovereign Lending

- Historians claimed Prussia chose London borrowing to *avoid* political
  concessions (like summoning estates *Stände*); Rothschild correspondence
  tells the opposite story
- Nathan insisted the loan be secured by a mortgage on Prussian royal
  domains, **guaranteed by the Stände** — arguing British investors
  needed security beyond a sovereign's mere good faith

> "[T]o induce British Capitalists to invest their money in a loan to a
> foreign government upon reasonable terms... some security, beyond the
> mere good faith of the government... should be held out to the
> lenders... Without some security of this description any attempt to
> raise a considerable sum in England for a foreign Power would be
> hopeless."
> — *Nathan's memorandum to Hardenberg*

- Key argument: constitutional regimes (like France) where a Chamber
  could sanction national debt offered better credit security than
  "uncontrolled" sovereign executives — a **constitutional monarchy
  was a better credit risk than neo-absolutism**
- Final contract was a compromise: clause 5 referenced a mortgage on
  royal domains under a household law passed with "assent of the
  provincial estates" — oblique but significant
- Nathan's letters to Rother showed contempt for those trying to
  renegotiate after signing:

> "The cabal there can do nothing against N. M. Rothschild, he has
> the money, the strength and the power, the cabal has only impotence."
> — *Nathan to Rother*

- **Key consequence**: Nathan's demand fed directly into Prussia's
  **"Decree for the Future Management of the State Debt"** (Jan 17, 1819),
  which required any future Prussian loan to be issued "in consultation
  with, and with the guarantee of, the future imperial estates assembly"
- This is why Prussia borrowed *least* of all German states in 1820s–30s;
  when the retrenchment policy broke down in 1840s, the consequences
  were revolutionary

### Innovations in the International Bond Market

- The 1818 Prussian loan was a structural watershed in global capital
  markets — three key innovations:
  1. **Denominated in sterling**, with interest payable half-yearly
     in London (not Berlin) — eliminated exchange rate risk for
     British investors
  2. **British-style sinking fund** for amortisation
  3. **Issued simultaneously** in London, Frankfurt, Berlin, Hamburg,
     Amsterdam, and Vienna — a major step toward a fully international
     bond market

> *The Times* later called Nathan "the first introducer of foreign loans
> into Britain" — prior practice of paying dividends abroad made foreign
> bonds too inconvenient for most British investors.

- German legal expert **Johann Heinrich Bender** (*On The Traffic in
  State Bonds*, 1825) identified Rothschild multi-city issuance as one
  of their principal contributions to modern economic development
- Rother reported to Hardenberg: "The Rothschild in this country...
  has an incredible influence upon all financial affairs here in London...
  it is, close to the truth, that he entirely regulates the rate of
  exchange in the City. His power as a banker is enormous."
- Nathan secured a second Prussian loan in 1822 for £3.5 million
  to the Seehandlung

### German Confederation Business

- **Amschel** and **Carl** in Frankfurt cultivated diplomatic contacts
  at the Confederation Diet (which met in Frankfurt, in the Thurn und
  Taxis palace), generating a stream of small loans to minor German states
- Clients: Grand Duchy of **Hesse-Darmstadt**, Schaumburg, Homburg,
  Saxe-Weimar, Anhalt-Coethen, Nassau-Usingen — loans rarely exceeded
  500,000 gulden (£45,000) individually but totalled 24.7 million gulden
  (£2.2 million) from Frankfurt house alone, 1817–1829
- The Confederation's 20 million francs (French reparations for German
  fortifications) was deposited with the Rothschilds in 1820 — a
  long-term windfall given the slowness of German bureaucratic decisions
- Hesse-Kassel relationship faded: William's spendthrift son succeeded
  him in 1821; apart from two loans (4.3 million gulden total), business
  dried up

### The Austrian Breakthrough

- Austria had initially resisted using Rothschilds (preferring **Arnstein
  & Eskeles**, **Fries & Co.**, **Geymüller & Co.**) for British subsidy
  payments; first major post-war Austrian loan (50 million gulden) went
  to the Anglo-Hanseatic Parish brothers with Baring, Bethmann, Geymüller
- Breakthrough in 1820: **Salomon** organised two lottery loans worth
  45 million Austrian gulden (~£4.8 million) jointly with **David Parish**
  — so profitable that Salomon resolved to remain in Vienna permanently
- 1822 Russia loan: Baring/Reid Irving had handled the 1820 Russian loan;
  by 1822 Nathan issued £6.6 million in 5% bonds priced at 77, sold
  easily at 80+ through London broker network led by brother-in-law
  **Moses Montefiore**
- By end of 1822, Rothschilds were undisputed "bankers to the Holy
  Alliance" — **Prince Pückler-Muskau** described Nathan as "the chief
  ally of the Holy Alliance" to his wife
- Austrian Emperor told his Frankfurt envoy that Amschel was "richer
  than I am" — not wholly facetious; *The Times* reported that James's
  mere appearance at the Paris bourse would boost Russian bond prices

### Finance and Revolution — The 1820s Crisis Wave

- The Holy Alliance's containment strategy quickly proved inadequate:
  - **1819**: Murder of **August von Kotzebue** by student **Karl Sand**
    → Metternich uses as pretext for crackdown on German liberals
  - **Jan 1820**: Cadiz mutiny → Spanish constitution reimposed on
    **Ferdinand VII**; same constitution extended to **Ferdinand I of
    Naples** six months later
  - **Aug 1820**: Military revolt in Portugal
  - **Mar 1821**: Risings in Piedmont and Greece
  - **1824–5**: Decembrist movement in Russia
- Unrest driven by discharged soldiers and secret societies
  (**Carbonari** in Italy, **Freemasons** in Spain)
- Congresses of **Troppau** (Oct–Dec 1820), **Laibach** (Jan 1821),
  **Verona** (Sep–Dec 1822) debated scope of armed intervention
- Rothschilds' position was **ambivalent** — revolution was both a
  threat (bond prices slumped) and an opportunity (new states needed
  new financing)

### Italy: Financing Counter-Revolution in Naples

- **Metternich** wrote to Salomon from Troppau (Dec 1820) about a
  25–30 million franc loan for the "future fate of the Kingdom of Naples"
- Salomon resisted going to Laibach publicly — worried press coverage
  would panic the Vienna market and expose the Rothschild role
- **Carl** sent to Naples with Austrian forces to manage cash supply,
  as the brothers had done for armies during Napoleonic Wars
- Metternich to Stadion: "We have embarked on a great undertaking...
  upon its success or failure the whole future depends; not merely
  the future of the Austrian monarchy, but that of the whole of Europe."
- Stadion described near-panic in Vienna when news of Piedmont revolt
  reached Laibach: "The whole of the population of Vienna is rushing
  to the Bourse to get rid of our public securities... destroying in
  one day the labours of the preceding five years."
- Naples fell March 24, 1821; Carl organised loans to reimburse Austria:
  - First loan: 16 million ducats (~£2m) at 60 (improved from 10m at 54
    to beat rival Milanese banker)
  - Nov 1821 second loan: 16.8 million ducats at 67.3
  - 1822 third loan: 22 million ducats
  - 1824 fourth loan: £2.5 million — total state debt ~£13 million
- Despite punitive terms, Neapolitan securities rose from 65 to 103
  in Paris; London market enthusiastic for sterling-denominated bonds
- **Carl** built good relationship with Neapolitan Finance Minister
  **Luigi de' Medici**, who accused Austria of profiting from
  prolonged occupation; Carl advanced Medici 1 million ducats from
  his own pocket when Vienna stalled — to Metternich's irritation
- **Vienna's dependence deepened in 1823**: Britain raised the question
  of £23.5 million outstanding wartime loans to Austria; Austria turned
  to Salomon to use Nathan's London influence to negotiate debt reduction
  — the first of many times the Rothschilds served as **unofficial
  diplomatic channel** for Metternich
- Outcome: new Rothschild-Baring-Reid Irving loan of £2.5 million;
  30 million gulden of new metalliques underwritten at 82.33, trading
  at 93 shortly after — "substantial profit to the banks"
- Further 15 million gulden loan in 1826; Austrian intervention in Italy
  yielded **multiple rounds of profit** for the Rothschilds

### Spain: Complexity and Non-Commitment

- After 1820, Ferdinand VII endured the liberal Cortes constitution;
  liberal government raised several loans (to cover revenue shortfalls)
  that Rothschilds initially avoided
- July 1822: Ferdinand and Ultra-royalists attempted coup; James
  became involved in effort by Spanish financier **Bertran de Lys**
  to reconstitute government on moderate lines — too late
- April 1823: French expedition under **duc d'Angoulême** (Louis XVIII's
  nephew) — analogous to Austrian Naples operation
- **James** served French paymaster role as **Ouvrard** had done before,
  supplying d'Angoulême with cash, even raising ransom for Ferdinand VII
- 1823: James won his first major French rentes issue — 462 million
  francs nominal (~£18.5 million), biggest single French government
  bond issue 1815–1848; won by outbidding Lafitte and three other
  Parisian bankers at 89.55 (above market), but rentes quickly rose
  above 90, reaching 100 by end of 1823 — net profit despite bold bid
- But the Rothschilds **declined to lend to restored absolutist
  Ferdinand VII** without guarantees France would not provide
- Three reasons for refusal:
  1. Ferdinand refused to honour Cortes-issued bonds
  2. He refused to repay France for the invasion costs
  3. Suspicion that money would fund a doomed attempt to reconquer
     South American colonies — dangerously bad credit risk
- Austrian ambassador in Paris noted to Metternich the contradiction:
  Rothschilds recognised Cortes government bonds and supported
  South American independence (profitable for business) even while
  nominally aligned with the Holy Alliance

> "Spain's bankruptcy is uppermost in my mind." — *James, 1826*

- Final stance: **calculated non-commitment** — neither fully royalist
  nor liberal, guided by credit risk assessment

### The South American Bubble — Rothschilds Stay Aloof

- 1822–4: speculative boom in South American bonds — Chile, Colombia,
  Buenos Aires, Guatemala all raising money in London
- **Gregor MacGregor**, Scottish adventurer styling himself "Caique
  of Poyais," raised £200,000 claiming to rule a malarial swamp in
  Honduras; even wrote Nathan proposing a Hebrew colony on the
  island of Ruatan
- Rothschilds stayed out — **one exception: Brazil**
  - Brazil retained monarchy (Emperor married to Austrian princess)
  - Close commercial ties with Britain via Portugal
  - 1823: Nathan issued £1.5m loan to Portugal secured on Brazilian
    revenues (Portugal had accepted constitutional government)
  - 1824: City group (Thomas Wilson) tested Brazilian bond market
    with £1m+ at 75; when bonds rose to 87, Nathan took over,
    issuing further £2m in 1825 at 85

> **Heinrich Heine** joked Nathan was "the great Nathan Rothschild,
> Nathan the Wise, with whom the Emperor of Brazil has pawned
> his diamond crown."

### Summary: Rothschild "Political Agnosticism"

- By summer 1825, Rothschilds had established dominance in European
  public finance — Prussia, Austria, Russia, France had all entrusted
  major loans to them
- Contemporary image as "bankers to the Holy Alliance" was a
  **caricature** — understated their **political agnosticism**
- The Rothschilds assessed business in *financial* terms: constitutional
  regimes were better credit risks; absolutism generated revolution,
  which destroyed bond prices
- James to Nathan, late 1826:

> "It would be a mortal sin to be dependent on a Villèle and on a
> Canning... What we now want to say is, '[You want] a loan? You can
> have one, as much as you want, and draw a certain profit from it.
> But to keep all the millions, to that we say no!'"

### *Saving an Old Lady* (section beginning)

- Declining interest rates across Europe in the early 1820s created a
  new business opportunity: **debt conversion** — replacing high-rate
  government bonds with lower-rate bonds
- In Britain: Vansittart had converted £150 million of 5% consols into
  4% in 1822; successor **Frederick Robinson** converted £75 million
  of 4% into 3.5% two years later — significantly reducing debt service
- For bondholders, conversions meant accepting less yield; many refused,
  instead redeeming British bonds and reinvesting in higher-yielding
  continental or Latin American bonds — **fuelling the speculative
  fever of 1822–4**
- In France: PM **Villèle** proposed converting 2,800 million francs
  of 5% rentes into 3% at 75 — over a third of French budget consumed
  by debt service (section continues beyond these pages)

<!-- pp. 201-220 -->

## Chapter 4 (continued): The 1825 Crisis and Nathan's Rescue

### The Villèle Conversion Fiasco

- French 5% rente conversion scheme: **James de Rothschild** and partners sought
  to convert state debt at lower rates, with 5 per cents rising to 106
- Proposal killed in Upper House after **Chateaubriand** and others claimed
  it was an "Anglo-Austrian racket" defrauding French rentiers
- Modified scheme in 1825 offered voluntary conversion with tax breaks;
  only 30 million francs exchanged — leaving James holding bonds as
  market price fell
- **Ouvrard** later claimed Rothschilds doubly insured themselves: demanded
  100 million in treasury bills as safety net AND quietly sold both
  5% and 3% rentes while appearing to support the scheme
- Suspicions confirmed in 1825, ending harmonious relations with **Villèle**
  since 1823; Villèle retaliated by organizing rival syndicate around
  **Laffitte** and Receivers-General for Haiti loan

> "[H]ad it [the Villèle conversion] been carried, the convulsion in
> the money markets of Europe which shortly followed it would probably
> have proved fatal to him with such a burden on his shoulders,
> notwithstanding all his vast resources."
> — Nathan's *Times* obituarist

### Causes of the 1825 Bubble and Bust

- **1825 crisis** prophesied by Nathan: result of resumed **gold convertibility**
  and monetary expansion/contraction cycle
- 1818–1823: Bank of England note circulation fell ~one third
- 1824: temporary gold influx caused note expansion; 1825: sharp contraction
- **Huskisson** at Board of Trade cut import duties → short-term revenue
  reduction + trade deficit as gold flowed out
- Nathan to Herries, April 1825: "The consequence of admitting foreign goods
  [without reciprocity] was that all the gold was going out of the country."
- Asset price collapse: Brazilian bonds issued at 85 → 81 by July → 56 by
  March 1826; Mexican, Colombian, Peruvian bonds all fell below 20;
  British 3% consols fell below 75 from a peak near 97

### Nathan's Rescue of the Bank of England

- Myth: Nathan threatened to exhaust Bank reserves by demanding gold for
  small-denomination notes — **Ferguson calls this diametrically false**
- Reality: Nathan had close, mutually beneficial relationship with Bank
  of England since 1823 (Portugal loan, borrowing silver dollars)
- December 1825: Rothschilds reversed their usual role — instead of
  borrowing gold, they **supplied** the Bank with specie from the continent
- James had been sending gold from Paris since early 1825; in January
  alone sent nearly £500,000
- Crisis peak: six London banks failed; Bank Governor warned government
  of imminent suspension of cash payments; Cabinet alarmed enough to
  order Guards regiment to remain in the City
- **Henry Thornton** and **Alexander Baring** knew Nathan held a gold reserve:
  Baring "persuaded the Jew" to release it, first at 2½% commission,
  then reframed as public spirit
- **Political complication**: Huskisson had spread rumors Rothschild house was
  in danger, sent Canning to inquire about James in Paris; Nathan showed
  his accounts proving personal worth of £2½ million
- Nathan's two key actions on December 17: (1) advised government to buy
  exchequer bills to inject liquidity; (2) delivered £300,000 in sovereigns
  to the Bank, continuing deliveries for a year
- Bank reserve touched its lowest point (just over £1 million) on December 24
- Total deliveries: £10 million by September 1826; gold sourced from
  France, Italy, Holland, Germany, Russia, Turkey, Austria

> "Had it not been for the most extraordinary exertions—above all on
> the part of old Rothschild—the Bank must have stopped payment."
> — Wellington, 1839

- Scale of crisis: 73 of 770 country banks failed; country came within
  48 hours of "putting stop to all dealings between man and man except
  by barter" (Huskisson's own admission)
- Ferguson's interpretation: rescue was part of Nathan's campaign to
  dominate the London bullion market, not pure altruism — but the crisis
  was itself the product of policies Nathan had opposed
- **Broader significance**: brothers were establishing the system of
  **international monetary co-operation** later performed routinely by
  central banks; their bullion market dominance now rivalled their bond
  market dominance

### The Rothschilds vs. Barings

- **Byron** in *Don Juan*: Baring and Rothschild "reigned over royalists and
  liberals" and could "seat a nation or upset a throne" — erred only in
  treating them as financial equals
- By 1825 they were not equals; as early as August 1820 the Bremen delegate
  to the German Confederation's Diet identified Rothschild power as unique:

> "This house has, through its enormous financial transactions and its
> banking and credit connections, actually achieved the position of a
> real Power; it has to such an extent acquired control of the general
> money market that it is in a position either to hinder or to promote,
> as it feels inclined, the movements and operations of potentates,
> and even of the greatest European Powers."
> — Bremen delegate to Frankfurt Diet, c. 1820

- **Simon Moritz von Bethmann** (Frankfurt banker): "N. M. Rothschild…
  constitutes the centrifugal point around which the stock exchange revolves.
  He alone determines the exchange, buying and selling £100,000 each day."

---

## Chapter 5: "Hue and Cry" (1826–1829)

### The Rothschilds as Public Figures

- Rothschilds became famous in the 1820s; as early as 1816 **Carl** noticed
  "these days a lot is written about us in consequence of the freedom of
  the Press"
- Carl complained to Amschel: "We are every day in the news" — absurd rumors
  circulated (e.g., that Amschel was to become Minister at the Diet)
- Amschel: "People think we are ten times as rich as we really are"
- **James** relished the fame: "It is indeed nice to possess so much prestige…
  'Il n'a jamais existé à Paris une maison aussi fameuse que la nôtre'"
- **Salomon** philosophical about caricatures: "As you say, so are kings and
  emperors… May God grant that this is the worst thing that ever happens to us"
- Nathan's attitude: "*Gagesh* [nobody] is not being written about"

### Public Relations: Vilification More Than Glorification

- Most Rothschild publicity was **hostile**, not laudatory
- Three distinct sources of anti-Rothschild sentiment:
  1. **Religious antipathy** — Jewish success in Restoration era was source
     of irritation to those who opposed post-Revolutionary religious equality
  2. **Economic rivalry** — Frankfurt bankers, Parisian rivals, London
     competitors envied meteoric rise; would have applied even without religion
  3. **Political radicalism** — identification with Holy Alliance and conservative
     regimes made them targets for liberal critics

- Ferguson's key point: **anti-Rothschaftildism ≠ anti-Semitism**; some of
  their most determined opponents were other Jews (e.g., Kassel)

### Frankfurt: The Bethmann Rivalry

- **Simon Moritz von Bethmann** — hitherto Frankfurt's pre-eminent banker —
  viewed Rothschild rise with relative equanimity initially
- Sept. 1815: actively sought partnership with Salomon and James; described
  Salomon as "a very estimable man of character"
- Feb. 1822: "The five Rothschild brothers are a remarkable phenomenon of
  our time. What they lack in genius they make up for with relentless activity,
  an enviable unity and mutual consideration."
- His mood changed when excluded from the 1821 Neapolitan loan: "I do not
  think it fair that I should commit myself to you for months while you retain
  the option to withdraw"
- German caricatures emphasized "unfair" Jewish business methods:
  - **I. Nussgeig's *Musterreiter***: Carl as "Blauschild," a travelling pedlar
    with bedraggled pony bearing muskets and swords
  - Later caricature: elegant Bethmann in coach-and-four vs. scruffy Amschel
    atop a cash box that a two-headed eagle struggles to pull forward

### Anti-Jewish Violence and the "Hep" Riots

- Rothschild wealth made them symbol of Jewish social mobility — a source
  of **Gentile resentment** in Frankfurt and beyond
- **Amschel**, September 1815: "They begrudge us Jews the eyes in our heads
  [and want] to drink our blood"
- Post-war anti-Jewish pamphlets and plays proliferated; best-known: *Unser
  Verkehr* (about a cowardly Jewish soldier)
- **"Hep" riots, August 1819**: noisy crowd rampaged through Judengasse,
  chanting "Hep Hep! Jude verreck!" and vandalising houses
- Rothschild office windows broken; Amschel received death threats; crowds
  gathered to mock his ennoblement chanting "Baron Amschel"
- Riots prompted Amschel to consider **leaving Frankfurt altogether**
- **Metternich's** disapproval of the riots reinforced Rothschild conservatism:
  Habsburg Emperor had traditionally "protected" Jews from the local populace;
  proto-liberal nationalism was sometimes anti-Jewish in rhetoric
- Paradox: the closer Rothschilds drew to the established order, the easier
  for critics to identify them with it
- **Goethe** on Frankfurt's minor legal concession legalizing Jewish–Gentile
  marriage in the 1820s:

> "This scandalous law will undermine all family sense of morality…
> Who knows whether or not the all-powerful Rothschilds are behind it?"

### Anti-Rothschild Sentiment in Paris and London

**Paris:**
- 1815: rivalry-based attacks — "It's always a case of 'The Jew has done
  too well'" (Salomon to Nathan)
- 1826: **Fournier-Verneuil's *Paris*** — first major French claim that
  government was corrupt puppet of "the aristocracy of finance, the most
  unfeeling and ignoble of all aristocracies," headed by "M. le baron R."
- Fournier combined liberal politics with virulent anti-Jewish rhetoric:
  called Rothschild co-religionists a "singular race of men" who profit
  from all quarrels — an embryonic **conspiracy theory** that would expand
  for decades

**London:**
- Volume of hostile allusions probably **greater in London** than anywhere
  else, reflecting Nathan's greater importance and press freedom
- **Alexander Baring** referred to Nathan disdainfully as "the Jew" — told
  Laffitte he could not do business with a Jew because "the operation
  would be spoiled"; Baring's associates at **Hope & Co.** (Labouchère,
  Sillem) felt their "honour would suffer" getting in line with a
  "Frankfurt Jew"
- Baring's actual complaint was about Rothschild methods: working 20
  transactions simultaneously, cutting Prussia's credit then issuing
  circulars — but he instinctively framed these as "Jewish" in character
- 1818 anonymous letter to Lord Liverpool: accused "The Jew interest alias
  Mr Rothschild" of straining "every nerve to defeat your objects" on the
  cash payments resumption debate

### The "Jew and the Doctor" Affair (1827–1828)

- **Political crisis**: Lord Liverpool's illness (Feb. 1827) → **Canning** formed
  coalition of Liberal Tories (Huskisson) and Whigs, excluding Ultra-Tories
- Canning died August 1827 → **Lord Goderich** (Robinson) commissioned to
  form Cabinet; King insisted **Herries** as Chancellor
- Conflict over appointment of **Lord Althorp** as finance committee chair
  (Tierney's initiative) → Herries threatened resignation if kept, Huskisson
  if reversed; Goderich resigned January 1828 → **Wellington** formed government
- Herries demoted to Master of the Mint; replaced as Chancellor by Goulborn
- Significance: Herries identified with the King, **Sir William Knighton**
  (royal physician/private secretary), and the financial interests of
  **New Court** hostile to Huskisson
- August 1827: Ultra-Tory *Morning Chronicle* suggested Herries's Rothschild
  connections disqualified him from serving as Chancellor
- February 1828 parliamentary debate: Whig MP **Thomas Duncombe** delivered
  famous speech alleging secret influence:

> "There is…a secret influence behind the throne, whose form is never
> seen, whose name is never breathed, who has access to all the secrets
> of State…master of unbounded wealth, he boasts that he is the arbiter
> of peace and war, and that the credit of nations depends upon his nod."

- Duncombe concluded Britain's finances should not be "controlled any longer
  by a Jew, or the distribution of the patronage of the Crown operated on
  by the prescriptions of a physician"
- **Peel** (for the government) denied knowledge of any such "mysterious,
  incorporeal, incomprehensible being" — but Duncombe's speech was widely
  followed up
- *The Times* letter signed "Algernon": "We cannot suffer the destinies of
  a mighty Empire to be wielded by the unclean hands of a Jew and a
  man-midwife"
- **Thomas Babington Macaulay** (writing as "Malcolm Macgregor, jun."):
  satirical verses about the "mysterious two, / Lords of our fate,
  the Doctor and the Jew"

### Caricatures: "The Jew and the Doctor"

- Two Cruikshank cartoons inspired by Thomas Dibdin's 1800 play *The Jew
  and the Doctor* (original play: a generous Jew raises a Christian child)
- Cartoons invert the story: Nathan portrayed trying to **bribe Wellington**
- **Illustration 5.ii** (George/Robert Cruikshank): Nathan as pot-bellied angel
  descending with bags of gold toward Herries ("Ex-Clerk, Ex-Commissary,
  Ex-Auditor, Ex-Secretary, Ex-Chancellor"), speaking mock-German-Jewish
  dialect: "Si help me Cot! de *Sinking Job* will go to de Bottom"
- **Illustration 5.iii** (Robert Cruikshank, March 1828): Nathan with sack
  marked "Old Rags" approaching Wellington: "By Cot dat Doctor is von tam
  Jew—he want my perquist—you know fat I do for you"
- Recurrent theme: **tottering government** inextricably tied to both a corrupt
  court and a corrupting banker; Wellington sits on coffin "Hic Iacit
  the Constitution"
- 1828 cartoon *An Untoward Event, or a Tory Triumph*: Nathan asked to help
  carry Wellington; replies "we'll not put our shoulders to it. He's no Daniel"
- Old Corruption and New Corruption portrayed as **two sides of the same coin**
- Pattern across cartoons: Nathan's Jewishness is always exaggerated —
  accent, appearance, company — whether the cartoon's primary target is
  religious identity or financial/political power

### Ferguson's Analytical Point

- **Duncombe** was a genuine maverick liberal who supported Chartism and
  Italian/Hungarian nationalism — and apparently also attempted to write
  *The Jews of England, Their History and Wrongs* (never completed)
- He and **Fournier** in France represent liberals of the 1820s who saw no
  contradiction in attacking conservative ministers and Jewish financiers
- Anti-Jewish rhetoric in this period still belonged to the **political left**,
  not the right — it would only later migrate exclusively to the right
- Anti-Rothschild hostility was a "synthesis of economic envy and religious
  antipathy, with an admixture of political radicalism"

<!-- pp. 221-240 -->

## Chapter 5 (continued): The Politics of the New Court Jews

### From Canning to Wellington

- **George Canning** vs. **Castlereagh**: both skeptical of "regenerating" Europe,
  but Canning pursued British interests with minimal regard for other great powers
- Canning's famous formulation: "For *Europe* I shall be desirous *now* and *then*
  to read *England*" — deliberately excluded wishes of other governments
- The Rothschilds had no objection to Canning's recognition of Latin American
  republics or refusal to sanction the French intervention in Spain
- But Canning's late moves (April–August 1827 as PM) alarmed them:
  - Sent troops to Portugal to support **Queen Maria** against **Dom Miguel**
    (Miguel backed by Bourbon Spain, backed by France)
  - This raised prospect of Anglo-French confrontation — Rothschilds now acutely
    aware of their stake in great-power peace (war destroys consol/rente prices)
  - Canning's anti-Turkish, pro-Russian policy over **Greece** also alarmed them:
    sent Wellington to St. Petersburg (April 1826) to agree joint Anglo-Russian
    settlement; joint naval force defeated Ottomans at **Navarino** (autumn 1827)

> "Cannon fire is bad for money" — Villèle's summary of Rothschild logic on war

- **Two reasons** Rothschilds opposed Canning's Eastern policy:
  1. They shared Metternich's pro-Turkish stance (failed 1825 Constantinople loan)
  2. Relations with St. Petersburg had soured since **Count Kankrin** became
     Finance Minister — openly called the Rothschilds' 1822 Russian loan "useless"

- James as early as November 1826: "It would be a mortal sin to be dependent
  on a Canning"
- When Canning received a Paris speech via Rothschild couriers 12 hours before
  the British embassy's official report, he was furious — wrote ambassador
  demanding the F.O. establish its own Paris communications to prevent
  Rothschild from obtaining official papers first

### Wellington as the Preferred Prime Minister (1828)

- **Duke of Wellington** emerged as PM in January 1828 — Nathan was delighted
- Wellington disapproved of Canning's foreign policy, shared the King's view
  that Canning had "played into the Tsar's hands" by turning against Britain's
  "ancient ally," the Sultan
- Nathan to Carl: "Consols have gone up because of our [new] Ministers. Praise be
  to God that we have good news, as Russia will wait [before further military
  action], through Wellington everybody is for peace"
- When asked what the City thought of Wellington, Nathan said they had
  "unbounded confidence in him"
- Concrete financial support for Wellington's foreign policy:
  - Purchased £1 million in exchequer bills (1828)
  - Purchased £3 million in exchequer bills (1829)
  - Provided **Dom Miguel** £50,000 "under the guarantee of the British Government"
    to take office as Regent in Portugal
  - Floated a **£769,000 loan** to Pedro, Emperor of Brazil, to stabilize
    Brazilian finances (still reeling from 1825 Latin American debt crisis)

- When Russia renewed hostilities against Turkey (1828), Rothschilds:
  - Politely declined a Russian loan request
  - Hoped for Russian military reversal throughout the campaign
  - After Russia's victory and the **Treaty of Adrianople** (September 1829),
    hastened to offer services to facilitate the indemnity payment anyway

- Rothschild pacifism clearly articulated: Nathan to Salomon on the Russia question:

> "There are some here who want us [Britain] to quarrel . . . with [the Russian
> ambassador] Lieven . . . I must tell you Wellington and Peel would like to
> quarrel with Russia, but in the end we should have to go to war. I am not for
> demonstrations, and we must see to maintaining peace. What's the good of
> quarrelling?"

- James quantified the stakes: if England earnestly attacked over the Turkish issue,
  rentes would fall at least 5 per cent; better reports would yield only a "small
  improvement" — asymmetric downside for war
- **Peace = bond market stability** became a first principle of Rothschild policy
  for the coming decade

---

### Strings of Influence

- The conspiracy theorists of the 1820s were closest to the truth when they
  alleged that **private financial interests** also shaped Rothschild political ties
- It was standard practice for European politicians of the era to accept favors
  from bankers — investment tips to outright bribes
- Amschel privately admitted they believed Jews "could not get by without bribing
  and that the Gentiles have the advantage"

### Three Mechanisms of Financial Influence

**1. Distributing bond stakes to officials:**
- 1818: Frankfurt house distributed shares in new **Prussian loan** to Frankfurt
  bankers (Bethmann, Gontard), sleeping partner **Buderus**, Austrian
  representative at Bundestag **Count Buol**, and other diplomatic corps members
- In Paris: political figures offered Prussian bonds included **Talleyrand**

**2. Personal loans to key individuals:**
- **Louis XVIII**: Nathan advanced £200,000 on behalf of British government for
  cost of return to France (1814); Nathan insisted on repayment with interest
  three years later — did not endear him to the Bourbons
- **Duc d'Orléans** (future **Louis Philippe**): loans in the 1820s — a more
  long-term investment that "paid ample dividends" in the subsequent decade
- **Prince Hardenberg's son-in-law**: received Prussian loans
- **Wilhelm von Humboldt** (Prussian ambassador in London) and **Rother**
  (key official in 1818 loan negotiations): given banking accounts which
  effectively functioned as overdraft facilities — Salomon offered Caroline
  von Humboldt point blank "whether he could be of any use in the matter of money"

**3. Gifts:**
- Carl: "One must have something when going to see the great and good,
  either gossip or something to show them"
- Nathan sent Amschel two tortoises (1816) to give to the Elector of Hesse-Kassel
  (arrived dead; Amschel had them stuffed and presented them anyway)
- Other gift requests: jeweled caskets, a horse "suitable for a lady," carved
  knife and fork with ivory handles "for someone who helped us"

### Key British Beneficiaries

- **Herries** — "your own Buderus over there" (Salomon's phrase); regular
  participant in post-war loans like the 1817 Paris city loan
- **Lord Stewart** (Castlereagh's brother, British representative in Paris):
  asked Salomon and James in October 1817 "to speculate for him in rentes";
  became "very friendly with us. Between ourselves he likes to gamble"
  — Salomon let him share in business to the amount of 50,000 francs rentes
- Mayer Amschel's precept recalled: "if a high-placed person enters into a
  financial partnership with a Jew, he belongs to the Jew"
- **Lord Melbourne's** brother **Frederick** received investment tips from James
  during his time as ambassador in Vienna
- British Treasury officials who directly borrowed from Rothschilds:
  - **George Harrison**: owed over £3,000 in 1825
  - **Charles Arbuthnot**: borrowed four times as much; privately referred to
    by brothers as a "bribery" relationship

### Wellington and King George IV

- **Wellington** banked with Rothschilds for a time — introduced by Lord Stewart
  to Salomon and James; not financially important (little overdraft use per
  surviving 1825 balance sheet) but Salomon prized the prestige:

> "It is a great honour . . . You may say, 'What does honour matter? Honour
> is not money.' As an honest man I tell you that now I prefer honour to money.
> One cannot do more [with money] than to eat . . . food does not taste good
> without honour. Wellington stands here higher in public esteem than the king
> himself." — Salomon Rothschild

- **King George IV** — relationship predated his accession by 15 years:
  - Earliest document: Mayer Amschel's hand, 1805 — bills of exchange from
    Prince George totaling 150,000 Frankfurt gulden (discounted in balance
    sheet at only 127,784 gulden, deemed questionable)
  - George had borrowed from the **Elector of Hesse-Kassel** in the 1790s;
    Mayer Amschel likely bought the debt from the Elector
  - Total royal debts acquired: Prince Regent owed **£109,000**, Duke of York
    **£55,000**, Duke of Clarence **£20,000** = **£184,000** total
  - Purchased in return for face value in consols — "far more than they were worth"
    superficially, but Nathan saw it as an "inspired investment" — a "master-stroke"
  - Salomon: "This makes me a very powerful man"
  - By end of 1817, Nathan was providing intelligence to the "Milan commission"
    gathering evidence against **Princess Caroline of Brunswick** (George wanted
    to divorce her)
  - 1822 (after George's accession): **£50,000 loan** secured on Hanoverian
    revenues; year later a further **£125,000** requested
  - Key intermediary: **George Harrison** (who shortly after borrowed personally
    from Nathan)

### The Saxe-Coburg Connection

- 1816: Princess Charlotte (Prince Regent's only child) betrothed to
  **Leopold of Saxe-Coburg** — Carl immediately cultivated Leopold in Frankfurt,
  extended him a bill for £700 and letter of credit
- Nathan soon entrusted with delivering Leopold's private correspondence to Germany;
  by August 1816, a loan of 10,000 gulden was under discussion
- When **Princess Charlotte died** (1817), brothers were so emotionally stricken
  they couldn't do business:

> "We lost our heads . . . It pains me very badly, this unfortunate event . . .
> money, honours are worth nothing, we are all only dust" — Salomon to Nathan

- But: Salomon urged Nathan to *increase* friendship toward the now-widowed Leopold:
  "I ask you to show him more feeling than hitherto"
- Leopold stayed in England; Rothschilds arranged life insurance for him and
  his father; Carl hosted him at his Naples villa (1826)
- Strategy proved "extremely shrewd": the **House of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha** and the
  House of Rothschild — both obscure German families that rose from obscurity
  to prominence during the 19th century — developed an almost **symbiotic
  relationship**
- Frankfurt house lent Saxe-Coburgs 3.5 million gulden between 1837 and 1842
- Rothschilds supported family members as they left Coburg to claim thrones
  across Europe
- When Duke of Kent (Prince Regent's brother) went to marry **Victoria of
  Saxe-Coburg** (producing future Queen Victoria), he took a letter of credit
  on the Frankfurt Rothschilds; Nathan offered Duke of Kent financial advice and
  exclusive messenger service; in 1823 lent **£400,000 gulden** to Prince of
  Leiningen (Duchess of Kent's son from first marriage)

### Metternich: The Prototype Relationship

- **Prince Klemens von Metternich** — dominant figure of European politics
  1809–1848 — also banked with Salomon
- Ferguson describes Metternich–Salomon as the prototype for the later
  **Bismarck–Bleichröder** relationship, except Metternich became emotionally
  and intellectually closer to his banker
- Despite aristocratic estates in the Mosel valley, Metternich was chronically
  "cash-poor" throughout his career
- Within a year of first meetings (Paris peace negotiations, 1815), he raised
  the possibility of a 300,000 gulden loan; brothers limited themselves to
  routine banking and occasional gifts (e.g., Wedgwood china, 1821) — too risky
  to lend heavily to a single individual
- October 1821: Metternich (with mistress **Princess Dorothy de Lieven**)
  publicly accepted Rothschild hospitality — "taking soup" with Amschel in
  Frankfurt; interpreted as a calculated gesture of support for the Frankfurt
  Jewish community during the civil rights controversy
- Less than a year later: 900,000 gulden loan — agreed just **six days** before
  the brothers received the title of **baron** from the Emperor
- The loan "sealed the friendship": thereafter Metternich received cash from
  Salomon at Verona (1823) for personal expenses; James hosted Metternich and
  "representatives of the Holy Alliance" at a lavish Paris dinner (1825)

> "Thus does the power of gold reconcile all the ranks and all the religions.
> One of the more curious spectacles of our time—rich as it is in contrasts—
> is that of the representatives of the Holy Alliance established in the name of
> Jesus Christ attending a banquet given by a Jew on the day that the law of
> sacrilege is being debated in the chambers." — *Constitutionnel* newspaper

- By end of 1820s, Rothschilds provided Metternich an **unofficial diplomatic
  channel** — he relayed political views indirectly to other governments through
  them; Salomon supplied him news from London, Paris, Frankfurt, Naples
- 1825–26: Metternich repaid much of the 1822 loan, then immediately took a
  new loan of **1,040,000 gulden** (c. £110,000) — half used to purchase the
  Plass estate, rest taken as cash
- His personal debt grew to nearly **70,000 gulden** by 1828; Frankfurt house
  advanced an additional 117,000 gulden to son Viktor
- Relationship maintained through gifts: American deer for Metternich's estate
  (1841), mother-of-pearl box from Paris for Princess Melanie, "lovely things
  to the Metternich children" at Christmas 1843
- **David Parish** (bankrupt banker), on eve of his suicide, accused the
  Rothschilds of using Metternich to exclude him from Austrian and Neapolitan
  loans — alleged Salomon had "understood better than I how to draw you into
  their [sphere of] interest"

### The Esterházy Connection

- **Prince Esterházy** — immense Hungarian estates, links to wealthier Thurn
  und Taxis family — among the most important (and problematic) Austrian clients
- Borrowed £10,000 (1820) and 300,000 gulden (1822); three years later Salomon
  partnered with **Arnstein & Eskeles** and **Simon G. Sina** for a 6.5 million
  gulden loan at 6% secured on Esterházy's estates — meant to "definitively
  reorder" family finances
- Instead: Esterházy ran continuous overdrafts — £28,000 in London (1825),
  2,300 gulden in Vienna (1828); by 1832 total debts reached 827,000 gulden
- 1836: another 7 million gulden lottery loan (after son Paul succeeded);
  1844: another 6.4 million gulden loan — chronic borrower for decades
- Esterházy "spoke very flatteringly of the family" to third parties;
  financial ties were inseparable from social and political ties

### Friedrich von Gentz: Purchased PR

- **Friedrich von Gentz** — Metternich's secretary; "intelligent, conservative
  and thoroughly venal man of letters — a kind of Central European Edmund Burke
  gone wrong"
- Had long sold his influence in Vienna for cash; before Rothschilds, regarded
  **David Parish** as "the matador, the pearl of the merchant class of all
  Christendom" (opinion linked to a 100,000 gulden stake in the 1818 Austrian loan)
- The Rothschilds purchased his allegiance: at Aix (1818), Salomon handed him
  800 ducats supposedly from a successful British stocks speculation; regular
  business thereafter
- Gentz's diary repeatedly notes "very agreeable communications" from Salomon,
  "important financial arrangements," "a proof of real friendship," and "highly
  welcome financial transactions with the excellent Rothschild"
- By 1829: Gentz's total debts to Salomon and other bankers exceeded 30,000
  gulden; Salomon eventually paid him an **annual retainer** (dispensing with
  fiction the loans would be repaid)
- What Gentz provided in return:
  1. News and access to Metternich
  2. **Public relations** — first Rothschild foray into press management:
     - 1821: Wrote twice to editor of *Allgemeine Zeitung* expressing "grave
       dissatisfaction" about anti-Rothschild articles; threatened Austrian ban
       on the paper if it continued; editor promised never to accept material
       "relating to the House of Rothschild (at least affecting its relations
       with Austria)"
     - 1822: Arranged newspaper article on Salomon receiving a Russian decoration
     - 1826: Wrote the first **"official" history** of the Rothschild family,
       published in the *Brockhaus Encyclopaedia* — described as attempt to
       "briefly and I hope not infelicitously to explain the phenomenon of the
       greatness of this House"
  3. In 1831, with Gentz's influence waning, Salomon made overtures to satirist
     **Saphir** to win him as a pro-Austrian/pro-Rothschild publicist

---

### Money Makes Money

- Ferguson's key argument: the conspiracy theorists misunderstood — it was **NOT**
  the network of favors and bribes that made the Rothschilds dominant. It was the
  **sheer scale and sophistication of their operations**
- Capital comparison (Rothschilds vs. **Baring Brothers**):

| Year | Rothschild capital | Baring capital |
|------|-------------------|----------------|
| 1815 | £500,000 (max)   | £374,365       |
| 1818 | £1,772,000       | £429,318       |
| 1825 | £4,082,000       | £452,654       |
| 1828 | £4,330,333       | £309,803       |

- From rough equality in 1815, Rothschild resources grew to **more than ten times**
  Barings' in as many years; Barings' capital actually *declined* while
  Rothschilds' increased by a **factor of eight**
- Key mechanism: Rothschilds **reinvested** the bulk of profits back into the
  firm; Barings tended to distribute profits to partners even in loss years —
  preventing capital accumulation
- By 1836 (next contractual settlement): Rothschild capital reached **£6,007,707**

### Market Dominance in Government Lending (1818–1832)

- **N. M. Rothschild** alone handled **7 of 26** foreign government loans
  contracted in London — roughly **38%** of total value (**£37.6 million**)
- More than twice the value of nearest rival, **B. A. Goldschmidt**
- Bank's own figures (per Ayer): total loans issued by Nathan may have been
  **£86 million** in this period
- **Frankfurt house**: 28 million gulden (c. £2.5 million) in government loans
- **Paris (James)**: near monopoly over French government finance — 7 loans with
  nominal capital of **1.5 billion francs (£60 million)** between 1823 and 1847

> "The house of Rotschild [sic] is merely a necessary consequence of the
> principle of state which has governed Europe since 1815; if it had not been
> a Rotschild, it would simply have been someone else . . . Rotschild reigns
> and governs on the bourse and in all the cabinets . . ."
> — **Alexandre Weill**, French journalist, 1844

- Ferguson's verdict: Weill was "too deterministic" — there had been moments
  in the 1820s when European state "principles" could have called the Rothschilds
  back out of existence. But his core judgment stood:
- **"If there was a sixth great power in the 1820s, it was no longer Barings,
  but Rothschilds."**

<!-- pp. 241-260 -->

## Chapter 6: Amschel's Garden

### Escape from the Judengasse

- In 1815, nearly all Rothschild wealth was in paper (bonds, securities)
  and precious metal — no real estate outside Frankfurt
- Inside the old **Judengasse**: the *Stammhaus* "zum grünen Schild,"
  where the brothers had grown up; their mother **Gutle** continued
  to live there until her death (a curiosity to observers)
- **Carl** by 1817 had enough of his third-floor room: "one is getting
  old. Also [it is galling] that one should make much money and
  live a dog's life while others who have not a tenth of our fortune
  live like princes"
- First escape: Salomon permitted to move to Schäfergasse, 1807
- Real break: **Amschel** bought suburban house on road to Bockenheim,
  1811 (10 Bockenheimer Landstrasse) — "for the first time, he found
  himself living in fresh air"

### Amschel's Garden — Symbol of Emancipation

- Amschel became consumed with acquiring the adjacent garden plot —
  a small suburban plot of a few acres, comparable to those owned by
  Gentile banking families like the **Bethmanns** and **Gontards**
- Not mere social status — he genuinely fell in love with open space
  after forty-two years in the cramped, pungent ghetto
- Spring 1815: in an act Ferguson compares to the prisoners' release
  into "free air" in Beethoven's *Fidelio* (1805), Amschel slept in
  the garden and wrote excitedly to Carl:

> "Dear Carl, I am sleeping in the garden. If God allows that the
> accounts work out as you and I want them to, I will buy it . . .
> There is so much space that you, God willing, and the whole family
> can comfortably live in it."

- **Nathan** backed Amschel against Carl's preference for a large town
  house, calling Carl's objections "a lot of nonsense"
- April 1816: part of garden bought; bidding for additional two-thirds
  of an acre. When he finally owned it all: "From today onwards the
  garden belongs to me and to my dear brothers"
- Brothers sent seeds and plants (including **African seeds from
  Alexander von Humboldt**); **Gutle** made frequent visits
- 1820s: house substantially enlarged in neo-classical style by
  architect **Friedrich Rumpf**; later added a pond, fountain,
  medieval folly
- Garden held **religious significance**: Tabernacles feast (*Sukkot*)
  could now be celebrated properly in a tent amid greenery
- **Political dimension**: under old Frankfurt statutes, Jews were
  forbidden from owning property outside the Judengasse and even from
  walking in public gardens — Amschel feared the Senate would
  block or confiscate the purchase
- The **"Hep" riots** brought abusive crowds outside the garden;
  when he was allowed to keep it, he suspected it was "a kind of
  bribe" to prevent him leaving Frankfurt
- By the mid-1830s a guidebook described the garden in semi-satirical
  terms:

> "The flowers are glittering in gold and the beds are fertilised with
> crown thalers, the summer houses are well papered with Rothschild
> bonds . . . each flower twinkles with ducats from Kremnitz rather
> than with leaves . . . Amschel von Rothschild resembles a lord in
> his seraglio."

### "Good Jews" — Refusal to Convert

- Conversion to Christianity would have made Amschel's garden far
  easier to acquire; the Rothschilds' refusal to convert was a
  defining fact of their family and business history
- **Ludwig Börne** (himself born a Jew) noted with grudging admiration:

> "they have declined the holy water of Christianity. Baptism is now
> the order of the day among rich Jews, and the gospel that was
> preached in vain to the poor of Judaea now flourishes among the
> wealthy."

- **Benjamin Disraeli** was also impressed: his character Younger
  Sidonia in *Coningsby* (partly based on **Lionel**) is "as firm in
  his adherence to the code of the great Legislator as if the
  trumpet still sounded on Sinai . . . proud of his origin"
- **Carl**, 1814: "I am a Jew in the depths in my heart." In Berlin
  he refused to marry a wealthy Gentile woman — "We have made our
  fortune as Jews and we want nothing to do with such people"
- Brothers viewed Bavarian banker **Adolph d'Eichthal** with suspicion
  precisely because he was a convert ("a mere 'goy' would have been
  less objectionable"). **James**: "It is a bad thing when one has
  to deal with an apostate."
- When Hamburg banker **Oppenheim** had his children baptised in
  1818, Carl sneered: "The only reason I find these people
  contemptible is that when they convert to Christianity they adopt
  only what is bad but nothing that is good in it."
- Brothers saw themselves as **role models**: every social success
  they achieved without converting weakened the argument for
  conversion — which most Jews undertook as a response to legal
  discrimination
- **James**, 1816: "we are still young and we want to work. And [as]
  much for the sake of our prestige as Jews as for any other reason"
- Amschel framed **Nathan's appointment as Austrian consul** in London
  as serving "the Jewish interest. You will prevent the apostasy of
  quite a few Vienna Jews."
- When a French encyclopaedia alleged Salomon had been baptised,
  he insisted the error be corrected in all subsequent editions

### Religious Observance — Degrees of Strictness

- **Amschel**: most orthodox; "invariably eschewing work on the
  Sabbath, keeping kosher strictly," regarded as "the most religious
  Jew in Frankfurt"; by 1840s had built a synagogue in his own house
- **Salomon**: kept kosher even when entertaining Metternich; refused
  to write letters on Sabbath and holy days
- **Nathan**: confirmed to "all the rites and ceremonies of our faith"
  even in Manchester; *shamas* brought him the palm branch daily
  during Tabernacle festival; Prince Pückler found him "unexpectedly
  well informed" on religion; wife **Hannah** subscribed to the
  orthodox Ashkenazim institution in London and monitored children's
  conduct closely
- **Mayer** warned at Cambridge (1837) to "avoid everything possible
  in infringing upon our religious duties," specifically to "abstain
  from these indulgences such as riding on Horseback on Saturdays"
- **James** kept a *mahzor* (holiday prayer book) in his office; on
  circumcision of a new son: "we have one more good Jew in the family"
- Younger brothers (Nathan, Carl, James) wrote business letters on
  the Sabbath when necessary — covertly if with Amschel
- One by one they abandoned strict kosher diet (English family still
  avoided pork); Heine joked James had "not gone over to the
  Christian Church" but had "gone over to Christian cooking"
- **Carl** to Amschel on religious laxity: "As to piety, when I am
  old I will be pious too. In my heart I am nothing but a Jew."
- Next generation split further: London Rothschilds found Paris
  branch too lax; Frankfurt **Reform movement** disturbed them
  (worshipped too much like Protestants)
- **Wilhelm Carl** (Carl's son) went to the opposite extreme of
  ultra-Orthodoxy; Hannah reported to Lionel on him with bemused
  concern, reassured he showed "nothing . . . to fear, that this
  religious devotion will be followed by fanaticism"
- Amschel withdrew a 150,000-gulden synagogue donation when the
  community chose a non-Orthodox rabbi; Anthony: "You have no idea
  what a parcel of Donkeys . . . the Jews are here"
- Rothschilds' religious activism was practical: **Nathan was
  *Parnass*** (warden) of the Great Synagogue in Duke Place; backed
  combining the three major Ashkenazi synagogues — foreshadowing
  the later **United Synagogue**

### Charity — "Kings of the Jews"

- Rothschilds had mythic status in the eyes of poorer Jews: "not only
  'the Jews of the Kings' but also the 'Kings of the Jews'"
- Classic *Schnorrer* anecdotes (unabashed Jewish scroungers) cast
  "Rothschild" as their long-suffering but ultimately indulgent
  victim — echoes of real era when their wealth gave them talismanic
  status
- Rothschild archives contain unsolicited requests from Jewish
  communities worldwide: Dublin Hebrew Congregation, New Hebrew
  Congregation at Liverpool, St Alban's Place Synagogue, etc.
- **Nathan's charitable institutions**: Bread, Meat and Coal Society
  (*Meshebat Naphesh*); Jews' Hospital (*Nevé Zedek*) at Mile End
  (vice-president, later president); Holy Society for the Assistance
  of the Poor; Bethnal Green Society for Relief of the Sick Poor;
  Governor of London Hospital (1826)
- **Main charitable interest: education**. Supported Jews' Free School
  in Spitalfields, donating 10 guineas to building fund (1817);
  N. M. Rothschild & Sons gave an average of **£9,500 a year** to
  the school throughout the 19th century — more than doubled by
  individual family benefactions
- Amschel gave 10% of Frankfurt house's **running costs** (not income)
  to the poor; in 1825 brothers donated 100,000 gulden to build a
  new Jewish hospital in Frankfurt "as a memorial to filial respect
  and fraternal harmony"
- **James** kept a low profile in Paris, channelling contributions
  through intermediaries (**Salomon Alkan**, **Albert Cohn**); in
  1836 stipulated donations to new synagogue be kept secret
- Rothschilds did **not** confine charity to Jews: donated at times
  of hardship in 1814 Germany, 1830 France, 1842 Hamburg, 1846
  Ireland without religious distinction
- Nathan's children supported London Orphan Asylum, London
  Philanthropic Society, Buckinghamshire General Infirmary; Charlotte
  was "one of the most liberal contributors" to a Church of England
  school at Ealing (1837)
- *Schnorrer* applying to Rothschilds included early socialist
  **Robert Owen** and a congregation of the Scottish Free Church

### "A Heavenly Good Deed": The Emancipation Struggle

- Rothschilds never lost sight of continued legal discrimination
  against Jews post-1815; Mayer Amschel's deathbed injunction: "bring
  to an end all the work . . . in the interest of our people"
- **Jewish emancipation** = gradual process of achieving full legal
  equality in European states; Rothschild involvement driven by
  moral obligation, not just self-interest
- Amschel, 1815: "I remain your brother, who wishes you, and me, and
  all Jews, all the best, Amschel Rothschild"
- **Legal landscape after 1815**:
  - *France*: best situation; Bourbons preserved Revolutionary
    emancipation; Napoleon's *décret infâme* (1808) not renewed;
    Jews excluded from political life before 1830 but few economic
    barriers
  - *Britain*: native-born Jews were British subjects but excluded
    from parliament, local government, ancient universities (along
    with Catholics and Non-Conformists before 1828-9)
  - *Prussia*: emancipation edict of 1812 gave equal legal rights;
    in practice excluded from bureaucracy and officer corps; after
    1822 also excluded from schoolteaching and municipal government
  - *Austria*: worst — denied right to own land, special poll tax,
    marriage restrictions, required "toleration permit" renewable
    every three years. Lionel (1827): "Jews are very much oppressed,
    they can hold no situation under Government nor possess any land
    property, not even a house in the town"
  - Salomon could only rent accommodation in Vienna; 1831 request
    to convert wealth to real property turned down despite argument
    it would "attract considerable capital sums to the country
    which will become subject to taxation"
  - *Frankfurt/western Germany*: **Dalberg's 1811 decree** giving
    Jews full citizenship effectively suspended after French withdrawal;
    March 1814 special Jewish oath reintroduced; membership of
    citizens' assembly restricted to Christians again

### Congress of Vienna — The Campaign Begins

- **Salomon's wife Caroline** first to spot the opportunity and urge
  action (July 1814, before her husband or brothers acted):

> "This matter interests me so much that, if I catch a simple word
> about it, I listen eagerly . . . Can't you, my dearest Salomon,
> contribute to this through your acquaintances over there? This
> would be a heavenly good deed, which cannot be bought even with
> very much money."

- Amschel and Carl lobbied actively; key contacts:
  - **Isaac Gumprecht** — leader of Frankfurt Jews in Vienna
  - **Jacob Baruch** (Ludwig Börne's father) and lawyer **August Jassoy**
  - Carl asked Nathan whether **Castlereagh** "could possibly help
    in the question of the civil rights with regard to the Jews"
- Placed great hopes on Prussian Chancellor **Hardenberg** — architect
  of Prussian emancipation; urged Nathan to send gifts to the
  Prussian Finance Minister Bülow's wife
- **Wilhelm von Humboldt** (Prussian diplomat) more scrupulous:
  refused a gift of three emerald rings from the Jewish delegation
  in 1814; two years later Amschel offered to buy caskets from him
  at an excessive price "if by it something could be achieved"
- Also courted **Metternich** — Salomon asked Nathan to make a
  speculative £20,000 British stocks purchase for "the great man
  who does everything for [the] Jews"

### Defeat and Setback

- Critical defeat: **Article 16 of the German *Bundesakte*** (June
  1815) — at suggestion of Bremen Bürgermeister Smidt, text changed
  from rights granted "in" to rights granted "by" the German states,
  effectively invalidating all Napoleonic measures and leaving the
  issue to individual states
- Brothers continued pressure after Napoleon's Hundred Days disruption;
  Amschel to brothers in Paris: "strike while the iron is hot"
- Salomon secured promises of support from both Metternich and
  Hardenberg → Austria and Prussia sent letters urging Frankfurt to
  uphold 1811 Dalberg agreement
- **Obstruction**: Baron vom Stein regarded as having "turned against
  the Jews"; British representative the Earl of Clancarty was "no
  friend of our people"; Austrian delegate Count Buol-Schauenstein
  shared Frankfurt's view that Jews "will soon overshadow Christian
  firms"
- **Frankfurt's October 1816 constitution**: confirmed equality of
  Christian citizens only; Jews left as second-class *Schutzgenossen*
  ("protected comrades"); authorities cited Amschel's garden as
  evidence of their "enlightened attitude" — which only made Amschel
  a target for those wanting stricter measures
- Kassel (Electoral Hesse): Jews got citizenship in return for
  payment, but with economic restrictions on real estate; Carl
  privately: the Elector was "an expert when it comes to going back
  on his word"
- Frankfurt Jewish community wrote to brothers (Sept 1816):
  "how tirelessly and eagerly you are working for us . . . [T]he
  good results which we were justified in hoping for have not been
  achieved"

### Financial Leverage as Political Weapon

- After Frankfurt defeat, Amschel angrily talked of "hurting" Gentile
  bankers "by doing business, even if it entails losses"
- Some German Jews looked to Nathan as an English *deus ex machina*;
  Hamburg Jew **Meyerstein** to Nathan (1819): "I think it might be
  easy to improve our lot should you approach the Prince Regent . . .
  it is from your direction that we expect the sun to rise also for us"
- Nathan credited with securing support from the Dutch King and
  protecting Jewish communities in Corfu and Hanover
- **"Hep" riots, August 1819**: anti-Jewish violence — paradoxically
  strengthened Rothschild hand against Frankfurt authorities
- James to Vienna banker **David Parish** (letter intended for
  Metternich's eyes):

> "What can be the result of such disturbances? Surely they can only
> have the effect of causing all the rich people of our nation to
> leave Germany . . . Who buys state bonds in Germany and who has
> endeavoured to raise the rate of exchange if it be not our nation?
> Has not our example engendered a certain confidence in the state
> loans so that Christian firms have also taken heart? . . . It seems
> to me to be really necessary that Austria and Prussia should devise
> measures to be applied by the Senate at Frankfurt for energetically
> dealing with [the agitators]."

- Rothschilds sought stronger Prussian support during negotiations
  for **1818 sterling loan**; raised the issue at the **Congress of
  Aix** — Amschel argued Salomon should attend "not for business
  reasons but in the interest of the whole Jewry"
- First contact with **Friedrich Gentz** came through this issue,
  as he and Metternich passed through Frankfurt on their way to Aix

<!-- pp. 261-280 -->

## Chapter 6 (continued): Jewish Emancipation — Frankfurt, Britain, and the "Exceptional Family"

### Frankfurt Emancipation Campaign — Partial Failure

- The brothers used **financial leverage** to lobby for Frankfurt Jews:
  Bremen delegate noted "several minor states" had recourse to Rothschild
  financial power, putting them in position to ask favors —
  "protection of a few dozen Jews in a small state"
- 1820: brothers pressed **Metternich** to lean on Buol, who backed
  Frankfurt authorities; also lobbied the Baden government
- Oct 1821: Metternich visited Frankfurt, signalled sympathy by lunching
  with **Amschel**; **Salomon** reached "important financial arrangement"
  with **Gentz**
- Amschel even wrote Metternich's lover **Princess Lieven** asking for
  withdrawal of instructions regarding Frankfurt Jews
- Lieven's private response was condescending — called it "the funniest
  letter imaginable... Four pages of sentiment, begging my help for the
  Jews of his town... naive confidence... laughable and touching"
- **Result: minimal concessions.** Frankfurt's 1824 law on "private
  citizen's rights" of "Israelite citizens":
  - Excluded Jews from political life
  - Restricted economic activities
  - Subordinated community to Senate commissioner
  - Permitted only 15 Jewish marriages/year (only 2 with outsiders)
  - Restored the Jewish oath in law courts
  - Applied to ~4,530 people (over a tenth of town's population)
  - Most restrictions remained until 1848; full legal equality not until 1864

> "Frankfurt citizenship papers... are said to have dropped 99 per cent
> below par... have not the Rothschilds and the Bethmanns stood at par
> for a long time? A businessman's religion is the same all the world
> over. The businessman's... office is his church; his desk is his pew,
> his copybook is his bible, his warehouse his holiest of holies, the
> bourse bell his church bell, his gold his God, his credit his faith."
> — Heinrich Heine (sarcastic commentary)

- **Heine** and Marx both portrayed Rothschild wealth as transcending
  religion — Ferguson argues this missed the point: it was Jewish rights
  in general at stake, not Rothschild comfort

### British Jewish Emancipation Campaign (post-1828)

- Discrimination in Britain did not personally inconvenience the
  Rothschilds — Nathan could trade at the Royal Exchange freely,
  buy property where he wished; university/political exclusion irrelevant
- Yet **Nathan** felt obligated to act on behalf of the Jewish community
  even for rights he had no intention of exercising himself
- **1828–29:** Protestant Dissenters then Catholics secured political
  emancipation — Jews blocked by the **Parliamentary Oath of Abjuration**
  ("upon the true faith of a Christian")
- Nathan galvanised partly by his wife **Hannah**: she told him she would
  go to the Lord Chancellor herself if he did not
- **Moses Montefiore** (Nathan's brother-in-law) recorded Feb 22, 1829:
  Hannah's "brief but impressive language" prodded Nathan to act

> "He said he would shortly go to the Lord Chancellor and consult him
> on the matter. Hannah said if he did not, she would."
> — Moses Montefiore diary

- Nathan and **Montefiore** worked together, urging caution vs. more
  aggressive approach of **Isaac Lyon Goldsmid** (Board of Deputies)
- **Lord Lyndhurst** (Lord Chancellor) was evasive — advised Jews to
  wait until Catholic business settled, guided by "public opinion"
- Nathan petitioned for British-born Jews only (his son Lionel signed,
  not Nathan himself); former Chancellor **Vansittart** (Lord Bexley)
  agreed to present it in Lords
- Board of Deputies thanked Nathan for his "zeal and attention...
  promoting through his powerful influence a relief to the Jews of
  this Kingdom"

### Wellington's Obstruction

- **Wellington** opposed any such bill; Feb 1830 meeting: told Nathan
  government would "not commit" itself and Jews "must be at their own
  risk" if they proceed
- **Robert Grant** (Liberal Tory) introduced a bill April 5, 1830 —
  defeated 228 to 165 on second reading
- Second bill passed Commons in 1833 but foundered in Lords (Wellington
  + bishops); same pattern repeated in 1834
- During **Peel's** ministry 1834–5, Nathan signed letter urging
  government to back enfranchisement — Peel declined
- 1836: Chancellor **Thomas Spring Rice** introduced another bill —
  failed again in Lords
- **Key political shift:** Nathan, long aligned with Tories, found himself
  siding with the Whigs over emancipation; his sons later pursued
  the battle as avowed Whigs and Liberals
- **Lionel's seat** in the House of Commons would not be secured until
  22 years after his father's death

### Anti-Emancipation Imagery

- 1830 cartoon in *Looking Glass* No. 3: bearded Jew in Commons listening
  to **Macaulay's** maiden speech, declaring "It's *Liberty of Conscience*
  my peoples vants—that's all" — bill in pocket labeled "Cent per cent
  interest" (Jews = finance)
- Cartoon *The Wise Men of the East and the Marquiss of West* (McLean's,
  No. 55): Nathan depicted telling Grant "Ah well, never mind: have you
  any Spanish to sell, I'll give you 48 for it" — pun on parliamentary
  "bill" vs. financial bill; implies Jews cared more about money than
  emancipation

---

### "The Exceptional Family" — Dynasty, Endogamy, and Succession

### The Problem of Dynastic Decline

- Most 18th–19th-century family firms lasted one or two generations —
  the "**Buddenbrooks** phenomenon" (Thomas Mann immortalised it)
- **Francis Baring** wrote ruefully in 1803: "Families founded on the
  acquirements of an individual do not last above sixty years... the
  posterity of a Merchant, Banker... abandon the pursuit of their
  predecessor as beneath them, or they follow it by agents... only a
  more rapid road to ruin"
- Barings themselves survived well, relinquishing control only in 1990s
- Rothschilds took exceptional precautions to avoid dynastic decadence

### Sons and Heirs

- **Mayer Amschel's will** required male heirs; Amschel had no children;
  other brothers produced 13 sons total:
  - **Salomon**: Anselm (b. 1803)
  - **Nathan**: Lionel (1808), Anthony (1810), Nathaniel (1812), Mayer (1818)
  - **Carl**: Mayer Carl (1820), Adolph (1823), Wilhelm Carl (1828),
    Anselm Alexander (1835)
  - **James**: Alphonse (1827), Gustave (1829), Salomon (1835), Edmond (1845)
- Intense anxiety about producing male heirs into the third generation —
  Carl's sons Mayer Carl and Wilhelm Carl had ten daughters between
  them, no sons
- Third generation's first boy not until 1840 (Lionel's son Nathaniel)
- **Hannah** (Nathan's wife) took a more balanced view: "of no consequence
  to our gratification whether a boy or a girl"

### The Endogamy Strategy

- Before 1824: Rothschilds married into similar Jewish merchant families
  (Eva Hanau, Caroline Stern, Hannah Cohen, Adelheid Herz, plus Worms,
  Sichel, Montefiore, Beyfuses connections)
- After 1824: **Rothschilds married Rothschilds** — a sustained policy
  of **endogamy** (cousin marriage)
- Of 21 marriages involving Mayer Amschel's descendants 1824–1877,
  **15 were between direct descendants** — extraordinary even by
  19th-century German-Jewish business dynasty standards

> "These Rothschilds harmonise with one another in the most remarkable
> fashion. Strangely enough, they even choose marriage partners from
> among themselves and the strands of relationship between them form
> complicated knots which future historians will find difficult to
> unravel." — Heine

- **Key marriages:**
  - 1824: **James** married his niece, Salomon's daughter **Betty**
    (James 32, Betty 19)
  - 1826: Salomon's son **Anselm** married Nathan's daughter **Charlotte**
  - 1836: Nathan's son **Lionel** married Carl's daughter **Charlotte**
  - 1840: Nat married James's daughter Charlotte; Carl's son Mayer Carl
    married Nathan's daughter Louise
  - 1849–77: Pattern continued into 4th generation

### Motivations for Endogamy

- **Primary reason:** prevent the five houses drifting apart; keep
  outsiders from acquiring shares in the immense fortune
- Each marriage accompanied by detailed legal agreements on property
  - James–Betty: Betty's dowry 1.5 million francs (£60,000) remained
    her separate property; Anselm–Charlotte: Charlotte received £12,000
    from her father + £8,000 from Nathan + £1,000 from Anselm;
    Anselm received £100,000 from his father and £50,000 from Nathan
- **Social difficulty:** By mid-1820s Rothschilds so wealthy they had
  outgrown peer Jewish families; already in 1814 struggled to find
  a suitable husband for sister **Henrietta** (their original choice
  rejected because of "horrible crowd connected with the Holländers")
- **Exclusivity of partnership:** In 1836, **Joseph Montefiore**
  (Henrietta's son) asked to join the firm after Nathan's death — Lionel
  rejected this, saying "there were already too many [partners]"; then
  demanded Montefiore change his name to Rothschild — killing the idea

### Marriage Was Not Romantic

- **Carl** openly said: "I am not in love... if I knew of another, I
  would marry her"
- **Amschel** acknowledged "the one creature I ever really loved I have
  never been able to call mine"; his nephew called their marriage
  "fifty years of matrimonial struggle"
- **James** on Betty after just months of marriage: "To deprive oneself
  of one's wife is difficult... She is an essential piece of furniture"
- **Salomon** and Caroline: separated much of the time (she in Frankfurt,
  he in Vienna); by 1840s he had "a reckless enthusiasm for young girls"
- **Lionel** to Charlotte: fervent love letters from Paris, but to
  brother Anthony simultaneously said "I have no particular fancy to
  get married just immediately" — letter-writing appears partly
  auto-suggestion
- Arranged marriages tolerated premarital liaisons ("sow wild oats")
  provided nothing interfered with the intermarriage system; **Anthony**
  in 1829 overstepped by forming serious attachment with unsuitable
  Frankfurt girl — recalled home by angry father

### Genetic Risks

- **Endogamy carried hereditary risks** — Pope Gregory VI banned
  cousin marriage since 6th century; 8 US states criminalized it
  in the 19th century
- **William Cobbett** used "Rothschild married his own niece" as argument
  against Jewish emancipation
- Jewish law had no such restrictions; Frankfurt ghetto's **Stättigkeit**
  had made intermarriage almost compulsory anyway
- Medical risk: if Mayer Amschel or Gutle carried a recessive harmful
  gene, with 4 cousin marriages among grandchildren there was a 1-in-16
  chance both partners inherited it — their children would have 1-in-4
  chance of expressing the disease
- **Tay-Sachs** disease (fatal brain damage) now known to be legacy of
  centuries of Ashkenazi endogamy
- Of Mayer Amschel's 44 great-grandchildren, 6 died before age 5
  (13.6% vs. ~25% typical Western European rate in 1840s — actually
  better than average)
- Speculative alternative: perhaps there was a Rothschild "gene for
  financial acumen" that endogamy helped perpetuate — but this "cannot
  easily be demonstrated"

---

## Chapter 7: Barons

> "When [Rothschild] obtained the title [of baron], it was said,
> 'Montmorency est le premier Baron Chrétien, et Rothschild est le
> premier Baron Juif.'" — Thomas Raikes

### Property Acquisition: Town Houses

- **Amschel's garden** in Bockenheimer Landstrasse was a symbol of
  ghetto emancipation, but property decisions were also driven by
  economic utility and social prestige — needing places to entertain
  political elite
- **Carl** purchased 33 Neue Mainzer Strasse, Frankfurt (1818)
- **Nathan**: offered £15,750 for Grosvenor House (1817) — deal fell
  through when seller demanded £19,000; eventually leased **107 Piccadilly**
  (1825) from a member of the Coutts family; by then had 7 children
- **James**: moved 1816–17 from rue Le Peletier to rue de Provence;
  Dec 1818 bought **hôtel at 19 rue d'Artois** (later rue Laffitte) —
  built for banker Laborde pre-Revolution, occupied during Empire by
  **Hortense** (Josephine's daughter) and Napoleon's Police Minister
  **Fouché**; Salomon bought 17 rue Laffitte next door years later
- **Salomon** in Vienna: could not buy property — Jews barred from owning
  in imperial capital; rented **Hotel zum Römischen Kaiser** until 1842
  when he finally secured an exemption

### Country Estates

- Nathan's first country property (1816): 8-acre estate on Newington–
  Stamford Hill road, Parish of St John at Hackney — family lived there
  rather than at New Court
- Later acquired **Gunnersbury Park** near Acton — built 1802 for
  George III's daughter Amelia; large Italianate villa with ornamental
  lake and neo-classical "temple"; Nathan commissioned architect
  **Sydney Smirke** to enlarge it and landscape specialist
  **John Claudius Loudon** for the park
- Nathan personally uncomfortable with country life — urban creature;
  complained neighbour built pig farm near his walk; did not ride,
  hunt, or watch horse races (contrast with James and his sons)

> "[Neuchatel] was always preparing for his posterity. Governed by this
> passion, although he himself would have been content to live forever
> in Bishopsgate Street... he had become possessed of a vast
> principality... not an hour's drive from Whitechapel."
> — Disraeli, *Endymion* (Nathan as "Neuchatel," Gunnersbury as
> "Hainault House")

<!-- pp. 281-300 -->

## Chapter 7 (continued): Lifestyle of the Brothers

### Country Estates

- **Nathan** bought **Gunnersbury** primarily for his children; he rarely stayed
  there himself and large-scale entertaining didn't begin until after his death
- **James** acquired a summer house at **Boulogne-sur-Seine** (1817), then
  the grander **Suresnes** estate (Salomon's purchase), then the 1,200-acre
  hunting château at **Ferrières** (1829), twenty miles east of Paris
  — James genuinely loved country life, unlike Nathan
- Frankfurt/Vienna brothers resisted rural estates: **Amschel** noted Germans
  always asked if you had a country estate, but he and **Carl** agreed it would
  be a mistake to rise to this "socially alluring bait"
  - Fear: claiming aristocratic status would fuel anti-Jewish backlash
  - Practical skepticism: Carl warned estates "bring in not more than two per
    cent" — land treated as just another investment with yield calculations

### Society: The Uphill Struggle for Social Acceptance

- Core rationale for grand houses was **instrumental**: brothers needed
  respectable venues to entertain ministers and diplomats (their key clients)
- Early experience was humiliating — in Dec. 1815, **Buderus** (their trusted
  partner in Hesse-Kassel dealings) threw a ball and excluded the Rothschilds:
  "We lent the silver. [But] the *Finanzräte* Rothschild are again left out"
- Amschel told: had he been invited, "rumours would have gone round that we
  had paid for the ball"
- Excluded from Frankfurt Casino (gentlemen's club) as Jews

### Turning the Tables: Rothschild Hospitality as Power

- May 1816: **Salomon** gave a dinner for leading diplomats plus Bethmann and
  Gontard — all accepted; word spread through Frankfurt society with amazement
- The shift astonished **Bremen Bürgermeister Smidt** (a determined opponent
  of Jewish emancipation), who reported in 1820 that until recently no
  Frankfurt banker would invite a Jew to dine, but now Bethmanns, Gontards,
  and Brentanos "eat and drink with the leading Jews" — because "no financial
  transaction of any importance could be carried through without the
  co-operation of these people"
- By the 1840s Amschel was giving dinners "about once a fortnight [to] all
  visitors of rank"

### Vienna: Harder to Crack

- **Metternich** had no objection to "taking soup" with Amschel in Frankfurt,
  but Vienna remained more religiously segregated
- **Gentz** noted in the 1820s the Jewish "aristocracy of money" dined
  apart from the Christian aristocracy
- **Frances Trollope** (novelist's mother, visited 1830s): Viennese bankers
  held enormous power yet were "uniformly unadmitted and inadmissible in the
  higher circles" — their social position was "more pre-eminently a false one
  than that of any set of people I have ever had an opportunity of observing"
- **Count Kolowrat** accepted a dinner from Salomon in 1838 only after saying
  "Rothschild attached such enormous importance to my coming that I had to
  sacrifice myself to the interests of the service"

### James in Paris: The Most Determined Social Campaigner

- **James** made the most determined effort at social success (superior
  education gave him confidence)
- 1816: first success inviting duc de **Richelieu**'s private secretary *à deux*
- Rival bankers **Baring** and **Labouchère** snubbed him flagrantly in 1818
- March 2, 1821: first full-scale ball at refurbished **rue d'Artois** hôtel
  — **Henrietta Mendelssohn** reported 800 people invited; at least as many
  "besieged him with visits, letters and pleas" for an invitation
- April 1826: sumptuous dinner attended by Metternich, Duke of Devonshire,
  Russian Prince Razumovski, baron de Damas (French Foreign Minister), and
  a galaxy of French aristocrats
- James averaged ~four dinners a week, sometimes sixty guests; the night before
  his daughter Charlotte's birth he had eighteen to dinner; the next evening
  twenty-six

### Hospitality as Extravagance

- **Chef Antonin Carême** (previously employed by the Prince Regent and Tsar
  Alexander) was James's principal attraction — his cuisine was legendary
- 1826 dinner for Apponyi: table dominated by silver-plated candelabrum
  worth ~100,000 francs; food so rich Apponyi resolved to pay his
  *visite de digestion* eight days late
- Invitation to James's 1821 ball became coveted when word spread that "all
  the ladies would be given a bouquet of flowers on entering the ballroom
  with a diamond ring or brooch"
- **Lady Sydney Morgan** wrote: Carême "deserves a laurel wreath for perfecting
  an art form by which modern civilisation is measured"
- **Disraeli** was one of the most frequent recipients of Rothschild food
  outside the family; described it in *Endymion*

### Snobbery: They Were Invited But Not Liked

- Despite social success, the brothers were **not liked** by those who
  accepted their invitations
- **Nathan** was widely found intimidating, coarse, and downright rude
- **Prince Pückler** visited New Court in 1826 and found Nathan casually
  ignoring him while giving instructions about bond prices
- Famous "**two chairs**" joke (most frequently reprinted Rothschild anecdote):
  eminent visitor shown into Rothschild's office; without looking up, Nathan
  invites him to "take a chair"; affronted dignitary demands recognition;
  Rothschild responds: "So take *two* chairs"
- **Disraeli**'s novel *Tancred* (character Sidonia, partly based on Nathan)
  captures the same brusque atmosphere perfectly
- **Wilhelm von Humboldt** wrote to his wife after dining with Nathan:
  "He is quite crude and uneducated, but he has a great deal of intelligence
  and a positive genius for money"

> "To give . . . mind, and soul, and heart, and body, and everything to business; that is the way to be happy. I required a great deal of boldness and a great deal of caution to make a great fortune; and when you have got it, it requires ten times as much wit to keep it."
> — Nathan Rothschild (table talk recorded by Thomas Fowell Buxton, 1834)

- **Ornithologist Audubon** failed to get Nathan to subscribe to *Birds of
  America*: Nathan offered five pounds for the £100 work — "What, a hundred
  pounds for birds!"
- To composer **Louis Spohr**: "I understand nothing of music. This"—rattling
  his pocket—"is my music; we understand that on 'Change"
- Nathan on philanthropy: "Sometimes, to amuse myself, I give a beggar a
  guinea. He thinks it is a mistake, and for fear I shall find it out, off he
  runs as hard as he can"

### Brothers' True Feelings About Socializing

- The brothers **privately hated** the social functions they gave
- Amschel "thanked God" when his dinners were over; Carl thought them
  expensive "humbug" but conceded "it is as good as bribes" (five 1817 dinner
  guests also received parcels of the Paris loan)
- Carl in Berlin: "I don't really care, because I find we always do better
  business with those who do not invite us"
- James confided to Nathan (Jan. 1825): "I am obliged to give a ball because
  the world claims that I am broke" — throwing balls was a **financial signal**,
  proof of continued solvency
- **James** privately: "I think of nothing else but business. If I attend a
  society party, I go there to become acquainted with people who might be
  useful for the business"
- Charlotte (Nathan's daughter) in 1829: hoped "the Season will be very lively
  as this is always, I think, an encouragement for trade"

### The Honours "Racket"

- Beyond parties, the Rothschilds aggressively acquired **formal marks of
  status**: titles, uniforms, decorations, orders
- 1817: **Emperor Francis II** granted noble status — arranged through Austrian
  Treasury official **Schwinner**, Finance Minister **Stadion**, and Metternich,
  as reward for the Rothschilds' role in paying British subsidies and French
  reparations to Austria
  - Six other Jewish families had also been ennobled, though all had converted
    to Christianity by 1848
- Ennoblement gave three assets: the prefix "von" ("de" in France/England);
  a coat of arms; and in 1822 the title "**Freiherr**" ("Baron")
- Sons and grandsons applied to be "**Financial Councillors**" from Hesse-Kassel
  and Prussia — purely honorific but allowed them to wear a uniform at court
- **Nathan** secured Austrian consul title in 1820; he and James became
  consul-generals in 1821-2 for their role in the Neapolitan crisis
- Uniforms mattered: Carl sought Hessian Kriegscollegium uniform in 1817;
  James was spotted at Charles X's 1825 coronation in his red consular outfit;
  a young **Charles Bocher** mistook him for an English general

### Medals and Orders

- Brothers eagerly collected decorations from 1814 onward
- Carl: publicly given a ribbon by Prussian Chancellor **Hardenberg** (1817)
- James: Order of St Vladimir from Tsar at **Congress of Verona** (1822);
  Knight's Cross of the French **Legion of Honour** (1823, full member 1841)
- Carl accepted the ribbon and star of the **Order of St George** from
  **Pope Gregory XVI** in 1832; Lionel accepted Spain's **Order of Isabella**
  in 1835 — which had originally been established to glorify the expulsion of
  Jews from Spain; **Heine** noted the savage irony
- **Austrian Baron Kübeck** was scandalized: "His Holiness receives a member
  of the House of Rothschild . . . decorates a descendant of the people that
  allowed Christ to be put to death . . . And still Rothschild refuses to become
  a Christian"

### Private Contempt for Honours

- Despite eagerness to collect, the brothers **privately mocked** the whole
  system — Carl called coats of arms "part of the racket"
- James joked that seeing a minister required dressing "as if on a visit to
  your bride"
- Carl addressed a letter satirically to "James de Rothschild, Knight of
  the Society for the Liberation of Christian Slaves [*sic*], Financial
  Councillor of Electoral Hesse etc."
- **Amschel** (1814): "If we had always worried about what other people were
  going to think, we would now be left with a great many decorations etc., but
  without money. And in the end, we would be left without praise, without
  decorations and without money"
- Two arguments FOR accepting honours: (1) improved access to corridors of
  power; (2) honours were "a mark of distinction for **our nation**"—i.e.,
  European Jewry. Rothschild ennoblement was widely seen in the Judengasse
  as a slap against those seeking to reimpose Jewish disabilities:
  "If one Jew is a Baron every Jew is a Baron"

### Nathan's Ambivalence Toward Titles

- Letters suggest Nathan **declined a knighthood** offered in 1815 or 1816
- 1816 ennoblement patents conspicuously omitted Nathan; coat of arms showed
  four arrows not five
- Nathan rarely used "Baron" or the prefix "de"
- Declined Prussian decoration in 1818, suggesting it be given to Salomon:
  "here in London I have no use for such a thing" whereas Salomon "loves
  ribbons and is a Baron who intends to live in Paris"
- James initially urged: "Let us remain merchants. It is extremely nice to
  possess the title and not to make use of it, except in private"
- 1827: **Prince Pückler** witnessed a tipsy Nathan don his Austrian consular
  uniform (a gift from Metternich) and perform an extended costume parade
  — described as a bid to *épater l'aristocratie*, treating diplomatic
  finery as little more than fancy dress

### "Fine Education": Culture and the Next Generation

- Despite "philistine" reputation, brothers showed some interest in high culture
  — partly forced by ownership of grand houses requiring art, and partly the
  social necessity of conversing on topics beyond money
- **James** was the only second-generation member with genuine cultural
  interest: read Schiller and Goethe in his twenties; retained artist Allard
  at 5 francs/month; subscribed to *Courrier des Spectacles* and
  *Journal des Théâtres*
- Brothers commissioned family portraits from artists including
  **Sir William Beechey**, **Louis Amié Grosclaude**, and
  **Moritz Daniel Oppenheim**; held theatre boxes in Frankfurt and Paris
- Brothers recognized potential **conflict between higher education and
  business**: Carl advised keeping Anselm in school "not more than another
  two years so that he should enter the business when 17 years old. Otherwise
  he would not be deeply attached to business"
- **Mayer** (Nathan's only son to attend an English university) proved this
  analysis accurate — less committed to business
- In practice, third-generation males entered firm later than Carl suggested:
  - **Anselm**: twenty-three before serious participation
  - **Lionel**: twenty when first writing business letters
  - **Anthony and Nat**: eighteen; **Mayer**: twenty-one
  - Carl's sons: none before age twenty; pious **Wilhelm Carl** not considered
    competent unsupervised until twenty-four
  - James's sons **Alphonse and Gustave**: nineteen before own business letters

<!-- pp. 301-320 -->

## Chapter 7 (cont.): The Third Generation — Education and Assimilation

### Rothschild Parenting Philosophy

- Older Rothschilds did NOT want to impose their own childhood deprivations on children
- **Anselm's** mother embraced contemporary ideals of **Bildung** (German concept of
  self-cultivation through education); genuinely wanted "a fine education" for its own sake
- **Nathan** was more playful: let children ride on his back, bought them
  a miniature carriage with four white goats; dislocated his shoulder horsing around
- 1821 family portrait by **William Armfield Hobday** captures a relaxed,
  indulgent paterfamilias — children pulling letters, dropping bonnets,
  the family dog chewing Lionel's hat
- At seventeen, **Hannah Mayer** enjoyed Brighton; Anthony was "a mighty hunter"
  whose father let him buy any horse he liked; applied to the Emperor of Morocco
  for an Arab horse — it died on landing in England ("the greatest misfortune
  he ever had suffered")

### Disraeli's Portrait: Sidonia as Rothschild Ideal

- In *Coningsby*, **Benjamin Disraeli** modelled young **Sidonia** on the
  Rothschild educational ideal: mastery of mathematics "almost instinctive,"
  command of all principal European languages by nineteen, grand tour
  through Germany and Italy
- This matched the actual curriculum: Lionel and Anthony's first teacher
  (a harsh Polish schoolmaster) was replaced when parents hired **Garcia**,
  a former bookkeeper, to run a more selective academy at Peckham
- 1827 grand tour sent Lionel (19) and Anthony (17) to Germany — not Italy
  (the classicist destination) — travelling with tutor **John Darby** through
  Saxony, Prague, Vienna, Baden, Strasbourg; paid a respectful call on **Goethe**
- Business training followed only after: in January 1829, a Frankfurt
  bookkeeper tasked with bringing Anthony up to banker-level numeracy —
  "the art of arithmetic and . . . arbitration of exchange"

### Education Across the Branches

- Anglo-German rivalry in education: in 1831 Charlotte wrote urging Mayer
  to write in German so he could compete with Uncle Salomon's boys
- **Mayer** (Nathan's youngest) studied at University of Leipzig, then
  Heidelberg; became the **first Rothschild to attend Cambridge** —
  first Magdalene, then Trinity (Oxford required subscription to the
  thirty-nine articles; Cambridge allowed Jewish non-conformists to attend
  but not receive degrees or scholarships)
- **Carl's** son **Mayer Carl** sent to Göttingen to study law, then attended
  Berlin lectures by **Friedrich Karl von Savigny** (jurisprudence) and
  **Leopold von Ranke** (the pre-eminent historian of the age)
- **Wilhelm Carl** (Carl's other son): fifteen years old, studying twenty
  subjects including five languages and five sciences under a team led by
  French physiologist **Henri Blanvalet**; his flight into religious
  Orthodoxy may have been partly a reaction against this relentless cramming
- **James's** son **Alphonse** attended Collège Bourbon (later Lycée Condorcet),
  tutored for his baccalauréat by **Désiré Nisard** (later director of
  the Ecole Normale and Académie Française member)
- **Carl's daughter Charlotte** — considered the brightest of the third generation —
  produced elegant English letters and intense German diaries

### Result: Becoming Gentlemen

- Goal was NOT to produce great intellectuals (by that measure, a failure)
  but to produce men and women who fit the European social elite
  without losing their desire to be bankers — and in that, a success
- Third generation no longer spoke the rough-hewn German of the **Judengasse**;
  observers noted nothing unusual about the idiomatic English of Nathan's sons
- English and French Rothschilds abandoned Hebrew-character letters their fathers used
  (though they could still read *Judendeutsch*); from late 1820s business
  conducted multilingually, each partner writing in his first language
- Third generation wrote English, German, and French as well as —
  often better than — their aristocratic contemporaries
- Cultural tastes were conventionally elite: **Scott's** novels, **Meyerbeer's**
  operas, **Murillo's** paintings, Marie Antoinette's furniture
- Adopted upper-class hobbies: riding, fox-hunting, stag-hunting, betting on
  racehorses, cigars, fine wine, "chasing unsuitable women"
- Clubbish nicknames: Lionel = "Rab," Anthony = "Billy" or "Fat Bill,"
  Mayer = "Muffy" or "Tup"
- "All outward traces of the Frankfurt ghetto had been expunged" — the
  first generation had become barons; now the third generation became
  something more elusive: **gentlemen**

---

## Chapter 8: Sudden Revolutions (1830–1833)

> *In the present state of Europe something great & decisive must be done
> or its kingdoms and their population will be soon again in worse confusion
> than they were under the French Revolution . . . It may be well therefore,
> without losing the advantages which money gives under the existing
> arrangements of society, to secure also similar benefits in case of sudden
> revolutions in all the states of Europe which may now any day take place.*
> — **Robert Owen** to Hannah Rothschild, July 1828

### The Revolutionary Wave of 1830

- July 1830: **King Charles X** of France overthrown by parliamentary
  opposition and popular violence in Paris — triggering a chain reaction
- Regime changes or attempts in Brussels, Warsaw, Modena, Bologna,
  Brunswick, Hesse-Kassel, Saxony, and Portugal
- Belgium, Italy, Poland: revolutionaries sought independence from foreign rule
  as much as constitutional reform
- England, Scotland, Ireland: constitutional reforms enacted without
  deposing a monarch; Hanover saw a change simply because George IV died
- Political instability continued past 1832 — Poland and Italy crushed,
  Holland forced to accept Belgian secession; uncertainty persisted through
  mid-decade

### Public Perception: Rothschild Power vs. Monarchs

- Rothschilds' survival of the upheavals convinced many their power equaled
  or exceeded that of kings
- **Ludwig Börne** (German-Jewish journalist, Frankfurt Judengasse origins,
  convert to Christianity and German nationalism): November 1831 bulletin
  explicitly "equated Rothschild . . . with kings":

> *Rothschild is the high priest of fear, the Goddess on whose altar liberty,
> patriotism, honour and all civic virtues are sacrificed.*
> — **Ludwig Börne**, tenth bulletin from Paris, November 1831

- Börne's January 1832 bulletin sarcastically imagined **Louis Philippe**
  being crowned "not at St Rémy at Rheims, but at Notre Dame de la Bourse,"
  with Rothschild officiating as archbishop; Louis Philippe's title
  would be "Emperor of the five per cents, King of the three per cents,
  Protector of bankers and exchange agents"
- Börne also accused the Rothschilds of being supporters of reaction —
  an argument that became harder to sustain once they lent to Louis Philippe's
  liberal monarchy AND helped establish Greece as an independent state
- Börne eventually argued Rothschilds were beginning to **supplant** rather
  than merely prop up European monarchies: "Would it not be a great blessing
  for the world if all the kings were dismissed and the Rothschild family
  put on their thrones? The new dynasty would never contract a loan . . ."
- Börne's hostility partly explained by his complex personal reasons —
  a Jewish convert who disliked the Rothschilds' accommodation with power

### Heinrich Heine's More Nuanced Analysis

- **Heinrich Heine** (poet and journalist, also a Jewish convert to Christianity)
  offered the most perceptive contemporary reading of Rothschild power
- Pre-1830 Heine: in "Travel Sketches," "Rothschild I" appears alongside
  Wellington, Metternich, and the Pope as a bulwark of reaction
- In "The Baths of Lucca," the character **Hirsch-Hyacinth** cuts Nathan's
  corns and reflects: "what you now have in your hand is the foot of the man
  whose own hands hold the whole world"
- Heine's famous pun: Salomon treated Hirsch-Hyacinth "like his equal,
  quite **famillionaire**" (*ganz famillionär*) — hinting the Rothschilds,
  despite vast wealth, were not mere props of the traditional hierarchy
- Allegory of Salomon's children's fancy-dress ball: children dressed as kings
  play at making loans; one boy dressed as Nathan Rothschild dominates —
  giving Austria a "kindly pat on the cheek," threatening to cut off Germany,
  and advising France to "behave yourself, make an honest living . . .
  or I'll lose my money" — until "the cake was brought in and they all started
  fighting for the best piece [and] tore the crowns off one another's heads"
- Heine's unpublished analysis from "The Baths of Lucca":

> *Revolutions are generally triggered off by deficiency of money; by
> preventing such deficiencies, the Rothschild system may serve to preserve
> peace in Europe . . . it does not inhibit one state from making war on
> another exactly as before, but it does make it difficult for the people
> to overthrow established authority.*
> — **Heinrich Heine**, unpublished passage

- But crucially, Heine also saw the Rothschild "system" as **potentially
  revolutionary in itself**: "it possesses the moral force or power which
  religion has lost, it can act as a surrogate for religion — indeed, it
  *is* a new religion"
- Heine's "Memorandum on Ludwig Börne" (1840): the striking paradox —

> *No one does more to further the revolution than the Rothschilds themselves
> . . . these Rothschilds, the bankers of kings, these princely pursestring-holders
> . . . nevertheless carry in their minds a consciousness of their
> revolutionary mission.*
> — **Heinrich Heine**

- James is the "**Nero of finance**," "reigning as absolute emperor over the
  stock exchanges of the world"; but like Nero, "ultimately a powerful destroyer
  of patrician privilege, and the founder of a new democracy"
- Heine's conversation with James: James explained how government bonds had
  "created the first conditions for . . . social progress" — mobile property
  in the form of rentes severed the link between wealth and land, drawing
  the propertied classes to Paris and enabling the city's cultural centrality
- Heine's famous historical trinity:

> *I see in Rothschild one of the greatest revolutionaries who have founded
> modern democracy. Richelieu, Robespierre and Rothschild are for me three
> terroristic names, and they signify the gradual annihilation of the old
> aristocracy.*
> — **Heinrich Heine**

  - **Richelieu** destroyed feudal nobility's sovereignty, subordinated it to
    royal despotism
  - **Robespierre** decapitated the subjugated nobility
  - **Rothschild** destroyed the predominance of land itself by raising
    state bonds to supremacy — "mobilising property and income and at the
    same time endowing money with the previous privileges of the land"
  - The new money-aristocracy is less stable than land-based aristocracy:
    "money is more fluid than water, more elusive than the air" — its
    impertinences can be forgiven because it will dissolve in the twinkling of an eye
- Heine in *Lutezia* (1840–41): caricatured James's health/mood as moving
  in tandem with rente prices; coined the famous phrase:
  **"[M]oney is the god of our time and Rothschild is his prophet"**
- The arch-conservative **Chateaubriand**, brooding in Venice after
  the Bourbon fall: "the Kings [had] become the chamberlains of Salomon,
  Baron de Rothschild"

### The Revolution and the Rente: James's Faustian Pact

- Ferguson's key argument: revolutions are not necessarily predictable —
  Eastern Europe 1989 illustrates how historians find patterns after the fact
- In early 1829, with the 3 per cent rente at 76.6, French political situation
  looked manageable; James hosted dinners "for the liberals & the Ministers"
  to keep friends with all parties
- By December 1829, ultra-conservative **Jules de Polignac** replaced
  moderate Martignac — yet rentes continued to rise, reaching 84+ and
  peaking at 86 by December 1829; appointment of Polignac did NOT
  immediately spell crisis
- James outbid rivals for a modest government loan in early 1830 to
  finance France's Algeria campaign — saw a contradiction between
  anti-government press rhetoric and financial market stability:
  "On the one hand the whole world is screaming that the Ministry is
  bringing about a revolution . . . on the other all the various consortiums
  are seen to be fighting among themselves to lay their hands on a lousy
  4 million rentes"
- Classic investor dilemma: sell a falling security at a loss or hold
  hoping for recovery — at the risk of further fall
- By February 1830, Finance Minister warned James: if the Chamber opposed
  the government, Charles X would dissolve it and force new elections
- James hesitated: saw Polignac as having "the courage of the devil";
  told Nathan "to remain quiet . . . the devil is not as black as he appears"
- Nathan assured **Charles Greville** that "Polignac's Government will stand
  by the King's support and Polignac's own courage"
- The brothers held ~25 million francs (£1 million nominal) in 4 per cent
  rentes, intended to sell gradually at a profit — accelerating sales
  now would collapse the very prices they needed; James called it "a
  diabolical situation"
- When Chamber voted 221-181 against the ministry, Charles X dissolved it
  and called elections — James found himself **buying** rentes to shore up
  the market rather than selling, at Polignac's request

> *Well, Polignac promised me that he will not instigate a coup d'état . . .
> so I went ahead and bought 100,000 francs of rentes [3.3 million nominal]
> because I had told him, "If you remain within the law then I promise you
> that there will be a rise."*
> — **James de Rothschild** to Nathan

- By May the 3 per cents rallied above 84 — but James could not simultaneously
  support the market AND sell; still held 25 million francs of 4 per cents,
  1.5 million of 5 per cents, 4.5 million of 3 per cents when the slide began
- From May onwards, losses mounted; neither James nor Nathan could bring
  themselves to crystallize losses by selling
- Government itself told James: "If you do not succeed in preventing the
  fall in values, everyone will believe that a coup d'état will occur"
- Ouvrard and others launched an unstoppable bear run; limits of Rothschild
  market power had been reached

### The July Revolution: Days of Decision

- Algeria campaign's success (news reached Paris first week of July) was
  swamped by the election results: resounding Opposition victory
- On July 26, **Charles X** invoked Article 14 of the 1814 Charter:
  three ordinances ending press freedom, dissolving the Chamber, and
  rigging the electoral system
- Trigger: liberal journalists like **Adolphe Thiers** of the *National*
  immediately denounced the coup; crowds took to streets when
  opposition newspaper offices were seized
- Nathan's eldest son **Lionel** arrived in Paris just in time; his letter
  captures the uncertainty: "One moment one thinks oneself on the eve of
  seeing a revolution, the next, that every thing in a short time will be
  again in order"
- Two days of fighting: 800 protesters and 200 soldiers killed; Charles X's
  troops driven from Paris; moderate liberals **Jacques Laffitte** and
  **Casimir Périer** suddenly irrelevant; king's belated offer to withdraw
  the ordinances too late
- **Lafayette** led a hastily improvised national guard; **Salomon** reported
  to Metternich on July 30: "the tricolour flag is flying on all public buildings"
- Lionel described euphoric Paris: streets crowded with laughing people,
  tricolour everywhere, trees cut down and pavements torn up for barricades
  in every street so "it was impossible for the soldiers & artillery to pass anywhere"
- James buried his bonds in the grounds of Salomon's house at Suresnes

### James's Survival and the New Regime

- James quickly switched sides with "alacrity and relief": offered Vitrolles
  only a rural hiding place; rejected all financial requests from the
  ousted Charles X until it was clear he was leaving
- His nephew exulted: "Never was there a more glorious week for France"
- When Polignac was put on trial, James shed no tears: "for all the good
  that Polignac has done for us, he might as well be damned"
- James donated **15,000 francs** for care of the street-fighting wounded;
  Anselm served in the bourgeois national guard; James dressed his
  three-year-old son **Alphonse** in a miniature guard's uniform
- The liberals' decision to offer the crown to the **duc d'Orléans** (Louis Philippe)
  was "a stroke of good luck for James" — he had already made Louis Philippe
  "a good friend" in the 1820s
- Rothschild political preference articulated by Salomon watching Louis Philippe
  take the coronation oath: "Thank God that we have come so far that the matter
  has ended so well, for otherwise the Rentes would not have stood at 79 but
  would have fallen to 39 God forbid"
- James gave Louis Philippe a personal loan of over **2 million francs** in
  April 1840; Heine confirmed the affinity was based on shared "adoration of money"
- Social barriers of the Restoration nearly vanished under the "Citizen King":
  royals, ministers, and ambassadors freely accepted James's invitations
  to dinners, balls, and hunting parties
- One Austrian source claimed: "in all Ministries and in all the Departments
  [Rothschild] has his creatures of all ranks to bring him every kind of information"

### Ongoing Anxiety About the New Regime (1830–1833)

- Despite closeness to Louis Philippe, Rothschilds were NOT convinced the
  regime would endure — with good reason
- Crowds calling for Polignac's execution (October 1830) rekindled fear
  the monarchy would be swept aside by republicans
- December 1830: warnings that republicans intended "attacking the house
  tonight & taking everything"
- Prussian ambassador Werther warned James that Louis Philippe would "go
  the same way as Louis XVI"; dinner guests told him "the old revolution
  started in a similar manner . . . we can't see how anyone here can feel
  secure"
- Multiple threats: Bonapartists seeking imperial revival; working-class
  unrest in Paris, Lyon, and other industrial centres
- James threw a "crowded and brilliant" ball on January 15, 1831 — the day
  after a violent anti-clerical riot, with the city echoing to the Marseillaise
  as guests danced; the duc d'Orléans sent apologies — the republic was
  being proclaimed in the streets outside

> *"It's terrifying, yes, it's frightful," said the young lady. "But let's dance
> while we can today. If it is true that we are going to have the republic tomorrow,
> that will mean the end of feasts and balls for ages."*
> — Guest at James de Rothschild's ball, January 1831

<!-- pp. 321-340 -->

## Chapter 8 (continued): The July Monarchy and Political Volatility

### French Political Instability, 1831-1832

- **James de Rothschild** maintained outward bravado at his Paris parties even as
  losses mounted — the duc d'Orléans was affronted at one of James's events
  in January 1832 when called "le grand poulot" by a Legitimist guest
- James tracked every ministerial shift obsessively: "a lot depends on what sort
  of Ministry we get"
- February 1831: James sought reassurance from **Louis Philippe** that the
  **Laffitte ministry** wouldn't be replaced by a more liberal one; consoled
  when **Périer** — himself a banker — emerged as likely successor
- **Casimir Périer** was meant to reduce the King's direct influence; his hold
  on power was always tenuous — near-miss elections, reform of the House of
  Peers, constant anxiety from the Paris letters

> "French Ministers are just like serviettes: after a period of time they require
> the attention of a washerwoman, and once they have had a rest they are as good
> [as new] again." — James to Amschel, 1839

- 1832 **cholera epidemic** (swept west from Russia, killed 18,000 in Paris)
  caused "complete paralysis" on the bourse and killed Périer himself on May 16
- Simultaneous threat: **duchesse de Berry** landed in the south, sparking fears
  of a Carlist civil war — not extinguished until her arrest in November
- Through the 1830s: working-class unrest in Lyon (1834), abortive republican
  coup (1839), Bonapartist invasion attempt (1840)
- James privately contemptuous of Louis Philippe ("duplicitous"), Finance
  Minister Humann ("an ass"), Thiers ("a little man") — relations only
  superficially intimate

### James's Financial Losses in the 1830 Crisis

- Between May 1830 and April 1831, **3 and 4 per cent rentes** fell 30-40%,
  reaching nadir of 46 and 75 respectively
- James and Nathan had held 6 million francs nominal of these securities, paid
  5.36 million francs — potential losses of 2.1 million francs (£86,000) on
  rente account alone
- James bought more rentes trying to stabilize the market; by November 1830
  holdings may have reached 30 million francs nominal — prices kept falling

> "We are sitting in a bowl of soup and we must now wait for it to be cooked...
> Every day there are so many rentes for sale but there are no buyers to be found."
> — James to Nathan, late August 1830

- Lionel confessed: "We have been all the time so misled by the abundancy of
  money and scarcity of stock, & by the peaceable assurances of the King, that
  we never could make up our minds to sell"
- **Anselm** (from Berlin) urged final liquidation; James resisted accepting a
  40% loss, ultimately forced to sell heavily at the market bottom, March 1831
- London house losses in 1830: over **£56,000** (5% of house capital);
  comparable losses bankrupted **Laffitte**, whose firm collapsed even as he
  reached the zenith of political influence
- In November 1830 James was forced to **suspend payments** due to the
  government for the pre-Revolution loan
- Rival banker **Ouvrard** temporarily supplanted James as dominant figure on
  the bourse; **Hottinguer** told James directly that "your establishment no
  longer makes the same positive impression on public opinion"
- **Lionel** observed James was "so much shaken by this revolution... he is no
  more what he was" — panic-selling at bottoms, buying at tops

> "Every day we have new scares, and every day new surprises hit us... I did
> some buying, so prices fell. When I sell, prices go up. It is absolutely
> disgusting." — James to family, 1831

- By October 1831 James felt "half frantic," isolated: "The world is speculating
  against me, and I am speculating against the world"
- Recovery only came in early 1832; James retreated to Boulogne in complete
  exhaustion once markets improved

---

### Consols and the Constitution

- The **multinational Rothschild structure** was the principal reason James
  survived — a domestic crisis in one house could be covered by the others
- Nathan's immediate response to Paris news: purchased and borrowed large
  quantities of silver and gold from the **Bank of England** — gold alone
  worth **£779,000** — shipped immediately to James
- This allowed James to keep paying the French Treasury under the loan
  agreement — a vital show of financial strength
- Nathan could bail James out partly because he had sold a substantial proportion
  of his own 4% rentes *before* the revolution broke out
- Naples house sent silver; its accounts show half-yearly profits unaffected
  by the revolution; Frankfurt and Vienna remained on sound footing

- **Revolutionary ripple effects across Europe:**
  - Salomon 10 million gulden poorer than six months before (November 1830)
  - **Elector William II** of Hesse-Kassel pressured by citizens' assemblies
    demanding a *Landtag*; had not used Rothschilds since 1823, now appealed
    to **Amschel** for 150,000 gulden advance — Amschel lent only 100,000
    given risk of German revolution
  - When Frederick William installed as co-regent with a liberal constitution,
    Amschel arranged two loans totaling 1.35 million gulden — paralleling
    James's pivot from Charles X to Louis Philippe
  - The failed **Frankfurt putsch** of April 1833 by radical incompetents was
    a welcome sign the political tide was ebbing

---

### Nathan and the British Reform Crisis

- Events in Britain less violent but analogous; contemporaries themselves saw
  the parallel between **French revolution** and **British Reform**
- Between January 1830 (consols at 95.6) and March 1831 (75.4), consol prices
  fell **20%** — less than Paris but substantial; remained below 1829 average
  of 91 until 1834
- **Duke of Wellington's** intransigent speech against reform on November 11
  caused a 6-point fall; radical **Francis Place** coined the slogan
  "To stop the Duke, go for gold!" (i.e., run on the Bank of England)

- James initially predicted Wellington would return to power (April 1831);
  deeply hostile to **Earl Grey's** Whig ministry and the **Reform Bill**

> "If the Reform Bill passes, it will bring the same results as the revolution
> did here... In England the King gives the people more than their rights,
> which will have consequences as bad as the contrary has had." — James to Lionel

- James feared Reform would unleash insatiable popular demands: "The plebeians
  believe that a Parliamentary reform will provide them with [free] bread and
  cake... they are revolutionaries at heart"
- **Lionel** took the opposite, more liberal view — pleased that Reform was
  humbling the aristocracy — but his attitude was also pragmatic: he tracked
  the connection between Reform passing and consol prices rising
- Markets effectively wanted Reform to pass: James argued in May 1831 that
  "the Reformers are winning can at the present moment only have a positive
  effect and cause a rise in the stocks"

- **Nathan's intervention with Wellington (May 1832):**
  - When William IV refused to create 50 new peers and Wellington was called
    to form an anti-Reform government, Nathan went directly to **Charles
    Arbuthnot** with a message for the Duke

> "Rothschild... came to tell me that if you let it be known... that you are
> resolved not to disappoint expectations which are so greatly raised... you
> will surmount all your difficulties... He is determined, he said, to keep
> up the Funds to his utmost, and he is confident he will succeed."
> — Charles Arbuthnot to Wellington

  - **Moses Montefiore** summarized Nathan's argument: Wellington should
    "form a Liberal Government... consent to some reforms... he must go with
    the world, for the world would not with him" — Wellington threw in the
    towel two days later

- What changed Nathan's mind? Likely: fear of another financial crisis, possible
  warning of a run on the Bank of England's reserve; also a deeper political
  shift — Nathan (and family) were moving toward Whiggism partly because Tories
  opposed **Jewish emancipation**
- Consol prices barely moved after Grey's return and the bill's passage —
  the anticipated boost never materialized
- Nathan willing to manage the **£15 million loan** to compensate slave-owners
  after abolition — dined with **Buxton** (leader of the Anti-Slavery Society)
  right after the legislation passed
- Ferguson's conclusion: the brothers lacked genuine commitment to reaction;
  when reform came — even by violence — they accepted it

---

## Chapter 9: The Chains of Peace (1830-1833)

> *Those who want war will doubtless turn to other bankers.*
> — **Friedrich Gentz**, 1830

### The Rothschilds' Fear of War

- The greater threat from the 1830 revolutions was not domestic upheaval but
  the possibility that revolution might trigger **war between the great powers**
- A revolution primarily hurt bonds in one country; a European war would crash
  *all* government securities simultaneously across all five houses

> "You can't begin to imagine what might happen should we get war, God forbid...
> all the securities would suffer such a fall that it would be impossible to
> sell anything." — James, October 1830

- James quantified the war risk: holding 900,000 rentes (30 million francs
  nominal) — peace would keep them at 75%, war would drop them to 45%;
  peace would improve them 10% within three months

- This explains widespread contemporary belief that Rothschilds **used financial
  leverage to preserve peace**:
  - **Ludwig Börne** argued Rothschild sales of Austrian bonds constrained
    Metternich in 1831 when he wanted to suppress revolution in Italy and Belgium
  - Austrian diplomat **Count Prokesch von Osten** (December 1830): "It is all
    a question of ways and means and what Rothschild says is decisive, and he
    won't give any money for war"
  - Austrian Finance Minister **Baron Kübeck** regarded Salomon as synonymous
    with "peace" by 1833
  - Prince **Pückler** compared the Rothschilds to Napoleon as forces shaking
    thrones — "without whom no power in Europe today seemed able to make war"
  - Prussian diplomat **Achim von Arnim** (1840s) on governments shackled by
    the "golden chains of that House"

- The myth crystallized in **anti-Semitic literature**:
  - **Alphonse Toussenel**, *The Jews — Kings of the Epoch* (1846): "The Jew
    *speculates on peace*, that is on a rise"
  - Capefigue and Chirac purported to quote a Rothschild: "There will be no war
    because the Rothschilds do not want it"
  - **Gutle Rothschild** (Nathan's mother) credited with: "It won't come to
    war; my sons won't provide money for it"

- The brothers **publicly encouraged** such notions — it made them appear
  potent and benign simultaneously
- But Ferguson distinguishes two mechanisms: (1) **financial leverage** —
  refusing loans to governments contemplating war; (2) **diplomatic channel**
  — acting as a faster, more discreet conduit for government-to-government
  communication than official couriers

---

### Lines of Communication

- The Rothschild communications network was real but less supernatural than
  the myth of **Disraeli's Sidonia** suggested
- In the 20 years after Waterloo (the original communications coup), the system
  was rudimentary — letters at the mercy of weather and postal delays
  - Paris to Frankfurt: ~48 hours (1814)
  - London to Frankfurt: up to a week
  - Paris to Berlin: 9 days (1817)
  - Salomon and wife "99 per cent" drowned when coach crossing a river in a
    storm (1817)

- **Private couriers** used from at least 1814 — Austrian secret police routinely
  opened letters passing through German "lodges"; diplomatic "bags" also
  compromised, so private couriers were the only secure option
- Couriers were expensive; brothers bickered about frequency; the very arrival
  of a courier alerted rivals to important news — letters were sometimes
  **backdated** and couriers sent in disguise to deceive competitors
- By mid-1820s, couriers were routine: December 1825 alone, Paris house sent
  18 couriers (to Calais, Saarbrücken, Brussels, Naples)
- Salomon infuriated when he couldn't find a courier willing to leave Vienna
  for Strasbourg at 10 p.m. on Christmas Day (1827)

- **Amschel's color-code system (1814):** blue envelope = exchange rate up,
  red = down — so the Frankfurt post office contact could signal which letter
  to rush through, saving half a day

- **Carrier pigeons** used from 1824; not regular enough for a code until the
  1840s: "A B in our pigeon dispatches means buy stock, the news is good.
  C D... means sell stock the news is bad"

- The communications edge was real but **temporary** — roughly 1815-1835:
  - Rivals quickly adopted their own couriers
  - Railway, telegraph, and steamship from mid-1830s onward erased the advantage
  - By 1840 Carl advised Paris not to send couriers to Naples — steamers
    arrived just as fast and couriers only alerted small speculators
  - After 1830, press censorship relaxed; by 1840s Nat simply referred brothers
    to French newspapers for political news his uncle would once have written

- **Diplomatic value of the courier service (c. 1815-1835):**
  - Statesmen used Rothschild couriers because they were faster than official
    posts AND allowed non-binding unofficial messages to flow between governments
  - 1822: **Chateaubriand** received an important despatch from the duchesse
    de Duras via "her protégé Rothschild" while in London
  - **Metternich** used Salomon's couriers at Verona (1822) and Pressburg
    (1825), trusting them more than his own
  - By 1823, "receiving news from Rothschild" was part of
    **Countess Nesselrode's** daily routine
  - 1826 report: Rothschild clerks traveling Naples-Paris monthly carried
    despatches of French, English, and Spanish ministers accredited in Naples,
    Rome, and Florence — plus intercourt communications between Naples, Rome,
    Turin, Paris, London, Madrid, Lisbon
  - 1826 Franco-Austrian crisis: a Rothschild courier carried Villèle's
    placatory note to Metternich
  - After 1840: **Queen Victoria** and **Prince Albert** also used the
    Rothschild postal service (Albert's Uncle Leopold was an old Rothschild friend)

- Brothers began using "we" in letters to mean both "we Rothschilds" and
  "our government" — blurring the line between commercial intelligence and
  diplomatic representation; not always clear whether they were influencing
  policy or policy was influencing them

<!-- pp. 341-360 -->

## Chapter 11 (continued): The Age of Revolution, 1830–33

### The Rothschild News Network

- **Prince Albert** (via adviser **Christian von Stockmar** and secretary **George Anson**)
  used Rothschild couriers from his arrival in England; Queen Victoria soon did the same,
  assuring Leopold in June 1841 her letters to Germany of "any *real* consequence"
  went "thro' Rothschild wh. is perfectly *safe* and very quick"
- The network gave the Rothschilds a unique **news service** for the European elite —
  political events and confidential intelligence relayed well ahead of official channels
- As early as 1817, **James** offered to relay French diplomatic despatches from Paris to
  London before they reached the French ambassador — via a "friend" in government circles
- By 1830 **Talleyrand** observed: "The English Cabinet always obtain their information
  by [Rothschild] ten or twelve hours before the arrival of Lord Stuart's despatches"
- The couriers' vessels took no passengers and departed at any hour — a structural advantage
- **Canning** suspected the brothers manipulated news to influence markets;
  **Villèle** felt the same but could not ignore the intelligence

> "The English Cabinet always obtain their information by [Rothschild] ten or twelve hours
> before the arrival of Lord Stuart's despatches, and this is not to be wondered at, seeing
> that the vessels which carry Rothschild's couriers belong to that firm." — Talleyrand, 1830

- The core aim: get political news first, then buy or sell securities before the news
  moved the market as a whole — not always achieved (the 1830 French revolution
  caught the Rothschilds completely off guard)

---

### Bankers' Diplomacy: The 1830–33 Crisis

- Post-July 1830, the **Rothschild correspondence** served as the primary back-channel
  between European governments — more reliable and faster than official despatches
- **James** (Paris): "I am constantly being consulted about everything" — saw the King,
  ministers, and principal ambassadors almost daily
- **Salomon** (Vienna): direct access to **Metternich**; copied brothers' letters to him
  whenever they contained diplomatically important information
- **Nathan** (London): access to diplomat **Frederick Lamb** and foreign envoys
  (**Talleyrand**, **Esterházy**, **Bülow**); less influential than under the Tories
- Frankfurt/Naples were outside the great-power loop; Berlin/St. Petersburg reached
  only through agents (Gasser in Russia, Richtenberger in Belgium)

**Recognition of Louis Philippe (July–August 1830)**
- James's first priority: push all powers to recognise **Louis Philippe** immediately
- Lionel argued non-recognition would destabilise France and encourage Belgian-style
  revolts in neighbouring provinces; the king gave James personal assurances of peace
- Louis Philippe's message to James ("My most ardent desires are centred upon the peace
  of Europe") was passed via James to Metternich through Ambassador Apponyi

**The Belgian Crisis**
- Brussels revolution (August 25, 1830): James brokered a meeting between French
  Foreign Minister **Molé** and the Prussian ambassador to forestall military clash
- Urged Nathan to oppose British-sponsored intervention on behalf of the Dutch King;
  concluded Belgian independence was practically and morally defensible
- James simultaneously relayed Louis Philippe's veiled warning to Metternich:
  he was opposing revolutionaries "as far as his position as constitutional monarch allowed"
  but was "compelled to show a certain regard for Liberal aspirations"
- Belgian question referred to London conference (Talleyrand + Aberdeen); but revolt
  in Warsaw then diverted Russian attention — the Polish uprising may have *prevented*
  general war by tying down Russia from February to October 1831

**Three Flashpoints, 1831–32**
- *First (early 1831)*: Austrian intervention in Papal states (Modena, Parma, Bologna)
  threatened French counter-move; James co-drafted the crucial French diplomatic note
  calling for international arbitration on the Belgian model; crisis passed by mid-April
- *Second (August 1831)*: Dutch invasion of Belgium raised war spectre again;
  Britain sanctioned French expeditionary force; danger receded by October;
  **24 Articles** signed November 15 but Prussia/Austria/Russia ratified only May 1832
- *Third (February–autumn 1832)*: French force occupied Ancona ("a serious blunder"
  per James); less serious than earlier crises; **Convention of London (May 1832)**
  preserved peace until the definitive 1839 settlement

> "The whole depends upon the question of war or peace. This govt. is for peace, but must
> be supported by the other powers and must not go against public opinion, or it would give
> too much strength to the opposition, which would then bring us war immediately."
> — Lionel, March 31, 1831

---

### James and the French Domestic-Foreign Policy Nexus

- James's central insight: fear of war in Paris was inseparable from fear of domestic
  radicalisation — being too aggressive abroad would bring more bellicose politicians
  to power in France
- Warned Metternich that French ministers sometimes spoke bellicosely only "for domestic
  consumption" — should not be taken literally abroad
- **Laffitte** (PM November 1830): James concluded he was heading for "complete anarchy"
  when Laffitte told him "If France does not declare war on Austria, in a matter of three
  weeks, the king will no longer be king and will lose his head"
- James advised Louis Philippe to appoint **Casimir Périer** instead; "talking to the
  king had the desired effect" — Laffitte resigned just over a week later
- James backed Périer as the French politician *least likely to go to war*:

> "Now, my dear Salomon, you must see that if my friend Périer takes office his ministry
> is supported, for thirty-two million people making a revolution are a danger to all countries."
> — James to Salomon, for Metternich's eyes, 1831

- James simultaneously pressed Salomon to lobby Metternich for Austrian restraint,
  arguing that Austria backing off would strengthen Périer's domestic position
- When Périer's position crumbled, James predicted "war within four days" if an
  "ultra-liberal" ministry took his place; Périer survived by taking limited military
  action against Holland with tacit approval of the powers

**Lionel's bleak political economy of war:**
> "There is in France too many young men, without employment and money and to get rid of
> them war is requisite, party spirit is also strong, and without a war, we should see the
> present king driven away." — Lionel, summer 1831

---

### The British Dimension: Toryism to Whiggery

- Rothschilds' shift from Tory to Whig alignment was driven by geopolitics, not ideology
- Nathan's Tory friends (Herries, Wellington) threatened that if France didn't yield,
  the British army would go to Germany; **Wellington as PM = war on France**
- The Whig position (relayed March 18, 1831): "if the other three powers take action
  against France, *we shall join France*" — far more congenial to James
- James feared Reform Bill defeat because Tory return = intervention against France
- "All now depends on England. The foreign powers would never declare war without England
  as an ally." — James to Nathan, January 1831
- Whig election victory of 1832 welcomed by James/Lionel/Anthony as "the best guarantee
  of peace in Europe"
- Nathan's decision not to support Wellington (unexpectedly back in office May 1832)
  reflected not just domestic commotions concern but foreign ministers' fear that
  Holland would gain British support and thereby trigger war

---

### Salomon in Vienna: Keeping Metternich Neutral

- Salomon returned to Vienna in October 1830 specifically "to impress upon Prince
  Metternich how important it now is to maintain peace"
- Metternich told Salomon in November 1830 he was prepared to "send troops . . .
  to keep [Italy] quiet" — and duly did so in Modena and Bologna
- Salomon's key service: his letters to James arrived up to three days before
  Austrian ambassador Apponyi's official instructions reached Paris
- Over Poland: Salomon forewarned Metternich's rival **Count Kolowrat**, who intervened
  "with uncharacteristic decisiveness" against Austrian assistance to the Tsar
- By July 1831 Salomon confidently assured brothers: "Austria will not make war, does
  not want war and is doing everything possible to avoid having a war"
- Austrian official Kübeck complained that "Prince Metternich is a veritable pendulum,
  swinging back and forth between Tatichev [the Russian ambassador] and war,
  and Salomon Rothschild and peace"

---

### Golden Chains: Financial Leverage and Its Limits

- The lobbying for peace derived force from two levers: (1) **communications channel**
  for informal diplomacy; (2) **financial pressure** — refuse loans to war-minded regimes,
  fund peace-minded ones
- Limits were severe in capitals where no partner was resident

**Prussia**
- 1830: Rothschilds caught mid-conversion of £3.8 million Prussian 5% bonds to 4% at 98;
  French revolution caused bonds to collapse to 79.5 — potential loss of £367,000+
- **Anselm** sent to Berlin for gruelling negotiations; eventually paid ~£140,000 indemnity
  (dwindling to ~£50,000 after deductions) to postpone the conversion
- Rother's argument to King **Frederick William III**: forcing Rothschilds to honour the
  contract at loss would cause them to dump bonds, damaging Prussian public credit;
  "financial transactions in which the von Rothschild firm do not act as intermediaries,
  but as opponents, are apt to fall through"
- In return, Rothschilds offered short-term cash advances of up to 5 million thaler
  against treasury bills — this secured the postponement; conversion resumed 1833
- No evidence of any attempt to influence Prussian *foreign* policy; Prussia gave
  Nathan the title of **Privy Commercial Councillor** and some porcelain as grudging thanks
- Rothschild financial leverage in Berlin sufficient only for commercial concessions,
  not political ones

**Russia**
- Rothschild influence in St. Petersburg was "almost non-existent"
- Russian Finance Minister **Kankrin** had never been on good terms with the Rothschilds
- James on Russia's request for a loan in early 1831: worried Kankrin lacked the cash
  to pay interest; "should it occur to the good man not to pay his interest, we will
  then be left floundering"
- James opposed taking any Russian loan direct; favoured commission only, small tranches
- Real anxiety was political: a Russia loan would be savaged in the Paris press,
  where sympathy for the Poles was intense

> "I beg you, in God's name, not to provide your name unless it is absolutely essential,
> that is, to register that 'Rothschild' has sold 'guns' . . . otherwise I am liable to
> be shot, for it will be said that I am selling guns to facilitate the shooting of the Poles."
> — James, after Nathan sold guns to Russia post-Ostrolenka

- A £1 million Russian loan resurfaced end of 1832; James still nervous but willing;
  **Kankrin "bamboozled" Nathan** by using Rothschild offer only to secure better terms
  from **Hope** (Russia's traditional banker) — Rothschilds excluded again
- James's verdict: "As far as I am concerned, Russia can go to the Devil, and we can
  quite happily do without them"

**London**
- Decline of Tory power → decline of Rothschild influence over British financial policy
- **Althorp** (Grey's Chancellor) was openly contemptuous of Nathan after their 1830 meeting
- British government barely borrowed in the 1830s (one exception: £15 million slave-owner
  compensation loan, 1835) — rendered Nathan largely superfluous
- Grey's resignation 1834 took Nathan wholly by surprise
- Nathan's leverage in London far less than James's in Paris because Britain didn't *need*
  Rothschild loans — influence was channel-based, not financial

**France (James's strongest leverage)**
- Paris house left in precarious state after 1830 revolution: large holdings of
  depreciating 3% and 5% rentes; 10 million francs still owed to Treasury on Polignac loan
- New French government immediately needed to borrow; James refused to be excluded
  despite criticising Laffitte's foreign policy — "big deals to be made here"
- James and Nathan sold ~28,000 British guns to the French government (while lobbying
  for peace) — a remarkable form of hedging
- James's key insight: France's fiscal weakness was the real constraint on war;
  "With what will they wage war? Consequently, I am convinced we will have no war"
- Périer explicitly recognised the fiscal constraint:

> "If we choose war, we will be unable to meet our debts, and I am therefore not prepared
> to join the ministry only to see the Treasury slide into bankruptcy the following day."
> — Périer to James, 1831

- 1831 "National Loan" public subscription was a failure: only 25 million of 80 million
  francs sold; consortium of banks (including Rothschilds) had to absorb the rest
- James's confession of impotence despite all his influence: "I am master of nothing.
  Times are no longer what they were. Previously, we would have taken on [such] a loan
  . . . by ourselves."

<!-- pp. 361-380 -->

## Chapter 9 (continued): Underwriting Peace — The Limits of Financial Power

### France: No Rothschild Monopoly

- 1832: **James de Rothschild** reasserted himself on the French market —
  Rothschild-led consortium underwrote a 40 million franc Paris city loan,
  then a 150 million franc government loan
- James delayed the larger loan until the Dutch relinquished claims on Belgium —
  using credit access as diplomatic leverage
- By early 1833, fears of French aggression faded; 3% rentes touched 80
- Key revisionist point: **no Rothschild monopoly** over French public finance
  in the 1830s — loans were handled by banking consortia, treasury bills
  distributed even more widely
- James's ministerial visits were less about leverage than about obtaining
  **financially sensitive news** ("going with Salomon to see Périer to hear
  whether he has any news")
- Ferguson's argument: if Prussia, Russia, and France had resolved to go
  to war over Belgium or Poland, the Rothschilds would have been **powerless
  to avert it** — the key variable was Metternich's Austria

### Salomon and Austria: Vienna's Financial Lever

- Nov 1830: **Salomon** told Gentz that after heavy losses, financing a war
  was "out of the question"
- Salomon was also NOT in a monopoly position in Vienna — spring 1830
  Austrian 30 million gulden loan issued via consortium with **Arnstein &
  Eskeles**, **Sina**, and **Geymüller**
- March 1831: Metternich requested 36 million gulden loan to finance
  intervention in Italy — Salomon participated alongside three other Vienna
  houses
- Salomon did not oppose Metternich's covert use of 20 million francs
  deposited from the 1815 **Treaty of Paris** in Frankfurt (German
  Confederation funds)
- Early 1832: Salomon threatened to withhold financial support if Metternich
  did not ratify the **24 Articles** on Belgium:

> "Your Highness is aware that we have subscribed a quarter of the last
> loan of 50 million and have also purchased securities on the Bourse in
> order to maintain the price of metalliques . . . I would humbly beg Your
> Highness to be pleased to let my manager know of your opinion as to the
> present situation and whether the Austrian Government will recognise
> Belgium."

- Metternich responded with reassurances about Russian and Austrian peaceful
  intentions — Austria then delayed ratification another three months anyway
- June 1832: Salomon's most explicit use of the financial lever — warning
  Austria against a second **metalliques** loan in 1832:

> "You cannot ride two horses at once; if our firm were forced to sell . . .
> what price could we expect to get? . . . What would the public say to a
> new loan? 'There will be war — there must be a war, as Austria is issuing
> another loan.'"

- Ferguson's rebuttal: this was primarily a **financial** argument to protect
  the Vienna house's own bond portfolio — not an anti-war threat
- Salomon was arguing for **Treasury bills** as an alternative, not blocking
  borrowing altogether
- A year later (1833) he and the other Vienna houses participated in a
  40 million florin metalliques issue; in 1834, a 25 million gulden lottery loan
- Conclusion: "If these were chains of peace, they did not bind tightly"

### Underwriting Peace: Lending to Both Sides

- Ferguson's central argument: Rothschild influence worked not by **denying**
  credit but by **making credit available** — underwriting settled outcomes
- **Belgian crisis** (1830–33):
  - Rothschilds had done business with **Société Générale** since 1827;
    within days of the Brussels revolution James re-established contact and
    advanced over 1 million francs
  - Nathan discussed a loan to Holland as a carrot to persuade the Dutch
    King to accept Belgian secession; Salomon saw it as helping "to control
    our war mongers"
  - When the Dutch invaded Belgium (Aug 1831), Nathan offered to sell guns
    to Brussels — wielding both carrot and stick
  - Only after Dutch withdrawal did Nathan and James revive the Dutch loan
    idea ("for if he has the money, he will not consider any warlike
    actions")
  - End of 1831: after **Leopold** signed the 24 Articles, Rothschilds
    (with Belgian banker **Osy**) floated a £2.75 million loan — five times
    the prior Holland loan
  - A contemporary British cartoon *The Protocol-Society in an Uproar*
    showed Nathan complaining: "Your Potecols are no use; help mi Cot,
    Shentlemen, if you don't make everyting out for me, I will lend you no
    more monish"
  - Anselm feared Belgium "will not be able to pay the Dividend for many
    years" but concluded "we must take things as they are and profit of the
    folly of the world" — war clause written into the underwriting agreement
  - Spring 1832: proposals for a second Belgian loan of £1.9 million; French
    government warned it would be "madness . . . to give the Belgians money
    . . . and give them every facility of making war"
  - **Thomas Raikes** (diarist): "Rothschild will not contract for the loan
    without binding the Belgians not to go to war. But there will be more
    temporising, as the stock-jobbing interest must prevail. All the nations
    of Europe want money, and dread a fall in the funds more than any other
    calamity."
  - Nov 1832: James reluctantly agreed to a 10 million franc short-term loan
    when French troops marched into Belgium — "One must help these people,
    for, otherwise, they will simply not know what to do"
  - In partnership with Société Générale, Paris house took more than half a
    new treasury bill issue; a remarkable gamble that paid off — Belgium
    became a **dynamo of European industrialisation**

- **Poland**: Rothschilds had Warsaw business links but were never interested
  in the Polish revolt's success — they sought to lend money to Russia (to
  crush the revolt) and sold guns to St. Petersburg

- **Italy / Papacy loan** (1832):
  - Brothers arranged a £400,000 loan to the Papacy with Italian banker
    **Torlonia** — even before political situation was stabilised
  - **Carl's audience with the Pope** (Jan 1832) was widely commented upon
  - **Ludwig Börne** sneered: "A poor Christian kisses the Pope's feet; a
    wealthy Jew kisses his hand . . . The Rothschilds are assuredly nobler
    than their ancestor Judas Iscariot. He sold Christ for 30 small pieces
    of silver; the Rothschilds would buy Him, if He were for sale."
  - **Heinrich Heine** gloated: "Like pagan Rome Christian Rome too was
    overcome and even obliged to pay tribute" — portraying James as having
    "all the money of this world in his pocket"
  - **Alfred de Vigny** (July 1837): "The Jewish banker says: '[God] has
    given me the royalty of wealth and the understanding of opulence, which
    is the sceptre of society.' A Jew now reigns over the Pope and
    Christianity. He pays monarchs and buys nations."
  - James initially wanted to let English banks (Wilson & Co., Wright & Co.)
    take the lead — two reasons: Jewish credit risk with the Pope ("if we
    should have a different Pope who is an evil man, he will say to himself
    that he could earn a ticket to Paradise if he refuses to pay anything to
    Jews"); and concerns about distribution (Catholic networks would place
    shares more easily)
  - Rothschilds structured the loan in three tranches with option to withdraw
    after the first — "the Pope, if he is in need of money, and he receives
    the same, will then ensure that peaceful conditions are maintained"
  - Demand exceeded expectations; Rothschilds cut out Wilson & Wright in a
    last-minute renegotiation; loan issued at 70, soon rose above 79, peaked
    at 83 in summer 1832, reached par by 1835

### The Consistent Logic: Great Power Guarantees

- Apparent contradiction: Rothschilds lent simultaneously to revolutionary
  Belgium and conservative Papacy
- Ferguson's resolution: the rationale was consistent — **Rothschilds lent
  to new states if they had the backing of the five great powers**
- Formal or informal great-power guarantees made loans attractive regardless
  of the borrower's political character
- This was a continuation of 1820s policy — contemporaries who called them
  "bankers to the Holy Alliance" **misrepresented** their actual strategy
- **Greece** (May 1832): powers signed a treaty guaranteeing a loan to the
  new King (a Bavarian, not the Coburg prince James had predicted); a 60
  million franc loan guaranteed by France, England and Russia; Rothschilds
  fought off **Bavarian banker d'Eichthal** and Spaniard **Aguado** for the
  deal
- Austrian diplomat **Apponyi**: "Mr. Rothschild, it must not happen that
  such a large deal, in which all the Powers are interested, should be
  completed without your participation"
- Where powers couldn't agree — e.g., **Portugal** (1830–34, Dom Pedro vs.
  Dom Miguel) — the Rothschilds kept their distance
- Ferguson's conclusion: in a **multi-polar world** seeking to resolve crises
  short of war, "the Rothschilds acted not so much to ensure peace — their
  power was more limited than that — as to *underwrite* it once it had been
  made"

---

## Chapter 10: The World's Bankers

> "The Rothschilds are the wonders of modern banking . . . We see the
> descendants of Judah, after a persecution of two thousand years, peering
> above kings, rising higher than emperors, and holding a whole continent in
> the hollow of their hands. The Rothschilds govern a Christian world. Not
> a cabinet moves without their advice . . . Baron Rothschild, the head of
> the house, is the true king of Judah, the prince of the captivity, the
> Messiah so long looked for by this extraordinary people. He holds the keys
> of peace or war, blessing or cursing."
> — *Niles Weekly Register*, 1835–36

### The Mythologized Image

- After 1832, as revolutionary fears subsided, the Rothschilds appeared to
  expand their financial reach geographically — prompting an outpouring of
  commentary
- **Thomas Raikes** (journal): "The Rothschilds, who began by sweeping out a
  shop at Manchester, have become the metallic sovereigns of Europe . . . No
  sovereign without their assistance now could raise a loan."
- **Prince Pückler** punned on German *Gläubiger* (believer/creditor): "the
  great R[othschild] could be compared with the Sultan, for the latter was
  the ruler of all believers, while the former was the creditor of all rulers"
- **Friedrich List** (economist): Rothschild was "the mighty lender and
  master of all the coined and uncoined silver and gold in the Old World,
  before whose money box Kings and Emperors humbly bow" — "King of Kings"
- **William Makepeace Thackeray** (*National Standard*, 1833):
  > "Here's the pillar of 'Change! Nathan Rothschild himself, / With whose
  > fame every bourse in the universe rings; / The first Baron Juif; by the
  > grace of his pelf, / Not 'the king of the Jews,' but 'the Jew of the kings.'"

### Anti-Semitic Caricature and Propaganda

- 1829 English print: Nathan as "the great humming top spinning a loan,"
  with kings bowing before him distributing coins
- *Die Generalpumpe* (c. 1840), anonymous German cartoon: depicted a
  grotesquely caricatured composite Rothschild as a **giant money pump**
  (*pumpen* = to pump/to lend) — standing knee-deep in gold, stomach = the
  earth itself, paper crown bearing names of major Rothschild loans
  (Prussian, Russian, Neapolitan, Austrian, Portuguese); badge reads
  "Executor of the Court of all the World"
  - Recipients of Rothschild money (Louis Philippe, Adolphe Thiers, Mehemet
    Ali, Ibrahim Pasha, British Chancellor of the Exchequer) are entangled
    in thorny tendrils sprouting from the money bag
  - The cartoon suggests Rothschild "not only pumps money to the world,
    but sucks it back like a monstrous heart"

### The Reality: Humdrum Appearance vs. Mythic Power

- The real Nathan bore little resemblance to these caricatures
- One contemporary description: "a very common looking person, with heavy
  features, flabby pendent lips, and a projected fish eye. His figure,
  which was stout, awkward and ungainly, was enveloped in the loose folds
  of an ample surtout."
- **Richard Dighton** etching *A View from the Royal Exchange* (1817):
  side-view of a stout man, top hat, stomach forward, one hand in pocket
- **Thomas Jones**, *A Pillar of the Exchange* (1829): Nathan beside his
  favourite pillar at the south-east corner — juxtaposition of white regular
  pillar vs. Nathan's dark protuberant shape; he is the pillar in solidity
  but its implicit opposite in form
- French sculptor **Jean-Pierre Dantan** (1832): terracotta statuette —
  lips drooping like a cod, distended belly defying gravity atop skinny legs
- Thackeray's accompanying sketch of *N. M. Rothschild, Esq.*: omitted the
  fat stomach but the accompanying verse called him "A greasy-faced compound
  of donkey and pig"
- Post-death silhouettes titled *The Shadow of a Great Man* — more
  sympathetic but not flattering; even family-commissioned portraits did not
  glamorise him
- American visitor: Nathan had "something commanding in his air and manner"
  — "Who is that?" / "The King of the Jews" was the exchange

### The Office: Mundane Bustle

- **Prince Pückler** (1826): found "the ruler of the City . . . in fact
  occupies here only an insignificant location . . . in the little courtyard
  of the counting house my access . . . was impeded by a van loaded with
  silver ingots"
- **Disraeli's *Tancred*** (fictional recreation): Rothschild-like "Sidonia"
  closeted with a foreign ambassador; visitors cool their heels; porter
  barely acknowledges them; the office is oak-panelled with Turkey carpet,
  crimson damask, iron cabinets, large tables covered with papers, glass
  door to counting-house full of clerks
- **James in Paris** (1837, Parisian journalist): James arrived between 3
  and 3:25 p.m. (5–10 minutes before close), accompanied by a nephew,
  "his entrance creates not the slightest sensation . . . his conversation
  is never long and no one whispers a word of it; the bell rings and he
  goes just like everyone else — with no more ceremony than accompanied
  his arrival"
- **Salomon in Vienna**: "Every day from the opening of the Bourse at 12
  o'clock to its close at four, he is besieged by brokers and stockjobbers
  anxious to give him reports of the tendency of the market"
- **Metternich's son Viktor** visiting James in the late 1820s: office was
  "like a positive magic lantern for people of the most various appearance
  . . . The great banker himself, who generally maintains an attitude of
  such dignified calm, betrayed a certain nervousness. Our conversation was
  frequently interrupted by bourse agents reporting quotations to their chief."
- Frankfurt bank described as "open plan" in its design

<!-- pp. 381-400 -->

## Chapter 10: The Rothschild System (continued)

### Nathan's Character and Working Style

- Visitors to Rothschild offices were invariably disappointed — no
  visible mystery, just brokers, clerks, and exchanging pieces of paper
- Mythologizing of Rothschild power (Hebrew talisman, Balzac's
  Nucingen fraud) arose because the mundane reality didn't explain
  the results
- **Nathan's** real advantage: extraordinary mental arithmetic and
  photographic memory for every transaction he'd ever made
- His *Times* obituarist noted he "never took a note" yet "could
  dictate the whole on his return home with perfect exactness"
- Behavioral paradox: received assassination threat "with a smile"
  in 1821, yet was "beside himself" when a stranger occupied his
  usual spot at the **Royal Exchange**
- The *Circular to Bankers* noted his "strong and unfettered will"
  and "pride of temper resulting from his high new position"
- Brutality in correspondence: nephews begged Lionel to have
  Nathan stop "such violent letters against Uncle Amschel" (1828)
- By the 1830s, fraternal strife less about Nathan's dominance and
  more about his **indifference** — he was too busy to engage the
  continental houses adequately

### Centrifugal Tensions Within the Partnership

- **Amschel** (Frankfurt) complained London gave preference to Paris
  and Vienna; Nathan had to be lobbied repeatedly to do business
  with his own brother
- **Carl** (Naples) leveled same complaint against **James** (Paris)
  in 1833; Nathan forced to arbitrate
- James's response showed family pride: "I am no less a Rothschild
  and I can stand on my honour as much as our brother Carl"
- These disputes show Nathan as "commanding general" — the pillar
  on which the entire edifice rested — but also that the system
  needed structural buttresses beyond his personality alone

### The Rothschild System: Partnership Agreements as Constitution

- The single "secret" of Rothschild success: **the multinational
  co-operation system** uniting five houses across Europe's major
  financial centers, making them collectively the world's largest bank
- Partnership agreements revised every few years — effectively a
  **financial federation constitution**
- Key milestones:
  - **1810**: First agreement, but untypical (Mayer Amschel dominant,
    Nathan excluded during wartime)
  - **1815**: First authentically "federal" agreement — all five
    brothers; total notional capital £336,000
    - Nathan: 27%; Amschel & Salomon: 20% each; Carl & James: 16%
    - Net profits shared equally; all expenses from London revenues
  - **1818**: Revised after Nathan's consol speculations grew capital
    from £336k to £1,772,000
    - Nathan now received **half** of London profits; brothers ⅛ each
    - Nathan also got 4/16ths of other houses' profits
    - New rule: 4% annual income on individual capital share for
      personal/business expenses; large purchases (estates, legacies)
      deducted from capital
    - Houses to inform each other of transactions **weekly**
  - **1825**: Restored equal profit-sharing as Frankfurt and Paris
    had grown to outstrip London; total capital now over £4 million
    - Salomon's son **Anselm** admitted as partner (married Nathan's
      daughter **Charlotte**)
    - Vienna and Naples kept as mere "branch establishments" of
      Frankfurt without separate capital until 1828 — to check
      centrifugal forces
    - Heirs bound to accept share without legal resort; lawsuit by
      heir = forfeit of one-third of deceased's share to the poor
      of Frankfurt, London, and Paris
    - Information-sharing shifted from weekly to **monthly**
  - **1836** (fateful Frankfurt meeting, Nathan died during):
    Continental partners secured more favorable terms — Nathan to get
    60% of London profits but only 10% from Frankfurt/Naples/Vienna;
    brothers 10% from London and 22.5% from continentals each
    - This increased London autonomy; rule retained after Nathan's
      death, rights transferred to his four sons

### Capital Growth: Scale of Rothschild Wealth

**Table 10a: Combined Rothschild Capital (£ thousands)**

| House     | 1797 | 1807 | 1815 | 1818   | 1825   | 1828   | 1836   | 1844   |
|-----------|------|------|------|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
| Frankfurt | 9.9  | 50.6 | 68   | 680    | 1,450  | 1,534  | 2,121  | 2,750  |
| Paris     | —    | —    | 55   | 350    | 1,490  | 1,466  | 1,774  | 2,311  |
| London    | —    | —    | 90   | 742    | 1,142  | 1,183  | 1,733  | 2,005  |
| Vienna    | —    | —    | 68   | —      | 25     | 110    | 268    | 250    |
| Naples    | —    | —    | 55   | —      | 130    | 268    | 268    | 463    |
| **Total** | 9.9  | 50.6 | 336  | 1,772  | 4,082  | 4,338  | 6,008  | 7,778  |

- In 1825: combined resources **nine times** greater than **Baring
  Brothers**; eleven times larger than James's Paris rival **Laffitte**
- Rothschild capital even exceeded the **Banque de France** (~£3m)
- Profits were volatile: best year 1834 (~25% of capital); worst
  1847 (~one-third of capital **lost**)
- Key structural difference vs. rivals: **Rothschilds ploughed back
  net profits**, accumulating capital; **Barings** maximized gross
  profits and distributed them, keeping capital roughly constant
  - 1829–1846: N. M. Rothschild capital up 90%; Barings up only 50%

### Surprising Finding: London Was Least Profitable

**Table 10b: Average Annual Profits (£ thousands), 1818–1844**

| House     | 1818–25 | 1825–28 | 1828–36 | 1836–44 | Average |
|-----------|---------|---------|---------|---------|---------|
| Frankfurt | 110     | 28      | 73      | 79      | 80      |
| Paris     | 163     | –8      | 38      | 67      | 75      |
| London    | 57      | 14      | 69      | 34      | 49      |
| Vienna    | —       | 8       | 11      | 17      | N/A     |
| Naples    | —       | 43      | 17      | 24      | N/A     |

- Counter-intuitive: the **Frankfurt** house was the most profitable
  of the three principal houses across 1818–1844; Paris second;
  London least
- **Naples** house — though regarded by contemporaries as run by the
  least gifted brother — never recorded a loss, not even in the
  crises of 1825, 1830, or 1836
- Carl's average annual profits £30,000+ (1825–29) on capital of
  only ~£130,000 — remarkable returns
- **James** lost £356,000 in 1825 crisis but recovered: £44,000
  profit the next year, £124,000 the year after
- Houses deeply interlinked: Naples balance sheets show 18–30% of
  assets were debts owed by other Rothschild houses; Paris house
  had 31% of 1828 assets as credits to other Rothschilds

### Revenue Sources: How the Rothschilds Made Their Money

#### Government Bonds

- Their "first love" and the activity most discussed in letters
- Between 1815–1859, London house issued **50 loans** (primarily
  government) totaling ~**£250 million** nominal — roughly a tenth
  of total British overseas assets in the 1850s
- Barings issued only 14 loans totaling £66 million in same period

**Table 10d: London House Loans by Borrower, 1818–1846**

| Borrower      | Total (£)   | % of total |
|---------------|-------------|------------|
| Britain       | 44,938,547  | 29.2%      |
| France        | 27,700,000  | 18.0%      |
| Holy Alliance | 29,029,566  | 18.8%      |
| Belgium       | 11,681,064  | 7.6%       |
| Private sector| 24,900,000  | 16.2%      |
| **Total**     |154,079,127  | 100%       |

- Biggest clients were **France and Britain** — not the Holy Alliance
  as mythologized; "bankers to the Holy Alliance" label was
  **exaggerated**
- Largest proportion of assets (~quarter to third) held in government
  bonds; rough policy across houses to keep ~one-third in
  "gilt-edged" **state securities**
- Much bond profit came from **speculation in existing bonds**, not
  just new issues — and this is harder to quantify from records

#### Bills of Exchange (Merchant Banking)

- The classic London merchant banker's business: accepting
  **commercial bills of exchange** — instruments giving buyers credit
  for 3–4 months to pay sellers
- Banker's role: act as acceptor (charging acceptance commission) or
  buy bill at discount (charging interest); accepting a bill = selling
  use of your creditworthy name
- In 1828, "bills receivable" = **quarter** of London house assets;
  "bills payable" = 5% of liabilities
- Nathan to Bank Committee (1832): "this country in general is the
  Bank for the whole world . . . all transactions in India, in China,
  in Germany . . . are guided here, and settled through this country"
- Rothschilds' bills strategy: **arbitrage on exchange rate
  differentials**, not commission income; Nathan charged **half a
  per cent less** than competitors to win volume, profiting instead
  on price spreads between European markets
- **Walter Bagehot** in *Lombard Street* called them "the greatest
  of the foreign bill-brokers" — but this accolade actually belonged
  to **Baring Brothers**
  - 1825: Nathan's acceptances £300,000 vs. Barings £520,000
  - 25 years later: New Court £540,000 vs. Barings £1.9 million
  - Gap widened further as **Kleinworts** and transatlantic trade grew
- Rothschilds less dominant in bills because the biggest volume came
  from transatlantic trade (Barings' turf), not Britain–Europe trade

#### Bullion and Specie

- **International bullion market** flowed naturally from bill-broking
- When exchange rates hit "gold points," it paid to ship specie;
  the Rothschilds did substantial business with the **Bank of England**
  and the **Banque de France**
- Bullion consignments worth tens of thousands of pounds passed
  regularly between Paris and London — literally silver-ingot vans
  blocking access to New Court
- Nathan: "My business . . . consists entirely in Government
  transactions & Bank operations"

#### Commodity Trade

- Original Rothschild business (Mayer Amschel; Nathan's textile
  roots), but interest **dwindled in the 1820s**
- Strategy: unlike Barings (wide range of goods), Rothschilds chose
  **dominant position in select markets**
- Key commodities: **cotton, tobacco, sugar** (Americas/Caribbean),
  **copper** (Russia), **mercury** (Spain — most important)
- Dabbled occasionally in iron, wool, wine — but never jacks-of-all-
  trades; Worms brothers' Ceylon tea plantation even named
  "Rothschild" but the bank never engaged in tea seriously

#### Insurance

- Nathan co-founded **Alliance Assurance Company** (1824) — the
  only joint-stock company he ever took a serious interest in
- Motivations debated: casual meeting with brother-in-law **Moses
  Montefiore**; employment for relative **Benjamin Gompertz**
  (accomplished mathematician/actuary); discrimination by existing
  insurers against Jewish business; or breaking the cartel of
  **Lloyd's**, London Assurance, and Royal Exchange on marine insurance
- **Duke of Saxe-Coburg**'s rejected life insurance application
  provided further impetus (1823)
- MP **Thomas Fowell Buxton** (one of Alliance's auditors) introduced
  bill to end marine insurance monopoly in House of Commons
- Alliance established with capital of **£5 million**; government
  persuaded and bill received royal assent June 1824
- Lloyd's shareholder obtained injunction restraining Alliance from
  marine insurance → required creation of separate **Alliance Marine
  Assurance Company** (also £5 million capital)
- Public skepticism captured in cartoon *A New Court Fire Screen*:
  depicts Rothschild, Montefiore, Gompertz at "Hollow Alliance Fire
  and Life Preserving Office," sign reading "No Persons to be admitted
  but those with empty heads and full pockets"
- Alliance proved its critics wrong: a securely founded enterprise,
  long-lived and prosperous; moved from 4 New Court to Bartholomew Lane
- Further insurance ventures: 1839, supported **Colonia** fire
  insurance (set up by Oppenheims) in Rhineland; 1852, London/
  Frankfurt/Paris as major shareholders in **Cologne Reinsurance
  Society**

> "He never hesitated for a moment in fixing the rate, either as a
> drawer or a taker, on any part of the world, and his memory was so
> retentive, that, notwithstanding the immense transactions into which
> he entered on every foreign post day, and that he never took a note
> of them, he could dictate the whole on his return home with perfect
> exactness to his clerks."
> — *The Times* obituary on Nathan Rothschild

> "I buy on the Exchange bills drawn from Liverpool, Manchester,
> Newcastle and other places . . . I purchase £6,000 or £7,000, and
> sometimes £10,000 of those bills in a week, and I send them to the
> Continent to my houses; my houses purchase against them bills upon
> this country which are purchases for wine, wool and other
> commodities."
> — Nathan Rothschild, testimony to Bank Committee (1832)

<!-- pp. 401-420 -->

## Chapter 10 (cont.): The Rothschild Network

### Expanding the Partnership — Next Generation

- Business volume exceeded what five brothers could manage personally;
  needed salaried agents plus expanded family partnership
- **Anselm** (Salomon's son): made partner 1826, but not trusted with
  sensitive Berlin negotiations until 1830; father's classic advice:
  "listen to everything and say little in reply"

> "You are now the plenipotentiary of all the brothers . . . and in the
> same way all the brothers will [have to] approve everything, as
> fundamentally the business entails a considerable risk, so do not
> write too little . . . and be hard-working and busy and in all these
> undertakings put your reliance in the Almighty."
> — Salomon to Anselm, c. 1830

- Within a year Anselm was criticising his uncles' post-July Revolution
  investment strategy; James quickly sought his assistance ("he really
  has character") — prescient: Anselm later limited damage to the five
  houses during 1848 crisis
- **Lionel** (Nathan's eldest): formally initiated into business 1828,
  appointed "Lieutenant General" while Nathan travelled to Frankfurt;
  Madrid trip 1835 judged a success; stepped into father's shoes 1836
- Younger brothers far more reluctant:
  - **Anthony**: cut short Frankfurt apprenticeship over a romantic
    entanglement; hated Frankfurt ("that stinking place"); James said
    he was "hard working" but failed "to bring the deals which will
    remain for future generations"; never lost his unreliable
    reputation — as late as 1840 brother Nat protested at his "very
    coarse language" in letters
  - **Nat**: more placid but resented Naples posting, complained he
    was "of no service" and "should be much better employed in London
    where I certainly might learn business in about a twentieth of
    the time"; eventually became James's favourite nephew; sent to
    Constantinople 1833 (unwise choice, amid Greek loan wrangle);
    spent career in James's shadow, perpetually a "disgruntled English
    gentleman in exile"

### Why No Sixth House?

- Brothers intermittently discussed Madrid, St Petersburg, and even a
  US house; plan for a **"sixth house"** across the Atlantic remained
  a pipe-dream
- Trusted only five sons enough: **Anselm, Lionel, Mayer Carl,
  Adolph, Alphonse** — Anthony, Nat, Mayer, and Wilhelm Carl lacked
  the spark or commitment
- Nathan's widow **Hannah** resolutely refused to allow younger sons
  posted overseas — a decisive obstacle

### Salaried Clerks and Agents

- Clerks had always existed since Judengasse days; partners regarded
  them as "drones" — worked hard, treated well, watched carefully
- Frankfurt office 1818: at least **nine clerks** with specialized roles
  (Radius & Kremm for bookkeeping; Berend for correspondence/ledger;
  Geiger for coupons; Hamburg for titled-customer correspondence;
  Heisler for bills of exchange; Kaiser for domestic matters)
- Frankfurt office costs: **150,000 gulden/year (~£14,000)**; Carl
  suspected clerks of "trickery"
- Paris: James spent **34,000 francs/year (£1,700)** on eight clerks,
  porter, messenger, two servants, coachman
- Key clerk dynasties: **Goldschmidt family** in Vienna — Moritz
  Goldschmidt was Salomon's chief clerk (moved from Frankfurt 1803);
  his sons Julius, Jacob, Alexander served Vienna, Frankfurt, and
  Paris respectively; nephews placed in Amsterdam, London, and Spain
- By 1830s New Court alone employed **30–40 people**, earning £50–£500/year
- Partners were paternalistic but never formalized hierarchy; Nathan's
  monopoly over executive decisions bred indolence — clerks were
  "spared difficult decisions and all but guaranteed bonuses"
- Crisis point: when both Nat and Anthony might leave to attend
  Nathan's deathbed, first time ever clerks had to be given
  **powers of attorney** — unclear who was senior in London office

### The Agent Problem

- Remote agents (Madrid, St Petersburg, New York) could not be treated
  as mere office-boys — they necessarily acquired local status and
  made independent decisions
- Rothschilds constantly suspected agents of **trading on their own
  account**; endless complaints of insolence, independence, incompetence
- **Gasser** (St Petersburg): James furious in 1829 that he showed
  "no interest at all in our business affairs" when silver shipment
  bound for Russia; threatened in 1838 to stop paying his 14,000
  roubles/year salary; "That stiff dog, who is only too glad to hold
  on to your money at no cost to himself"
- **Lazare Richtenberger** (Brussels, from 1832): first fully-fledged
  Rothschild agent; still occasionally dismissed as an "ass" despite
  punctilious subservience — sometimes acted before receiving
  James's instructions
- **Daniel Weisweiller** (Madrid, from 1834): most important 1830s
  agent; indispensable despite "triple dose of vanity"; Anselm wanted
  to replace him by 1843 ("the man is half cracked & fancies himself
  of the highest importance"); Anthony confronted him directly but
  admitted: "He is an uncommonly clever agent and it would be
  difficult to replace him . . . I have seldom or never seen a more
  disagreeable cold hearted calculating agent"
- **Hanau** (New York): criticized immediately for "over-hasty
  dealings" — though if he'd taken longer to learn the ropes he
  would have been criticized for idling; only Rothschilds could fault
  an agent for "directing too much of his attention towards finding
  out all the business he could for us"

### Associated Banks — Partners vs. Associates

- Distinction matters: salaried agents vs. **associated banks** who
  corresponded regularly and got preferential business
- By end of 1840s associates in: Amsterdam, Baltimore, Berlin, Cologne,
  Constantinople, Florence, Hamburg, Milan, Odessa, Rome, Trieste
- **Warburg** (Hamburg): lobbying for Rothschild business since 1814;
  regular dealings not until 1830s; Carl Heine (poet Heinrich's uncle)
  preferred until 1860s
- **Samuel Bleichröder** (Berlin): tried to supplant the Mendelssohns
  as Rothschild's Berlin banker; not until 1860s that his son
  **Gerson Bleichröder** gained special status — proximity to
  **Bismarck** made him valuable for political intelligence

> "Bleichröder? What is Bleichröder? Bleichröder is the one per cent
> I let him have."
> — James to Herbert Bismarck

- Other associates: Oppenheims (Cologne), Schröders (London),
  Banque de Bordeaux — all minor players before 1848
- Major rivals (Barings, Thomas Wilson, Goldschmidt in London;
  Laffitte, Hottinguer, Mallet in Paris; Geymüller, Sina, Eskeles
  in Vienna; Bethmann and Gontard in Frankfurt) increasingly treated
  as **complementary** — the Rothschilds saw themselves as *primus
  inter pares* with responsibility for overall financial stability
- Contrast with 1820s callousness toward Parish collapse: by 1830s–40s,
  willing to rescue rivals — assisted **Laffitte** in 1831 and 1838;
  Salomon argued for bailing out **Geymüller** in 1841:

> "To sit back and watch the bankruptcy of a man of 65 years—of a
> house which has existed for so long . . . was just impossible . . .
> If Steiner and Geymüller do have to stop their payments, what a
> spectacle it would be . . . several million—as many as 3 or 4
> million—gulden of acceptances and bills would be turned away."
> — Salomon, 1841

- Salomon overruled by brothers and nephews in that case
- This **quasi-central-bank mentality** also shaped Lionel's 1839
  view on joint-stock bank regulation: "how to keep these gentlemen
  from getting too fat and getting themselves and the country into
  scrapes without too much cramping the circulation"
- Rothschilds' relationship with actual central banks was close and
  symbiotic: Bank of England (Nathan's short-term loans in 1820s;
  Rothschilds rescued BoE in 1825; BoE advanced bullion to bail out
  James in 1830); Banque de France; Austrian Nationalbank

### 'Change — The Bourse and Brokers

- James's advice on Paris bourse (1836): don't aim for immediate profit
  — get brokers dependent on you, "spread the sugar about in order to
  catch the birds later on"
- Brokers were "indispensable worker-ants of nineteenth-century finance";
  most dealings conducted **orally**, leaving little historical trace
- Favourite brokers: **Menet & Cazenove** (London) sold £2m of foreign
  stocks for Rothschilds in 1834 alone, £1.4m the next year;
  partnership of **John Helbert Israel** and nephew **John Wagg**
- Even favourites treated casually: **Alfred Wagg** recalled Baron
  Lionel writing an **arbitrary fee of £500 or £1,000** on settlement
  days "varying in amount according to the humour he was in"
- Tactical reason for using many brokers: need to conduct some
  operations **surreptitiously**
- By late 1820s Nathan was "the master of the exchange" — smaller
  traders watched his positions, crediting him with superior
  information; overt Rothschild buys or sells could trigger market-
  wide imitation he didn't want
- Nathan's counter-tactics: if he had bullish news, he would commission
  brokers **initially to sell** half a million; common practice to
  have one set of agents selling and another buying the same stock
  simultaneously "so that there was no ascertaining what in reality
  was the object of his manoeuvres"
- Salomon in Vienna used a **jobber on 12,000 gulden fixed salary**
  who maintained runners to report price fluctuations from both the
  official Bourse and the "Panduren-Lager" (Grünangergasse café —
  unofficial after-hours market)

### Press Relations

- Financial press was a double-edged sword: eroded Rothschild
  information advantage but created new opportunities for market
  influence
- In 1820s more often targets of press attacks than manipulators
- Gradually built influence over sympathetic papers:
  - Salomon through **Gentz** → German *Allgemeine Zeitung*
  - **Heinrich Heine** as *Allgemeine Zeitung* Paris correspondent
    ensured positive (if satirical) James coverage in 1830s
  - James steadily expanded influence over *Moniteur Universel*
    and *Journal des Débats*
  - 1839: James could assure nephews he would "see to it" that the
    French government was "attacked in all the newspapers" if it
    opposed his railway plans: **"If one can't make oneself loved
    then one has to make oneself feared"** (quoting Mayer Amschel)
- Nathan built enduring relationship with **The Times** — sharing a
  pigeon-post service Boulogne–London by end of 1830s; close friend
  **Thomas Massa Alsager** (City correspondent, joined *The Times*
  1817, leading financial writer until 1846)
- Radicals and Chartists called *The Times* "the Jew's harp"
- Rothschilds used *The Times* and *Journal des Débats* connection
  to plant pro-Jewish articles targeting the King of Prussia (1842)

### Legal Disputes and Fraud

- Rothschilds operated in an era of minimal financial regulation;
  anachronistic to charge them with "insider dealing"
- Balzac's *Comédie humaine* character **Nucingen** (modelled on
  James) supposedly made fortune through bogus bankruptcies — Ferguson
  dismisses this as fiction with "little economic sense"
- Very few legal actions against Nathan; in only one did charges stick:
- **Brookman case (1829)**: Nathan advised Brookman in 1818 to sell
  20,000 francs of French rentes and buy new Prussian sterling loan;
  rentes promptly rose 10%, Prussian bonds fell 7%; Nathan had kept
  Brookman's rentes for himself rather than selling to third party;
  then sold Prussian bonds (against Brookman's instructions) and
  advised fresh purchase of rentes; charged Brookman fees for
  transactions that never actually occurred — the rentes remained in
  Rothschild hands throughout; Vice-Chancellor found Nathan guilty of
  "fallacious statements," ordered repayment of all losses plus 5%
  interest plus costs
- The Rothschilds were more often **victims** of fraud than perpetrators:
  - 1824: Frenchman Doloret fraudulently obtained bills worth £9,670
  - 1825: James's clerk stole ~1.5 million francs in banknotes
    concealed in a specially designed belt
  - 1838: Clerk **Samuel Green** absconded with cheque for £2,900
  - 1839: Paris house robbed
  - 1845: Madrid office — gold and securities worth ~£40,000 stolen;
    also Spanish piastres worth ~£5,600 stolen from Rothschild coach
    London–Paris
  - 1863: Extortion attempt — man who lost heavily on bourse demanded
    100,000 francs from James via threatening letters

---

## Chapter 11: Nathan's Death and Legacy (1836)

### The Frankfurt Gathering — Wedding and Business

- **Lionel de Rothschild**'s marriage to **Charlotte** (Naples branch) in 1836
  was the largest Rothschild family conclave of the nineteenth century
- **Endogamous marriage** was deliberate policy: James had married niece
  Betty in 1824; Anselm married cousin Charlotte two years later; many
  more to follow — primary goal was keeping capital within the family
- The gathering doubled as a **marriage market**: younger siblings and
  cousins assessed for compatibility. Mayer Carl eyed for Louise;
  Louisa Montefiore considered for Anthony; Joseph Montefiore spurned
  by both Hannah Mayer and Louise

> "Only fancy, to be seated as I am sometimes between *Grossmutter* and aunt Eva and to be stuffed so full as scarcely to be able to breathe." — Louise de Rothschild on the Frankfurt gathering

- Younger Rothschilds raised in England found Frankfurt "tediously
  provincial" — Jews there still subject to legal discrimination their
  London/Paris counterparts did not face
- **Music lesson with Rossini** provided the only relief for Louise

### The Partnership Renewal

- The **third and most important** purpose of the 1836 gathering: renewing
  the Rothschild partnership agreement
- Partnership had been renewed periodically: new contracts in 1815,
  1818, 1825 (Anselm admitted as sleeping partner), 1828 (Anselm
  became full "real Associé")
- By 1836 Nathan wanted **Lionel** elevated to partner on equal footing
  with Anselm — this was the primary business item
- All five brothers had not met together since **1828** — shuttling had
  declined as brothers aged and local commitments grew
- Key agenda items: Spain (civil war), Greece, Naples, Belgium —
  all countries where Rothschilds held financial interests
- **Railway financing** newly on the agenda: James deeply involved in
  French rail network; needed access to British capital through Nathan
- Nathan himself was **skeptical of railways** — preferred US loans and
  sovereign lending over industrial concerns; sat out the 1836 British
  railway "mania" (29 new companies chartered that year)
- A **brewing US financial crisis** (monetary tightening in London) also
  hung over the meeting

### Partnership Terms Agreed

- Negotiations held in **strict secrecy** — other family members excluded
- Nathan proposed London take half the combined profits; others
  accepted immediately without dispute

> "Till now, thank heavens, there has not been one angry word between the Brothers. They pass their time at [Papa's room] and the [counting] house, and dine altogether at one of the three houses quite *en famille*." — Lionel de Rothschild

- Frankfurt artist **Moritz Daniel Oppenheim** painted portraits of all
  five brothers to mark the occasion
- Rothschild motto: **"Concordia"** — this was one of the rare moments
  it was truly lived out

### Nathan's Final Illness

- **Only shadow** over the gathering: Nathan Rothschild was dying
- He had suffered a recurrence of an **ischio-rectal abscess** — first
  struck at Brussels before arriving in Frankfurt
- German doctors attempted to lance the boil repeatedly; no anaesthesia;
  excruciating pain. **Professor Chelius** from Heidelberg summoned
- Nathan refused to postpone the wedding on his account; rose at 6am
  on the wedding day, walked to the ceremony, made jokes to "shorten
  the speech of the worthy Rabbi"

> "Papa has a most terrible boil on his bottom and suffers very much from it. He has not yet been able to leave his bed and has a great deal of pain." — Lionel de Rothschild

- By end of June recovering enough to dictate orders, but partnership
  agreement finalization postponed — irritating James and Lionel alike
- Doctors continued opening and draining wounds through July with no
  real improvement; Nathan sought comfort in "Soda Water, Lavender,
  Oranges, Arrowroot and fruit" sent by courier from England
- **July 24**: Nathan lapsed into "violent" fever — onset of **septicaemia**
- In near-delirium he summoned Lionel, dictating orders to sell
  English Securities, Exchequer Bills, £20,000 India Stock, and
  Portuguese securities — even at 2% loss. So out of character that
  Lionel was stunned: "such sales across the board seemed almost
  incomprehensible"

### Nathan's Deathbed Instructions

- Nathan died before the new partnership agreement had been signed —
  a fraught moment for the firm's future
- **Salomon** informed Austrian Chancellor **Metternich**: the new
  three-year contract had been fully drawn up and ready for signature
  when Nathan died
- Nathan had just enough energy for a final exercise of his
  "domineering will": dictated his wishes to Salomon

**Four deathbed instructions:**
1. Sons to "carry on in harmony and peace the banking house founded
   by me under my name in London"
2. Wife **Hannah** to have a vote on all important consultations; sons
   not to "embark on any transaction of importance" without her
   motherly advice
3. The London firm and the four brothers' houses were to remain
   partners — sons to follow uncles' advice
4. New partnership contract not to be terminated within **five years**;
   trading capital of all four brothers and N.M. Rothschild locked up
   for five years; nobody to draw from working capital; individual
   interest draw reduced from **4% to 3%** — preserving capital, no
   speculative ventures for the young men

> "He charged his eldest son, and through him all those who were not present, always to apply all their efforts to keep the business property intact and not to participate in any risky ventures. He gave them much wise counsel, bade them avoid all evil company and always to keep in the way of true virtue, religion and righteousness." — Salomon de Rothschild

- Final words to family: maintain "harmony, constant love and firm
  unity" — a conscious echo of his own father Mayer Amschel's
  dying words
- To daughter Betty as she took leave: "Good night for ever."
- To Salomon: "It is not necessary that I should pray so much, for,
  believe me, according to my convictions I have not sinned."
- News conveyed to London by **carrier pigeon from Boulogne** in a
  single three-word sentence: **"Il est mort."**

### Legacy and Legend

#### Market Impact

- Nathan's death had **economic effects comparable to very few deaths**
  in the 19th century — one of only a handful with such consequences
- For comparison: when Austrian Emperor Francis died the year before,
  there was only a minor Viennese panic; Nathan's death removed the
  market's "strongest prop"
- *The Times* had been anxiously reporting on his health; on July 27
  reported (wrongly) his condition was "not at all dangerous"; on
  August 2 categorically denied reports of his death
- City opinion was less sanguine — Spanish and Portuguese securities
  fell 1.5%; market nearly frozen as traders feared Rothschild loan
  call-ins

> "The variations of all stocks & their wild fluctuations seem to arise much from Nathan's death. In the end the emancipation of the money market will be a benefit, but the sudden cessation of a despotic rule is apt to exhibit such symptoms." — **Alexander Baring**

- Paradoxically, when death was **confirmed** August 3, there was a slight
  **rally** — markets had already discounted the event; confidence that
  his sons would continue business as usual
- But from first week of August through year-end, consol prices fell
  steadily to nadir of **87 in November**
- **Bank rate** (Bank of England base lending rate) raised for first time
  in nine years from 4% to 4.5% on July 21; raised again September 1
- Rothschilds' London house suffered its **first loss since 1830** in 1836:
  equivalent to more than **4% of capital**
- *Times* obituarist (**Thomas Massa Alsager**, probably) called Nathan's
  death "one of the most important events for the city and perhaps for
  Europe, which has occurred for a very long time"

> "It is impossible at once to replace that moral influence which the acknowledged good judgement of the head of that opulent firm had established for himself not only in Great Britain but throughout the whole of the commercial world." — **David Salomons**, pamphlet on monetary matters

#### Funeral and Public Mourning

- Funeral cortège on August 8: headed by city police, inspector on
  horseback, 40 mourning coaches (Goldsmid, Cohen, Samuel, Israel
  families), then carriages of Lord Mayor, **Mr Sheriff Salomons**,
  35 foreign ambassadors' and noblemen's carriages — **75 carriages total**
- Procession took more than a quarter hour to pass through Cornhill;
  shops shut; windows crowded with spectators
- Among mourners: **Prussian, Russian, Austrian, and Neapolitan
  ambassadors**, Lord Stewart, the Duke of Marlborough
- Jewish community turned out in force; Chief Rabbi **Solomon Hirschell**
  preached at the Great Synagogue, Duke Place; Nathan buried in
  northwest corner of Jewish burial ground, Whitechapel Road
- Seven members of Great Synagogue community attended New Court
  daily for a year to form the required "minyan" for the **Kaddish**

#### Nathan's Wealth — Richest Man in the World

- His share of combined Rothschild capital at death: **£1,478,541**
  (quarter of the total £6 million partnership)
- Had also given children ~£800,000 before death; bequeathed further
  £1,192,500 in will
- **Total estimated wealth: ~£3.5 million** (excluding Piccadilly and
  Gunnersbury Park properties)
- Nearest banking rival in London: **Baring Brothers** with capital of
  only **£776,650** — less than half
- Outstripped contemporary industrialists and even the wealthiest
  aristocratic landowners: richer than ironmaster **Richard Crawshay**,
  cotton manufacturers **Robert Peel** and **Richard Arkwright**, the
  Dukes of Queensberry, Sutherland, and Cleveland
- Not until 1857 did anyone leave more to heirs — textile/banking man
  **James Morrison** left £4–6 million
- Key distinction: aristocrats had comparable incomes but massive
  **debts** — Duke of Devonshire's encumbrances grew to £700,000 by
  1830s; half his income consumed by interest; Duke of Buckingham went
  bankrupt in 1848 with £1.5 million in encumbrances
- Nathan's income averaged **£87,623/year** in his last five full years
- Had arrived in England with just **£20,000**; began as cloth merchant
  in Manchester — the self-made man ideal embodied
- **James** (Paris) was probably already the richest man in France;
  together the Rothschilds were "without question the richest family
  in the world"

#### The "Rothschild Myth" — The Hebrew Talisman

- To poorer Jews, Nathan's rise had "almost mystical significance" —
  legend of the **"Hebrew talisman,"** magical source of his luck,
  circulated in Jewish lore
- An anonymous text published in London ~1840 (four years after
  Nathan's death) narrated the talisman story — one of the earliest
  examples of what Ferguson calls the **"Rothschild myth"**
- The text may have been by an anti-Jewish *agent provocateur* despite
  appearing Jewish in authorship — its militancy anticipates the
  French anti-Rothschild pamphlets of the 1840s and prefigures the
  *Protocols of the Elders of Zion*
- Story: a phantom narrator (anti-Christian demon) witnesses French
  pillage of Frankfurt's Jewish quarter during Napoleonic occupation;
  finds a young Jewish man weeping over the loss of the family shrine;
  bestows a magical talisman (a ring with the signet of Solomon) on
  this youth — commanding gold to flow to him
- The young man is revealed as Nathan Rothschild; the narrator
  declares his gold has done more than kings' swords to "war upon"
  the Nazarenes

> "Europe's kings in adverse hour / Have sought and found thine aid. / More than their swords thy gold hath done, / In many a bloodless triumph won." — William Heseltine, "Reflections at the Grave of N. M. Rothschild Esq." (1836)

- Mourning merchandise produced: rings, brooches, medals, printed silk
  mourning scarf in four languages inscribed "Equally Distinguished
  for his Commercial Skill & Enterprize & for his Charitable and
  Benevolent Disposition" plus list of his best-known loans and total
  wealth — sold as far as Vienna
- Obituaries appeared in English press, *Journal des Débats*, and
  (at Salomon's prompting) *Allgemeine Zeitung*
- Lithograph *The Shadow of a Great Man* (Mons. Edouart, August 6,
  1836) depicted Nathan's silhouette at his pillar in the Royal
  Exchange, holding four keys — representing succession to his four
  sons; widely reproduced including by one of his own clerks

<!-- pp. 441-460 -->

## [Continuation] The Rothschild Myth: The "Hebrew Talisman"

### The Talisman Fantasy
- A mid-19th century anti-Semitic tract portrayed Nathan as wielding
  a supernatural talisman granted by a mysterious narrator-figure,
  explaining his seemingly impossible rise to wealth
- The mythologized account: Nathan financed Wellington at Waterloo
  AND bribed French generals to desert Napoleon — "There was but one
  man on earth who both COULD and would provide the millions of
  golden pounds . . . That man was ROTHSCHILD"
- The talisman's condition: Nathan lent the money only in exchange
  for "the re-establishment of Judah's kingdom — the rebuilding of
  thy towers, Oh! Jerusalem!"
- The "twist": Nathan betrayed his supernatural master, selling
  the secret agreement for the restoration of Judea in exchange
  for a "petty English Emancipation Bill" and "a petty English
  peerage for himself"
- Punishment: the talisman disappears; Nathan "never ventured upon
  the Exchange again" (i.e., his death is divine retribution)

> "There was but one man on earth who both COULD and would provide the
> millions of golden pounds, required for the instant purposes of the
> English minister. — That man was ROTHSCHILD."
> — *The Hebrew Talisman* tract, c. 1840

- The narrative is a **Jewish version of the Nibelung saga** — a magic
  ring that corrupts as it empowers
- Illustrates how potent the Rothschild mystique had become by 1840;
  Nathan's death fed myths rather than dispelling them
- An American paper (non-Jewish) reported that extra watchmen were
  placed at Nathan's grave "to prevent the committal of any
  sacrilegious act" — rumors circulated that a "Jew's eye" would be
  worth a fortune

> "As Nathan Rothschild died, a myth was born which was to prove as
> enduringly potent and dangerous as any myth of the nineteenth century."
> — Ferguson

---

## Succession: James vs. the Nephews

### James as Perceived Heir
- Conventional assumption (and **Heinrich Heine**'s view): **James de
  Rothschild** automatically inherited Nathan's mantle as "commanding
  general" of the family
- Heine, March 1841: described James holding court at **rue Laffitte**
  in "a labyrinth of halls, a barracks of wealth"; office decorated
  with "busts of all the European monarchs who have contracted loans
  from his firm"
- Heine's famous description — brokers and agents approached James's
  private office "as Moses once felt on Mount Horeb when he realised
  he was standing on holy ground"

> "I like best to visit him in the offices of his banking house, where I
> can philosophically observe people — not only the Chosen People, but all
> the others too — bow and scrape before him. There you may watch a
> twisting and bending of backbones such as the most accomplished acrobat
> would find difficult."
> — Heinrich Heine on James de Rothschild

### James's Office: A Chaotic Court
- **Ernest Feydeau** (visited rue Laffitte regularly in the 1850s)
  described James besieged from 9 am to 4 pm by a procession of
  brokers, jobbers, and sycophants
- James would barely glance at quotations handed to him, sometimes
  dropping them in the wastepaper basket "with malicious pleasure"
- The office noise: "all the tongues of the world were spoken,
  including Hebrew" — jewelers, art dealers, "pretty women" all
  sought audiences
- James worked 5 am to close of bourse, dined in a small room beside
  the office while brokers continued their parade around his dinner table
- Feydeau's verdict: James was "less a king holding court than a
  prisoner of his own work ethic" — kept going by "a singular tyranny
  of habit"

> "You are annoying me! Dat isn't true! Leaf me in peace!" — James's
> typical civility to brokers, per **Alexander Herzen** (visited 1849)

- James once tore a broker's quotation in two when the price annoyed
  him and called him a "blested impecile"
- Famous exchange: broker **Manuel** dared to greet James with "Good
  day, baron, how are you keeping?" — James: "Vat's dat got to do vit
  you?" Manuel replied: "You could drop down dead as I stand here, and
  I would no more care than if a dog died." — considered mythic
  impudence on the bourse

### Reality: James Did NOT Hold Nathan's Authority
- James was quick to assert dominance after Nathan's death but the
  London, Paris, and Frankfurt houses were by the late 1830s
  **roughly equal in capital** — no one could dictate as Nathan had
- Key recurring complaint from James: London house neglected
  continental interests, failed to answer letters promptly
- **Salomon** (September 1837), patronizingly invoking Nathan's memory:
  "Whenever he saw that others wanted to push us out of a business deal
  he always wrote, 'My dear brother, we have to push it through.'"
- James (1839) accused London of collecting half profits on Spain
  business while leaving Paris to bear all the risks — "as soon as
  one House notices such behaviour in the other this will generate a
  feeling of mistrust and everything will then simply collapse, God
  forbid"
- Amschel and James agreed in 1839: "the loss of our brother Nathan
  was a terrible blow and one can't expect that youngsters will get
  the same respect, fear and trust as do the older generation"

### The Nephews Push Back
- **Lionel**, **Nat**, and **Anthony** were often irritated by the
  uncles' meddling; Anthony to Lionel: "I assure you that it is a
  great bother to arrange with people who are so very sententious
  about money affairs"
- **Amschel** used his will (constantly redrafted) as leverage over
  nephews — another source of discontent
- The younger generation characterized by **conservative caution**
  vs. the uncles' Frankfurt-ghetto-bred restlessness: New Court
  did more bill-broking, less bond speculation; "We prefer dealing
  largely with a little less profit to keeping a very large stock
  on hand and holding out for very high prices" — Nat
- Nat, visiting Paris in 1846: "I am convinced the more, there is
  no place like our old New Court. Where would the rubbishy French
  shares be, if we did not support them?"
- James to nephews (1845): "my heart breaks when I see how everyone
  is trying to push us out of [every] business deal. [Even] the stone
  on the wall is envious and is our enemy" — a paranoid competitiveness
  the next generation could not inherit

### Partnership Renegotiation
- When partners met in Paris, the 1836 agreement was left unaltered;
  **Hannah** (Nathan's widow) noted: "The counting house of each[,]
  having their own capital[,] should be independent"
- **Lionel** later withdrew £340,250 from London's share of combined
  capital to equalize proportions and interest received — ending the
  situation where Nathan's estate had been the biggest "shareholder"
- More significant: Lionel defeated James's proposal (first raised
  ~30 years earlier) to make the partnership between the five houses
  **public** — London always insisted on secrecy, refusing any
  document that might reveal money arrangements
- Result: the precise nature of the five-house relationship remained
  "a secret between the partners and their lawyers"

### National Divergence
- By mid-1830s each Rothschild house had become the pre-eminent
  force in its base country's public finances
- Lionel and brothers developed emotional identification with England;
  Salomon grew increasingly aligned with **Metternich** and Austrian
  imperial interests; James could not avoid French national priorities
- When great-power interests clashed (as they did periodically),
  Rothschild neutrality became "less and less easy"
- The family's response: seek business in peripheral regions — Iberia,
  America, the Low Countries, the Near East — but these areas raised
  their own conflicts between houses

---

## Chapter 12: Love and Debt

### The Hannah Mayer Crisis (1839)
- April 29, 1839: **Hannah Mayer Rothschild** (Nathan's second daughter)
  renounced Judaism to marry **Hon. Henry Fitzroy**, a Christian
- Fitzroy was objectively a good match by worldly standards: younger
  son of Lord Southampton, Magdalen Oxford / Trinity Cambridge,
  Deputy Lieutenant for Northamptonshire, MP for Lewes, aged 32
- But he was a Christian, and Hannah Mayer had previously been
  proposed to by **Prince Edmond de Clary** in Paris (Nathan had
  dismissed that too)
- Nathan's will stipulated younger daughters could marry only with
  consent of mother AND brothers; in the event of disagreement,
  his own brothers had the "final, binding word"
- Financial deterrent: Hannah Mayer already held £62,500 (£12,500
  on father's death + £50,000 invested at 4%); the additional
  £50,000 dowry she forfeited by marrying without consent
  was evidently not enough

> "nothing could possibly be more disastrous for our family, for our
> continued well-being, for our good name and for our honour than such
> a decision, God forbid . . . To renounce our religion, the religion of
> our [father] Rabbi Mayer [Amschel] Rothschild of blessed memory, the
> religion which, thank God, made us so great."
> — James to Lionel

### The Wedding and Its Aftermath
- James tried to intervene in person but was prevented by illness;
  proposed Hannah Mayer come to Switzerland — too late
- Wedding took place at **St George's, Hanover Square**; only brother
  **Nat** attended; mother escorted Hannah Mayer no further than
  the church gates
- *The Times* noted it was "the first instance of a member of the
  Rothschild family abandoning the faith of their fathers"
- James's furious response from Paris:

> "She has unfortunately robbed our whole family of its pride and caused
> us such harm that it can no longer be redressed . . . We shall therefore
> wipe her from our memory and never again during my lifetime will I or any
> other member of our family see or receive her."
> — James de Rothschild

- Hannah's own mother echoed this: she "irrevocably separated herself
  from me," though the mother privately admitted she still wanted
  news of her daughter
- Only **Nat** defended Hannah Mayer, arguing she had done "no more
  than marry 'a Christian in a Christian country'" — firmly sat on
  by James

### Ferguson's Analysis: Religion as Endogamy
- James's "religion" argument was, at its core, about keeping the
  Rothschild fortune within the Rothschild family — **endogamy**
  not piety
- The uncles were not strict religious observers; James "dutifully
  played his part" in Jewish communal life (supported Society for
  Encouragement and Aid of Jewish Indigents; lobbied for Jewish
  civil rights abroad) but was fundamentally clannish
- James's real fear: Hannah Mayer's rebellion jeopardized "all the
  nicely conceived projects . . . that Mayer will marry Anselm's
  daughter, that Lionel's daughter will marry the child of another
  member of the family so that the great fortune and the Rothschild
  name will continue to be honoured"
- Disraeli's fictional **Sidonia** (*Coningsby*) claimed "no earthly
  considerations would ever induce him to impair that purity of race"
  — but for real Rothschilds, **"earthly considerations" counted
  for as much as racial or religious exclusivity**
- James to Nat: "Don't imagine . . . that I have taken to playing
  the role of a religious man, but I must admit that I take a lot
  of pride in my religion"

### Anthony's Near-Apostasy and the Montefiore Marriage
- Months after Hannah Mayer's marriage, **Anthony** was suspected of
  similar intentions; **Amschel** leant on him heavily to marry
  **Louisa Montefiore** (a cousin)
- Anthony complained: "Uncle A. was a regular bother asking me about
  getting married . . . writing to Uncle S. that I only waited until
  his death to marry a Christian"
- Pressure worked — Anthony was "less romantic and more biddable"
  than his sister; he negotiated financial terms with Amschel
  before agreeing
- James (from Naples) remained watchful: "He is very weak and is
  easily led . . . I will do everything in my power to bring this
  affair to an end"

<!-- pp. 461-480 -->

## Chapter: Family, Marriage, and Social Ascent (continued)

### Endogamous Marriage — Happiness and Its Costs

- The intermarriage strategy was re-established after the troubled 1836/1839 weddings
- **Anthony** became engaged to **Louisa Montefiore** in Nov 1839; **Mayer Carl** married his cousin **Louise** in London; **Nat** married **Charlotte** (James's daughter) in the same year
- The contrast between the 1842 wedding at **Ferrières** — rose-strewn paths, champagne, toasts, James toasting the King — and the grim 1836/1839 weddings was complete
- **James and Betty**: mismatched to outsiders; diplomat **Lord William Russell** in 1843: "She handsome — he vulgar"; but Betty's letters show genuine deep affection; no evidence of marital strife
- **Lionel and Charlotte** (London, 1836): also seen as ill-matched — he industrious/conscientious/emotionally flat; she brilliant, mordant, intellectually one of the most gifted Rothschilds of her generation
- Charlotte wrote to Lionel in rare outburst: "Ever since I became your wife, I have had to do what others want, never what I would like to do. Pray that I shall be compensated in Heaven."
- **Disraeli** fictionalised the match in *Endymion* (the Neuchatels): the wife "not a contented spirit" who "had imbibed not merely a contempt for money, but an absolute hatred of it" — yet the husband's supreme will meant her "over-refined fantasies . . . produced not the slightest effect on the course of his life"

### Hannah Mayer — The Price of Apostasy

- **Hannah Mayer Fitzroy** (who had married Christian **Henry Fitzroy** in 1838, converting to Christianity) was never fully forgiven
- By 1848 she was partially reconciled — receiving presents, invited to Garboldisham; Betty "made my peace with HM" in 1849
- But within family she was treated like a Victorian "fallen woman" — every misfortune read as divine punishment
- When Fitzroy was passed over for Secretary at the Admiralty (1852), family registered her "fury" with grim satisfaction
- When the Fitzroys' son **Arthur** died (fallen from a pony), niece **Constance** (aged 15) could "not help thinking that all the misfortune . . . have been a punishment for having deserted the faith of the fathers"
- **Henry Fitzroy** died the following year; Charlotte tracked the "decline and fall" of Hannah Mayer and her daughter **Blanche** with "outward sympathy and inward relish"
- From Feb 1864 Hannah Mayer was seriously ill; Blanche became engaged to artist/architect **Sir Coutts Lindsay** — Bohemian, twice her age, with a shady retinue; Hannah had wanted a nobleman for her daughter
- Charlotte visited and found Hannah "completely overcome by her conflicting feelings; she had been crying and sobbing almost shrieking"
- With poetic justice, **Blanche** had followed her mother's example: choosing a husband against her mother's wishes, just as Hannah had done 25 years earlier
- Blanche distanced herself from her dying mother, visiting only five minutes a day; Charlotte catalogued her as "utterly heartless," "a heartless serpent," "the unnatural daughter," "that horrible Blanche"
- **December 1, 1864**: Hannah Mayer died; Charlotte called her life "a long martyrdom"
- Charlotte's final grievance: Hannah Mayer's will failed to dispose of **£7,000** in savings, which passed by default to the Lindsays — "Rothschild money passing into other hands still rankled, a quarter of a century after Hannah Mayer's initial lapse from grace"
- As late as **1882**, when Blanche's marriage foundered on Sir Coutts's infidelity, Anselm's son Ferdinand predicted she would "repent . . . in the long run" — Hannah Mayer's crime, though punished, had not been forgiven

---

## Section: City and Country — Social and Cultural Ascent

### The Paradox of Hannah Mayer's Persecution

- Her persecution coincided with the **acceleration** of the family's social and cultural assimilation
- By converting, she crossed the one barrier the Rothschilds themselves wished to preserve — the only one remaining between them and the European elite
- **Thackeray** in *Punch*'s "Book of Snobs" (1846-7): cited the "Scharlachschild family" as archetypes of the "Banking Snob" who "receives all the world into his circle," dispensing "princely hospitalities"

### Residences — *Le Style Rothschild*

- After Nathan's death the Rothschilds greatly increased time and money devoted to social and cultural pursuits; **James** led the way
- **1836**: James commissioned **Charles-Edmond Duponchel** (architect, designer, theatre producer) to reconstruct his **rue Laffitte hôtel** — money no object
- Result was described by **Heine** as "the Versailles of the absolute reign of money": Renaissance-style wood-panelled salons with paintings by **Joseph-Nicholas Robert-Fleury** (Charles V, Luther, Henry VIII), Rothschild arms subtly juxtaposed with those of the **Medici**; central heating via four brick ovens; running water from roof tanks; gas lighting from moustached statuettes
- This became known as ***le style Rothschild*** — "which combined all the richest elements of those which had preceded it . . . The heavy golden cornices, the damask hung walls, the fringed and tasselled curtains of Genoese velvet, the marble and the parquet"

> "Here everything comes together which the spirit of the sixteenth century could invent and the money of the nineteenth century could pay for; here the genius of the visual arts competes with the genius of Rothschild." — **Heinrich Heine**, 1836

- **Disraeli** (1843) to his sister after attending Salomon's ball: "an hotel in decoration surpassing all the palaces of Munich — a greater retinue of servants & liveries more gorgeous than the Thuilleries [sic] — & pineapples plentiful as blackberries"
- Disraeli later paid fictionalised tribute in *Coningsby* (Sidonia's Paris residence) and *Tancred* (dinner "served on Sèvres porcelain of Rose du Barry, raised on airy golden stands of arabesque workmanship")
- Austrian diplomat **Apponyi** (who found the Renaissance style unsuitable for Paris) still conceded: "a luxury which surpasses all imagination" — chairs of ormolu bronze with Rothschild arms in enamel on every high back

### Ferrières and Country Houses

- **Ferrières** (James's château outside Paris): rebuilt in mock-Tudor style by architect **Joseph-Antoine Froelicher**; 1840 model farm added; English-style dairy, brick-kiln, British machinery
- Salomon's **Suresnes**: enlarged with elaborate glass galleries; Salomon's passion was the garden — yew-trees transplanted from Melun requiring 11 horses per tree; *The Times* compared it to how "Louis XIV planted the grounds at Versailles"
- **English Rothschilds** (Hannah at **Gunnersbury**, impressed Disraeli in 1843 as "a most beautiful park . . . worthy of an Italian Prince"); Lionel extended the estate to 620 acres between 1840 and 1873
- English branch sought more rural Buckinghamshire seat for hunting; **Nathan** rented **Tring** in 1833; Hannah bought land near **Mentmore** (1836); **Mayer** bought farms at Mentmore/Wing (1842) — foundation of a substantial Rothschild enclave

### Land as Investment, Not Feudal Compromise

- Ferguson's counterintuitive argument: Rothschild land purchases were NOT a dilution of their capitalist spirit or a compromise with feudalism
- **Lionel** was unimpressed by great aristocratic piles: Castle Howard was "just the same as Blenheim, only much smaller . . . altogether a place not worth putting oneself out to go to see"
- Land was bought as investment — **Lionel** on Creslow (1844): "a 33 per cent purchase would pay me 3 per cent" — estates bought at the bottom of the market (e.g. after Duke of Buckingham's bankruptcy in 1848)
- Secondary rationale: concentration of land in one county was a source of **political influence** under British local government — their land agents Horwood and James explicitly advised buying in one area only

### Property Rights and Jewish Emancipation in Vienna

- **Salomon** continued to live in the rented Hotel zum Römischen Kaiser in Vienna — Jews prohibited from owning real estate
- Jan 1837: Salomon addressed a "special appeal" to **Metternich** on behalf of his "co-religionists"; Metternich replied the Emperor would grant **individual** Jews (not general emancipation) permission to own houses
- Classic *Hofjude* dynamic: the state "bought off" the Jewish banker with individual exemptions rather than general rights
- Salomon resisted until **1842** — then accepted, buying the Renngasse hotel and adjoining house; acknowledged the compromise: "a privileged exception in the midst of my fellow believers, who . . . ought to have the right to enjoy the same rights"
- Rothschild family did NOT criticise Salomon — they saw general rights and individual privileges as complementary: "if the former could not be had, the latter should be accepted"
- **1843**: Salomon also obtained Emperor's permission to buy an estate in **Moravia** (at Koritschau) and pass it to heirs — required adopting the tone of "the humble but deserving court Jew," listing financial contributions to Austria
- Lord Chancellor Count **Inzághy** was candid: it was "highly desirable that Baron Rothschild should be more closely bound to the Imperial State of Austria by the investment of his money in real property"
- Salomon also acquired the castle of **Schillersdorf** in Prussia (1842); Heine warned in 1846 that "Prussian aristocrats would like to use the paw of the plebeian to stir up public opinion against the *exceptional family*"

### Frankfurt — Architectural Assertion of Equality

- **1831**: **Amschel** commissioned **Friedrich Rumpf** (Paris-trained) to redesign house on the Bockenheimer Landstrasse — neo-classical villa with Corinthian columns; style matched the Gentile elite, signalling new self-confidence
- **1834**: Amschel bought a four-storey house on the prestigious **Zeil**; Anselm bought a similar "palais" on Neue Mainzer Strasse (no. 45) by the same architect
- **Untermainkai 15** (today the Frankfurt Jewish Museum): expanded by Rumpf with Oriental features — Moorish corner pillars, arabesque balustrades — to dominate the street subtly; "a symbol of the Rothschilds' now well-established dominance of the city's economic life"
- Frankfurt was the first branch where Rothschilds **built their own** country houses rather than merely renovating — sparked an internal aesthetic debate; the English (Charlotte and Louise) favoured English styles, but the German Rothschilds prevailed with Loire château and Renaissance designs

---

### Elite Pursuits — Entertaining as Corporate Hospitality

- After 1836, Rothschild entertaining escalated dramatically in both scale and social reach
- **James's ball in March 1836**: guests were "a strictly selected set of aristocratic illustrations, able to make an impression by reason of great name or high rank or (in the case of the ladies) beauty and finery" — Heine's description
- After the July Monarchy ("bourgeois monarchy"), the Faubourg Saint-Germain had less cause to remain aloof from Rothschild invitations
- **Lionel at Gunnersbury, July 1838**: over 500 guests including Dukes of Cambridge, Sussex, Somerset, and **Wellington**; Ernst I of Saxe-Coburg (Prince Albert's father) attended later balls
- In Frankfurt (1846): guests included the **King of Württemberg**, Prince Loewenstein, Prince Wittgenstein

> "To visit the Neuchatels became the mode; all solicited to be their guests, and some solicited in vain." — **Disraeli**, *Endymion*

- For the Rothschilds themselves, these events were a duty — "an early form of corporate hospitality" — not pleasure
- **Nat** to his brothers (1843): "Here we have stinking balls night after night; you have no idea how sweaty the old French ladies smell after a long waltz"
- The family also took the waters at spas (Aix, Gastein, Wildbad, Kissingen) — the "done" thing; James primarily regarded it as a medical necessity; Mayer: "You have no idea how dull this place is"

### Hunting — A New Rothschild Passion

- Three distinct activities: **shooting** (pheasants, at Ferrières from the early 1830s), **stag-hunting** (attracted the English nephews to Buckinghamshire in the 1840s), and **horse-racing** (requiring professionally bred horses and jockeys)
- Shooting was initially social intelligence-gathering as much as sport — Lionel in Sept 1832 accompanied Montalivet and Apponyi shooting "in any other times . . . would be very amusing, but now one goes with these great personages to hear what is going on"

<!-- pp. 481-500 -->

## Chapter [Lifestyle & Culture, cont.]: Sport, Art, Music, and Letters

### Hunting as Social Performance

- **James de Rothschild**'s shooting at **Ferrières** was pure corporate hospitality —
  1835 slaughter of 506 partridges, 359 hares, 110 pheasants in honour of the
  **duc d'Orléans**; game bought in specially, guests given servants, dogs, guns
- Critics (Capefigue) called it grotesque: "Bad kennels, bad hounds, horses dead-beat
  after the first gallop, greedy gamekeeper"
- Lionel, shooting grouse with James in Scotland 1843, noted the contrast acerbically:
  at Ferrières "all the game is driven to him and he has but to fire away"

> "Here we have to walk after the dogs and to seek for the game, which is a much greater
> excitement and at the same time more fatiguing." — Lionel on Scottish grouse shooting

- English nephews preferred **stag-hunting on horseback**; began with a pack of
  staghounds in the **Vale of Aylesbury** in 1839, renting stables at **Tring Park**
- This enthusiasm directly prompted the purchase of **Mentmore** three years later
- **Nat's** 1840 exhortation to brothers: "Ride like trumps, and do not let the Queen's
  people fancy we are all tailors" — hunting was proof of social legitimacy, not just fun
- Sons of a textile merchant **Nathan Rothschild** had to demonstrate they were not
  "all tailors" by acquitting themselves over Buckinghamshire hedges and gates
- Irony: the sedentary lifestyles of older Rothschilds may have contributed to the ailment
  that killed Nathan; Nat later suffered serious injury in a riding accident, vindicating
  Nathan's old warnings about bankers and horses

### Horse-Racing

- **Anthony** began owning racehorses around 1840; one won the Champs de Mars in Paris
  — pre-eminent owner at the time was the **duc d'Orléans** (died in carriage accident 1842)
- **Disraeli** wrote that October: "Anthony succeeds the Duke of Orleans in his
  patronage of the turf & gives costly cups to the course wh[ich] his horses always win"
- **Mayer** established a racing stable at **Newmarket** in 1843; registered the
  **Rothschild colours as dark blue and yellow** (after toying with amber, lilac, red)

### Investing in Art

- Art patronage went beyond mere aristocratic mimicry — it was a genuine passion and
  a form of serious **investment**
- **Heinrich Heine** in 1828 mocked James as a philistine lacking culture; by 1843
  (published in *Augsburger Zeitung*) he reversed himself, noting James had
  "the capacity of finding (if not always of judging) the leading practitioners in every
  other sphere of activity" — compared to **Louis XIV** for identifying talent in others
- **Benjamin Disraeli** on first meeting James: "a happy mixture of the French Dandy &
  the orange boy" — the Frankfurt roughness and the Parisian aesthete coexisted

> "He does not, perhaps, understand a single note of music; but Rossini was always a
> friend of the family. Ary Scheffer is his court painter . . . Herr von Rothschild knows
> not a word of Greek; but the Hellenist Letronne is the scholar he favours most."
> — Heine, *Augsburger Zeitung*, 1843

#### The Collections

- First notable Rothschild art purchase: **Jean-Baptiste Greuze**'s *The Milkmaid* —
  acquired by James as early as 1818; Greuze remained a family favourite
- **Lionel** began collecting in 1831 with Greuze's *Virtue Faltering*; later acquired
  *The Parting Kiss* and others; Anthony owned *The Nursery*
- Favourite seventeenth-century Spanish artist: **Bartolomé Esteban Murillo** —
  Lionel discovered him in Madrid in 1834; by end of 1840s James, Lionel, and their
  mother **Hannah** all owned Murillos
- Dominant taste: **seventeenth-century Dutch masters**
  - James (1840): **Rembrandt**'s *The Standard Bearer* from George IV's collection,
    hung in the grand salon at rue Laffitte; also owned *Portrait of a Young Man*
  - **Franz Hals**, **Anthony van Dyck**, **Peter Paul Rubens**, **Jacob van Ruisdael**,
    **Philips Wouwermans** all represented
  - Lionel by c.1850: three **Meindert Hobbema**, three van Ruisdael, five works by
    **Aalbert Cuyp** (including *View on a Frozen River*), seven **David Teniers the
    Younger**, still-lifes by Jan van Huysum, Rachel Ruysh, and others
- Family coordinated purchases: James wrote "We want to do it together. Perhaps we will
  get some nice paintings" when arranging for a Roman collection auction to be held in
  Paris (1841) rather than London
- Shared tendency to favour **secular over religious subjects** — but they also bought
  Christian iconography (Murillo's *Infant Christ as the Good Shepherd*, Domenichino's
  *Head of a Magdalene*, Andrea del Sarto's *Madonna and Child*, Jan van Eyck)
- **Lionel** had distinct enthusiasm for **eighteenth-century English portraiture** —
  ahead of his time: **Sir Joshua Reynolds** (*Portrait of Master Braddyl*, *Portrait of
  Mrs Lloyd*, *Miss Meyer as Hebe*), **Thomas Gainsborough** (*Portrait of the Hon.
  Frances Duncombe* for £1,500 in 1871), George Romney's *Portrait of Emma, Lady Hamilton*
- **Frankfurt Rothschilds** had different tastes: **Mayer Carl** more interested in gold
  and silver ornaments than paintings; by 1870s had amassed a "**Goldschatz**" of 5,000
  items including **Wentzel Jamnitzer**'s Merkelsche Tafelautsatz (a masterpiece of the
  German Renaissance) and an ivory horn — the latter turned out to be a contemporary
  forgery by **Reinhold Vasters**

#### Art as Investment

- Old Masters functioned as **status symbols AND financial assets** — as much a form of
  investment in the nineteenth century as they are today
- James's entire collection insured for **10 million francs (£400,000)** — in 1844
  equivalent to a quarter of James's share in the five houses' combined capital
- Market dynamics: French Revolution had uprooted aristocracy and flooded the market
  with private collections sold *en bloc*; 1830 revolution led to the duchesse de Berry
  sale; 1848 saw the great **Stowe auction**
- Despite frequency of auctions, demand for Old Masters outstripped supply: Velazquez's
  *Lady with Fan* sold to Nat for 12,700 francs in 1843 — more than three times what
  banker **Aguado** had paid just six years before
- Mayer's investment philosophy (shopping for Italian sculpture, 1846): "one ought always
  to buy the very best of everything and not to mind the price" — the very best could
  only appreciate in value
- But 1848-9 political upheaval slumped the art market as steeply as financial markets;
  later James always let a picture go rather than overpay — "hated the idea of buying
  at what might prove to be the peak of the market"

### Piano Lessons: Musical Patronage

- Musicians were a **prerequisite for a successful soirée** — the most obvious reason
  for Rothschild enthusiasm; but relationships went far deeper than mere entertainment
- **Nathan** (January 1828): treated dinner guests to post-prandial performance by
  **Ignaz Moscheles** — Felix Mendelssohn's tutor
- **James**: **Rossini** performed at his dinner (introduced to Salomon by Metternich
  at the **Congress of Verona**); **Chopin**'s Paris career reportedly launched at a
  performance at the rue Laffitte in 1832 (scholars debate authenticity)
- Chopin played again at rue Laffitte in 1843 alongside his pupil **Karl Filtsch**;
  James reportedly "adored" Filtsch's playing
- Other performers at Rothschild houses: **Felix Mendelssohn**, **Franz Liszt**,
  **Charles Hallé** (pianist/conductor), **Joseph Joachim** (violinist)
- Anthony's vivid account of Liszt's 1842 private recital:

> "as curious to look at as to hear, with his long hair at times streaming over his face,
> at others completely thrown back by a violent toss of the head, his wild eyes which he
> now and then turns on every side as if to mean sometimes 'Am I not wonderful?'"

#### Teachers More Important Than Performers

- Piano was "the nearest thing the nineteenth century had to the television" — female
  Rothschilds were expected to excel at the keyboard
- **Charlotte** (Nathan's daughter): her *livre d'or* records lessons from Moscheles,
  Mendelssohn, **Vincenzo Bellini** (inscribed "Dolente immagine di Fille mia"),
  **Louis Spohr**, **Rossini**, **Giacomo Meyerbeer**, and later **Luigi Cherubini**
  and **Chopin** (who added Mazurka Op. 67 no. 4); Rossini wrote a six-page piano solo
  for her as a "Petit Souvenir"
- Youngest sister **Louise**: Rossini personally offered her singing lessons —
  "very good natured and always comes at the hour and day I like"
- **Chopin** taught Nathan's Charlotte, her daughter **Hannah Mathilde**, and Betty's
  daughter (another Charlotte); dedicated two pieces to the family: **Waltz Op. 64 No. 2**
  and **Ballade Op. 52**
- Hannah Mathilde composed piano pieces, an orchestral waltz, and six song sets
  (settings of Victor Hugo, Théophile Gautier, Goethe, Longfellow); her "Si vous n'avez
  rien à me dire" performed at the **Paris Opéra** by soprano **Adelina Patti**

#### Musicians as Social Equals

- **Rossini** invited to Lionel's wedding in 1836 as a friend — "to add to the gaiety of
  our party" — not as entertainer; Lady Grenville sniffed that it was Mme Rossini's
  "first appearance in decent company I believe"
- Financial ties: **Johann Strauss** senior's 1838 England tour partly financed by Lionel;
  after 1842 Rossini banked at de Rothschild Frères; **Paganini** used Rothschilds to
  relay a gift of 20,000 francs to **Hector Berlioz**; **Adelina Patti** borrowed
  £4,000+ from Paris house while on tour in Argentina
- Even **Richard Wagner** — who demonised "Jewry in Music" — effectively banked with
  the Rothschilds as his wife **Cosima** held an account with the Paris house
- Deeper affinity: both the Rothschilds and many great musicians (**Meyerbeer**,
  **Joachim**) were beneficiaries of **Jewish emancipation** — parvenus and foreigners
  who had risen by virtuosity

### Men of Letters: Heine and Balzac

#### Heinrich Heine

- **Heinrich Heine**: nephew of Hamburg banker **Salomon Heine**; had early negative
  encounter with Nathan in London (Nathan reportedly told him he "had no talent for
  business"); by 1834 had cultivated close relationship with the French Rothschilds
- Grillparzer, dining with Heine at the Rothschilds, observed: "It was apparent that his
  hosts were afraid of Heine, and he exploited their fear by slyly poking fun at them"
- Famous Heine jests at James's expense (James as slow-witted straight man):
  - On wine called "Lachrymae Christi": "Christ weeps when rich Jews can afford such
    good wines while so many poor folk go hungry"
  - James: "Comment trouvez-vous mon chenil?" — Heine: "Don't you know that *chenil*
    means dog-kennel? If you have so low an opinion of yourself, at least don't trumpet
    it abroad!"
  - On the Seine's polluted state: James notes the source is clear — Heine replies:
    "Yes, M. le baron; and I hear that your late father was a most honest man."
- Reality behind the jests: correspondence shows Heine increasingly a **humble supplicant**
  to James's patronage, not a licensed jester
- In *Ludwig Börne*, Heine called James's development of financial capital as socially
  revolutionary as Richelieu and Robespierre — far from insulting; Heine nervously sent
  proofs to **Betty** (James's wife) as a precaution
- In *Augsburger Zeitung* articles (early 1840s) Heine repeatedly praised James,
  compared him favourably to banker **Benoît Fould**, praised his philanthropy
- June 1843 "Lutetia" piece: likened James to the sun — everyone pays homage hoping
  to be warmed by his golden rays; Heine explicitly denied wanting to join the "horde
  of beggars" around James

> "I counsel every man who is in dire need of money to go to M. de Rothschild; not in
> order to borrow from him (I doubt whether he would have much success in that endeavour!)
> but to comfort himself with the sight of the misery money can cause." — Heine, "Lutetia"

- When publisher **Julius Campe** sent Heine a critical Rothschild history (Friedrich
  **Steinmann**'s *The House of Rothschild: Its History and Transactions*), Heine wrote
  that suppressing it would repay the service "which Rothschild has shown me for the
  past 12 years"
- Financial dependence only began after uncle **Salomon Heine**'s death (December 1844):
  Heine's allowance halved by cousin Carl; bitter family wrangle until 1847
- James then involved Heine in a railway share speculation earning 20,000 francs (1846);
  offered "most preferential treatment" in French government loan (1847)
- By 1852 Heine had become a **Schnorrer** (beggar), writing abject letters linking
  requests to James's financial successes; received shares in Austrian **Creditanstalt**
  from Anselm; dead within two months of last request
- Key insight from Heine's own "Retrospective Explanation": the friendship endured only
  because he **never asked for money** — "Had I done so, our friendship would soon have
  been at an end"
- Role of **Betty de Rothschild**: Heine conducted an "elegant flirtation" with her
  in the 1830s; signed himself "your faithful protégé" (*Ihr ergebener Schützling*);
  called her "earliest patroness in Paris"; praised her publicly as "not only one of
  the best looking women in Paris but [one] who is also distinguished in intellect"
- Friendship faded in 1840s — Betty became "a doubting Thomas"; money ultimately
  corrupted the relationship as Heine had foreseen

#### Honoré de Balzac

- **Balzac** and Heine as mirror images: where Heine fretted about offending James,
  Balzac caricatured him with only perfunctory disclaimers; where Heine decorously
  flirted with Betty, Balzac tried to palm off an old mistress on James; where Heine
  agonised over share options, Balzac happily borrowed and avoided repaying
- Famous Balzac aside (1837): encountering Heine and James in the street —
  "*C'est-à-dire tout l'esprit et tout l'argent des Juifs*" — it was the money that
  interested him more; characteristically misspelt James's name as "Rostchild"
- First met at **Aix**, summer 1832; James immediately offered letters of introduction
  and courier use for Balzac's planned Italian trip
- Balzac borrowed 500 francs from **Salomon** in Vienna; in 1842 offered James tickets
  for his disastrous play *Les Ressources de Quinola* (about a steamship sinking)
- 1844: dedicated *Un Homme d'affaires* to "Monsieur le Baron James de Rothschild /
  Conseil Général d'Autriche à Paris, Banquier"
- James reciprocated by forwarding letters to the Polish Countess Balzac was wooing,
  easing customs passage, and providing **150 shares in the Northern railway** (1846)
- Balzac promptly borrowed 17,000 francs against those shares; also borrowed ~50,000
  francs by mortgaging his fiancée's Polish estate to buy a house in the **rue Fortunée**
- After 1848, relations strained: James refused a 2,500 franc draft drawn by another
  of Balzac's bankers; Balzac attempted crude fraud (payment rerouted to mother
  under her maiden name); by February 1849 frantically trying to cover Northern railway
  share payments
- Balzac acknowledged the Rothschilds' difficult post-1848 position: "The House of
  Rothschild, like beavers after a thunderstorm, has to occupy itself with repairing
  the disasters which 1848 has wrought in all its finances"
- Balzac died August 1850; **James walked behind his coffin** alongside Victor Hugo,
  Alexandre Dumas; thirty-two years later the Rothschilds bought the house in the
  rue Fortunée from his widow for **ten times** the original price

#### James as Baron Nucingen

- Scholars dispute James as the model for Balzac's fictional banker **Baron de Nucingen**,
  but Balzac himself told his future wife in 1844: James was "Nucingen to the last detail,
  and worse"
- Nucingen introduced in *Le Père Goriot* (1834-5): "a banker of German origin made a
  baron of the Holy [Roman] Empire," speaks with thick phonetically-rendered German
  accent, lives ostentatiously in rue Saint-Lazare
- In *Histoire de la Grandeur et de la Décadence de César Birotteau* (1833-7): coarse
  and ruthless; Balzac notes his deliberate retention of atrocious French pronunciation
  — "in order to be able to renege on promises given well but badly kept"
- *La Maison Nucingen* (1837-8): key to Nucingen's success is a succession of **bogus
  suspensions of payment** — a pattern of manufactured bankruptcies that enriched him
  at creditors' expense
- Ferguson's conclusion: "fictionalised he may be, but Nucingen *is* James, to the
  extent that Balzac could never have created the former had he never known the latter"

<!-- pp. 501-520 -->

## Chapter 12 (continued): Balzac's Nucingen — James de Rothschild in Fiction

### La Maison Nucingen as Satire, Not Portrait
- **Balzac** is careful to distinguish **Baron de Nucingen** from Rothschild:
  Nucingen is "the son of some Jew who converted [to Christianity] out of
  ambition" and "secretly envies the Rothschild brothers" — but resemblances
  are unmistakable
- Nucingen's second great coup: massive bond purchase before Waterloo
  (mirrors Nathan's famous coup)
- Physical description echoes James: "Cubic, fat, heavy as a sack, immobile
  as a diplomat... impenetrable, you never see him coming"
- Political parallel: Nucingen said to have been "created a peer by the July
  Revolution, and a grand officer of the Legion of Honour" — exactly what
  James received from Louis Philippe

> "His genius embraces everything. This elephant of finance sells deputies
> to the ministers and the Greeks to the Turks."
> — Balzac, *La Maison Nucingen*, on Nucingen

- Underlying moral of *La Maison Nucingen*: "the debtor is stronger than
  the creditor"
- Most memorable passage: "There are arbitrary acts which are criminal when
  committed by an individual against another individual, which are expunged
  when they are extended to a multitude, just as a drop of prussic acid
  becomes innocent in a bucket of water."
- This made it easy for the political left to claim Balzac after his death

### Evolution Across the Comédie Humaine
- In *Splendeurs et Misères des Courtisanes* (1838-47): Nucingen cast as
  world-weary *vieil lard* (old lecher) besotted with a prostitute; extorted
  for a million francs by **Lucien Chardon** and the criminal **Vautrin**
- Balzac's romantic critique of capitalism: "All rapidly accumulated wealth
  is either the result of luck or discovery, or the result of a legalised
  theft... The 1814 constitution proclaimed the reign of money"
- Nucingen described as "this Louis XIV of the counting house"
- Balzac's description of Nucingen as art patron nearly identical to
  **Heine**'s "Lutetia" — Ferguson notes plagiarism seems possible
- More sympathetic portrayal in later works reflects growing personal
  friendship between **Balzac and James**
- Final appearances in *Un Homme d'affaires* (1845) and *La Cousine Bette*
  (1846): Nucingen merely the last resort of desperate borrowers
- Key irony: Balzac dedicated a book about disreputable creditors to James
  on the very eve of his own request to James for financial assistance
- The sum **Baron Hulot** tries to borrow from Nucingen in *La Cousine Bette*
  mirrors the actual amount Balzac borrowed from James that year

---

## Chapter 13: Quicksilver and Hickory (1834-1839)

> "I simply can't see why, when we ask you for the time being not to do
> something or other, then, without any particular reason, the very same
> thing happens, because everyone must know what is best for the place
> where he resides."
> — James to his English nephews, October 1836

### Overview: Geographical Overreach
- The Rothschild bond-issuing system was immensely lucrative but had limits
- In the 1830s they attempted to extend their reach to new regions —
  **Iberia** and ultimately the **United States**
- Ferguson's retrospective judgment: the greatest omission of the period was
  the **failure to establish a stable Rothschild base in the USA**
- The route to America ran through the unstable finances of Spain and Portugal

### Iberian Dilemmas

#### The Structural Problem
- Iberian politics resembled the Wars of the Roses more than ideological
  liberalism vs. conservatism — dynastic civil wars, not revolutions
- Civil wars require borrowed money — an opportunity for bankers
- The Rothschilds' core fear: other powers becoming embroiled, triggering
  a general European war (their "recurrent nightmare")
- No such escalation occurred, but without decisive foreign intervention
  the civil wars dragged on inconclusively
- Result: by the late 1830s interest was not being paid on loans issued
  just years before
- **Spanish and Portuguese bonds** played the same role in the 1830s bond
  market as **Latin American bonds** had in the 1820s
- James's verdict (repeated): they were little better than "shit"
- Root cause: both countries had come to rely heavily on revenues from
  their transatlantic empires — when those were lost, chronic national
  insolvency followed

#### Portugal: The Less Complex, Less Lucrative Story
- Nathan had lent to both sides in the coming civil war:
  **Dom Miguel** (whose 1828 coup he backed) and **Dom Pedro**
  (Emperor of Brazil, father of **Queen Maria II**)
- April 1831: Pedro forced to abdicate in Brazil, set off to restore his
  daughter in Portugal
- French liberals and British Whigs saw Pedro as a liberal kindred spirit,
  casting Miguel as a Portuguese Charles X
- By July 1832 Pedro seized Oporto; May 1834 Miguel surrendered, aided by
  English sea captain **Charles Napier**
- Pedro died four months after restoring Maria — lived just long enough
- Political instability continued: Maria's supporters split into moderate
  **"Chartists"** (1826 constitution) and radical **"Septembrists"**
  (1822 constitution); coups in 1837 and 1842, another revolution in 1846

#### The Portuguese Bond Debacle
- By 1832 **James** had begun participating in operations of Spanish
  financier **Juan Alvarez Mendizábal**, who issued a £2 million loan for
  Pedro
- James pessimistic from the start — called it "Portuguese rubbish"
- His position: only a guarantee from Britain and France would make it
  "a nice piece of business"; **Palmerston** wisely refused to give one
- 1835: Rothschilds issued a **£4 million loan** for restored government of
  Maria II — knowingly dealing in what would today be called **junk bonds**
- Bonds issued at 67.5; fell to 55 within a year; by 1839 stood at just 25
- James's candid self-description: "We have a great many asses who have
  been buying this shit"
- James's rationale for staying involved: these bonds were "the only thing
  on which one can gamble and speculate... one can never hold on to them"
  — pure speculation, not investment

> "Your Portuguese are giving me a fever. Never before in my life has
> anything upset me so much. These people are nothing more than the scum
> of the earth."
> — James to London, December 1836

- March 1835: James proposed sending someone to Lisbon two months before
  interest fell due — the Rothschilds were too exposed to allow default
- Trap: if they always covered interest, bondholders would expect it
  indefinitely — "you will be unable to retreat"
- When Goldschmidt offered a more generous refinancing deal, Rothschilds
  retaliated with selling; **Lionel** wrote from his dying father's bedside:
  "We can job in and out and only study our own advantage"
- 1837: forced to offer one final advance "to prevent it being said that a
  Rothschild loan was not paid," then attempted to pull out
- Led to "a protracted and highly embarrassing legal wrangle" with the
  Portuguese government
- Lionel's spin: "our name is not lost." James was unconvinced: "I don't
  wish to speculate with any money whatsoever on this muck"
- When **Barings** was approached for a loan in 1846, a partner argued
  against it: "Portuguese credit has been so tainted by the mismanagement
  of the Jews and Jobbers... that it would not be a very desirable connexion
  for any House wishing to stand well with the public"

#### Spain: More Complex, More Promising

**The Dynastic Question**
- Did **Salic law** apply? If so, Ferdinand VII's brother **Don Carlos**
  was heir; if not, his daughter **Isabella** (born 1830) would reign
- Isabella's legal case was stronger — Salic law had been secretly repealed
  by **Carlos IV** in the **Pragmatic Sanction of 1789**
- When Ferdinand fell ill in 1832, Carlos had enough force to temporarily
  compel revocation; Ferdinand's recovery sent Carlos fleeing to Portugal
- Ferdinand died September 1833; Carlos returned to Spain ten months later
  to mobilize supporters — civil war was now inevitable
- Ideological overlay: **Carlism** was strongest in rural Navarre and the
  Basque provinces; Isabella's cause appealed to Madrid bureaucrats and
  commercial interests

**Four Reasons to Back Isabella**
1. Short-run profits from selling new high-yield bonds to investors bored
   with consols and rentes
2. Diplomatic signal of the **Quadruple Alliance of 1834** (Britain,
   Portugal, Spain, France) suggesting foreign support for Isabella
3. The **mercury mines of Almadén** — one of only two major world sources
   of mercury (quicksilver), essential for refining silver/gold in Latin
   America; Spain traditionally mortgaged the mines to private companies
   (the Fuggers had held them in the 16th century)
4. Cuba and the Philippines: Cuba's importance in the **tobacco trade**
   was particularly attractive

**Three Reasons for Caution**
1. Protracted, inconclusive civil war — Carlists not defeated until 1839;
   repeated government changes between **Moderados** and **Progresistas**;
   **General Espartero** eventually forced Maria Christina to abdicate as
   Regent in 1840; replaced by **General Narváez** in 1844
2. The **"Cortes bonds"** — issued under the liberal regime of the early
   1820s, repudiated by Ferdinand after crushing the revolution; a law of
   1831 formally "deferred" interest payments for forty years; English
   holders blocked any new Spanish paper on the London exchange until
   they got better terms
3. Support of the **"Northern courts"** (Austria, Russia, Prussia) for
   Carlism — Metternich exerted considerable diplomatic pressure, especially
   through Salomon

**The Almadén "Sleeping Partnership" (1830)**
- As early as December 1830, James and Nathan entered a "sleeping"
  partnership (2.5% commission on sales) with the company leasing the
  Almadén mines — a foot in the door
- James committed the Rothschilds to share all Spanish business with a
  Paris consortium led by the Spaniard **Aguado** — provided camouflage
  but awkward restrictions; by summer 1833 Lionel found Aguado more
  hindrance than help

**Family Divisions Over Spain**
- Spain placed greater strain on family harmony than any other pre-1848
  issue — threatened to break up the partnership between the five houses
- Nathan keen for bigger, independent role; supported by nephew **Anselm**
  and less consistently by **Lionel**
- James vacillated constantly: "With this country there is a lot of money
  to be made, but on the other hand, one could lose a great deal of one's
  reputation" — his constant refrain throughout the 1830s
- **Salomon** generally opposed overt involvement due to Metternich pressure,
  but also wavered

> "You know my dear Papa how he [James] is — one minute he is for and
> one minute he is against the Business."
> — Lionel, impatiently

**Nathan's Unilateral Plunge (April 1834)**
- Nathan ignored warnings from Metternich, Austrian ambassador Apponyi,
  Russian ambassador Pozzo, and three French ministers (Broglie, Rigny,
  Soult) all advising the Rothschilds to avoid Spain
- April 18, 1834: Nathan unilaterally proposed to advance the Spanish
  government **15 million francs** to pay June interest on undeferrred bonds
- No firm guarantee on Cortes bonds; no security for the advance
- Wellington sardonically noted they were now "in the boat"; the boat
  "began to sink almost at once"
- Public reaction: two cartoons portrayed Nathan as a "**Jew-dish-us
  cakeman**" selling a "rice cake" marked "Loan" — "Who's for a slice?
  Who's for a slice? All Hot! All Hot!"
- Nathan's probable motive: pre-empt rivals (**Thomas Wilson** or Aguado)
  and establish himself as court banker to Maria Christina ahead of a major
  new loan; also anticipated short-run speculative profit from announcement
  boosting bond prices

**The Toreno Disaster**
- French consortium bankers promptly sued James for Nathan acting without
  regard to the consortium contract — James had to offer Aguado a share of
  all future loans to avoid losing in court
- A new Finance Minister, **Toreno**, took over in Madrid a month after
  the advance was paid and immediately reneged — claimed Rothschilds had
  promised to lend twice the amount
- Toreno planned a drastic "reduction" of Spanish public debt — cutting
  nominal value of bonds by up to 75% — which the Rothschilds called a
  "declaration of bankruptcy"
- Toreno's appointment coincided with Don Carlos returning to Spain and
  a cholera outbreak in Madrid; bond prices plummeted, causing suicides
  and murder threats on the Paris bourse
- James's fundamental weakness laid bare: "My dear Nathan, we don't have
  any troops to force the Government to do that which it does not want to do"
- August 1834: Lionel sent to Madrid (accompanied by lawyer **Adolphe
  Crémieux**) to negotiate face-to-face; Toreno convinced him only a
  full loan could avert bankruptcy and republican government
- January 1835: Rothschilds reluctantly accepted 15 million francs
  equivalent as a share of a new loan issued by rival **Ardouin**
- Salomon later estimated losses on the whole contract at **1.6 million
  francs**

**The Almadén Prize**
- During Lionel's Madrid stay, the Almadén contract fell due for renewal
- Lionel outbid four other companies — essentially by **bribing Toreno
  and the Queen** and offering to pay 5% more than the highest rival bid
- Mines producing 16,000–18,000 hundredweight of mercury/year in 1835
- Under the 1835 contract: paid 54.5 pesetas (£2.18) per hundredweight;
  could resell in London at 76–80 pesetas, or to silver refineries in
  Mexico for up to 150 pesetas
- Minimum profit: **£13,000/year**; when production stepped up in 1838,
  annual income rose to **£32,000** — over 13% of the London house's total
  net revenue from mines, and 38% of London house profits (half shared
  with Paris)
- By the 1840s, **20% return** from Almadén was James's target
- Strategic pivot: instead of issuing bonds for Spain (worthless paper),
  the Rothschilds would now finance the government through short-run
  advances on mercury royalties; later extended to copper and Cuba tobacco
- **Commodities proved the best security for loans to unstable states**

**Salomon's Extraordinary Letter to Metternich**
- To clear himself of guilt by association with Nathan's intervention
  advocacy, Salomon wrote a letter to his clerk **Leopold von
  Wertheimstein** in Vienna — explicitly intended for Metternich's eyes
- Claimed the collapse in Spanish bond prices after Toreno's appointment
  was engineered by the Rothschilds as "vengeance" — Nathan had sold
  £2 million of Spanish bonds to ruin Toreno's credit
- Salomon and James had gone to Talleyrand, Guizot, Broglie, and Louis
  Philippe to argue France's credit "would go to the devil" if they
  intervened in Spain
- Salomon on Nathan in this letter:

> "My brother Nathan Mayer is one of the ablest men as far as the
> Exchequer and price movements are concerned but has no special aptitude
> in other matters... [H]e is a child in politics... In other matters that
> are not concerned with the Bourse, [he] is not particularly bright;
> he is exceedingly competent in his office, but apart from that, between
> ourselves, he can hardly spell his own name."
> — Salomon von Rothschild, letter intended for Metternich

- Salomon even claimed Nathan's Spanish advance threatened to break up the
  brothers' partnership entirely
- As late as 1840 — after Don Carlos was defeated — James still refused
  to lend to Spain under the Rothschild name without a guarantee from
  England and France

**Metternich's Leverage and its Limits**
- Metternich used intelligence from Austrian chargé **Hummelauer** and
  junior official **Kirchner** (supposedly assisting Nathan with consular
  duties) to stay informed of Nathan's actions
- Metternich appears to have succeeded in scuppering a planned
  Anglo-French guaranteed loan to Toreno's successor **Mendizábal**
- Nathan — responding to Salomon's pressure — leaked the Anglo-French plan
  to Vienna, effectively killing it
- Nathan told Palmerston he had "no confidence in the solvency of
  Mendizábal's government"
- When Palmerston noted planned crown land sales would raise money, Nathan
  replied: "Yes, in time, but not in time for the May dividend. It is like
  telling me at seven o'clock when I want my dinner [that] there is a calf
  feeding in a field a mile off."
- By 1837: Rothschilds had more or less completely withdrawn from the
  Spanish bond market; Nathan's last instructions to his sons were to
  liquidate all Spanish holdings
- Spanish bonds trading as low as 19 — James called them "muck" or "shit"
- However: Ferguson argues Metternich did not fully "win" — if France and
  Britain had intervened militarily, the Rothschilds would likely have
  resumed large-scale lending to Spain

<!-- pp. 521-540 -->

## Spain: Mercury, Almadén, and the Limits of Political Neutrality

### The Spanish Dilemma (mid-1830s–1840s)

- **James de Rothschild** privately wanted France to intervene in the Carlist War despite
  publicly opposing it — intervention would unlock massive profit in bills, mercury,
  and "everything else"
- Strategy after declining a full bond loan to **Mendizábal**: maintain Spanish exposure
  via advances on **Almadén mercury** (up to £100,000), pay salaries of Spanish
  diplomats in Paris, and pursue Havana bills — all kept secret from Metternich
- Rothschilds drew the line at issuing bonds; advances and commodity deals were
  acceptable cover

> "If we should be so fortunate that we, over here, decide to intervene [in Spain],
> this could make a difference for us of many hundreds of thousands of pounds
> sterling... I spoke so much [in favour of intervention] that my tongue nearly
> fell out of my throat." — *James to Nathan, March 1836*

### Almadén Monopoly Under Threat

- After Mendizábal's fall (August 1837), the **Cortes** sought to revoke the Almadén
  contract, claiming it had been improperly modified in 1835
- Defenders of the contract warned that depriving Rothschilds might cause them to
  back **Don Carlos** — described as "the monetary dynasty of Europe, and a new
  lever in the balance of power"
- Resolution: Rothschilds extended larger advances (£200,000–£400,000) to retain
  the mines rather than issue bonds; gave their agent **Weisweiller** wide latitude,
  including tolerating his partnership with court governor **Manuel Gaviria**
- Rival banker **Aguado** repeatedly dangled large loan proposals to challenge the
  Almadén monopoly; Finance Minister **Alejandro Mon** warned James that without
  a £5m loan they would lose the mines
- **Salomon** continued opposing bond involvement while under Metternich's scrutiny;
  Carlists briefly occupied Almadén in April 1838, raising real operational risk

### Political Ambiguity as Strategy

- Through successive Spanish coups and pronunciamentos of the early 1840s,
  Rothschilds remained bankers to the exiled **Maria Christina** while simultaneously
  keeping Weisweiller on good terms with **Espartero** and then **Narváez**
- The 1843 agreement to import 12 million Havana cigars into Austria served as a
  peace offering to reconcile **Metternich** to ongoing Spanish/colonial business
- **Queen Isabella's marriage question** (mid-1840s) was another diplomatic minefield:
  France wanted Francisco de Asis + duc de Montpensier (Louis Philippe's son);
  Palmerston backed a Coburg; Metternich pushed Montemolin (Carlist heir)
- Rothschilds were "reluctant onlookers" — their refusal to back a loan was
  misread by Guizot as political commentary on the marriage, when it was simply
  continued no-bond policy dating back a decade
- **Mercury contract renewal crisis (1847):** Rising purchase price (54.5 to 70
  pesetas) + falling world prices after **Lionel Davidson** confirmed Mexican deposits
  in 1845 = deadlock. Spanish government demanded £600,000 advance; Rothschilds
  refused without better terms. James: "If one could earn 20 per cent then I would
  be all in favour of going ahead, but as matters stand at present we stand to make
  only a trivial sum."

---

## "That Blasted Country": America

### Why the Rothschilds Failed in the United States

- Despite America's explosive economic growth after 1820, the Rothschilds "never
  quite rose" to the challenge — Ferguson calls this the **single greatest strategic
  error** in the bank's history
- Standard explanations (Barings had sewn up the market; J. P. Morgan later eclipsed
  them) are insufficient — Rothschilds had ousted stronger rivals elsewhere
- **Real structural obstacles:**
  1. **Federal system** — central government borrowing needs were minimal; individual
     states proved among the least reliable creditors of the 19th century
  2. **Anti-bank populism** — America's deep suspicion of large (especially foreign,
     especially Jewish) banks made the institutional partnerships Rothschilds relied
     on impossible to sustain
  3. **No reliable central bank partner** — unlike Bank of England or Banque de France,
     US central banks kept being abolished on political grounds

### The Bank of the United States (BUS) Problem

- **First BUS** (founded 1791 by **Alexander Hamilton**): killed by Republican Congress
  on constitutional grounds
- **Second BUS** (1816, $25m capital): became focus of populist "money power" attacks;
  President **Andrew Jackson** vetoed charter renewal in 1832, declaring
  "The Bank is trying to kill me, but I will kill it." Lost public status 1836
- Without a stable institutional partner, Rothschild business model couldn't work
  in America
- Anti-Semitic hostility surfaced immediately: **Governor McNutt of Mississippi**
  denounced "Baron Rothschild" for having "the blood of Judas and Shylock
  flow[ing] in his veins"

### Rothschild Entry: Early 1830s

- Entry point: arranging payment of £1 million owed to the US Treasury from France
  (early 1830s) → replaced **Barings** as federal government's London agent
- Mid-1830s: London and Paris houses doing substantial volume in bills generated
  by American cotton/tobacco exports; advanced sums to bankers **J. L. and S. I.
  Joseph**
- The 1836–7 American financial crisis forced a decision about the nature of
  Rothschild representation in America

### August Belmont: The Accidental Agent

- **August Belmont** (born **Schönberg**) had joined the Frankfurt house as an apprentice
  at 15, risen rapidly; sent to America in 1837 ostensibly to assess the crisis
  and then proceed to Havana
- James's real priority was Cuba: "Spain receives all her income from that land
  and it is one of the most profitable business ventures" — US commitments had
  been cut to just £9,000, written off as "a lost cause"
- Belmont defied orders: instead of going to Havana, he set up at **78 Wall Street**,
  announcing **August Belmont & Co.** as Rothschild agent

> "He is a stupid young man... and we are not so desperate for new business...
> Instead of going to Philadelphia to collect the 300,000 francs from Cohen he
> says, 'I shall remain in New York.' Such an ass needs to be kept on a short
> leash." — *James on Belmont*

### The Battle to Send a Rothschild to America

- James spent months trying to persuade nephews **Anthony** or **Anselm** to go;
  no one wanted to make the trip
- Fundamental problem: **London house** (not Paris) conducted most US business
  because Britain was a bigger buyer of American cotton/tobacco; James had to
  defer to his nephews despite his greater enthusiasm
- James eventually accepted the situation — "America is more suited to England
  than it is to France" — and the London/Paris profit-sharing friction over
  American business persisted for decades
- Belmont refused to go to Cuba, leveraged his position to get bill-discounting
  authority, salary raised to £500 (paid jointly by London and Paris), and a
  £10,000 credit line — threatening to switch to rival houses if denied
- Rothschilds "never quite forgave" Belmont: he fought a duel (1841), converted
  to Christianity for social advancement, and eventually built a political career
  that took him to the leadership of the **Democrat Party**
- **Lionel Davidson** sent to New York in 1839 to control Belmont; Nat called him
  "a clever intelligent fellow... if you can manage to keep him down." Davidson
  was eventually redirected to Mexico; **Hanau** sent to New Orleans (1843)

### The BUS Disaster

- After Barings dropped the BUS as European agent (1836–7), Rothschilds eagerly
  stepped in; James called the BUS "the wealthiest people in America" and imagined
  flooding America with Spanish mercury to dominate the market
- Initial flow of American state bonds — New York, Indiana, Alabama, Missouri,
  Michigan — plus bank and canal shares
- By September 1839 the BUS was clearly over-extended: cotton crop failure,
  capital tied up in long-term ventures, funding via high-yield post notes
- BUS European agent **Samuel Jaudon** warned he could not meet his acceptances;
  Rothschild advances to him reached £300,000 — effectively locked into bad paper
- Reluctantly took over BUS drafts on Hottinguer worth 5.5 million francs (£220,000);
  attempted to pass losses to investors via BUS debentures
- **Lionel** argued caveat emptor: "the purchaser must take his chance and must
  know that he is running some risk." **Nat** blamed James for the whole mess,
  pointing out it was the Paris house that had accepted Jaudon's bills over
  London's objections
- October 1839: BUS suspended payments; 1841: finally collapsed, triggering state
  defaults on bonds Jaudon had used as security

> "You may tell your government that you have seen the man who is at the head of
> the finances of Europe, and that he has told you that you cannot borrow a dollar,
> not a dollar." — *James to US Treasury representatives, after BUS collapse*

- **Anthony's verdict (1842):** "let us get rid of that blasted country — as much
  as we profitably can. It is the most blasted & the most stinking country in the
  world — & we must get rid of it, & that stinking Belmont in the Bargain."
- Despite this, the Rothschilds resumed American cotton/tobacco dealings almost
  immediately; scars from BUS shaped persistent suspicion toward the US economy

---

## Trouble in Threadneedle Street

### The 1836–9 Crisis and the Bank of England Feud

- American crisis strained Rothschild–**Bank of England** relations to breaking point;
  Bank of England's note circulation had declined almost without interruption
  since 1825 — bullionist system with no major gold discoveries
- American crisis drained gold and silver across the Atlantic; Rothschilds torn
  between US commitments and pressure from both Bank of England and **Banque de
  France** to maintain European liquidity
- London house owed Bank of England at least £300,000 (borrowed December 1835,
  not due until October) + short-term £120,000 advance from June 1836
- **James** committed to supplying Banque de France with silver while sending gold
  to London only belatedly (end of November 1836); criticized Bank of England
  Governor for allowing reserves to sink dangerously low

### The Silver Standard Rumor and Escalating Conflict

- James alarmed by rumor France was considering switching to a **silver standard**;
  feared if England did the same, gold would flow from France to England causing
  universal crisis
- When Bank of England began buying silver (summer 1837), James threatened to
  stop sending gold to London; accused Governor of indecision ("changed his mind
  from day to day")
- James's advice — "under no circumstances should he allow any American House to
  collapse" — was ignored
- Former Bank Governor **Timothy Curtis** wrote conciliatory letter but insisted
  the Bank must retain adequate silver; by March (following year) James was
  convinced "your English Bank is out to destroy our business"

### The 1839 Banque de France–Bank of England Rescue

- Bank of England reserves reduced to £3.7 million by American crisis; turned to
  **Banque de France** for assistance
- Governor of Banque: **comte d'Argout**; James initially wholly opposed — argued
  that Banque lending to Bank of England during peacetime was dangerous because
  in wartime, France would need that money and England would not reciprocate
- James and **Anselm** refused to participate even when Banque Deputy Governor
  invoked the service Rothschilds had rendered to the Bank of England
- Anselm's warning to London cousins invoked **Nathan's** legacy: "do not trust
  the Bank without any guarantees... as the Bank being involved in difficulties
  may *stop* suddenly. Mind, you are not your good father."
- **Hannah** similarly cautious: "I would not advance any thing to the Bank without
  having Exchequer Bills or any other Government security."
- James's boycott strategy failed: the deal between Curtis and d'Argout proceeded
  without Rothschilds; Barings and a consortium of Paris houses got the business
- James forced into humiliating volte-face: resolved "to go into the business with
  the Bank as far as I possibly can" — but he had left it too late
- Aftermath: James fantasized about revenge against Curtis (canceling a private
  loan of £5,000), acknowledged "they are stronger than us" — but knew he could
  not start a "war with the Bank"
- **1843**: Lionel closed the Rothschild account at the Bank of England
- Net result of James's American enthusiasm: large bad debts from the defunct BUS
  and lasting bad feeling with the Bank of England

---

## Chapter 14: Between Retrenchment and Rearmament (1840)

> "Monsieur Rothschild knows Europe prince by prince and the bourse courtier
> by courtier. He carries all their bank balances in his head... He says to
> one such: 'Your account will go into the red if you appoint that minister.'"
> — *Michelet*

### The Paradox of Peace

- **Fundamental paradox of Rothschild pacifism:** governments that heeded
  Rothschild advice and avoided war also curtailed military spending — and
  therefore stopped needing new loans
- After 1833 the major powers "effectively ceased to be Rothschild clients";
  peace was making the five houses redundant
- **Prussia:** Zollverein (1834) revenues rising; debt service fell from 22% of
  total expenditure in 1821 to 11% in 1850; public debt halved relative to
  annual revenue by mid-century. When 1844 conversion negotiations for the old
  1818 sterling loan into thaler bonds resumed, Rothschild hopes for a new loan
  were unrealistic — "their old friend **Rother** no longer needed them"
- **Britain:** The 1835 slave-owner compensation loan was the last major British
  government loan before the Crimean War, reflecting **Sir Robert Peel's** fiscal
  conservatism; net government borrowing 1836–41 was only ~£4 million total

### Peel's Fiscal Revolution (1841 onwards)

- Peel's program had four elements:
  1. **Debt conversion** — reduced interest on £250 million of stock from 3.5% to 3.25%
  2. **Income tax** — reintroduced at 7d in the pound on incomes above £150
     (previously only a wartime measure)
  3. **Bank Charter reform** — redrafted Bank of England's Charter to perfect the
     bullionist system (based on his 1819 committee)
  4. **Trade liberalisation** — 605 import duties repealed 1842–46, 1,035 reduced;
     culmination: repeal of the **Corn Laws** (seen by most Tory backbenchers
     as a betrayal of rural constituents)
- Peel's reforms meant sustained fiscal surpluses → no need for government
  borrowing → Rothschilds increasingly marginalised from British sovereign finance

<!-- pp. 541-560 -->

## Chapter [continuation]: Spreading the Net — 1834–1848

### Peel's Reforms and the Income Tax Problem

- **Peelite finance** set the benchmark for fiscal and monetary orthodoxy for the
  rest of the 19th century — 3% consols rose from 87 (Oct 1841) to 101 three
  years later, signaling City approval
- The programme was incoherent in practice: **Bank Charter Act** restricted
  domestic banknote circulation as the Bank of England's gold reserve declined,
  aggravating depression; budget surplus lasted only 1844–7 before the
  1847–8 crisis put Britain back in deficit
- **Income tax**, supposedly temporary, quickly looked permanent — even
  **Gladstone** (Peel's ideological heir) never gave up hope of abolishing it
- **Peel** had conceived income tax as early as 1830 as a way of "reach[ing]
  such men as Baring, his father, Rothschild" — the Rothschilds were duly
  "reached" in 1842 and were less than pleased
- Additional Rothschild grievances: Tories opposed **Jewish emancipation**;
  Tory ministry threatened to revive an Anglo-Russian alliance against
  liberal France

### Rothschild Tax Anxieties

- **Nat** foresaw practical difficulties: "How will it be possible for tax
  collectors to ascertain the real incomes of merchants & bankers who by and
  large do not know themselves what they can term their income until their
  balances are made?"
- Asked his brothers: do you value stock at market price or pay only on realized
  profits? — exposed the Rothschilds' cavalier accounting practices
- Not contemplating evasion: Nat advised giving commissioners "an exact amount
  of the profits . . . a few hundred pounds more or less is of little
  consequence"
- Biggest concern: if earnings from **foreign investments were taxed**, bondholders
  would switch to domestic investments — catastrophic for a bank specializing
  in **capital export**

> "I think my dear Lionel, you ought to make strong representations to the
> government about charging the income tax upon all coupons of foreign bonds
> paid in London . . . it is a great pity & will in a good measure stop
> business." — Nat to Lionel

- Practical effect: British (but not foreign) holders paid tax on foreign bond
  income, tempting clients to use the Rothschilds under bogus foreign names
- **James** feared income tax would spread to France — heralding an end to the
  golden age when governments *borrowed* from capitalists rather than *taxed* them

### Lean Years: Austria and France (1834–1841)

- Both Austria and France were relatively quiet for Rothschild lending:
  no new Austrian loans; France's public works financed from taxation, not
  borrowing; French national debt actually *reduced* by 169 million francs
- Only offering was another **conversion** — which James regarded with little
  enthusiasm given past experience

### Russia: The Elusive Loan

- Russia's different situation had the same net effect: public spending rose
  1833–1839 but was financed by printing **paper roubles** (inflation)
- **Kankrin's currency reforms** (1839, 1843) replaced paper rouble with a
  "hard" rouble backed by gold and silver — creating demand for a
  **stabilisation loan** to build the bullion reserve
- James eagerly proposed floating it simultaneously in London and Paris:

> "not only because it will enhance their credit but also because it is in
> their own best interest to ensure that all the wealthy people [in England
> and France] have a substantial investment in Russia and would suffer a
> financial loss if ever such an unfortunate idea as to march into Russia
> and wage war . . . were to be implemented" — James

- **Salomon** agreed: a Russian loan would "bring us back on top with all the
  great powers in Europe"
- Repeated failure: London Rothschilds proposed terms too low (70 less 2%
  commission = 68 for Russian 3% paper, when Austrian 3%s stood at 81)
- Salomon, briefed by **Metternich**, argued Kankrin's stated railway
  investment purpose was merely a cover for **army expenditure**
- Key argument against Russia: "With Russia, the money that flows in is
  buried, poured away into the colossal European and even Asian domains of
  this empire" — unlike Western loans where money circulates back to the public
- Rothschilds refused to buy the loan "*à forfait*" (firm underwriting),
  preferring commission (with right to return unsold bonds)
- Talks in 1844 and 1846 equally inconclusive: "once it had seemed that the
  Rothschilds no longer needed the great powers; now it began to seem that
  the powers no longer needed the Rothschilds"

### Spreading the Net: German States

- Response to diminished great-power business: James and Salomon moved into
  **industrial finance** (railways); Frankfurt house targeted **smaller German states**
- Frankfurt house transactions (from Berghoeffer's list):
  - 3.5 million gulden bonds for **Saxe-Coburg-Gotha** (1837–42)
  - 9.9 million gulden for **Nassau**
  - 6.7 million reichsthaler **lottery loan** for **Hesse-Kassel** (1845)
  - Loans to **Hesse-Darmstadt**, **Baden** (14 million gulden, 1845)
  - **Bavaria** loan (1835) → Carl and Amschel appointed "court bankers"; Anselm
    received Bavarian consulship in Frankfurt
  - Mid-1840s: **Württemberg**, Frankfurt itself, Denmark (£3 million, 1835)
  - Hanover approached but deal fell through at eleventh hour
- **Prussia** was the exception: debt-to-revenue ratio *fell* 1825–1850 due to
  the 1819 State Debt Decree restricting borrowing; all other German states
  saw ratios rise (railway construction debt)
- Minor transactions demanded as much effort as great-power loans, due to
  pressure from representative bodies on previously autonomous financial
  bureaucracies
- The Frankfurt house's dominance was so complete that local people talked of
  "**Rothschild shipments**" of specie and "**Rothschild money**"
- Liberals saw the Rothschilds as propping up reactionary regimes; when
  **Johann Stüve** (Hanoverian liberal) came to power in 1848 he sought to avoid
  "dirty transactions with Rothschild"
- **Amschel** and his nephews were politically indifferent — Baden was a
  "model" constitutional monarchy; Hanover (after King Ernst August abrogated
  its constitution in 1837) was among the most conservative regimes in Germany.
  Both got loans.

### Loans to Aristocratic Clients

- Frankfurt house profits also from minor princes: **Prince von Bentheim-Tecklenburg**,
  **Prince Viktor zu Isenburg**, major landowners like **Count Hugo Henckel von
  Donnersmarck**
- Novel 1840s extension: Salomon's Vienna associates lent 12.3 million gulden
  (1843–45) to Austro-Hungarian noblemen — mostly **Hungarian** aristocrats
  including **Prince Paul Esterházy**, Count Móric Sándor, Count Joseph Hunyady,
  Count Lajos Széchényi (brother of reformer István Széchényi)
- These loans were analogous to West End banks (e.g., **Coutts & Co.**) lending
  to the English aristocracy — land-rich, cash-poor grandees
- Political embarrassment: Hungary would soon plunge into secessionist war
  with Austria — the Rothschilds had financial ties to both sides

### Italy: Naples, the Papacy, Piedmont

- Continued dominance in **Two Sicilies** (Bourbon regime), though worried about
  local competition for Carl's position
- Low opinion of the Neapolitan government: James told Carl (1839), "Your
  Finance Minister is not a man you can reliably count on. He is a real
  blackguard . . . the only man who can accomplish anything in Naples is the
  King himself and the Minister of the Interior"
- **Papal finances**: Salomon used leverage over Rome's debt to protest
  ill-treatment of the **Jewish community of Rome** through Metternich — feeding
  the perception (in **Alfred de Vigny**'s words) that "A Jew now reigns over
  the Pope and Christianity"
- Ferguson notes: primary concern was profit, not reform of the Papal regime

### The Piedmont-Sardinia Negotiation (1834)

- Paris house invited to bid for a £1 million loan — fierce competition
- James sent **Lionel** to Turin; correspondence reveals Rothschild negotiating
  doctrine in detail
- James's instructions on tactics:

> "our competitors *come to you (for in no case must you go to them
> yourself)* . . . the business must be done by you in *our sole name*;
> for you were the first on the spot, and in no case can it suit us to be
> in the background or to join our name to another."

- On losing the deal: "*If the business be in the least feasible, do it, even
  if it should give no profit whatever, even if it were necessary to lose 2 or
  3 hundred thousand francs to prove to those gent[lemen] that we are not
  afraid of a sacrifice when we want to baffle them.*"
- Lionel ultimately outmaneuvered ("outbid") by the "**Bande Noire**" of French
  bankers led by **Hagermann**; relations with Turin remained embryonic before 1848

### The Rothschild Reputation by the Early 1840s

- By early 1840s observers saw the Rothschilds as having acquired "a unique
  power of their own which was independent of the great powers and nearly
  universal"
- **Alexandre Weill**, "Rothschild and the Finances of Europe" (1844): while
  "Rothschild" had *needed* the states to become "Rothschild," he now no
  longer needed them
- **Jules Michelet** (1842): James knew "Europe prince by prince, and the bourse
  courtier by courtier"
- States that borrowed: conservative states to avoid parliamentary oversight of
  finances; progressive states (esp. Belgium, German states) to fund railways

---

### "Absolument le Maître des Finances de Ce Pays": Belgium

- Best case study of pre-1848 Rothschild strategy
- After Belgian secession from Dutch rule (1830), James moved swiftly to
  establish financial foothold in Brussels — lifeline of credit in stormy
  first three years
- Mid-1833 to 1838: James defended dominant position established with
  **Société Générale**; key instrument was state loans to finance **King Leopold I**'s
  railway network — **Belgium** was breaking British precedent by having
  government rather than private sector finance railways
- Belgian logic: railways had strategic value — needed to avoid dependence on
  Dutch-controlled canals and rivers
- Rothschild preference: state bonds always struck them as less risky than
  private railway shares
- Belgian banking system created three new institutions in partnership with
  Société Générale; **Banque de Belgique** (founded 1835 with largely French
  capital) was a genuine rival

### Belgian Crisis of 1838–39 (Dutch-Belgian Settlement)

- The **1832 articles** required Belgium to evacuate **Luxembourg** and **Limburg** and
  split pre-1830 Dutch debt equally — Belgium resisted
- James was eager to secure a new 36-million-franc loan (first major Rothschild
  bond issue since Nathan's death) to assert both the firm's bond-market
  dominance and his own leadership within it
- When Prussia occupied Luxembourg to force Belgium's hand, James momentarily
  hesitated — but when it was clear France would not intervene he moved quickly,
  issuing bonds simultaneously in London, Paris and Brussels
- Belgian coal bubble burst in 1838: the sudden slump nearly broke the
  **Banque de Belgique** and put the **Société Générale** under pressure — James
  stepped in and bailed both out, strengthening his position
- In December 1838, James had a war-escape clause inserted in the loan
  agreement: the Rothschilds could annul if war broke out
- Belgium requested additional advance against treasury bills — James flatly
  refused; used the Metternich channel to signal that Belgium would "not get a
  farthing" until it accepted the settlement

> "They won't get a farthing from me until they give way . . . as long as
> the articles are not accepted the Belgian Government will not get a
> halfpenny from us, although they have been begging for money for months."
> — Salomon (via Metternich)

### Consolidating Belgian Monopoly

- After settlement, James aimed at total monopoly: "the arrangement of the
  Belgian question is going to be followed by a need for money and this will
  be a moment we ought to exploit in order to make ourselves the **absolute
  masters of the finances of this country**"
- By 1840 James was in Brussels personally: "I lectured them about how to put
  themselves on a better footing . . . They are content enough to let us guide
  them, now that I have pointed out to them all the mistakes they have made
  in attempting to act without us"
- Further loans: November 1840 (60–80 million franc discussion); 28.6 million
  francs two years later; Belgium "addicted" to borrowing
- When James fell out with a Belgian minister in 1842, he instructed Lionel
  to visit **King Leopold** at Windsor and subtly indicate "there will be no
  market anywhere for Belgian bonds" if that minister remained
- **Belgium raised five major loans 1830–1844**, combined nominal value ~300
  million francs — almost all underwritten by the Rothschilds
- Classic Rothschild market tactic: when Belgium tried to sell bonds directly
  to the public by subscription, Nat and James quietly sold off Belgian bonds
  to make markets "flat" and force the government to return cap in hand —
  which it did by 1845
- French ambassador confirmed: without Rothschild, Belgium had "realised that
  it would be impossible for it to find a penny on any bourse, domestic or foreign"

### Dutch Operations

- Anselm (October 1840) visited the Hague; when Dutch government needed
  payment from Belgium, Anselm offered a modest advance
- 1842: Rothschilds offered to cash Belgian bonds given to Holland (at
  substantial discount) — acting on behalf of both parties in the same
  international transfer; characteristic Rothschild arbitrage role
- Dutch Finance Minister complained: press accused him of being "sold to"
  the Rothschilds; he told Anselm "I wish most sincerely to do alone with
  you, if only I could save my reputation of an honest man" — three months
  later forced to resign under opposition pressure

---

### Roads to Damascus: France and the Eastern Question

### French Political Risks

- **James**'s definition of a "good ministry": one that pursues pacific policies
  abroad and balances the budget at home
- Fear of **Thiers**: James warned in 1837 that "Rentes will fall because Thiers
  is in favour of a policy of intervention [in Spain]"; thought of another
  Thiers ministry was enough to convince James to "get out of the [French] funds"
- Liked the **Molé ministry** precisely because it was "weak" (less likely to
  pursue aggressive foreign policy)
- March 1, 1840: Thiers back in office — James pessimistic, began slowly
  selling 3% rentes; believed France could "only extricate herself from her
  current predicament by means of war" in the long run

### The Eastern Question

- The **"Eastern Question"**: could the sprawling **Ottoman Empire** be preserved
  intact? The empire was economically backward, religiously divided,
  administratively ramshackle, and politically despotic
- Four of the "big five" European powers had interests in the region where
  Ottoman rule was in decline: Austria and Russia (geographic proximity);
  Britain and France (commercial, strategic, religious interests)
- Rothschilds vital to Eastern diplomacy because money was always needed —
  the fundamental problem of governing the region was its **chronic narrowness
  of its tax base**
- Second reason for Rothschild interest: position of their "**co-religionists**"
  (Jewish communities) in Ottoman-controlled territories

### The Greek Loan and First Eastern Crisis

- **Greek independence** first drew the Rothschilds into Eastern affairs
- Greek bonds guaranteed by Britain, France and Russia — looked straightforward
- 60 million francs to be issued; 11 million francs to pay Turkey as indemnity
  (through the Rothschilds); rest to Greek government via **d'Eichthal** (who
  dominated the transaction through his close Bavarian ties with the new Greek king)
- November 1831: **Mehemet Ali**, ruling Pasha of Egypt (Albanian by birth),
  revolted against Sultan **Mahmud II** — claiming inadequate reward for military
  services against Greece; sent his son **Ibrahim** to invade Syria, seizing
  Gaza, Jerusalem and Damascus
- **Sultan** sought British support; **Palmerston** rejected advice of his man in
  Constantinople (**Stratford Canning**) and refused, seeking compromise
- Sultan turned to Russia instead: February 1833, **Treaty of Unkiar Skelessi** —
  secret article binding Sultan to close the Black Sea Straits to warships "au
  besoin" (at Russia's request); Austria and Prussia endorsed at **Münchengrätz**
- Financial complications: French guarantee for Greek loan unratified; Greek
  indemnity payment to Turkey now due — technical difficulties proliferated
  under diplomatic strain
- **Nat** went to Constantinople expecting decorations from the Sultan; left
  "sick & tired of the Turks and their shameful double dealing"
- 1836–7: Greece threatened to default on interest — new bonds issued to
  fund dividends; markets quickly learned to value British-guaranteed bonds
  over French- and Russian-guaranteed ones
- Problem persisted into the 1840s; the Greek loan became an ongoing headache

<!-- pp. 561-580 -->

## [Chapter 14 cont.]: The Eastern Question, Damascus Affair & Fall of Thiers

### Anglo-French Divergence on the Eastern Question

- **1836-7**: France resumes colonisation of Algeria (former Ottoman fiefdom);
  **Palmerston** steers Britain toward pro-Turkish policy to undermine
  Russian dominance in Constantinople
- When war re-erupts between the Sultan and **Mehemet Ali** (April 1839),
  France backs Ali; Britain and Russia cut a deal: replace **Treaty of
  Unkiar Skelessi** with international Black Sea agreement, force Ali
  out of Syria but let him keep Acre
- French government (Soult) rejects the proposal but is diplomatically
  isolated — Paris house reports it is "in a rather embarrassing position"
- French humiliation on Eastern affairs strengthens argument for
  **Thiers'** more aggressive foreign policy approach

### The Damascus Blood Libel (February 1840)

- **February 5, 1840**: Sardinian Capuchin friar **Father Tommaso** and
  his servant Ibrahim vanish in Damascus; last seen in the Jewish quarter
- **Comte de Ratti-Menton** (French consul) fans allegations that Jews
  committed ritual murder, pressures the Egyptian governor to arrest
  Jews and torture confessions
- Tortured testimony snowballs — one Jew tortured to death, a barber
  lashed 500 times alleged involvement of two rabbis and merchant
  **David Arari**; one convert to Islam "confirmed" the ritual murder
  story to save himself
- Pattern: "As with early modern witch-hunts, the more bizarre the
  story grew, the greater the number of people who were implicated"
- ~70 people arrested; children taken hostage to force fugitives
  to surrender themselves
- Arrest of **Isaac de Picciotto** (Jewish merchant, Austrian subject)
  transforms witch-hunt into international incident

### Austrian Intervention & Rothschild Mobilisation

- Austrian consul **Caspar Giovanne Merlatto** protests to Damascus
  authorities; consul-general **Anton Laurin** complains to Mehemet
  Ali and tries to restrain Ratti-Menton
- Laurin sends his reports to the Austrian consul-general in Paris —
  who was **James de Rothschild** — urging pressure on the French
  government to rebuke its consul
- By March 15, Dutch Jewish leader **Hirsch Lehren** urges the
  Rothschilds to "speak to the kings and to their ministers"; March 27
  Constantinople community writes to Salomon, Carl, and Lionel
  appealing to "the tie which so strongly binds together the whole
  Jewish community"
- French Foreign Ministry responds only with a toothless internal
  investigation (vice-consul investigating his own superior)

### Press Campaign & Crémieux Mission

> "the only means we have left is the all-powerful method here of calling
> in the newspapers to our assistance" — **James de Rothschild**, April 7, 1840

- James plants detailed account (based on Laurin's Austrian consul
  reports) in the *Journal des Débats* and *Allgemeine Zeitung*
  of Augsburg — counter-programming against pro-ritual-murder
  coverage in the *Quotidienne* and *Univers*
- James enlists **Adolphe Crémieux** (vice-president of the Consistory
  of French Jews since 1834) whose long letter appears in *Gazette des
  Tribunaux* and *Journal des Débats*
- **Nat** proposes funding Crémieux's trip to the Middle East; **Lionel**
  attends the Board of Deputies meeting (April 21) and the delegation
  received by Palmerston
- Rothschilds contribute at least **£2,500** toward the costs of the
  **Crémieux–Sir Moses Montefiore** expedition to Alexandria
- **Salomon** persuades Metternich to press the Vatican (rumour that
  Tommaso was alive hiding in a monastery — false); **Carl** loads
  Montefiore's ship and later tries to get the Catholic Church to
  expunge the murder allegation from Tommaso's gravestone

### Sincere Motives — but Diplomatic Calculation Too

- **Nat**: the aim was "to show people generally that the day is gone
  by when any religious sect may be neglected with impunity"
- **Heine** (tipped off by James) contrasts James's "nobler spirit"
  with rival banker **Benoît Fould's** indifference
- Ferguson's key argument: the Rothschilds *were* sincerely outraged,
  but **James and Salomon attached more importance to the diplomatic
  ramifications** — the affair was an ideal tool to undermine Thiers
- Thiers (just become premier) could not criticise Mehemet Ali's Syria
  regime without disowning his own consul; he doubled down, telling
  James "the case is based on truth; we had better let the matter rest
  . . . [as] the Jews in the East still maintain such superstitions"
- Montefiore mission succeeds: Mehemet Ali issues a *firman*
  (August 28) denying ritual murder as Jewish practice; prisoners
  "honourably discharged" a week later

### Limits of Rothschild Jewish Ambitions

- Wild speculation in press (from 1830) that Rothschilds aimed to
  "reclaim the Holy Land" — **Niles Weekly Register** (1830) imagines
  sultan selling Jerusalem to the Rothschilds
- Socialist **Charles Fourier**: Rothschilds should "lead the Hebrews
  back to Jerusalem and erect once again the throne of David and Solomon"
- British Evangelicals, Lady Palmerston: "fanatical and religious
  elements . . . are absolutely determined that Jerusalem and Palestine
  shall be reserved for the Jews"
- Ferguson's verdict: **no evidence** the Rothschilds harboured Zionist
  intentions; family involvement in Zionism was "a much later development"
- **Lionel** was privately uneasy about the "rumpus" made by Crémieux —
  felt the expedition showed "rather too much warmth of feeling";
  Montefiore sent partly "to moderate [Crémieux's] zeal"
- When Damascus agitation leads to plans for a Jewish hospital in
  Jerusalem, the French Rothschilds make their contribution conditional
  on a secular school alongside it; Palestinian Jewish community vetoes
  this, Rothschilds withdraw — scheme not revived until 1853-4

### Toppling Thiers: The Financial Mechanism

- On August 3 there was "a tremendous fall in the price of rentes"
  as the British naval expedition closed on Ibrahim Pasha
- 3 per cents fall from high of **87 in July** to **79 in early August**,
  touching **73.5 in early October**
- The Rothschilds did **not** cause this fall; it was a generalised
  panic on the Paris bourse. But they did nothing to check it — and
  crucially, they had **no reason to**
- **Nat**, August 2: "Thank God the house has scarcely any [rentes]" —
  they had already cleared out of French government bonds entirely
- **Guizot** (French ambassador in London) failed to realise this;
  he thought James was genuinely fretting about his holdings
- Heine theatrically reports James's "toothache" and "colic" as the
  rente fell — in fact James was play-acting for Heine's readers
  while privately musing "I could make a fortune"
- The financial logic: if Thiers wanted to finance military
  preparations he needed to borrow, but with rentes collapsing he
  could not borrow. Ferguson: "This was the way in which not only the
  Rothschilds but the financial markets as a whole exerted leverage
  over a government they disapproved of"

### James's Reply to the *Constitutionnel* Attack

- Pro-Thiers *Constitutionnel* attacks James as "agent of Metternich"
  and "King of Finance" with no right to meddle in French affairs

> "I have never at any time encouraged opposition to the Government,
> for the simple reason that I have never wished to play a political
> role. I am, as you state, a financier. If I desire peace, I desire
> it honourably, not only for France, but for the whole of Europe.
> *Financiers have the opportunity of rendering services to the country
> under any circumstances, and I think that in this respect I have
> never been slow to respond.*" — **James de Rothschild**

- The menace was unmistakable: this time James's services would not
  be forthcoming

### Fall of Thiers & Aftermath

- **October 20, 1840**: Thiers ("the little blackguard") resigns
- New government formed by **Soult and Guizot** — Nat: "the bourse
  has the greatest confidence"
- After Thiers' fall, Heine reports (March 1841) James "now quite
  restored and looks sound and well"

---

## "Walls of Jericho": Rearmament Loans 1841–1847

### Armed Peace as Business Opportunity

- Eastern Crisis demonstrates a paradox: tension could be *profitable*
  for Rothschilds — provided it did not escalate to outright war
- In the 1830s complete peace had dried up new sovereign loan business;
  from 1840, rearmament generated new demand without causing war
- Thiers' legacy — costly new fortifications around Paris — obliges
  the Soult government to issue a major new loan in **1841**

### The 150 Million Franc Loan (1841)

- Rothschilds disliked the fortifications project (it threatened to
  reduce the value of **Salomon's villa at Suresnes**, near the planned
  defences), yet they did not hesitate to meet government needs
- Finance Minister **Théodore Humann** (a former banker; James privately
  calls him "a rogue" and "a blackguard") — negotiations marked by
  extreme brinkmanship
- James refuses to cut short a visit to Salomon in Vienna when
  summoned; repeatedly threatens to walk away — "We want—indeed
  have—to make the loan" (privately), but drives a hard bargain
- **150 million franc loan** issued October 1841 on James's terms —
  "normal service" resumed with French Treasury
- Further loans in **1842 and 1844** (200 million francs each);
  competitors Hottinguer, Baring, and Laffitte can't dislodge
  Rothschild dominance

### Austrian Rearmament Too

- **Anselm**: "As long as France continues arming, Germany must follow"
- **1841**: new Austrian government loan of 38.5 million gulden (shared
  with Sina and Arnstein & Eskeles), first in seven uneventful years
- Further 40 million gulden Austrian loan two years later
- Conclusion: "Once the Rothschilds had regarded peace as the *sine
  qua non* of financial stability; but an armed peace was more profitable"

### James's Power Over the July Monarchy (1840–1847)

- **Countess Nesselrode** thinks James "viceroy and even King" — he
  told her he knew all the French ministers, saw them daily, and
  complained directly to the King if policies were "contrary to the
  interests of the government"
- Key leverage: the King knew James had "beaucoup à perdre" (much to
  lose) and so "il a toute confiance en moi, m'écoute et tient compte
  de tout ce que je lui dis" — ("has complete confidence in me, listens
  and takes account of everything I say")
- Rothschild financial support for Guizot effectively **conditional on
  avoiding outright conflict with Britain** and devoting loan proceeds
  to railways rather than fortifications

### The Spanish Marriages Crisis (1846–7)

- **Louis-Philippe's** plan to marry his son (Duc de Montpensier) to
  the Queen of Spain's sister threatens to give France a claim to the
  Spanish throne — Palmerston treats it as potential *casus belli*
- James shuttles back and forth trying to engineer an Anglo-Spanish
  trade treaty as compensation; Guizot stands his ground
- October 1846: James in "deep gloom," expecting French and Austrian
  troops in Spain; Guizot tells James "very angrily" to keep his
  opinions to himself
- James: "Never before have I seen the Government so strong and
  stubborn. I think that even if this were to lead to an outbreak of
  war, God forbid, they would still not change their stand"
- Family tensions: **Alphonse** and **Anselm** resent Palmerston's
  aggression; Anselm advises James "not to mix personally in the
  evolution of great historical events"
- Crisis resolved peacefully by February 1847 — but Palmerston
  immediately raises Greek arrears on British bonds, starting another
  Anglo-French war of words

### Chapter End: Limits of Financial Power

- The Rothschilds' growing list of sovereign clients gave them genuine
  diplomatic leverage; Belgium and Syria crises seemed to prove that
  "war could be averted by discreet manipulation of the European
  states' purse-strings"
- But Ferguson warns: **financial power was not absolute** — it
  depended on the *internal stability* of European states
- 1840s deficits were symptoms of political malaise, not just
  military spending — railway subsidies and declining tax revenues
  equally important
- "It was not a war which brought the defensive walls of the July
  Monarchy tumbling down but a revolution; and against that threat
  the fortifications round Paris offered no protection"

---

## Chapter 15: "Satan Harnessed": Playing at Railways (1830–1846)

### Railways as Symbol of Creative Destruction

- **1836**: Rossini travels by train Paris→Frankfurt (Belgian lines);
  loathes it, composes satirical piano piece *"Un petit train de
  plaisir"* — a railway journey ending in derailment, two deaths,
  and heirs celebrating
- Epigraph from **Joseph von Eichendorff's** play *Das Incognito*:
  "They've got the Devil into reins!" — on-stage railway disaster used
  to symbolise capitalism's anarchic energy
- **Friedrich List** (nationalist economist): railway is "a tonic for
  the national spirit" and "a tight belt around the loins of the
  German nation" — key to "internal unification" of Germany alongside
  the Prussian customs union (1834)
- **Metternich** regarded railways with deep unease: the "transformation
  in political and social conditions" they produced threatened the
  Central European status quo
- Both left and right saw the railway accident as "the perfect symbol
  of that crisis of capitalism"

### Nathan's Absence from British Railway Mania

- Counterintuitively, **Nathan Rothschild** took virtually no part
  in industrial finance once established as a London banker
- Exception: abortive North Wales mining venture in 1825 (lost money
  when mining companies collapsed)
- Nathan took no part in the **Liverpool–Manchester Railway** (opened
  1830) or the subsequent British railway mania
- When **James** visited northern England in 1843: "What is happening
  here with the railways is quite amazing and had I come here earlier
  we would most certainly have built this railway. It must yield enormous
  sums. Never have I seen so many people as [are travelling] between
  Liverpool and Manchester."
- Nathan's principle, told to **Thomas Fowell Buxton's** son Edward:

> "If I were to listen to all the projects proposed to me, I should
> ruin myself very soon. Stick to one business, young man. Stick to
> your brewery, and you may be the great brewer of London. Be a brewer,
> and a banker, and a merchant, and a manufacturer, and you will soon
> be in the Gazette." — **Nathan Rothschild**

- **Hannah** (Nathan's wife) was the sole railway enthusiast among
  the English Rothschilds — writes letters to Lionel and Charlotte
  evangelising railway travel's advantages; **Nat** in 1848 declines
  to meet Lionel at Calais because "railway travelling makes my head
  ache so terribly"
- Ferguson's verdict: Nathan's abstention reflects City of London norms
  — established merchant bankers preferred to concentrate on government
  and commercial finance; the move to industrial finance was exceptional,
  not obvious
- Disraeli (writing decades later) claimed Nathan had anticipated the
  bust that ended the first railway boom — but this is probably
  retrospective myth-making

<!-- pp. 581-600 -->

## Chapter: Railways and Industrial Finance (1830s–1845)

### The Rothschilds and Railways: A Reluctant Entry

- London's major banks (with the exception of Glyn's) were
  disinclined to finance British railways — the commercial/overseas
  orientation made them uninterested; also, railway companies could
  sell shares directly to the public without banking intermediation
- **Lionel** monitored British railway development as Austrian consul,
  but the brothers' primary interest was in *exporting* innovations
  *after* they'd been proven in Britain — not pioneering them
- In Britain, industry turned to provincial joint-stock banks
  (proliferating in the 1830s–40s), not City banks like the
  Rothschilds
- In France, the **haute banque** was less wary of industrial
  investment; repeated efforts from the 1820s to create new financial
  institutions for infrastructure (e.g. **Laffitte**'s 1825 Société
  Commanditaire de l'Industrie) foundered due to government opposition
  — especially from the **Banque de France**, which was deeply
  suspicious of joint-stock banks
- **James** shared this suspicion; he was sceptical of Laffitte's
  revived 1837 caisse proposal (250 million francs) and equally
  skeptical when the **Pereires** attempted a similar challenge in the
  1850s
- No sign before 1835 that James would be any more expansionist than
  Nathan in railway finance

### The Policy Shift: Mercury Mines to Railways

- The **Almadén mercury mines** deal (acquired as collateral for
  Spanish loans) marked a subtle shift: the Rothschilds were
  acquiring monopoly rights over *sale* of commodities, not managing
  production directly
- Success of Almadén encouraged **Salomon** to seek similar
  arrangements with other governments — e.g. a monopoly over mercury
  mines in Austrian-controlled Istria and Dalmatia
- Also moved into silver/gold refining and coin minting (formalised
  in France in the 1840s, England in the 1850s)

### Railways as Surrogate State Bonds

- Key insight: the Rothschilds viewed **railway shares as surrogate
  state bonds** at a time (mid-1830s) when European governments were
  issuing fewer new bonds
- On the Continent (unlike Britain), governments often became directly
  involved in railway construction — Belgium and some South German
  states even financed railways via state bonds, making Rothschild
  underwriting techniques directly applicable
- But railway investment was fundamentally different from bond
  investment:
  - Bonds: predictable, steady interest stream from states
  - Railway shares: unspecified future dividends, dependent on traffic
    projections (largely guesswork)
  - Revenue projections almost always exceeded actual traffic
  - Bankers who sold railway shares could NOT remain indifferent to
    the companies' long-term management — dragged into operational
    oversight just as they were dragged into state politics
- Short-term attractions (underwriting profits, share issue gains)
  inevitably led to **longer-term commitments**
- Railway involvement made the Rothschilds publicly conspicuous in a
  new, more dangerous way — ordinary people experienced railway
  companies directly (especially accidents), making Rothschild
  exploitation more visible than their role as state creditors
- First time the family's **Judaism was reframed racially** — not as
  religious identity but as supposed explanation for capitalist
  exploitation — emerged in the context of early railway criticism

---

### Salomon's Line: The Nordbahn

- First Rothschild railway conceived and built in **Habsburg
  territory** — paradoxical given Salomon's conservative temperament
  and his role as quasi-"court Jew" to **Metternich**
- Salomon personally disliked railway travel (still refused the
  Belgian rail link as late as 1846)
- Idea originated with **Franz Xavier Riepel**, professor at the
  Vienna Polytechnic Institute — proposed linking salt mines of
  Wieliczka (Galicia) and iron/coal mines of Moravian Ostrau to
  Vienna, over 200 miles, plus extension south to Trieste
- Salomon dispatched Riepel (with **Leopold von Wertheimstein**) to
  England to study railway building firsthand
- Initial petition to the Emperor shelved; Crown Prince quipped:
  "Even the coach to Kagran isn't always full" — classic Habsburg
  bureaucratic inertia
- Salomon took over an existing horse-drawn railway (Danube to
  Gmündensee) from an insolvent French engineer named **Zola**
  (the novelist's father)
- In April 1835 — six weeks after Emperor Franz's death — Salomon
  successfully petitioned new government; success owed more to
  **Metternich** and **Kolowrat** backing than to Salomon's
  arguments about public benefit
- Named the line the **"Kaiser-Ferdinands-Nordbahn"** — flattering
  royal vanity to neutralise political opposition; enlisted
  **Metternich**, **Kolowrat**, and Treasury head **Count
  Mittrowsky** as board members (nobles lending respectability in
  exchange for financial perks — standard English practice, essential
  in Austria)

### Nordbahn: Financial Reality

- Projected cost: 12 million gulden (£1 million); actual cost
  ~27,750 gulden per mile vs. projected 16,600 — massive overrun
- Projected construction: 10 years; final stretch to Bochnia not
  completed until **1858**
- Share issue was a spectacular short-term success: of 12,000 shares
  (1,000 gulden each), Salomon retained 8,000; 4,000 offered to
  public attracted **27,490 applications** — huge oversubscription
- Competing banker **Sina** immediately sought the Vienna-Trieste
  concession; at the Nordbahn's second general meeting, **Ludwig von
  Pereira** (Arnstein & Eskeles) launched a technical and financial
  critique that alarmed the Emperor
- Boardroom battle climax October 1836: Salomon moved a resolution to
  commence building or liquidate — won 76 of 83 votes, forced Sina
  and Eskeles to resign
- Early years were a financial drain: for over two years
  (pre-passenger service), the company poured money into materials
  and 14,000 workers for zero return; kept afloat by a Rothschild
  advance of **8 million gulden**; shares fell below par
- Turning point from 1841: Salomon's manager **Goldschmidt** detected
  improving traffic; unexpectedly high passenger volumes (especially
  Sunday day-trippers) boosted receipts — up to **10,000 people per
  day** on the Vienna-Neustadt stretch by 1841
- Shares rose above par to 103 in 1843, reached 129 in 1844,
  **228 by 1845** — enormous belated capital gain for original
  investors, especially Salomon himself

> "The Nordbahn had required the expenditure of large sums of money,
> and . . . patient waiting; sacrifices that I was called upon to
> make, to the amount of several hundred thousand." — Salomon

### Salomon's Entrepreneurial Vision

- Salomon was not merely a speculator — he genuinely envisaged an
  **integrated Austrian transport system**: Galicia/Moravia to Vienna,
  then south to Trieste and north into Hungary
- His June 1844 trip to Pressburg for the **Central Hungarian Railway
  Company** meeting was treated as a near-royal visit — Danube
  steamer made an unscheduled stop, hotel guests evicted, competing
  **Istvàn Széchényi** tried to challenge his board control
- Local Jewish community gathered on the riverbank to greet him;
  Count **Esterházy** blocked them from firing 40 celebratory rockets
  to avoid a "breach of the peace" due to anti-Jewish tensions

### Vertical Integration Strategy

- Salomon pursued **vertical integration** alongside railways:
  - Needed Austrian iron/steel supply independent of British imports
  - First bid for **Witkowitz Ironworks** (Ostravian coalfields)
    blocked because Jews were prohibited from owning land
  - Leased it indirectly via Archbishop of Olmütz, **Count Chotek**,
    in 1841 in partnership with banker **Geymüller**; bought outright
    after Geymüller went bankrupt
  - Witkowitz was the **first Habsburg works to use the puddling
    process** for rail production; remained a core Austrian Rothschild
    industrial asset for nearly a century
- Also co-founded the **Austrian Steamship Company (Austrian Lloyd)**
  in 1835; bailed it out in the 1830s with a 500,000 gulden loan
  secured by mortgage on seven steamers; profits grew from ~82,000
  to ~370,000 gulden between 1841 and 1847
- Salt factory investment in Venice was part of the same Adriatic
  expansion strategy
- Risk: loosely connected business empires are especially vulnerable
  to deteriorating economic conditions — and a deterioration was
  approaching

---

### Frankfurt: The Taunusbahn

- Frankfurt house played a **modest role** in railways before 1848 —
  partly temperament, mainly political environment
- Southern Germany's fragmented states meant even short railway lines
  crossed multiple jurisdictions — the Frankfurt–Mainz line (under
  20 miles) spanned three separate states; took **17 months** just to
  secure land purchase legislation in Hesse-Kassel
- Bavaria, Baden, Württemberg, and Hanover built railways on the
  Belgian model (state-funded) — Rothschilds could only underwrite
  bonds, not lead projects
- The **Taunusbahn** (Frankfurt–Mainz) concession secured in 1838
  required **Amschel** and **Bethmann** to buy out a rival company
  authorized along a parallel route — costly and politically messy
- **Anselm** in 1838: "here in Germany, railways get off the ground
  only with a great deal of effort"
- Result: it was the **Oppenheims** and **Bethmanns** who led private
  railway building in southwest Germany; Rothschilds participated as
  sleeping partners only
  - Oppenheim led Rhineland consortium at ~25% of 3 million thaler
    capital; Rothschilds (Paris + Frankfurt combined) held only
    a fortieth
  - Bethmanns led the £200,000 Taunusbahn consortium
- By the mid-1840s the Frankfurt house confined itself to floating
  **state bonds earmarked for railways** (e.g. Hesse-Kassel 1845)
  and declined private schemes like the Leipzig-Frankfurt line
- Limited involvement in Italy too — James politely rebuffed a
  Florence-Leghorn proposal: "We have enough railways of our own [in
  France] without embarking on those of Italy as well"

---

### Paris: James and the Pereires — "The Chief Rabbi of the Rive Droite"

- **Heinrich Heine** mockingly called James the *fons et origo* of
  the French railway network — in reality, it was the **Pereires**
  who "discovered" Rothschild by persuading James to commit his
  financial resources
- **Emile** and **Isaac Pereire**: Sephardic Jews from Bordeaux
  (grandfather fled Spain), disciples of **comte Henri de
  Saint-Simon** — utopian prophet of a technocratic, corporatist
  industrial society where "productive" classes rule under a "new
  Christianity"
- An unlikely partnership: the Pereires' friend **Prosper Enfantin**
  hesitated to associate with "the damned soul of a Rothschild"
- Emile was pragmatic enough to recognize the indispensability of
  Rothschild capital — their pilot project (Paris to Saint-Germain)
  would cost over 100 times what the brothers could muster themselves
  (they had only 30,000 francs)

> "The involvement of the Rothschild bank in the railway from Paris
> to Saint-Germain is not only of great importance for this particular
> venture; it will necessarily have a determining influence on the
> later realisation of all the great industrial undertakings."
> — Emile Pereire, May 1835

- Political backing secured from **Emile Legrand** (Director-General
  of Ponts et Chaussées) and the skeptical **Thiers** (who dismissed
  railways as a "toy")
- Initial capital consortium: **d'Eichthal**, **Thurneyssen**,
  **Davillier**, James — d'Eichthal held 23.5% of the 5 million franc
  capital, same as James
- Saint-Germain line: cost 11 million francs vs. projected 3.9
  million; traffic fluctuated wildly (surge on summer Sundays,
  collapse on winter weekdays); nonetheless completed **ahead of
  schedule** in August 1837; Pereires reduced running costs from 52%
  to 44% of gross receipts in three years

> "I would recommend that we don't sell any St-Germain shares for the
> time being, because I believe that there will be a substantial rise
> in these . . . I am absolutely convinced that people in France
> simply have no idea how easy it is to travel by such means . . . I
> am certain that in twenty years' time there won't be a single
> Postmaster left in the world, and people will only travel by train
> . . . I am in love with the railway." — James to nephew Anthony,
> June 1836

### The Rive Droite and Rival Competition

- Pereires' ambition: concentrate all Paris rail traffic through
  Saint-Germain and the **Gare Saint-Lazare** terminus
- The **Rive Droite** (Paris–Versailles via the right bank) was the
  next phase; de Rothschild Frères was the largest shareholder with
  just under a third of the 11 million franc capital
- The **Fould brothers** secured a rival concession for a parallel
  line to Versailles along the *left* bank after "a campaign of
  intrigues" in the Chamber of Deputies
- Heine mocked the absurd rivalry between "the Chief Rabbi of the
  Rive Droite, Baron Rothschild" and the "Chief Rabbi of the Rive
  Gauche":

> "For the French Jews, as for the French as a whole, gold is the god
> of our times and industry the prevailing religion . . . it is
> possible to divide the Jews of this country into two sects: the
> sect of the Right Bank and the sect of the Left Bank . . . run by
> two famous rabbis of finance, who rub each other up the wrong way
> as much as Rabbi Shammai and Rabbi Hillel in the ancient city of
> Babylon." — Heinrich Heine

- Two parallel lines to Versailles were economically irrational —
  insufficient traffic for both; actual returns meagre; shares
  burdened by cost overruns
- James warned grimly in September 1837: "One of these days it will
  start to stink . . . because too many shares are arriving on the
  scene"
- 1838 market slump forced merger discussions; Rothschild company
  effectively absorbed the Fould company; both eventually absorbed
  into the **Ouest line in 1851**

### The Nord Concession: Railway Finance as Political Leverage

- James used his near-monopoly on **rentes issues** as explicit
  leverage to win the Northern (Nord) railway concession
- In December 1842: "If we get the loan then we are masters over the
  railways. The Finance Minister said to me today, 'I won't do
  anything without you and the whole Ministry shares my views. The
  railway from Belgium will be offered to you in preference to anyone
  else.'"
- James threatened the French government openly: if the Rive Droite
  was not supported, "I will see to it that it is attacked in all the
  newspapers"; threatened to publicly resign and withdraw from all
  industrial business — "If you can't gain someone's friendship then
  you have to make them fear you"
- **Legrand's Law of 1842**: the state would purchase rights of way
  and construct buildings, leasing lines to railway companies who
  provided rolling stock — the framework James had long sought
- Nord concession finally awarded **September 1845**: Paris and London
  Rothschild houses held **25.7%** of the 200 million franc capital;
  Hottinguer 20.15%, Laffitte-Blount 19.5%
- Compromises: Pereires' preferred terminus (Gare Saint-Lazare)
  jettisoned; rivals (Laffitte-Blount, Hottinguer) given substantial
  stakes — but all as junior partners
- **Laffitte** had hoped to lead a single grand loan to build the
  entire Legrand network; instead became a sleeping partner —
  "effectively admitting defeat yet again"

### The French Railway Network: Carve-Up in Progress

- James saw the various railway lines as interconnected: "the various
  railways have to be viewed as cousins of each other and when [the
  share price of] one rises the others will then follow"
- Rothschilds took stakes across the network:
  - **Nord** (Paris–Belgium/England): largest and most important
  - **Paris-Strasbourg**: substantial shareholding
  - **Grand-Combe** (coal mines near Alès to Marseille): supported
    **Paulin Talabot** with 6 million francs in 1839
  - **Paris-Lyon**: modest stake contemplated
  - **Lyon-Avignon**: small stake
  - Bordeaux line: backed a consortium; lost concession but sought
    partnership in the Bordeaux–Cette connection
- By November 1845 railway **merger mania** was in full swing:
  Anselm described the Rothschild office as chaotic with people
  seeking "fusions" of Creil & St Quentin with Lyons lines
- Saint-Simonians like **Enfantin** encouraged railway consolidation
  into concentrated ownership; the bankers needed little persuading —
  as early as 1844 Hottinguer, Blanc, and d'Eichthal were proposing
  to James that they collectively acquire "the whole line of railroads
  from Calais to Avignon . . . to avoid competition"

<!-- pp. 601-620 -->

## Chapter 15 (continued): The Railway King — Railways, Public Opinion & Anti-Semitism

### The English Connection: London Nephews' Ambivalence

- **James de Rothschild** delegated much railway detail work to London nephews,
  especially **Anthony**, who became more expert than his uncle
- But the London brothers never lost their deep suspicion of industrial finance
- **Anthony** (May 1838): "There is nothing new here—but Railroad Companies...
  there are so many that one gets quite sick of them"
- **Nat** was openly hostile to the Nord project, resenting pressure from
  **Pereire & Eichthal** to go "largely into the railroad to Chartres"

> "The stinking railroads engross all our attention & for my part I wish his
> Majesty had them all, they only give us trouble & bother & no remuneration."
> — Nat Rothschild, spring 1842

- Nat's core objection: **operating** railways (vs. speculating in shares)
  locked up capital in an illiquid, potentially dangerous way
- Feared that if a financial crisis occurred, all the shares would be worthless

> "I am against the [Belgian railway] affair because I am afraid of the anxiety,
> bother & trouble which it will surely occasion us—the moral responsibility of
> it will rest entirely on us, & I wd sooner leave to others the profit."
> — Nat Rothschild

- **Anselm** in Frankfurt also opposed heavy railway involvement —
  suggesting this was partly generational, partly a matter of milieu
- Nat spoke for the younger Rothschilds: "the conservative feeling has the
  ascendant over the acquiring sentiment—with me at least"
- **James**, by contrast, could not resist "le grand rôle" — driven by
  competitive fear of losing business to rivals like Pereire
- Nat's portrait of James's psychology: "in a sort of fever about it, he thinks
  it a good business, & is afraid of it, he fancies the rival company will get it
  & then regrets it doubly"

### The London Market as Essential Backstop

- James recognized the Nord project **depended on London capital** — French
  market alone could not fund it
- Nat urged involving **Glyn's** (the one City house serious about railways)
  and engineer **George Stephenson**
- By 1843 Nat's opposition softened as English interest grew; he believed
  shares would "go like hot rolls" on the London market
- **Mayer** reported from London: English investors determined to enter every
  railway or loan regardless of scale, given fortunes being made by share jobbers
- Anthony (Sept. 1845): "Try my dear Rabbi to show that the English people can
  take off as many shares as the stinking French frogs"
- **James's entrepreneurial vision + London market's capital** = recipe for
  success: Nord shares soared from 500 to 760 francs

### Vertical Integration: Coal Mines

- As Nord prospered (daily takings exceeded 20,000 francs on opening,
  despite being incomplete and short of engine-drivers), James followed
  **brother Salomon's example** by pursuing **vertical integration**
- Paris house invested **3 million francs** in Belgian coal mines (with
  **Talabot brothers**), reasoning coal demand would grow with every new
  railway on the continent
- The Nord could obtain coal at competitive cost; Belgian coal transport
  became a staple revenue source for the line

### Strategic Divergence: Paris vs. London Houses

- London house chose **not** to build a long-term industrial portfolio —
  safer in the short run, reduced exposure when railway shares slumped in 1847–8
- But **in the long run**, the Paris house alone captured the immense capital
  gains from industry in the second half of the nineteenth century
- This divergence was a **profoundly important** strategic fork in the family

---

### The Impact of Rail: Macro Statistics

- Between 1828–1848: ~1,250 miles of track built in France;
  investment peaks in 1841, 1843, and 1846–7
- Initially financed by ~500 *sociétés en commandite* (1826–1838),
  nominal capital 520 million francs; in 1845 alone, 28 companies set up
  with nearly as much capital
- **Rothschild dominance**: their name appeared in only 4 of 32 concessions
  granted 1835–1846, but of 225 million francs contributed by French banks
  to railway capital formation, the Rothschilds accounted for
  **84.6 million — 38% of the total**, nearly a tenth of all capital subscribed
- Key structural advantage: **direct familial link to London market**
  — roughly half of all capital invested in French railways by 1847 was British;
  only a quarter of French locomotives were domestically produced
- State subsidies (from new Ministry of Public Works, 1840–1849):
  ~7.2 million francs annually — a fifth to a quarter of annual gross investment

---

### Cultural Responses: Poetry, Jokes & Propaganda

#### The Railway as Wonder of the Age

- A poetaster named **Hugelmann** composed "To Rothschild" to mark the Nord
  inauguration (June 14, 1846) — cast James as genius taming a dragon
  (the locomotive), binding it to serve mankind
- **Heinrich Heine** was moved to write in a similar vein when James announced
  the Nord bid: "The House of Rothschild... now places itself at the head of
  great national undertakings, devoting its enormous capital and its immeasurable
  credit to the advancement of industry and the prosperity of the people"
- When the Orléans and Rouen lines opened (May 1843), Heine described the
  railway as a world-historical event on par with the discovery of America,
  gunpowder, and the printing press

> "Our entire existence is being ripped up and hurled on to new tracks; that new
> relationships, pleasures and torments await us... The railways are another such
> providential event."
> — Heinrich Heine

#### Heine's Ambivalence: The "Ruling Aristocracy of Money"

- Even as he celebrated the railways, Heine warned they were concentrating
  power in the hands of a **"ruling aristocracy of money"** exercising
  "more and more control every day over the rudder of state"
- Aristocratic and military elites — even admirals — begged James for share
  options; Heine observed that shares issued above par meant every allocation
  was effectively a **"present of money"** from Rothschild to the recipient

#### Railway Jokes

- **Prosper Mérimée** (Feb. 1846) recounted a joke playing on French *action*
  (share): Rothschild's rabbi asks his seven-year-old son the difference between
  a good and bad action — "A good action is an action of the Nord, a bad action
  is an action of the Rive Gauche"
- **Count Nesselrode** relayed the archetypal "mot de Rothschild": to Count
  Tassilo Festeticz — "If you want your capital without interest, buy land.
  If you want your interest without capital, buy shares"
- Betty's four-year-old son **Edmond** took to praying "for Papa and for the
  *chemin de fer du Nord*"

---

### Anti-Semitic Backlash: Toussenel, Dairnvaell & the Pamphlet War

#### Alphonse Toussenel's *The Jews, Kings of the Epoch*

- Growing journalist hostility in the 1840s to what critics called a
  **"dangerous and corrupting private monopoly"**
- **Alphonse Toussenel** argued the government effectively ceded all Nord
  profits to Rothschild's company for 40 years while retaining all expenses
  ("for the nation"):
  - State pays ~100 million francs for land
  - Company advances ~60 million francs for rails/rolling stock
    (to be reimbursed at concession expiry)
  - Company receives ~14 million francs annual income from the line
  - State borrowing the money itself would have cost only 2.4 million francs/year
- Toussenel's socialist critique: profits came from "labour of the French
  worker and artisan" — the people bore the costs, financiers took the gains
- But his economic argument was **inextricably linked to visceral anti-Semitism**:
  denounced "traitors, hacks, deputies, ministers who would sell France to the Jews"
- In 1840s, "Jew" became synonymous in this discourse with **"exploitative capitalist"**
- Toussenel portrayed all railway companies as satellites of a single
  cosmopolitan, Jewish *haute banque* — "Baron Rothschild, the King of Finance,
  a Jew ennobled by a very Christian King"

#### Georges Dairnvaell (*writing as "Satan"*)

- Within a year of Toussenel, Dairnvaell published *The Edifying and Curious
  History of Rothschild I, King of the Jews*
- Alleged the Rothschilds secured the Nord contract corruptly — distributing
  **15,000 shares to deputies** — then defrauded shareholders via unauthorised
  share issues
- James as "Rothschild I... the speculator-monarch... a capitalist who enriches
  himself incessantly while the fathers of children lose all but their last
  crust of bread"
- These charges were recycled by later anti-Semitic journalists through the
  1880s–1890s (**Chirac**, **Drumont**, **Scherb**) and even after 1945

#### The Pamphlet War (1846)

- Dairnvaell's charges unleashed at least **seven separate publications**
- Pro-Rothschild: *First Official Response of M. Baron James Rothschild*
  (claimed Dairnvaell had blackmailed James for 5,000 francs not to publish)
- Anti-Rothschild: *War on the Swindlers* (Dairnvaell); *Rothschild I, his
  Valets and his People*; *Ten Days in the Reign of Rothschild I, King of the Jews*
- The most sophisticated anonymous work (*Judgement Passed against Rothschild
  and Georges Dairnvaell*) rejected culpability for Fampoux but argued the
  "proletarian" had been right to attack the "millionaire" — equating Judaism
  with capitalism outright
- **This fusion of anti-Semitism and socialism** would prove the most dangerous
  long-term threat to the Rothschilds' position

---

### An Accident Happens: Fampoux, July 8, 1846

- June 14, 1846: James invited **1,700 guests** to celebrate the Nord
  inauguration — party lunched at Lille, dined at Brussels, returned to Paris.
  Cantata by **Berlioz** and **Jules Janin**; press invitations to
  **Victor Hugo, Alexandre Dumas, Prosper Mérimée, Théophile Gautier**
- Dairnvaell: the day "when the royalty of Rothschild I was officially
  recognised" — James proclaimed "King of Europe, Asia, Africa, America,
  Oceania and other places, and above all, King of the Jews"
- **July 8, 1846** (3 p.m.): Train derailed at **Fampoux** when a rail gave
  way on an embankment beside a marshy lake. Second locomotive halted
  suddenly, snapping chains; 13 carriages derailed, one crushed, three sank
  in lake. **Between 14 and 39 people died**

#### The Rothschilds' Response

- Anthony (first bulletin): "Poor people... a thousand pities—as it will
  certainly do no good for the moment—it has certainly put me out a great deal"
- True concern revealed in the same letter: revenues were 27,000 francs/day;
  shares fell to 712; primary preoccupation was **limiting share-price damage**
- Salomon's reaction: "a stroke of luck no person of high rank was grieved
  by the disaster, as the alarm about it would have been even stronger"
- Anthony (to Lionel): the accident "was a great misfortune—The shares would
  certainly have been 800 fr[ancs]... the receipts will very soon get up again"
- The Rothschilds' **primary concern throughout was the share price**, not the
  human toll — a callousness traceable to earlier accidents on the Saint-Germain
  line in the 1830s, where James blamed the press for falls in share prices

#### Conspiracy Theory and Recovery

- With shares falling toward 650 and receipts down 40%, Anthony floated the
  theory the accident was "done intentionally" — tampering with rail clamps —
  to allow short sellers to profit
- Recovery: traffic rebuilt from third-class passengers upward; by end of August
  first freight trains ran; Nord timetable published in **Bradshaw** for the
  first time; gross profits estimated at **3.2 million francs**
- **Mayer** with "heroic insouciance": "on the Austrian line a dreadful accident
  occurred the very first day and now the shares are at 100 per cent premium
  which I am positive the French Northern will be"

#### Long-Term Significance

- Ferguson's verdict: the Rothschilds' "stark economic rationality" in
  responding to Fampoux — prioritising the share price over the victims —
  made the revolutionary storm of 1848 a kind of **"terrible nemesis"**
- The railways gave the Rothschilds unprecedented public prominence and made
  them obvious targets for the social revolution already in preparation
- Contemporaries saw the Vienna and Paris Rothschilds' railway ventures in
  **Faustian terms**: they had "harnessed Satan" — and now Satan (Dairnvaell)
  had turned on Faust

---

## Chapter 16 (cont.): "The Worst Revolution That Ever Happened" — Road to 1848

### 1830 vs. 1848: The Rothschilds as Targets

- In 1830 **James** had been sufficiently distanced from **Charles X** to switch
  easily to the Orléanist side; by 1848 the family was far more deeply
  identified with the established regimes across all of Europe
- As bankers to the **Austrian imperial government** and numerous smaller
  German and Italian states, they appeared to nationalist revolutionaries
  as paymasters — if not masters — of the **Metternichian system**
- **Eduard Kretschmer**'s 1848 cartoon *Apotheosis and Adoration of the Idol
  of our Time* depicts "Rothschild" on a throne of money surrounded by
  kneeling potentates — canonical image of the period
- Poet **Karl Beck** (1846) lamented Rothschild's refusal to use financial
  power on the side of the "peoples" rather than their detested princes
- 1848 revolution was also *social*, not just constitutional — **socialist**
  (and ultra-conservative) arguments against economic liberalism voiced
  alongside older arguments for political liberalism
- The Rothschilds had come to personify material inequality of the early
  industrial era; the Nord railway accident crystallized this: "Rothschild I"
  callously counted state-subsidized profits while third-class passengers died

### Anti-Rothschild Sentiment: Socialists and Nationalists

- **Alexander Herzen** (1847) defined the bourgeoisie as "a solid estate,
  the limits of which are the electoral property qualification below and
  Baron Rothschild above" — liberalism propagating a "malicious irony"
- Critics of Rothschilds as capitalists routinely conflated their wealth
  with their **Judaism** — Karl Beck's "interest-calculating brethren,
  filling the insatiable money-bag for themselves and their kin alone!"
- **Karl Marx**, "On the Jewish Question" (February 1844):

> "What is the secular basis of Judaism? *Practical* need, *self-interest*.
> What is the worldly religion of the Jew? *Huckstering*. What is his worldly
> God? *Money* . . . We recognise in Judaism, therefore, a general *anti-social*
> element of the *present time* . . . the *emancipation of the Jews* is the
> emancipation of mankind from *Judaism*."

- Marx quoted **Bruno Bauer**: "The Jew, who in Vienna, for example, is only
  tolerated, determines the fate of the whole Empire by his financial power.
  The Jew . . . decides the fate of Europe."
- Marx argued "money has become a world power and the practical Jewish spirit
  has become the practical spirit of the Christian nations"
- Ferguson notes the socialist argument could stand without racial prejudice
  (Marx himself was Jewish); it would be **Richard Wagner** and others who
  later developed the explicitly racial version
- **Wilhelm Marr** (1843 letter to his father): "The time is ripe to share
  Rothschild's property among 3,333,333.3 poor weavers" — roots of his later
  **Anti-Semitic League** lie here in the 1840s

### Heine's Satirical Counter

- **Heinrich Heine** (politically close to Marx in 1848, but later mocking):

> "The main army of Rothschild's enemies is made up of have-nots; they all
> think: 'What we don't have, Rothschild has.' They are joined by the main
> force of those who have lost their fortune; instead of ascribing their loss
> to their own stupidity, they blame the wiles of those who managed to hold
> on to what they had. As soon as a man runs out of money, he becomes
> Rothschild's enemy."

- Heine's Jewish story adapted as James's imagined reply to communism:
  "The communist wants Rothschild to share his 300 million francs. Rothschild
  sends his share: exactly 9 sous. 'Now leave me alone!'"

### Charitable Counter-Measures

- Rothschilds fully aware of mounting animosity — took "ostentatious"
  charitable steps to counteract it
- **Salomon** (Vienna): 25,000 gulden for Danube aqueduct (1835); 40,000
  gulden to found scientific institute in Brünn; major donations after Hamburg
  fire (1842) and Pesth/Ofen floods
- Strategy shift: pre-1830s charity confined to Jewish communities of
  Frankfurt, London, Paris; now Salomon targeted causes valued by the
  **Habsburg elite**
- At dinner for **Count Kolowrat** (1838), Salomon offered pleasure of his
  company as equal to 1,000 gulden; Count immediately asked for the money
  for a poor man — Salomon obliged
- Salomon portrayed in 1850s sentimental novella as a Viennese Santa Claus,
  but **Hermann Goldschmidt** (Moritz's son) remembered him as "a brutal
  egoist, a man without wisdom or education" who ate to excess, was habitually
  rude, had a lecherous passion for "very young girls," and in 1847 — depths
  of slump — spent immense sums building a new Renngasse residence
- **Amschel** (Frankfurt, May 1847): distributed bread ration cards during
  acute food shortages — received unanimous Senate thanks but little popular
  goodwill; nephew **Anselm** warned against corn-dealing visibility:
  "there were a great many riots all & everywhere against corn dealers"

### The Irish Famine and Lionel's Relief Effort

- Irish famine: ~775,000 deaths, 2 million emigrated — worst calamity of the 1840s
- **Lionel** took the lead establishing the **British Association for the
  Relief of the Extreme Distress in the Remote Parishes of Ireland and
  Scotland** at New Court — raised £470,000; even solicited from
  "ardent Hibernophobe and Protectionist" **Disraeli**
- Rothschilds contributed £1,000 — second largest after Queen's £2,000,
  on par with the Duke of Devonshire's
- Lionel personally involved in "regulat[ing] the purchase and shipment of
  provisions to Ireland and the formation of depôts around the coast"
- Future Liberal Irish Secretary **W. E. Forster** impressed: "Rothschild,
  Kinnaird, and some dozen other millionaire city princes meeting every day,
  and working hard. A far greater sacrifice to them than mere gifts of money."
- Lionel was a **Free Trader** but recognized free trade alone wouldn't
  solve the famine given the general European cereal deficit
- Contrast: Alphonse viewed Peel's Corn Law repeal "without admiration" as
  "utter revolution"; his father "very much regretted" Peel's fall (mainly
  for diplomatic reasons — Palmerston's return)

### James and the French Food Crisis

- 1846 French wheat harvest 15% below the 10-year average — worst since 1831
- **James** began purchasing grain January 1846 in anticipation; by spring
  1847 offered to buy 5 million francs worth of corn/flour for Paris
  "at our risks & peril and in the event of any loss accruing we s[houl]d
  bear it & the profit to be distributed in bread tickets to the poor"
- Genuinely feared social consequences: "The situation with our grain, which
  really isn't good, does scare me a lot" (November 1846)
- Salomon explicitly wrote of "making our name popular" with "the masses"
  by providing cheap bread and salt
- Backfired: improved 1847 harvest confounded James's expectation prices
  would stay high; Nat complained: "There never was anything so stupidly
  managed as this corn operation"
- In Paris "nobody can imagine anything done disinterestedly" — widely
  perceived James had acted as a grain speculator; rumour spread that
  **Rothschild bread** was laced with ground glass and arsenic
- Violence in faubourg **Saint-Antoine** (May 1847) partly directed against
  grain merchants including James

### The Banking Crisis of 1846–47

- Agrarian crisis → monetary crisis: grain-importing countries drained
  gold/silver, hitting monetary systems across Europe
- Britain: corn imports surged from 251,000 tonnes (1843) to 1,749,000
  tonnes (1847); gold reserves fell from £15.8m (1844) to £9.8m
- Bank of England forced rates from 2.5% (March 1845) to 10% (October 1847),
  forcing suspension of the **Bank Charter Act of 1844**
- **Lionel** and **Barings**' **Joshua Bates** consulted by PM **Lord John
  Russell** and Chancellor **Sir Charles Wood** — but Wood was
  "utterly confounded at the ignorance they displayed"
- **Peel** told Wood that Lionel was not among "those who really understood
  the question of currency" — preferred Jones Lloyd, W. Cotton, Norman, and
  the Bank Governor; a telling sign of the Rothschilds' *lost influence over
  monetary policy* since Nathan's death
- **Banque de France** crisis from October 1846: previous rescues (1825,
  1836–9) had been by the Banque for Bank of England; now roles reversed;
  James excluded from the 25-million-franc silver transaction, done by
  **Hottinguer**; his 5-million-franc follow-up offer rejected by Governor
  **d'Argout** — bad blood since Nathan's death still unresolved
- **Benjamin Davidson** sent via Riga to St. Petersburg with gold-laden
  carriages to broker Banque de France/Russia deal — failed; Davidson
  "effectively unable to do business as a foreign Jew"

### The Beyfus Collapse and Family Tensions

- In 1847 the house of **Haber** collapsed, threatening to take down the
  **Beyfus brothers' bank** (two of Mayer Amschel's daughters — Babette
  and Julie — had married Beyfuses)
- Bail-out: 1.5 million gulden, done "with extremely bad grace" by London
  and Paris; Nat: "the only regret I experience is that our worthy relatives
  have thought it fit to come to their assistance"
- **James** insisted on rescuing them "so near a relation," overriding
  grumblings of Amschel, Salomon, and Carl — illustration of his family
  leadership
- **Arnstein & Eskeles** also threatened (domino effect from Haber);
  Metternich called Salomon urgently from Paris to avert "immeasurable
  calamity"; by September 1847 Salomon held 1,520,000 gulden in
  Eskeles drafts (1,185,000 from Haber)
- Salomon told Anselm: "With God's help we shall remain the Rothschilds"
  — his brothers suspected a grave mistake; they were right

### Salomon's Disastrous Austrian Loan (1847)

- February 1847: Salomon took a new Austrian government loan of 80 million
  gulden (with Sina and ailing Eskeles), at 2.5% and 5%, requiring payment
  to Vienna of 84 million in cash over five years
- Ostensibly for railways; in fact Austria was arming for intervention in
  **Lombardy and Venetia** — Salomon knew this from Metternich
- Then added a further 3.7 million gulden at 4% bonds which he pledged
  *not to sell* — keeping them "in his own safe" for interest of 4.6%,
  while London short rates stood at 5.85%; **Kübeck** was simultaneously
  warning Metternich that intervention in Italy would cause "the complete
  breakdown of our finances" and that Austria was "on the verge of an abyss"
- Metternich, when Salomon got cold feet in January 1848: "Politically,
  things are all right; the exchange is not. I do my duty but you do not
  do yours."
- Salomon's total commitments computed in February 1848: **4.35 million
  gulden** (≈£610,000) — more than double the Vienna house's 1844 capital
- Nat: "Prince Metternich takes our good Uncle in so that he may continue
  his financial operations, I fancy the F'furt house will find a little
  difference in their balance the next time they make it up."

### French Rentes Loan and the Eve of Revolution

- French budget by 1847: 55% higher than twelve years earlier (railway subsidies)
- **James** secured 250 million francs of the 350-million-franc nominal
  rentes issue, priced at 75.25 — two points below market; bid apparently
  rigged: Finance Minister **Dumon** had leaked the "secret minimum"
- James held 170 million francs back (selling only a third at once),
  expecting 3% rentes to rise above 77 — another miscalculation
- **Irish Famine Loan** (England, March 1847): £8 million, co-underwritten
  with Barings; issue price 89.5, quickly fell to 85 — embarrassed
  underwriters and the investing public

### Italian Loans and Pre-Revolutionary Warning Signs

- **Carl** (Naples): keen to lend to Bourbon regime but saved by its
  "chronic indecisiveness"; Rome: Papal deficit doubled in 1847,
  Roman 5% rentes below par for first time since 1834
- James intrigued by election of **Pius IX** (1846) — "supposedly a liberal"
  — halted Roman bond sales expecting "some really positive changes"
  (partly re: position of Roman Jewish community)
- Italian agent **Hecht** warned revolution was "at the eve to break out" —
  deterred a new Papal loan; **Adolph**'s January 1848 visit to Rome
  confirmed alarm
- London house's "amazingly ill-timed" suggestion of a Piedmont loan
  (January 1848!) rejected by **Alphonse**: "a country which can be
  considered as . . . already in full revolution"
- **Belgium** — loan request also turned down, yet it proved one of the
  *least* affected countries in the coming upheaval

### "The Worst Revolution That Ever Happened" — Precursors

- Harbingers the Rothschilds monitored but initially discounted: civil wars
  in Galicia and Switzerland; abortive **United Diet** (Landtag) called by
  **Frederick William IV** in Berlin 1847; liberal stirrings in South Germany
- Austrian annexation of **Cracow** read as just another Polish partition —
  Nat: "I suppose lots of them will be shot"
- True alarm: **artisans' revolt in Sicily** (January 1848) and
  **Ferdinand II**'s granting of a liberal constitution — Nat called it
  "stinking news" (Rothschilds, as usual, first to hear)
- Carl still cool-headed enough to discuss a loan to the Bourbon regime as
  late as February 19, 1848
- **Anselm** on liberal attacks against Ludwig I in Munich:
  "in the highest politics just as in the most lowly social relations,
  the people imposes its will and dictates the law to the higher power"

### France: Nat's Prescient Reports, February 1848

- The Rothschilds had never fully trusted the **July Monarchy**; death of
  Louis Philippe's eldest son (1842) deepened pessimism — the King himself
  confided that after his death "the Revolution of 1830 would begin again"
- James received a personal death threat in 1846 — forwarded it to government:
  "The man who wants to shoot at me could just as well shoot at the King,
  or vice versa"
- **Nat**'s report from Paris, February 20, 1848 (two days before the
  fateful Reform banquet):

> "I think a change of ministry wd. remedy the evil but in the mean time it
> is impossible to say what will occur—no one can tell how a french mob will
> behave . . . I really recommend you most strongly to sell stocks & public
> securities of all sorts and descriptions."

- The very next day Nat was more optimistic, comparing the situation to 1830
  and expecting it to pass — underestimating how fundamentally different
  1848 would prove

> "Of such grievances, multiplied a thousand-fold, are revolutions made."
> — Ferguson, summarizing the accumulation of discontent directed at the
> Rothschilds and the European financial system on the eve of 1848

<!-- pp. 641-660 -->

## Chapter 16: 1848 — The Revolution and the Rothschilds

### Nat's Fatal Miscalculation (Paris, February 1848)

- **Nat de Rothschild** (Paris) was a "temperamental pessimist" who picked
  the worst possible moment to turn optimistic — he repeatedly assured
  his brothers no serious revolution was coming, right up to the barricades
- Feb 23: With National Guard mutinying, Nat still hoped a ministry change
  (Guizot out, Molé in) would suffice — called the émeute "not of a very
  serious nature, very little real fighting"
- **Rue des Capucins massacre**: fifty demonstrators shot dead by soldiers
  guarding the Foreign Ministry — triggered Louis Philippe's abdication
- **Louis Philippe** fled to England; provisional government formed including
  **Alexandre Ledru-Rollin**, **Alphonse de Lamartine**, socialist
  **Louis Blanc**, and a token worker named Albert
- Nat's verdict: "We are in the midst of the worst revolution that ever
  happened" — immediately sent wives and children to Le Havre for England

### The Pan-European Spread

- 1848 was shaped by memory of past revolutions: those recalling 1830's
  failures wanted a more authentic republic; those fearing the 1790s feared
  neo-Jacobins — tension unresolved until late June
- **Pattern across Europe**: relatively few monarchs definitively deposed;
  most fled capitals temporarily and made constitutional concessions when
  civilian police proved inadequate
- **Germany**: began in Baden → Hesse-Kassel, Hesse-Darmstadt, Württemberg;
  Bavaria's **King Ludwig** forced to abdicate (reputation damaged by
  **Lola Montez** affair)
- **Frankfurt** itself threatened — 1848 posed danger to ancient republics
  with over-narrow definitions of citizenship
- **Austria**: **Metternich** received news of Paris revolution via Rothschild
  courier; reportedly said "Eh bien, mon cher, tout est fini"
  — fled March 14 in disguise with barely enough money, financed by
  a credit-note from **Salomon Rothschild**
- Emperor Ferdinand replaced Metternich with arch-rival **Kolowrat**;
  radicals (May 15) forced Emperor to flee to Innsbruck
- **Prussia**: Frederick William IV capitulated March 17 after street
  fighting in Berlin; German revolution thus aimed at both constitutional
  reform AND transformation of the German Confederation itself
- **Italy**: Ferdinand II granted Sicily a parliament, Charles Albert and
  Pius IX issued constitutions in March; Venice and Milan revolted against
  Austrian rule
- Structural pattern: two overlapping revolutions everywhere —
  one constitutional (educated classes), one economic (artisans, workers)

### The Rothschilds' Divergent Reactions

- **Not a uniform ideological response** — attitudes ranged widely within
  the family

**Salomon** (Vienna):
- Comprehended the calamity only in religious terms; blamed Louis Philippe's
  incompetence, Princess Metternich's vanity, Palmerston's irresponsibility
- Compared 1848 to 1789, the Peasants' Wars, the Crusades, and a biblical
  plague of locusts — saw it as a divine test of faith

**Nat** (Paris):
- Most traumatized; suffered something like physical/nervous collapse
- "A worse 'political cholera' never yet infected the world"
- Every letter to brothers concluded with warnings to sell all stocks and shares

**Amschel and Carl**:
- Treated revolution like a natural disaster — inexplicable but survivable
- Carl dismissed Italian nationalism as "the stupid projects of a few
  deranged minds"
- Amschel baffled by Frankfurt parliament's inconclusive debates —
  contemporary cartoon shows him asking new "Reich Trade Minister"
  Arnold Duckwitz: "Nothing to trade yet, Mister Minister?"

**James** (Paris):
- Most pragmatic: "all regimes were at once unreliable and financially
  biddable" — inclined to salute whichever flag was run up
- Refused to let Alphonse serve in the National Guard — assertion of family
  interests over politics, not explicitly anti-republican
- Shed no tears for Louis Philippe

**Anselm, Lionel, Mayer Carl, Alphonse** (next generation):
- Occasionally expressed sympathy with liberal reforms, but distinguished
  these sharply from radical democracy, socialism, communism
- Anselm attended Frankfurt pre-parliament debates with detached interest;
  warmly welcomed the moderately liberal Austrian constitution of March 1849
- **Anthony**: regarded German princes as "a set of donkeys"; thought
  Frankfurt parliament's united Germany project "*Right* and reasonable"
- **Gustave** (19): rushed back to Paris to see the revolution, disappointed
  by "tristesse," working-class unrest, and poor calibre of republican politicians

### The Women's Views — Starkest Contrasts

**Betty** (James's wife):
- Vehemently hostile; applauded her four-year-old grandson who declared:
  "If I had money, I would buy a gun to shoot the republic and republicans"
- Called National Assembly deputies "the wild beasts of our great Parisian
  menagerie"; Frankfurt parliament "an agent of false doctrines and anarchy"
- Delighted when **Robert Blum** was shot in Vienna; regretted the same
  hadn't happened in Paris
- Bizarrely (given her parents were born in the Frankfurt ghetto) expressed
  nostalgia for the *ancien régime* — called the nineteenth century "an evil age"

**Charlotte** (Lionel's wife):
- Derived moralistic satisfaction and sense of "historical acceleration"
  from the crisis; thrilled by German unification prospects
- Wrote in her diary: events in "six weeks have been almost as eventful as
  the six years which saw Louis XVI's death, the great Terror, the
  Convention and Napoleon"
- Could find positive things to say even about French republicans:
  **Ledru-Rollin** "has honest intentions for France"
- Ideal of united Germany strictly monarchical, but repudiated neither
  reform nor republic entirely

**Louisa** (sister-in-law of Charlotte):
- Saw positive aspects to "this wonderful Revolution" — if the house
  could weather the storm, losses however severe were bearable
- Claimed the effect on family fortunes did not disturb her at all —
  "simple indifference, or, rather, dislike to grandeur and display"

### The Threat to Property

- The Rothschilds' real fear was **property**, not personal safety
- Male Rothschilds were "singularly cool as the bullets began to fly":
  James was seen on Feb 24 walking toward the ransacked Tuileries
  arm-in-arm with an unidentified companion even as gunshots continued —
  told a young National Guardsman who warned him away:
  > "My young friend, I tank you for your adfice. But tell me, vy are
  > you here? To do your duty, isn't it? Vell then, I too, Paron de
  > Rothschild, haf come for the same ting... mine is to go to the
  > Minister off Finance, to see vether they may not need my experience
  > and my counsel."
- Salomon stayed in Vienna until June despite "drumming in the streets"
- Anselm stayed until Oct 6-7 — when armed revolutionaries occupied the
  roof of the Rothschild offices after the lynching of Count Latour;
  **Moritz Goldschmidt** had to disguise himself as a milkman to rescue
  the bank's papers
- Amschel never left Frankfurt; slept through a crowd gathering outside
  his house; hung nationalist flags from windows to be left in peace;
  Frankfurt office hit by four bullets in September 1848

**Physical/property threats**:
- Salomon's villa at Suresnes ransacked (along with Louis Philippe's
  at Neuilly)
- Arson on railway stations/bridges of the **Nord company**
- Gustave reported Paris walls showing "lists where to plunder and we are
  mentioned as having 600,000,000 francs"
- Amschel's windows smashed three separate times; he sent "the greater
  part of our disposable effects" to Brussels and Amsterdam
- Goldschmidts' house in Vienna ransacked by workers building barricades;
  Anselm and Nat sent silverware and porcelain to London for safekeeping

**Formal expropriation threats**:
- Berlin associate **Bleichröder** relayed reassurances March 18 —
  "absolutely no cause to fear for private property" — James dismissed:
  "They won't touch a hair on your head, but they'll pose progressively
  until you have nothing left to eat"
- **Railway nationalization**: most dangerous formal threat; Nord owed
  government 72–87 million francs it couldn't repay — easily justified
  government takeover; Nat actually would not have minded (he never liked
  the railways); James resisted surrendering the backbone of his industrial empire
- In Venice, Salomon's salt factory vulnerable to **Manin**'s republican regime

### The Financial Catastrophe

**Table 16a — Security price collapses, 1846–1848:**
- Austrian 5% metallique: peak 112.25 (Dec 1845) → trough 58.00 (Mar 1848) = **−48%**
- French 3% rente: peak 84.25 (Feb 1846) → trough 32.00 (Apr 1848) = **−62%**
- French 5% rente: peak 121.00 (Jul 1846) → trough 50.75 (Apr 1848) = **−58%**
- Roman 5%: peak 105.60 (1843) → trough 71.80 (1848) = **−32%**
- British 3% consol: −22% (least affected)

- James held ~170 million francs of new 3% rentes; by April worth less than
  half what he paid — still obligated to pay French Treasury ~10 million
  francs/month over two years beginning November
- Paris house owed ~10 million francs to railway companies (Nord,
  Strasbourg, Grand-Combe); assets were depreciating stocks while
  liabilities fell due in cash
- At one point in April, James's **cash reserve reduced to little more than
  1 million francs** — when a clerical error made it seem even less, he
  joked of "giving up business, going to the country and living off potatoes"
- Rumours circulated that he was smuggling gold out of Paris in manure carts;
  police placed him under surveillance; Apponyi reported he was "bled white"

**Vienna house — even worse:**
- Salomon saddled with massive industrial stakes (Witkowitz ironworks,
  Nordbahn, Austrian Lloyd) — **27% of assets** in illiquid industrial shares
- Pending obligations ~8 million gulden; could not be paid
- Salomon owed other Rothschild houses principally Frankfurt ~£1.7 million
  (half his total liabilities)
- Frankfurt house simultaneously pressed: owed money to Württemberg,
  Hesse-Kassel; "fortress money" deposited by German Confederation might
  be withdrawn; wrote off 1.3 million gulden already advanced to Beyfuses
- Each house thought the other owed it money; none was in a position to pay;
  Salomon pledged houses and estates (5 million gulden notional value) as security
- **Three of five Rothschild houses on verge of insolvency**

> "The Rothschilds, whose wealth only two months ago exceeded the reserve
> of the Bank of England, have lost the greatest part of that wealth."
> — Charlotte (Lionel's wife)

### Metternich in Exile — End of an Era

- Metternich wrote Salomon two lengthy apologia letters from exile
  (Arnhem and England), repaying his banker with a philosophical defense:
> "What disorder the world has fallen into! . . . The danger of the day
> was not on the field of political war, but of *social* war. On this
> field too I have held the reins in my hands as long as was humanly
> possible . . . If I am asked whether that could have been avoided by
> what naive utopians call Reform, I reply with a categorical *No*."
- Lionel gave Metternich 323,000 gulden advance secured against heavily
  depreciated railway shares; further 5,500 gulden loan to Princess Melanie;
  combined Metternich debts reached 216,500 gulden by following year;
  rescheduled repayment on 1827 loan — still outstanding in the 1870s
- Anselm's verdict on Metternich's theories: "can't be of great help to
  the world now"

### Survival — How the Rothschilds Made It Through

**Why the revolutions failed** (and thus why the Rothschilds survived):
1. **Limited rural support**: constitutional republicanism had shallow roots
   outside major cities; urban classes deeply divided (liberal bankers vs.
   guild-reviving artisans)
2. **No great-power war**: Rothschilds' greatest fear was war radicalizing
   revolution; Lamartine's France declined to export revolution;
   Palmerston's Britain couldn't decide whether to back it
3. **Nationalist contradictions**: competing nationalisms cancelled each other —
   German, Magyar, Czech, Italian movements worked at cross-purposes
4. **Habsburg military recovery**: armies under **Windischgrätz**, **Jelacic**,
   **Radetzky** crushed revolutionaries; Prague fell June 1848;
   Charles Albert's Piedmontese defeated at **Custozza** (July 25);
   Vienna capitulated November 1848; Hungary not finally defeated
   until summer 1849

**The sine qua non — family concordia:**
- London house (and to lesser extent Naples and Frankfurt) bailed out the
  stricken Paris and Vienna houses — Mayer Amschel's injunction to
  maintain unity never mattered more
- **Naples house** was relatively unaffected: profits slumped to 2,709 ducats
  (first half 1848) but recovered to 58,229 ducats (second half); down only
  ~40% for the year; Carl was able to send money to Frankfurt in April
- **England** untouched by revolution: Corn Laws repeal and Bank Charter Act
  suspension (1847) had defused pressure; Chartist demonstration on
  Kennington Common (April 10) proved "a damp squib"
- London house had suffered its worst-ever year in 1847 (losses £660,702 =
  30% of capital) but rebuilt strongly: profits £132,058 (1848),
  £334,524 (1849)
- The family was less rich than before 1848, but far from destroyed —
  Charlotte admitted as much to Count Dietrichstein, who had delivered
  the pointed compliment that she "no longer enjoyed such a high position
  in the world"

<!-- pp. 661-680 -->

## Chapter: Surviving 1848 — The Third-Generation Response

### Lionel's Hard Line Toward the Continental Houses

- **Lionel de Rothschild** refused easy bail-outs to the Paris, Frankfurt,
  and Vienna houses; made uncles "sweat and pay" for their salvation
- His first reaction to **Salomon's** pleas was outright refusal to accept
  bills of Sina's; when he did send silver to Frankfurt, London house
  turned a profit on the shipments
- **Anselm** arrived in Vienna April 10 to clean up Salomon's "Augean
  stables" with "a marked lack of filial compassion" — forbade further
  financial sacrifice on behalf of Arnstein & Eskeles or Heinrich &
  Wertheimer
- Anselm to Salomon: the situation was "fatal" and Salomon was in "such
  a state of moral collapse" that staying longer would only harm his health
- The 1848 crisis within the family marked "the end of the dominance
  of the second generation" — the 1848 revolution *within* the house

### The American Lifeline: Belmont's Critical Role

- London's ability to assist Paris and Vienna depended on **August Belmont**
  remitting funds from America — making 1848 "the decisive test of
  Belmont's agency"
- Belmont had speculated heavily in tobacco and financed the **US-Mexico War**;
  advanced substantial sums against treasury bills for the **$15 million
  indemnity** under the **Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo**
- **Lionel Davidson** in Mexico handled mercury trade and took a hand in
  the indemnity payment; agents in Cuba and New Orleans made large advances
  on tobacco and cotton
- James: "We are too much in the hands of these people" — fear of
  over-dependence on the American agency
- When Alphonse was sent to New York to "bring the errant agent to heel,"
  Belmont hastily dispatched large silver consignments to London — the most
  important stabilising influence on European finance in 1848
- Belmont's position: "semi-dependent and semi-independent, simultaneously
  that of an agent and a correspondent" — he refused to be replaced;
  packed Alphonse off to New Orleans and carried on

### Central Bank Intervention as Second Factor of Survival

- **Bank of England** had suspended its gold reserve rule in October 1847,
  setting the precedent; harder to persuade continental counterparts
- In Paris, **Banque de France** suspended convertibility; government set
  up *comptoirs d'escompte* and *magasins généraux* for emergency liquidity;
  revolution's enduring effect was to eliminate provincial banks of issue
  and centralise power at the Banque de France
- Vienna's **National Bank** banned gold/silver exports and suspended
  convertibility in May
- Fear of paper money inflation was acute — nobody had forgotten the
  **assignats**
- Rothschild access to American and English silver proved crucial:
  Banque de France placed large silver orders through New Court as early
  as April 1848
- Anselm leveraged this silver supply as bargaining chip with Vienna's
  National Bank — used it to prolong Salomon's accumulated due bills
  by two years, with bald threat: "Either the prolongation of the bills
  or the fall of the houses of Eskeles and Wertheimer, which would also
  seriously compromise the portfolio of the National Bank itself"

### James's Survival Strategy in Paris: Negotiating from Weakness

- **James** held ~170 million francs of 3% rentes, now worth roughly
  half what he had paid — the Paris house was most vulnerable
- Feb 24: James visited Ministry of Finance to get new republic to pay
  interest on Greek bonds the previous regime had guaranteed
- Quid pro quo: Feb 25 he announced a donation of 50,000 francs to
  wounded fighters, pledged to "offer his co-operation to such a good
  and honest Revolution"
- Feb 26: Summoned to police prefecture by **Caussidière** on suspicion
  of smuggling money abroad; James steered between admitting bankruptcy
  and revealing his true wealth:

> "People think I am made of money, but I only have paper. My fortune
> and my cash are converted into securities, which at the moment have
> no value. I am far from wishing to declare bankruptcy, and if I must
> die, then I am resolved to do so; but I would regard flight as
> cowardice."

- Caussidière then asked James to open credit for a print works (150
  workers); James returned next day with Lionel, handed over 2,000 francs
  "to be distributed as [he] intended"
- April: government demanded 500,000 francs (balance of pre-revolution
  mortgage with **Louis Philippe**) plus railway debt to the state
- James responded with threats: failure of the Rothschilds would be
  "to kill the goose that lays the golden egg" — government would lose
  both public and private services; Ferrières could not be auctioned;
  employees' jobs would be lost; **Lamartine, Caussidière, and Crémieux**
  had already been granted favours
- Clerks at de Rothschild Frères protested salary cuts, declaring:
  "You are richer than anyone and we won't [accept a pay cut]"
- James bought time; by third week of May, government commission decided
  to repurchase railway concessions from companies rather than nationalise

### The June Days and the Rothschild Political Stance

- **"June days" (22-28 June 1848)**: working-class revolt crushed by
  General **Eugène Cavaignac** — Marx argued bourgeoisie allied with
  militarism against proletariat
- Rothschilds did little to promote restoration of "order"; James sent
  Alphonse to Frankfurt specifically to keep him *out* of the fighting
- Military restoration of order was thus a *deus ex machina* from the
  Rothschild perspective — they welcomed Cavaignac cautiously, did not
  actively sponsor his campaign
- Same pattern in Naples (Ferdinand reclaimed Sicily) and Vienna
  (**Windischgrätz** bombarded revolutionaries into surrender, November)

### James as "Indispensable Debtor"

- Reconstruction under Cavaignac: ideal moment to bury railway
  nationalisation, reschedule Nord debts, resolve the 1847 loan question
- New Finance Minister **Goudchaux** converted 3% bonds of 1847 into
  5% — effectively turning a 25-million-franc loss into an 11-million-
  franc profit; critics cried conspiracy (Goudchaux was Jewish, as was
  **Crémieux**)
- Ferguson's verdict: James had adopted the stance **Balzac** had
  anticipated — "the indispensable debtor who owes his creditors so much
  that they dare not let him fail"
- As **Mérimée** noted: government's financial position was "diabolical";
  collapse of de Rothschild Frères would have made matters catastrophically
  worse
- By July, James was once again closeted with the Finance Minister,
  "now a great favourite and as there is no other Banker or person with
  money or disposition to come forward, he is naturally very much looked
  up to"

### Public Perception: The Miraculous Survival

- The radical *Tocsin des Travailleurs* devoted a leader (August 1848)
  to James, ironically admiring his survival amid universal ruin:

> "You are a wonder sir. In spite of his legal majority, Louis-Philippe
> has fallen, Guizot has disappeared, the constitutional monarchy and
> parliamentary methods have gone by the board; you, however, are
> unmoved! . . . Wealth fades away, glory is humbled, and dominion is
> broken, but the Jew, the monarch of our time, has held his throne."

- As late as November 1848 rumours circulated that James intended to
  liquidate — yet the Rothschilds had in fact survived

### Section: *Tranquillity and Order* — Diminished Political Influence

- Key difference from 1830: in 1848 the Rothschilds lacked diplomatic
  influence because they were too financially preoccupied to play their
  familiar role in great-power politics
- London partners used their new dominance over the continental houses to
  **veto** numerous loan proposals to post-revolutionary regimes:
  Austria, Hungary, Rome, Lombardy, Prussia, Baden — all refused
- Paradox: **Salomon** appears to have suggested lending money to
  Hungarians to buy English guns even while lamenting the Habsburg collapse

### Mayer Carl and Political Caution

- Austrian government asked Salomon to help mediate the "Italian
  difficulties" by sending a family representative; younger Rothschilds
  refused
- **Mayer Carl**: "we should not mix in politics, because, however things
  turn out, it is harlequin who gets the kicks and harlequin, that is us.
  Also I don't believe that Lombardy is going to pay anything to Austria."
- Anselm delighted at **Radetzky's** defeat of Piedmont at **Custozza**
  but miscalculated Austrian diplomatic intentions — assumed Austria would
  still relinquish Italian territory
- Mayer Carl expected **Frederick William IV** to accept the German crown
  from the Frankfurt parliament (he contemptuously refused, calling it
  "a diadem moulded out of the dirt and dregs of revolution")

### The Vienna House Decision: Writing Off £1.7 Million

- Even after Anselm's salvage operation, Vienna owed Frankfurt an immense
  £1.7 million plus a smaller sum to Paris house
- London partners vetoed loan proposals and held back throughout 1848
- Summer 1848: "congress" at Frankfurt decided to preserve Vienna house
  by writing off most of this money
- Alphonse's candid statement of the London partners' "true goal":
  to free London from "a solidarity incompatible with the political
  activities and the ardent business spirit of the first generation"
- Symptom of deepening mistrust: London partners began distinguishing
  between letters they would let uncles see and those they kept private
  — a "revolutionary suggestion" since private correspondence had been
  the lifeblood of the partnership

### Relations with Palmerston and Intelligence Failures

- Rothschilds had poor relations with **Lord Palmerston** throughout 1848
- Charlotte: Palmerston's policy was "laughable"; Nat: "any change in
  the Foreign Affairs will be an improvement on Ld. P[almerston]"
- Betty to James: Palmerston was "the bad genie, breathing fire everywhere
  and sheltering behind political puppets"
- Intelligence based more on defence estimates than first-hand ministerial
  contacts — partly due to Lionel's focus on the Jewish parliamentary
  emancipation question

### James and Louis Napoleon: Pragmatism over Distaste

- **Louis Napoleon Bonaparte** was the figure the Rothschilds viewed
  with the most suspicion and contempt in the entire nineteenth century
- Anthony: Louis Napoleon "gets drunk every night & God knows what else"
  and wanted only "plenty [of money] so that he can roger comfortably &
  get drunk when he likes"
- James called him "a stupid ass" — but was pragmatic: dined with him
  just 18 days after his election as President (Jan 16, 1849), explaining
  "I could not refuse his invitation"
- James had lent Louis Napoleon 20,000 francs before the election; once
  Napoleon had public funds, James cut his credit immediately:
  "I promised him 20,000 francs before his budget was passed but now he
  is getting money from the government, so I don't want to throw away our
  money and so I won't give him a penny more"
- Betty loathed Napoleon more viscerally; told **Macaulay** France was
  "floundering between a nobody and a head garotted by a subversive,
  useless minority"
- Core fear: Louis Napoleon would replicate his uncle's expansionist
  foreign policy and plunge Europe into general war
- James to nephews (mid-1848):

> "The situation looks blacker now, because the people now have to
> make war . . . At the bourse everyone was horribly black . . .
> I am trying to liquidate."

- By early 1849, James assumed Napoleon would "not rest till he has made
  himself Emperor" — regarded this as "a great mistake"
- Relief when Napoleon intervened in Italy on the side of the Pope
  rather than backing the Roman republic — at least not an expansionist
  war against the major powers

### Return to Business: The Piedmont Loan

- Rothschilds held back from new lending as long as political uncertainty
  persisted; Anselm dismissed Austrian 60 million gulden loan as "a great
  nonsense"; James refused Paris city loan three times
- Only after military defeat of revolution was complete did lending resume
- **Anselm** on Piedmont: the indemnity to Austria would generate "a
  beautiful and safe piece of business"
- James negotiated skilfully: sounded out Turin government in advance,
  hinted at rival deal with Italian bankers to shut them out, went in
  person to Vienna and Milan to offer 15 million franc advance on the
  Piedmontese indemnity
- Result: secured control of more than half the 76 million franc
  Piedmontese loan; left only 8 million to Italian bankers, rest to
  public subscription
- James told **Camillo di Cavour** he was "very anxious to have dealings
  with this country; he has repeatedly told me that he regards Piedmont
  as established on a much sounder basis than Austria"
- Cavour was shocked James had "bamboozled" Finance Minister Nigra;
  called him "this cunning old rascal Rothschild" — Cavour would later
  prove a formidable obstacle to Rothschild Italian ambitions
- James declared the loan could lead to a financial "marriage" with Italy
  as a whole

### Return of Confidence: Rentes Rise and Railway Revival

- Paris 5% rentes rose from 74 to 93 in the year after December 1848
  — main barometer of improving financial opinion under the Bonaparte
  presidency
- **Nat** observed at the Rome expedition: "In general when troops begin
  to move bondholders are frightened; in this case as it is for the
  re-establishment of order, perhaps I trust it will produce a good effect"
- First signs of railway revival: **Léon Faucher** appointed Minister
  for Public Works; February 1849, the **Pereires** launched their most
  ambitious scheme yet — Paris-Lyon-Avignon railway (forerunner of
  the Paris-Lyon-Marseille line), with state investing 147 million francs
  and guaranteeing 5% return; company to put up 240 million francs for
  a 99-year concession
- The Pereires had approached **Delessert** and then **Barings** to raise
  capital — "a first hint of the breach which lay ahead"
- James's counter-move: fired **Isaac Pereire** off the Nord board in May
  1849, telling Anthony: "You have no idea what scoundrels these little
  fellows are . . . when these people don't need you, they give you a
  kick in the arse"
- James appeared alongside Napoleon and Changarnier at Nord line opening
  in July — symbolic reassertion of railway dominance
- James's restored self-confidence: "Above all, it is good that people
  realise that nothing gets off the ground without us and when we demand
  something, then it is a case of giving Rothschild all he wants"

### The Herzen Friendship: James as Political Paradox

- James formed an unlikely friendship in 1849 with **Alexander Herzen**,
  founding father of Russian socialism, who coined "Land and Freedom"
- Herzen had moved to align with **Michael Bakunin** and **Pierre-Joseph
  Proudhon** (*la propriété, c'est la vol*) and personally financed
  Proudhon's journal *Voix du Peuple* 24,000 francs while Proudhon was
  in prison
- Herzen's fortune was aristocratic (illegitimate son); Rothschilds helped
  him bank and invest ~10,000 roubles as he sold Russian property
- When Russian government blocked Herzen mortgaging his mother's estate
  at Komostra, James accepted the bill and grew angry at Russian refusal:
  "No, I shan't allow myself to be trifled with; I shall bring an action
  against the bank; I shall demand a categorical reply from the Minister
  of Finance!" — drafted stiff letter threatening St Petersburg with
  legal action and press exposure
- Despite warning from **Count Kiselev** (Russian ambassador) about
  Herzen's politics, James took his side — partly as a joke, partly to
  extract higher commissions (tried to raise commission from 0.5% to 5%)
- Herzen described the encounter memorably: "When half an hour later I
  was mounting the staircase of the Winter Palace of Finance in the Rue
  Laffitte, the rival of [Tsar] Nicholas was coming down it"
- The Herzen episode substantiates **Heine's** earlier claim that James
  was "at heart more a revolutionary than a reactionary"

### James and Political Neutrality: The Rothschild Philosophy

- Marx's accusation that Rothschilds were "financiers of reaction" was
  misleading; James's paramount concern was resuming normal business —
  he called himself "a friend of business" who wanted to "keep the wheels
  turning"
- James was willing to do business with the Roman Republic before the
  Pope was restored; accepted a deposit saying "as I am [now] a Republican"
  — an irony from a man who called it the "accursed republic" at other times
- Any loan to the Pope was conditional on granting civil rights to Roman
  Jews; Anselm on the restored Pius IX: "intolerant in the highest degree,
  I am tempted even to say inhuman. If the Pope could do business with
  any other house, he would certainly break with us"
- James and Lionel strongly objected to Salomon supporting the Austrian
  currency while rivals profited from speculating against it —
  political neutrality over dynastic loyalty
- As Lionel reported from Wildbad (August): "The Liberal party in Germany
  is very different from the liberals in England. All persons of property
  or who are in business are for the old state of things" — 1848 had
  made European liberals more conservative

<!-- pp. 681-700 -->

## Conclusion: The End of the Revolutionary Era (pp. 681-682)

### Herzen's Transformation: Insurgent to Investor

- **Alexander Herzen**, Russian revolutionary exile, had publicly attacked the Rothschilds
  as emblems of capitalist exploitation — then became their client
- Tsar Nicholas I refused to release Herzen's inheritance; **James de Rothschild**
  confronted the Tsar personally and secured payment, treating the episode
  like a battlefield victory ("something like Marengo or Austerlitz")
- Six weeks after that audience, the money was paid; Herzen recalled
  being "on the best of terms with Rothschild" thereafter
- After Herzen's expulsion from Paris by the Bonapartist regime, James
  continued managing his investments (appears in 1851 balance sheet
  owing 50,000 francs), secured him travel permits, and handed his
  account to the London house during his English exile

> "A Rothschild . . . must be in his office in the morning, to begin
> the capitalisation of his hundredth million; in Brazil there is plague,
> and war in Italy, America is falling to pieces—everything is going
> splendidly: and, if someone talks to him then of man's exemption from
> responsibility and of a different distribution of wealth, of course
> he does not listen." — Herzen on the Rothschild worldview

- Herzen's arc — from Rothschild critic to Rothschild client —
  was **emblematic of a Europeanwide shift in mood** post-1848
- James knew Herzen's funds were financing the radical paper
  *Voix du Peuple*; it did not trouble him
- Ferguson's closing argument: rapid, sustained economic growth
  after 1849 made another 1848 much less likely — the future lay
  in **conflicts within capitalism rather than against it**,
  and between states rather than between classes

---

## Appendix 1: Prices and Purchasing Power (pp. 683-686)

### The Problem with Simple Inflation Conversion

- The pound sterling in 1800 was worth ~25x its modern value
  (written c. 1995); by 1900 it was worth ~50x, since prices
  *fell* during the 19th century
- Purchasing power of the pound has declined ~98% since 1900:
  a pound in 1900 terms = ~two decimal pennies today
- **Conventional method**: multiply historic figure by inflation
  index (e.g. ×35.5 to convert 1836 pounds to 1995 pounds)
  - Nathan's £3.5m estate at death (1836) → **£124.25 million** in 1995 terms
- **Problem**: inflation indices ignore structural changes in the
  economy — what money *buys* has transformed entirely
  - Labour was far cheaper 150 years ago (hence vast servant
    households); taxes were negligible
  - Many modern "necessities" were expensive luxuries or
    non-existent; price baskets are not stable over 200 years

> "A fortune . . . is essentially the power to purchase so many
> acres of land, to employ so many workers, to maintain so many
> residences." — James de Rothschild's biographer

### The GDP Method: A More Meaningful Measure

- Better approach: express wealth as a **proportion of GDP**
  - UK GDP in 1836: £562 million
  - Nathan's £3.5m = **0.62% of UK GDP**
  - 0.62% of 1995 UK GDP (£605,100m) = **£3,752 million** —
    much larger than the crude inflation-multiplier figure
- Per capita GDP method: Nathan's £3.5m vs. per capita GDP
  of £22 in 1836 = **160,000× per capita national income**
  - 160,000 × 1995 per capita GDP (£10,430) = **£1,669 million**
  - Conclusion: by modern equivalence, Nathan was close to
    being a **double billionaire**

### Inequality Factor: Why Even This Understates It

- All GDP-based measures miss the **extreme inequality** of
  the 19th century — no progressive taxes, no welfare state
- As late as 1911-13, **87% of adults** in England & Wales
  (16 million people) had total wealth under £100
- Only 0.2% (32,000 people) had wealth over £25,000
- The gulf separating the Rothschilds from nearly everyone
  was therefore vastly larger than modern comparisons suggest
- Nathan's grandsons **Natty, Leo, and Alfred** died in 1915-17
  and left £6,494,000 combined — **0.1% of all capital** owned
  by adults in England and Wales; equivalent to what
  191,000 men from the bottom 87.4% of the population held

### Were the Rothschilds the Richest Family?

- Nathan left more than ironmaster **Richard Crawshay**,
  cotton manufacturers **Robert Peel** and **Richard Arkwright**,
  the Duke of Queensberry, Duke of Sutherland, Duke of Cleveland
- Nearest rival at death (1836): banker **William J. Denison**
  at £2.3m; not surpassed until 1857 by textile/banker
  **James Morrison** (£4-6m)
- Period 1860-99: only 23 individuals left estates ≥£1.8m;
  **four were Rothschilds** (Lionel, Anthony, Nat, Mayer)
- The brothers collectively left **£8.4 million** — if Nathan
  had left it to a single heir (like aristocrats), Lionel
  would have been unambiguously the richest man in Britain
- **James de Rothschild** (Paris) was probably the richest man
  in the world: reported ~1,100 million francs (£44m) at death
  in 1868; more realistic estimate ~193m francs (£7.7m)
- From 1900 onward, English Rothschilds ceased to be
  exceptional — at least 46 British millionaires in 1900-39
  left as much as **Natty** (£2.5m)
- French and Austrian houses remained dramatically richer:
  - 1905: **Edouard, Gustave, Edmond** each had personal shares
    worth £5.8m; **Albert** (Vienna) had £5.9m total share
  - Combined capital of all Rothschild houses at peak
    (December 1899): **£41.4 million** divided among 10 partners
    — excludes substantial private art and real estate holdings
- Ferguson's verdict: **"It is almost inconceivable that any
  other family could match this."**

### Modern Equivalent: No True Counterpart Exists

- The Saudi royal family does not hold a comparable share
  of world resources today
- **Bill Gates** (c. 1995): $36.4bn (£21.7bn) personal fortune
  = **0.49% of US GDP** — slightly less than Nathan's 0.62% of
  UK GDP in 1836
- Per capita comparison favors Gates: his wealth is 1.3 million×
  American per capita GDP vs. Nathan's 160,000× British per
  capita GDP — but this mainly reflects **population growth**
  restraining per capita income, not superior relative wealth
- Conclusion: **no modern individual or family has achieved
  comparable relative wealth** to the Rothschilds at their peak

