## Notes Section: Selected Endnotes of Interest (pp. 689-700)

### Introduction Notes
- Ferguson cites **Chekhov's "Rothschild's Fiddle"** as essential
  reading to understand how the vast majority of 19th-century
  Europeans lived — in wretched poverty, unlike the Rothschilds
- The Alphonse de Rothschild note: James's son **Alphonse**
  opposed preserving documents, insisted on destroying papers
  relating to French reparations of 1815, fearing they might
  "impugn the patriotism of his father"
- Name spelling note: "Mayer" vs. "Meyer" — Ferguson uses
  "Mayer" throughout following the subject's own gravestone
  preference

### Chapter One Notes (Origins)
- Frankfurt was one of **51 self-governing towns** within the
  Holy Roman Empire (which also comprised 94 kings/princes,
  103 counts, 41 church prelates)
- The Judengasse house was preserved until 1944; restored in
  the 1880s as a historic monument by family decision;
  housed two Rothschild charities

### Chapter Two Notes (The Elector's Treasure)
- William IX's officials preferred **bearer bonds** over
  personal loans: legally more secure, more liquid,
  more anonymous — gave little away about the Elector's
  total wealth
- 1812 debt reschedule: Prince of Wales owed £140,000;
  Duke of York £66,667; Duke of Clarence £20,000
- Total assets of the Frankfurt firm at Mayer Amschel's death:
  excess of 970,000 gulden, including 70,000 in bonds
  and 110,000 in other loans

### Chapter Three Notes (The Commanding General, 1813-1815)
- Total sum transferred by Nathan's "single and confidential
  agency" in 1814-15: **£18 million** (per Herries)
- Nathan was furious to learn James had a riding accident —
  "to be riding at all was a sign of dilettantism"
- The rally in gilt prices increased profit margin on the
  Prussian subsidy deal from zero to 3%

### Chapter Four Notes (A Court Always Leads to Something, 1816-1825)
- Byron's lines: 1930 edition had "Jew Rothschild and his
  fellow-Christian, Baring" — Ferguson argues Byron intended
  to put both bankers on equal footing despite different religions
- French reparations breakdown: 700 million francs total;
  138m for border fortresses; 100-139m to each great power
  for Hundred Days costs; 240m to private claimants
- Prussian loan details: 5% bonds totalling £5m in three
  tranches (70, 72.5, 75); Nathan kept secret 4% commission
  to defuse Berlin criticism; Rothschilds retained £1.5m
  for themselves, netting large profit when price hit 83
- 22 of 26 foreign government loans (totalling £52.4m)
  issued 1823-26 were in **default within a few years** —
  a spectacular sovereign debt crisis

### Chapter Five Notes (Hue and Cry, 1826-1829)
- Brazilian loan: James admitted "quite frankly that in two
  years these people will not pay anything" — but it boosted
  Brazilian bond prices in the short run; loan was apparently
  never repaid, so Nathan kept the pledged jewels
- The "HEP" riots: origin of the antisemitic slogan variously
  explained as acronym of "Hierosolyma est perdita" or
  sound of bleating goats alluding to Jews' beards
- A Frankfurt diplomatic dinner hosted by **Amschel** drew
  leading European ministers; the *Courrier Français* explained
  the British ambassador's absence: "England has no need of money"

### Chapter Six Notes (Amschel's Garden)
- Of eight German-Jewish merchants in Manchester in 1806,
  Nathan was **the only one who maintained his religious affiliation**
- **Schnorrer** jokes (Jewish beggars asking Rothschild for
  charity) circulated widely; typical: "So young—and already
  a Rothschild" as a child passes in a sumptuous perambulator
- Hannah Rothschild was irresistibly attracted by bourse
  speculation during revolutions; confessed to husband
  she hadn't "made a great deal of money" — her son later
  wrote hoping she'd been "a great Bull during the enormous
  rise in all the funds"

### Chapter Seven Notes (Barons)
- Betty (James's wife) told a guest admiring her house:
  "If you had seen the hotel of M. Solomon Rothschild
  (which is next door), you would think our house was
  only the stables attached to it"
- Rothschild coat of arms went through multiple revisions;
  Vienna heralds stripped it down to eagle and hand
  grasping four arrows; motto "Concordia, integritas,
  industria" incorporated later
- When Macaulay dined with Nathan he "did not see one Peer,
  or one star, except a foreign order or two, which I
  generally consider as an intimation to look to my pockets"
- Nathan's grandson dropped the "de" on receiving a British
  peerage — hence both "Rothschilds" and "de Rothschilds" exist today

