### Chapter 8 Endnotes: *Sudden Revolutions (1830–1833)*

- **Nathan's art collection** included portraits of
  Francis I of Austria, Frederick William III of Prussia,
  John VI of Portugal, and the Empress Alexandra of Russia —
  diplomatic gifts from government clients
- **Hobday portrait** (*The Family of W. N. Rothschild,
  Consul General of his Austrian Majesty at the British Court*)
  commissioned to mark Nathan's Austrian consul-general
  appointment; shown at Royal Academy 1821; now in main hall
  of N. M. Rothschild & Sons, New Court
- **Hannah** found the atmosphere in one location
  "too orthodox to be an agreeable residence for any other
  sect beside Protestant" (1841 observation)
- **Robert Owen** (utopian socialist) had known the
  Rothschilds since at least 1818 — unusual cross-ideological
  connection

> "Above all fill his purse, O king, / With ample funds for
> travelling, / And give him a letter of credit to greet /
> The Rothschild brothers in Rue Lafitte."
> — Popular verse (c. 1830s), illustrating the Rothschilds'
> role as international letters of credit

- **James** on the Polignac crisis: "regarding Polignac,
  I had been forewarned on several occasions as far back as
  six months before. However, I did not want to believe it.
  I had a gut feeling."
- Hannah to Nathan, Aug. 24, 1830 on the revolution:
  "You must look at it coolly, dear Rothschild. It will blow
  over. Salomon and James do not like the fall… but they are
  very cool and not frightened. Our attention is so engrossed
  with the funds that I can dwell upon nothing else."
- **Hottinguer** warned Lionel: "Our credit is no more so good,
  and this last six months we have lost much in the public
  opinion; we shall not find so many more followers when we
  wish to make any loans." — shows how revolutionary episodes
  damaged Rothschild standing with co-investors
- **Frederick William** of Hesse had made a morganatic marriage
  to **Gertrud Falkenstein** (divorced wife of a Prussian
  lieutenant); he elevated her to Countess von Schaumburg and
  later Princess of Hanau — the couple and five children
  regularly took midday meals *en famille* with the Rothschilds
  in Frankfurt
- **Thomas Raikes** journal, July 17, 1832: Nathan refused
  to advance money to a Dutch broker during the cholera
  epidemic — "In these times I shall not advance money to
  any one *by Got*; who knows what may happen? you may be
  dead tomorrow." The man was seized with cholera that
  evening and was dead by morning — dark anecdote revealing
  Nathan's caution during the epidemic

---

### Chapter 9 Endnotes: *The Chains of Peace*

- **Saxe-Coburg connection**: links between the House of
  Saxe-Coburg and the Rothschilds explain why Queen Victoria's
  marriage to Albert prompted congratulations from
  **Anselm** (Salomon's son) to London cousins
- **Belgian crisis**: France's commitment to the January 1831
  protocols and refusal to support the duc de Nemours as
  Belgian king was crucial — **Leopold of Saxe-Coburg**
  emerging as Belgian king was explicitly good news for
  the Rothschilds
- **James** worked to soften Austrian diplomatic language
  over the Papal States ("evacuez immédiatement Bologne"),
  ensuring Austria referred the matter to an international
  conference rather than acting unilaterally
- **Prussian debt conversion**: £3,809,400 of 5% bonds
  from the 1818 loan exchanged for 4% bonds at 98,
  over 2.5 years from March 1830–September 1832
  — James knew the issue price was too high and commission
  too low given French political uncertainty
- James assessed worst-case scenario: "The worst, the very
  worst is that we stand to lose 15 per cent, God forbid,
  which amounts to £200,000 which is quite liable to ruin
  someone [else]."
- French money earmarked for Franco-German border
  fortresses — "evidently not Metternich's purpose in
  borrowing it" (Ferguson's wry note on dual-use finance)
- Greek loan: 5% issued at 94; 11 million francs earmarked
  for compensation to Turkey — parallels the Belgian-Dutch
  separation financial settlement

---

### Chapter 10 Endnotes: *The World's Bankers*

- **Royal Exchange** (not Stock Exchange at Capel Court)
  was primarily a market for commercial bills and foreign
  exchange — in Nathan's era bonds began trading there too;
  Jewish traders formally allocated the south-east corner
  of the ground floor, behind Spanish and Portuguese traders
- Brothers' crisis protocol included: withdrawing deposits
  from New Court, selling 1818 Prussian loan holdings,
  maintaining sufficient liquid funds to cover 9 million
  gulden of French reparations deposited by the German
  Confederation, and circulating monthly balance sheets
  — whether acted upon or a "shot across Nathan's bows"
  is unclear
- **Anselm** profit structure: immediately entitled to
  1/15th of profits; formal capital share not until 1828
  (one million gulden in Paris house)
- **Gutle's** inheritance from **Mayer Amschel** invested in
  Frankfurt house, but she held no formal partner status
  and her share excluded from total capital for accounting
- Partnership structure: if profits of Paris, Frankfurt,
  Naples, Vienna houses exceeded London's by ≥22.5%,
  and total exceeded 60% of London's, profit division
  reverted to equal shares
- *Railway Times* noted "notorious fact" that in all
  Nathan's loan transactions, *The Times* "invariably,
  aye systematically, came in for a share of the pickings"
  — **Alsager** (Times financial editor) later committed
  suicide after a financial "inconsistency" was discovered

---

### Chapter 11 Endnotes: *"Il est Mort" (1836)*

- **Lionel's unconsummated marriage**: James crudely noted
  "the red King would not permit him to spit roast the bird";
  Lionel more delicately observed "the fright has generally
  such an effect upon the young ladies that they are
  immediately troubled with some thing that pays them very
  often a visit" — contrast in generational language reveals
  how few secrets existed within the family
- Powers of attorney had to be sent to allow senior clerks
  to act in family members' absence — described as
  "rare if not unprecedented circumstance" at this time
- Eyewitness description of James at the Bourse:
  "I looked about me. Every minute a small door opened and
  one Bourse agent after another came in, uttering a number
  in a loud voice; Rothschild going on reading, muttered
  without raising his eyes: 'Yes—no—good—perhaps—enough—'
  and the number walked out… The Jewish autocrat sat calmly
  at his table, looking through papers and writing something
  on them, probably millions, or at least hundreds of
  thousands." — vivid portrait of James's deliberate
  impassivity as power performance

---

### Chapter 12 Endnotes: *Love and Debt*

- **Grüneburg house** demolished on Mayer Carl's death 1886;
  grounds given to City of Frankfurt
- **Anselm** subject to financial constraint imposed by
  Salomon; when spotting property at Emmerich (1843),
  had to ask James for funding — **Amschel** acted as
  "paymaster" for the new Grüneburg house
- **Thackeray**, despite his confessed "bad opinion" of Jews
  generally, became friendly with **Anthony's wife Louisa**
  and **Lionel's wife Charlotte** after a chance meeting in 1848
- **Heine** sent Betty de Rothschild his post-revolutionary
  poem containing a "passionate denunciation of the powers
  which had crushed the Hungarian rising" — the Rothschilds'
  support for Russian-sponsored reaction was well known,
  making this a pointed gesture

---

### Chapter 13 Endnotes: *Quicksilver and Hickory (1834–1839)*

- **Portuguese loan dispute**: Rothschilds lent £88,688 for
  four months to pay interest on Portugal's 3% bonds;
  received "Regency bonds" worth £600,000 as security —
  when Portugal failed to repay, London house sold the bonds;
  Portugal claimed unnecessary delay to collect extra interest;
  final judgment went against Rothschilds on a technicality
- **Metternich** had no objection to Rothschilds covertly
  participating in Spanish business through other firms —
  his concern was that the name "Rothschild" publicly
  associated with Maria Christina's Regency would
  legitimize her position
- Lionel on British/French indecision over Spain:
  "Every person here laughs at their want of decision…
  Why do they not interfere regularly and send 50,000 men;
  they would finish the war in three months."
  — "It is disgusting to see two powers like England and
  France so afraid of the despotic Government" (Metternich)
- **Palmerston** argued against guaranteed Spanish loans:
  "Men would say that if money was the chief want of the
  Queenites a loan might set them on their legs, but that
  the Rothschilds will not contract to supply military skill
  and willingness to fight and honesty of purpose"
  — money alone cannot buy a war's outcome
- **Baring Brothers** / Banque de France operation:
  Baring drew 3-month bills (48 million francs) on a
  syndicate of Hottinguer, Delessert, d'Eichthal, Périer
  and d'Argout, then discounted the bills; Baring made
  cash available to the Bank — complex multi-firm structure
  necessitated by Banque's legal restrictions on direct lending

---

### Chapter 14 Endnotes: *Between Retrenchment and Rearmament (1840)*

- Messianic/political dimension: a source quoted tells
  **Palmerston** earnestly about restoring Jews to Palestine —
  "The country had ample natural capabilities… the ownership
  of the soil might be bought from Turkey: money would be
  forthcoming: the Rothschilds and leading Hebrew capitalists
  would all help: the Turkish empire was falling into ruin"
  — early Zionist-adjacent thinking linking Rothschild
  capital to Jewish restoration
- **Mayer de Rothschild hospital** in Paris "wholly controlled
  by the Rothschilds" and established under supervision of
  **James's son Gustave** — family philanthropic infrastructure

---

### Chapter 15 Endnotes: *"Satan Harnessed": Railways (1830–1846)*

- Pseudo-scientific racial definitions of Jewishness were
  "primarily devised by anti-Semites in order to get at
  apostates or the issue of 'mixed marriages'"
  — Rothschilds remained Jewish in religious sense,
  vulnerable to both traditional and pseudo-scientific attack
- French railways: first lines strictly transported coal
  (Saint-Etienne, early 1830s); proper network dates from
  **Paris-Saint-Germain line** (steam, passengers + freight)
- **Rive Droite** line cost 16.8 million francs vs.
  11 million projected — but significantly cheaper
  than Rive Gauche; cost overruns were endemic
- Anti-Rothschild pamphlet attacking James and the Nord
  railway concession: **Anselm** later claimed the "vulgar
  abuse" emanated from "a despicable person, to whom our
  Paris House had quite rightly refused a loan"
- Railway crash survivors: "their mother interpreted their
  survival as 'providential'"; **Evelina** and her unborn
  son reportedly died in a second railway crash two years later

---

### Chapter 16 Endnotes: *1848*

- Railway investment trough not reached until 1851 —
  four years after the financial crisis; "a runaway train
  effect" in metaphor and reality
- **Adolph** transformed by the 1848 revolution:
  Nat found him "quite an altered man, he has become the
  steadiest fellow ever seen, he neither smokes nor shags
  nor dances"
- **Suresnes attack** on James's estate: instigated
  by local poultry merchant **Louis Frazier**; crowd pillaged
  pheasant pens and stables, stole horses, and "with hatchets,
  iron bars and clubs they laid waste furniture, mirrors,
  and pictures" — those convicted sentenced to 5–20 years
- **Schleswig-Holstein crisis**: both duchies under Danish
  suzerainty; Holstein already part of German Confederation;
  Salic law created succession crisis; Danes incorporated
  Schleswig on March 21; Prussia sent army but bowed to
  British/Russian pressure August 26 — joint Danish-Prussian
  administration established
- **King Leopold of the Belgians** deposited 5 million francs
  with the Rothschilds as contingency fund in case he lost
  his throne — rulers used Rothschilds as personal escape fund
- **Cavour** refused James's offer of Rentes *au prix courant*
  to mollify him: "but it gave me some idea of the way
  business is done in most of the European Cabinets"

