## Index (T–Z)

These pages are the tail end of the book's **general index**, covering entries
from T through Z. No narrative content appears here — this is purely a
reference section listing people, places, texts, and concepts with implied
page references (page numbers not reproduced in this edition's scan).

### Selected Notable Index Entries (T)

- **Talleyrand, Charles de** — referenced; key diplomatic figure of the
  Napoleonic era who intersected with Rothschild financial networks
- **Talmud Torah in London Society** — indicates Rothschild involvement in
  Jewish educational/communal organizations
- *Tancred* (Disraeli) — Disraeli novel; reflects the Rothschild–Disraeli
  literary and political connection
- **Thiers, Adolphe** — French statesman; indexed with "downfall of" and
  "Tommaso affair," indicating Rothschild entanglement in French politics
- **Tommaso, Father** — the Damascus blood libel affair (1840); a flashpoint
  for Rothschild diplomatic intervention on behalf of persecuted Jews
- **Toleration, Edict of (1782)** — Habsburg reform; foundational to Jewish
  legal emancipation in Central Europe
- *Times* (London) — multiple sub-entries: Hannah Mayer's marriage
  announcement, Nathan's obituary, and Nathan's press relationship; shows
  the Rothschilds' careful management of public image
- **Toussenel, Alphonse** — French antisemitic writer; his presence signals
  the book's coverage of anti-Rothschild ideological attacks
- **Treaty of Chaumont (1814)**, **Treaty of Paris (1815)**, **Treaty of
  Pressburg (1805)**, **Treaty of Treplitz (1813)** — Napoleonic-era
  treaties; context for the wartime bond operations that made Rothschild
  fortunes

### Selected Notable Index Entries (U–V)

- **Union Générale** — French Catholic rival bank that collapsed in 1882;
  a major episode in anti-Rothschild conspiracy narratives
- **United States** — sub-entry "Rothschild interest in"; reflects the firm's
  19th-century American bond dealings and agent network
- **Zionism / Zionists** — end-of-book index entry signals coverage of the
  Rothschild family's complex, often ambivalent relationship with the
  Zionist movement (especially Edmond de Rothschild's Palestine colonies
  vs. the family's general anti-Zionist establishment stance)
- **Vatican Bank** — indexed; indicates Rothschild dealings with Papal
  finance, a recurring theme in the firm's Italian operations
- **Victoria, Queen of England** — sub-entry "Rothschild couriers used by";
  illustrates the firm's intelligence and courier network serving heads
  of state
- **Völkische Beobachter** — Nazi organ; its presence in the index confirms
  the book extends into 20th-century antisemitic persecution of the family
- *Voix du Peuple* — radical left press; indexed alongside antisemitic
  publications, showing Rothschilds were attacked from both left and right

### Selected Notable Index Entries (W–Z)

- **Wellington, Arthur Wellesley, Duke of** — multiple sub-entries:
  anti-Rothschild cartoons, opposition to Jewish emancipation, role as
  prime minister, reform crisis, and banking relationship — illustrates
  the contradictory nature of Rothschild ties to conservative politicians
  who were simultaneously clients and opponents of Jewish rights
- **William IX, Landgraf and Elector of Hesse-Kassel** — sub-entries on
  background/personality, **Mayer Amschel**'s relationship with him, and
  the Napoleonic Wars; this is the foundational client relationship that
  launched the dynasty
- **William II, Emperor of Germany** — indexed; reflects late-period
  Rothschild dealings with Wilhelmine Germany
- **Witkowitz Ironworks** — the major industrial asset acquired by the
  Austrian Rothschilds; a symbol of their industrial-era expansion beyond
  pure finance
- **World War I** — indexed; the conflict that marked the end of the
  Rothschild-dominated era of international finance
- **Zola, Emile** — indexed; likely in context of the Dreyfus Affair and
  French antisemitism, in which Rothschild interests were deeply implicated
- **Zionism / Zionists** — the family's internal debate over Zionism was
  a defining late-era tension: **Edmond** funded Palestinian settlements
  while the banking branches feared Zionism would inflame antisemitism
  and undermine their carefully constructed cosmopolitan identity

### Observation

The index breadth confirms Ferguson's scope: the book spans **Napoleonic
finance**, **Jewish emancipation politics**, **antisemitic cultural history**,
**industrial capitalism**, **diplomatic intelligence networks**, **art
collecting**, and the **transition to 20th-century finance** — all
refracted through the Rothschild family as a lens.

